<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DAVIES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PATON DAVIES, 91, DIPLOMAT WHO RAN AFOUL OF MCCARTHY OVER
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graf to replace `Eisenhower administration' with
`executive branch') (EDS: An abridged version, OBIT-DAVIES-ABRIDGED, will also be
filed) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL T. KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Paton Davies, a leading diplomat who was among the ``old
China hands'' driven from the State Department after Sen. Joseph
McCarthy questioned their loyalty and labeled them Communist
sympathizers in the 1950s, died Thursday at his home in Asheville,
N.C. He was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and about a dozen of the country's most eminent China
scholars and diplomats found themselves accused of having ``lost
China'' after Mao Tse-tung's Communist forces defeated Chiang
Kai-shek's Nationalists, which were supported by the American
government, in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   In his attacks, McCarthy was echoing the indignant arguments of
the China lobby, as the powerful American backers of Chiang
Kai-shek were known. Among those accused of ``selling out'' Chiang
were several diplomats, including Oliver Edmund Clubb, John Carter
Vincent and John Stewart Service, and academics like Owen Lattimore
and John King Fairbank.
</P>
<P>
   But of all those Americans whose careers were blighted in the
hunt for scapegoats, Davies may be one of the most poignant
examples. He was a decorated hero of World War II destined,
according to his superiors, for high rank in the State Department.
He was regarded as a tough foe of Stalinism whose World War II
reports from China were much concerned with the threat of Soviet
domination. In 1950 he had even proposed that the United States,
with its superiority in nuclear weapons, engage in a ``preventive
showdown'' with the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on Nov. 5, 1954, Secretary of State John Foster Dulles
dismissed him from the Foreign Service, maintaining that Davies had
``demonstrated a lack of judgment, discretion and reliability.''
According to ``The China Hands,'' a book by E.J. Kahn published in
1972, Davies was then told that if he ever needed a recommendation
for a new job, the secretary of state would be happy to provide
one.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal took place four years after McCarthy began his
pursuit of the State Department's Far Eastern division, describing
it in a Senate speech as the home base of ``individuals who are
loyal to the ideals and designs of Communism rather than those of
the free, God-fearing half of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped up his accusations that the executive branch was
sheltering Communist sympathizers, McCarthy first asserted that he
had a list of 205 State Department policy shapers who were ``known
to the secretary of state as being members of the Communist
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Later he mentioned a list of 57 names, and a list of 81. Pressed
to identify anyone, he declared that Lattimore, a Johns Hopkins
University professor who specialized in Mongolian studies and had
no official ties to the State Department, was ``the top Russian spy
in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davies and his colleagues were accused, it was noted that
many were named John, which gave rise to a bitter riddle: Who was
responsible for losing China? John S. Service, John Carter Vincent,
John Paton Davies and John Kai-shek.
</P>
<P>
   In hearings that lasted for years, several of the China hands,
including Davies, Service and Vincent, were accused by Gen. Patrick
J. Hurley, Roosevelt's special envoy and then ambassador to China
in 1944-45, of sabotaging his efforts to prevent the collapse of
the Nationalist government. Among other things, they were attacked
for having known and met with Chinese Communist leaders.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the case against Davies arose from his role in the
Tawny Pipit Affair. The tawny pipit, a bird that sings loudly in
flight, was the code name for a covert intelligence-gathering
operation contemplated after the fall of the Chinese Nationalist
government in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   After the lowering of the Bamboo Curtain when the Communists
took over, Davies was delegated by George Kennan, director of
policy planning in the State Department, to attend a meeting with
Defense and Central Intelligence representatives on ways to obtain
intelligence from China. Davies suggested that approaches be made
to half a dozen Americans friendly with the Chinese Communist
leaders, with an eye toward enlisting them as double agents.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was never pursued, but in 1952 Davies' critics
contended that he had been trying to infiltrate the U.S.
intelligence network with Communist sympathizers so they might
eventually subvert their country in support of China.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by a Senate subcommittee on internal security,
Davies parried questions while adhering to his understanding that
anything involving the CIA had to be kept secret. Later,
subcommittee members tried to charge Davies with perjury on the
basis of his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Kennan, who had worked with Davies in Moscow, strongly defended
him. In his ``Memoirs 1950-1963,'' Kennan noted that Davies had
originally run afoul of Hurley by trying to warn him against Soviet
perfidy, and largely as a result of the general's charges had
suffered ``years of harassment and humiliation.'' This, Kennan
said, reflected ``the nightmarish quality'' of that time, and he
described Davies as ``a man of broad, sophisticated and skeptical
political understanding, without an ounce of pro-Communist
sympathies, and second to no one in his devotion to the interests
of our government.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Like several other American figures in the Chinese drama, John
Paton Davies Jr. was born in China _ in Kiating, Sichuan province,
on April 6, 1908. His parents were Baptist missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years at the University of Wisconsin, another at
Yenching University outside Beijing and a fourth at Columbia, where
he graduated in 1931. He joined the Foreign Service and returned to
China the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Stationed successively in Kunming, Beijing, Mukden and Hankou,
Davies spent the next decade observing the advance of the Japanese
armies into China, protecting U.S. interests and eventually
evacuating U.S. civilians. In Hankou, then the Nationalists'
capital, he met the leading Communists, witnessed the rout of the
Nationalist forces by the Japanese and saw atrocities committed by
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   When Japan attacked Pearl Harbor on Dec. 7, 1941, Davies was in
Washington, on the State Department's China desk. He seized an
opportunity to join the staff of Gen. Joseph Stilwell, who had just
been named commander of the China-Burma-India theater.
</P>
<P>
   Stilwell's forces suffered defeat in Burma; after leading a
painful retreat, Stilwell was given responsibility for organizing
the defense of India and China. Davies served as his chief
diplomatic aide, political adviser, interpreter, sometime press
spokesman and Dutch uncle (occasionally warning the tough soldier,
known as Vinegar Joe, to restrain his candor and optimism).
</P>
<P>
   Tensions quickly developed between the Americans and the Chiang
government, then based in Chongqing. In his reports, Davies
expressed fear that China was headed toward a civil war that the
Communists would win, and that American support of Chiang against
Mao would drive the Chinese Communists toward the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Long afterward, he said he had mistaken the Communists' evident
popularity with the idea that their ascent to power had something
to do with democracy. He also said he had underestimated the grip
of Maoist ideology in theorizing that the Communists would be open
to American investment. In essence something like this did happen,
but it took another three decades.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, 1943, Davies was on a C-46 transport flying to China
from India when an engine failed and all aboard were ordered to
jump.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sevareid, who was aboard as a radio correspondent,
recounted the story: none of the 17 passengers had ever used a
parachute, and all hesitated. Davies, as the senior official,
jumped first, his attache case stuffed inside his shirt. It took a
month for the group to walk out of the jungle, and according to
Sevareid it was Davies who rallied them when it seemed impossible
to go on. At one point, Sevareid said, Davies gave him his last cup
of water. Davies received the Medal of Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   In summer 1944, an observation group called the Dixie Mission
was sent to the Communist headquarters at Yenan after prodding by
Davies and the U.S. Army. The mission confirmed reports of
Communist strength in the north. Davies made several trips there
and passed along two offers from Mao, one to visit the United
States to discuss further ties and the other to cooperate with a
contemplated U.S. landing on the Japanese-held coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not now abandon Chiang Kai-shek,'' Davies wrote in a
memo on Nov. 15, 1944, ``but we must be realistic. We must not
indefinitely underwrite a politically bankrupt regime. We must make
a determined effort to capture politically the Chinese Communists
rather than allow them to go by default wholly to the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley, who at the time accepted Stalin's assurances of support
for Chiang and of disdain for the Chinese Communists, now began to
denounce Davies and his colleagues, saying their criticism of the
Nationalists was meant to undermine his attempt to unify the
various Chinese military forces against the Japanese. Arriving in
Yenan in November 1944, he sent Davies back to Chongqing. Davies
was relieved to obtain a transfer to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow in
January 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley gained the Communists' assent to a coalition with the
Nationalists, but Chiang rejected it, proposing one unacceptable to
the Communists. In August 1945 the Japanese surrendered, and the
opposing Chinese armies raced to take over their sectors in a civil
war in which the United States backed the losing side.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hurley returned to Washington and resigned as ambassador in
November 1945, blaming the China hands, including Davies, for the
failure of his mission. The hunt for those who ``lost China'' was
well under way.
</P>
<P>
   The first victim was Service. The FBI arrested him, accusing him
of espionage in providing classified reports on China to a small
magazine called Amerasia, but he was cleared by a grand jury. He
was then accused of disloyalty on nine more occasions before
finally being dismissed on the ground of ``reasonable doubt'' of
his loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   At the embassy in Moscow, where Davies had been promoted to
first secretary, echoes of Hurley's charges aroused indignant
rebuttals from Ambassador Averell Harriman and Kennan. Secretary of
State James F. Byrnes, on a visit, jestingly asked a Soviet leader
to be nice to Davies because Hurley was calling him a Communist.
</P>
<P>
   From 1947 to 1951, Davies served on the State Department's
policy planning staff, under Kennan. He foresaw the French defeat
in Indochina and urged that the United States avoid getting
involved. Like Kennan he remained suspicious of Moscow, and in one
paper called for a ``preventive showdown'' while the United States
still had a monopoly on atomic bombs.
</P>
<P>
   He was nevertheless a major target of the China lobby, one of
whose stalwarts was another son of missionaries to China, Henry
Luce, founder and publisher of Time magazine. When Time accused
Davies of undercutting Gen. Douglas MacArthur by warning of Chinese
intervention in Korea, Kennan wrote an angry rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   Assigned to Germany in 1951, Davies was called home in the next
year to testify about the Tawny Pipit Affair. He was cleared of a
Senate subcommittee's perjury charge but was transferred to Lima,
Peru, where he served as charge d'affaires.
</P>
<P>
   Still McCarthy hammered away at him and at Tawny Pipit until, in
late 1954, a special security board ruled that while Davies'
loyalty could not be questioned, his employment was ``not clearly
consistent with the interests of the national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies was informally invited to resign, which would have
assured him a pension. He refused. Dulles summoned him and, in a
few words, told him he had been dismissed. It was then that the
secretary offered to provide a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   Davies said nothing, although he later termed the offer
``bizarre,'' because he had been found lacking ``in judgment,
discretion and reliability.'' In a statement he said: ``There has
been enough recrimination. I am not prepared to add to it and
thereby detract from the strength of my country in its mortal
struggle with the Communist enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned to his family in Lima.
</P>
<P>
   In India in 1942, he had married Patricia Grady, a correspondent
for The Washington Post and the daughter of Henry F. Grady, the
first American ambassador to India. She survives, as do their seven
children: Sasha, of White Plains, N.Y.; Tiki, of Washington; John
G., of Baton Rouge, Louisiana; Susan, of Chatham, N.Y.; Jennifer,
of Seattle; Deborah, of London, and Megan, of New Orleans. Also
surviving are a brother, Donald, of State College, Pa., and 11
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had no experience in the woodworking trade, Davies
set up a shop in Lima to design and make furniture. It succeeded,
modestly. He also wrote a weekly column for a local newspaper, and
worked his writings into a book published in 1964, ``Foreign and
Other Affairs.'' In it he took a tough view of American policy in
Latin America, suggesting that Washington show more willingness to
support strong governments.
</P>
<P>
   About this time Davies returned to Washington to, as he put it,
raise his children in a democratic American climate. Friends began
a quiet effort to obtain his official rehabilitation, but it was
not until 1969 that he was granted a government security clearance
to work on a research project on Latin America at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. Even this action was not formally
announced by the State Department, though he did obtain a pension.
</P>
<P>
   Davies and his family then lived for several years in Malaga,
Spain. He and his wife settled in Asheville, N.C., when their
children began attending college.His second book, ``Dragon by the
Tail,'' was both a memoir and a history of Chinese-American
relations from 1931 to 1945. It appeared in 1972, as the Nixon
administration's involvement with China was renewing American
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Davies concluded the book with this thought: ``The truth of the
matter is that China has been since the fall of the Empire a huge
and seductive practical joke. The Western businessmen, missionaries
and educators who had tried to modernize and Christianize it
failed. The Japanese militarists who tried to conquer it failed.
The American government, which tried to democratize and unify it,
failed. The Soviet rulers who tried to insinuate control over it
failed. Chiang failed. Mao failed.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 Davies, along with Fairbank and Service, was invited to
testify before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee. Its
chairman, William Fulbright, welcomed them by saying: ``It is a
very strange turn of fate that you gentlemen, who reported honestly
about conditions, were so persecuted because you were honest about
it. This is a strange thing to occur in what is called a civilized
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, while Davies was still living in Spain, the
American Foreign Service Association held a luncheon at the State
Department in honor of the old China hands. Davies was among those
invited, but he stayed home. He told friends it would have been a
long way to go for lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
