<HEADLINE>
U.S. WOMEN'S TEAM TURNS GREEDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The buzz was exhilarating while it lasted. At 165
days, it was the Joy Fawcett of all hangovers.
</P>
<P>
   Fawcett, you surely remember, is a mother of two and the
smotherer of many would-be goal scorers. The celebrated defender
for the U.S. women's national team provided one of the divine
storylines of the 1999 Women's World Cup, what with her graceful
juggling of marriage, motherhood and soccer.
</P>
<P>
   For three glorious weeks last summer, Fawcett and her 19 U.S.
World Cup teammates turned the world on with their smiles. They had
more spunk than Mary Richards, more camaraderie than the WJM
newsroom and not a trace of Ted Baxter's ego.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team commanded headlines wherever it went. By the time
Brandi Chastain bared her sports bra after a shootout win over
China in the final, they had collectively enjoyed more exposure
than a swimsuit model.
</P>
<P>
   They carried themselves like role models, these women who were
seeking neither fame nor fortune, but, rather, self-fulfillment.
The U.S. squad was the cause that refreshed a sporting nation
thirsting for athletes who hadn't let success spoil them.
</P>
<P>
   That was then.
</P>
<P>
   Now the best female soccer players in the world, for all their
visibility, are barely recognizable. The sobering truth is the wide
eyes and sweeping smiles are gone, replaced by outstretched palms.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team handed the U.S. Soccer Federation a red card the
other day for mishandling the negotiations for a new contract to
replace the one that expired in July.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty they've imposed is a stiff one for soccer fans who
anticipated falling in love all over again with the Americans at
the Australia Cup, the U.S. team's first major competition since
the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Superstar Mia Hamm and Company have decided to stay home, their
love of the game superceded by cash concerns. Call it a Y2Karat
problem.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter that the U.S. team is old enough to remember
well the days when wealth was measured in loose change.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, which is to say a decade ago, the women played
for little more than $10 a day in meal money.
</P>
<P>
   Last year each player earned $65,000 in salary and bonuses. That
put them well ahead of the average American worker but nowhere near
their male peers. So what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep doesn't make as much per movie as Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis doesn't net as much per victory as Pete Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the tool of your trade is a ball or a ballpoint pen,
women typically continue to be paid less to do the same job.
</P>
<P>
   Parity doesn't come with one penalty kick.
</P>
<P>
   Equality isn't achieved in a day, or even three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sport mirrors life. Injustices happen; just ask the Chinese
players, who watched U.S. goalkeeper Briana Scurry get away with
taking a step forward before each of their penalty kicks in clear
violation of the rules.
</P>
<P>
   If there was justice for all, soccer's world governing body
(FIFA) wouldn't have decided to move the dates of the next women's
World Cup up a year, to the fall of 2002. In this new slot it'll
have to be very strong indeed not to drown in the wake of the men's
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   FIFA's message, coded or not, was clear: Women's soccer, for all
its success this year, continues to trail its big brother.
</P>
<P>
   Until women's soccer gains more of a foothold in its own world
federation, the U.S. players can't afford to put growing their bank
accounts ahead of growing the game.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, pardon us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about money,'' Hamm said.
</P>
<P>
   From the mouths of Babes, isn't that what David Letterman would
say?
</P>
<P>
   When Hamm says it's not about the money, it can mean only one
thing: Women's soccer reached its goal. It's now like all the other
professional sports. &QL; 
!hair! &QL; 
!ital!
</P>
<P>
   Karen Crouse's column appears in the Daily News four days a
week. She can be reached at (818) 713-3619.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
