A8212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-24 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John P.Lopez
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT is becoming sadly apparent that the Astros not only are moving
their Double-A farm club from Jackson, Miss., to Round Rock next
season.
</P>
<P>
   They also are taking a good chunk of what a season ago would
have been Triple-A talent to Enron Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton and Derek Bell to the Mets for Octavio Dotel, Roger
Cedeno and a long-shot pitching prospect?
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a line from someone whom Astros owner Drayton McLane
Jr. might today resemble: Bah, humbug.
</P>
<P>
   This was a deal only McLane could love. It was an $11 million
salary chop at a time when McLane already knows he'll reap a
windfall from his new stadium's revenues and merchandising provided
by the Astros' new logo.
</P>
<P>
   McLane definitely will get his. But Astros fans are getting
lumps of coal compared to the gems that took the field a season
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gone to the Mets is a warrior of a lefthander and an outfielder
in Bell who, while flaky, drove in at least 108 runs in two of the
past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Astros fans get only more promises and potential, albeit great
potential. Astros fans get only more talk of getting younger and
looking to the future.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard it all before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we heard it when another recently departed star, Carl
Everett, arrived in Houston in 1997. We also heard it in 1993 when
Hampton arrived from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   After developing Everett and Hampton into arguably the best two
players on the team in 1999, the Astros shipped them off to two of
baseball's big clubs at the ripe old ages of 28 and 27,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In putting their spin on this deal with the Mets, the Astros
told us they were happy they could become younger and still put
terrific talents such as Dotel and Cedeno on the field for the 2000
season.
</P>
<P>
   No argument here. Dotel is quite the prospect, with a live arm,
good breaking stuff and much potential. There's that word again.
Potential.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno will step in and provide the best speed on the club. He
also should fill the ever-important No. 2 spot on manager Larry
Dierker's lineup card and likely cover lots of ground in center
field at the Gashouse.
</P>
<P>
   Both players could become stars. But then what? More
cost-cutting? More promises and potential?
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you cut it, Thursday's deal, coupled with the
previous cost-cutting deal that sent Everett to the Red Sox,
signaled the Astros' admission that they are like so many other
mid-market teams. They are little more than a glorified farm team
for the big clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The difference here is that the Astros promised more. They
brought in Randy Johnson two seasons ago and sold fans on what
looked like a dogged pursuit of a world championship. They brought
in Moises Alou and put together a murderous pitching staff that
revolved around Hampton and Jose Lima.
</P>
<P>
   They collectively marched to McLane's mantra: What have you done
today to become a champion?
</P>
<P>
   But today, instead of marching they are stepping gingerly
through the offseason, slashing salary and all but slashing their
championship ring fingers clean off.
</P>
<P>
   After boldly winning a third consecutive NL Central title in
1999, they are slipping back to mediocrity and promising only hope.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Cedeno could become a special player in the future _
there's that word again _ there is no ignoring that he is anything
but the complete package and joins a team loaded with outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Dotel could be a great pitcher someday _ yet again,
there's that ``someday'' _ he possessed a pedestrian 5.38 ERA and
had bouts with wildness last season.
</P>
<P>
   It will not be a horrible Astros team in 2000, but it will be
hard-pressed to contend for the division title. Jeff Bagwell and
Craig Biggio alone should keep the team at or slightly above .500,
but that's still taking a step backward.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 Astros outfield does not figure to be as productive as
a season ago. The left side of the infield, with the light-hitting
Tim Bogar at shortstop and the injury-riddled, 36-year-old Ken
Caminiti at third, could be a question. Catching duties are up in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   And the pitching staff just lost its No. 1 man, a lefthander,
replaced by a righthander who in 2000 figures to be the No. 3
starter at best.
</P>
<P>
   There was much medication dished out by Astros brass in the wake
of Thursday's painful trade, everyone putting on happy faces and
hoping fans wouldn't recognize what this trade was all about.
</P>
<P>
   It was about getting worse instead of better. It was about more
promises and potential.
</P>
<P>
   The only hope now is that Dotel and Cedeno someday will fulfill
their potential. Then again, by that time they'll probably be
shipped off to one of the big clubs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
