<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WINS IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAIE, Hawaii _ It began with a turnover. Then he missed a layup.
A few minutes later, he clanked a short turnaround, a swooping hook
and another chippie. At that point, early in the second half, UCLA
forward Jerome Moiso figured out the best remedy for his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wondered if I should keep shooting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Bruins, Moiso didn't listen to himself.
Instead, he regained his composure and turned on his talent just in
(over)time to lead UCLA to a much-needed 103-98 victory over South
Florida on Thursday in the Pearl Harbor Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Through baskets and assists, Moiso accounted for nine of UCLA's
15 overtime points. His sensational baseline dunk energized the
Bruins early, and his difficult turnaround with 43 seconds left
helped clinch the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it,'' said Moiso, who scored 20 points and grabbed
eight rebounds. ``Dan (Gadzuric) was in foul trouble. (Actually,
Gadzuric had fouled out.) I was the only big guy in there. I had to
keep it going.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso's heroics, combined with timely shooting by point guard
Earl Watson, enabled the Bruins (6-2) to claim third place in this
fourth-rate tournament. (Colorado State beat San Jose State for the
title.)
</P>
<P>
   Always the spinmeisters, they reveled in their resiliency
following Wednesday's loss to Colorado State. They basked in their
late-game execution, and they treated it like an NCAA Tournament
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about how much we should win by, we just
needed a win,'' Watson said. ``This is the type of loss that could
have ended our season.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the tournament draw had more to do with the outcome
than UCLA's performance. While Colorado State used the
Gonzaga-esque approach and forced the Bruins to play a half-court
game, South Florida, much like DePaul, removed the shackles and let
them gallop.
</P>
<P>
   This was an offseason pickup game in the Men's Gym against
out-of-shape NBA players _ full of fast breaks and bad shots, with
little defense and no structure.
</P>
<P>
   It was an ABA game without the red, white and blue ball _ more
dunks and alley-oops than screens and bounce passes.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was perfect for the fun-and-gun Bruins. They
scored as many points in the freewheeling first half against USF as
they did in 40 grinding minutes against impeccably-prepared
Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obviously a wild game, one of the more wild ones I've
been involved in,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``But it was
probably just the remedy we needed coming off (Wednesday) night.
The tempo and pace was more to our liking.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, without Moiso's overtime brilliance, they'd have lost
for the third time in five games.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA appeared to take command with seven minutes left when
freshman Jason Kapono buried two 3-pointers from the left corner _
the exact spot from which Kapono missed the game-winner against
Colorado State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stays with you, but it's not the kind of thing I wanted
to dwell on,'' said Kapono, who scored 17 points. ``I've taken big
shots before.''
</P>
<P>
   The baskets gave UCLA an 80-72 lead, but it didn't last. South
Florida countered with a 12-2 spurt as the Bruins committed four
turnovers in seven possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Moiso's free throws steadied UCLA, then Watson drained a
3-pointer for an 88-85 advantage with 17 seconds left. Nonplused _
and wide open _ Bulls forward B.B. Waldon responded with a
3-pointer from the right wing to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins scored first when Moiso found Ryan Bailey for a lay
up. A few minutes later, Moiso spun to the left baseline and
elevated for a jam over South Florida center Scott Johnson. On the
ensuing possession, Moiso hit Matt Barnes for a lay-up to give the
Bruins a 99-93 lead.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-point play by South Florida's Altron Jackson,
Moiso sealed the victory with a masterful turnaround from 12 feet
as the shot clock expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had lost today,'' he said, shaking his head, ``I
wouldn't have wanted to play anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
