<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIET YEAR IN TV SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As long as you're no longer astonished by what the networks pay
for sports, 1999 was a pretty benign year in TV sports.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from heaving $17.6 billion at the cleats of the NFL, the
networks went to the money trough again to pay NASCAR ($4.2
billion), the NCAA ($6.2 billion) and Major League Baseball ($800
million) for the rights to their games. Leagues and teams now view
the networks as their own personal ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   The interesting stuff in the contracts were the terms and years.
CBS' contract for the NCAA basketball tournament wasn't up until
2003, but it went ahead and signed an 11-year extension anyway.
NASCAR was the hot property of the late '90s, but it hardly has the
kind of track record that warrants Fox committing to eight years of
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   And CBS' NCAA deal includes Internet rights. If all the
e-soothsayers are right about the promise and reach of the net,
this could be the best deal of the third millennium. A look back at
the good, bad and Gray on the tube in 1999:
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Hottest trend: (end) Ignoring the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from an uptick in NFL Nielsens and white-hot NASCAR
numbers, ratings for sports events remain in decline. But that's no
longer the big concern of the networks. As they continue to lose
market share to cable, satellite and the Internet, they are
gravitating to one-time events that can carry a day (or week) or
those aimed at a select demographic group.
</P>
<P>
   Sports fills both needs. So while Fox may not get super-duper
ratings from the World Series, it will win the ratings showdown for
a week or two, deliver males with wallets to advertisers, and have
a platform to promote its latest lousy animated series.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Worst trend: (end) News show repeats.
</P>
<P>
   When FSN decided to build its main late show at 10 p.m., ESPN
responded by adding an extra SportsCenter at the same time. All
this does, though, is stack one news wheel atop the other with
little differential, making the viewer feel like he's in Bill
Murray's ``Groundhog Day.''
</P>
<P>
   FSN gets a flick on the fist, too, for too often airing the same
news show on both West outlets. That's cheating the viewer, not to
mention the cable companies paying for two outlets.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Biggest loser: (end) The fine folk at Disney.
</P>
<P>
   Already paying the biggest NFL tariff ($1.1 billion a year for
ABC and ESPN), Disney surrendered in its legal battle with baseball
over Sunday night games, to the tune of $800 million over six
years. It even paid baseball a $125 million signing bonus as part
of the settlement. Did Kevin Malone negotiate this deal?
</P>
<P>
   ABC also lost the Triple Crown series to NBC, and ESPN lost its
part of the NASCAR deal. ABC kept the Indy 500, but it's damaged
goods. Keith Jackson's retirement u-turn shined a negative light on
Disney management, the Monday Night Football booth was trimmed to
two in an economy move, and the network that set the standard for
sports coverage under Roone Arledge won only one Emmy in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Biggest winner: (end) Fox Sports Net, for hiring
Keith Olbermann.
</P>
<P>
   The K.O. Kid rubs some viewers wrong, but he's a credible voice
in a jungle full of screaming banshees. One only has to look at the
wasteland of empty-headed, fratboy SportsCenter anchors trying to
fill his earpiece to judge his impact. The whole SportsCenter gig
has become such a double-edged putty knife -- must see, but
virtually unwatchable -- that Olbermann's old tag-team partner, Dan
Patrick, has moved to the highbrow world (!?!) of radio sports
talk.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Best programming: (end) That would be ESPN's
SportsCentury series, mainly the 50 profiles produced by Mark
Shapiro. The episodes were fresh and fleshed out with details of
the athlete's less-heroic or less-endearing moments or traits, like
Martina Navratilova's homosexuality, Bill Russell's aloofness, and
Carl Lewis' lack of U.S. status.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Worst programming: (end) ESPN Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what can happen when a good idea falls into the wrong
hands. When it was merely Classic Sports Network, the events aired
were indeed vintage, classic or events that had slipped under the
radar.
</P>
<P>
   But since ESPN bought the network, it has degenerated. Just
because the ABC library is now available doesn't mean viewers want
to watch vintage 1962 barrel jumping, a random minor bowl game from
the early '90s, or hackneyed theme shows.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Best comeback: (end) Marvelous Marv Albert.
</P>
<P>
   After being banished for more than a year after his sexual
assault case, Albert slowly began earning his career back a piece
at a time, until finally this week regaining his role as NBC's No.
1 NBA play-by-play man.
</P>
<P>
   On the sports totem pole of transgressions against society,
Albert's sin was minor. I know people who were more mortified to
learn Albert likes show tunes than rough sex. But Albert's
appearance on Letterman this week was a too-jolly flashback to his
pre-assault days. It had a bad vibe.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Best moment: (end) The women's World Cup final game,
which earned an 11.4 Nielsen rating and shocked all of the jaded
suits who believe men won't watch women's sports. The success of
the event underscores that the sports audience is anxious for
something fresh.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Worst moment: (end) Jim Gray's interview of Pete Rose
during the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   It was a unanimous choice, and a fitting subtext to what TV
sports reporting is all about. The most useless species is the
sideline reporter, whose job it is to fetch a coherent 10-second
sound byte and act earnest in the process. In the history of the
genre, there hasn't been a single clairvoyant moment of great TV
sideline sleuthing, except maybe the day John Dockery returned some
trash heaped on him by Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   Gray's attack was pre-meditated, which made it wrong, and he
wouldn't let it go, which made it worse. And the essence of his
question could have been asked in a way that would have delivered a
portrait of Pete Rose, man in denial. Instead, we got Pete Rose,
the victim.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I hope NBC promotes Gray to ``Dateline'' and sends
sends him to Colombia, where he could roll out some of his tough
questions for the drug cartel.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Honorable mention: (end) HBO's ``Real Sports'' and
ESPN's ``Outside the Lines,'' beacons of the business ... NBC's NBA
trio of Tom Hammond, Bill Walton and Steve Jones, maybe the best
three-man booth ever. If nothing else, they have fun ... Jim Rome,
for the consistency of his talk show and growing profile of ``The
Last Word.'' ... Tiger Woods, for his Nike ``bouncing ball''
commercial, which was merely the best performance of the year.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold Dishonorable mention: (end) NBC's poor handling of
CBS-bound Dick Enberg, who deserved better for all he's done for
the network. Enberg graciously stepped away from events he wanted,
baseball play-by-play and Olympic studio host, for the good of the
network. When he merely wanted to finish his career as a NFL
announcer, the network dissed him ... Norman Esiason, the most
annoying thing on TV since the infomercial ... Ahmad Rashad ...
ESPN's hockey production team, because Brett Hull's skate is still
in the crease ... FSN, for its rude gassing of president Kitty
Cohen ... KTLA, for the Eddie Arnold/Claudia Trejos debacle ...
KXTA (1540 AM), for firing Joe MacDonnell ...
</P>
<P>
   (set rest 8 pt)
</P>
<P>
   AND NOW THE NEWS -- USC has settled its lawsuit with former
announcers Larry Kahn and Mike Lamb ... ESPN Classic airs a
Muhammad Ali marathon on Christmas day, and it will air all 50
SportsCentury profiles back-to-back and so on Jan. 1-2. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
