<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, Dec. 24.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-SUBURBS (Mayville, South Africa) _ The modest one-room
houses in this fledgling black suburb are the most tangible symbol
of the post-apartheid government's commitment to redressing South
Africa's stark inequalities. And the changing lives within the
brick walls offer an intimate view of the hopes and hardships of
ordinary black people still struggling to climb the economic and
social ladder. By Rachel Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-MUDSLIDES (Caracas) _ Coping with the flood/landslide
disaster has been hampered by fact that Venezuela is between
constitutions and political systems. Supporters of President Chavez
like him even more for the way he has handled things; his opponents
dislike him even more for the way he has handled things. By Larry
Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-CREW-MAYOR (New York) _ As recently as last week, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani was grudgingly content to leave the fate of his
former friend, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, in the hands of the
seven members of the Board of Education. After all, the mayor is on
the verge of declaring his candidacy for the Senate and needs
stability. But in recent days, people close to the issue say,
Giuliani became fed up with the long-playing Rudy Crew psychodrama
and let it be known that the chancellor's ouster would make a fine
Christmas present. By Dan Barry.
</P>
<P>
   CRUISE-WORKERS (Miami) _ These are boom times for the cruise
industry. Record numbers of passengers are packing bigger and
grander ships. Miami-based Carnival Corp. is averaging $2.8 million
a day in profits this year, almost all tax-free because the company
is registered in Panama. But the benefits have been slow to trickle
down to the 70,000 or so workers who keep the fleets running and
passengers dining and dancing. Although living conditions have
improved, pay for most has risen little, and some workers say their
work has become more grueling as ships have grown into floating
cities bustling with activity 24 hours a day. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-DAVIES (Undated) _ John Paton Davies, a leading diplomat
who was among the ``old China hands'' driven from the State
Department after Sen. Joseph McCarthy questioned their loyalty and
labeled them Communist sympathizers in the 1950s, died at his home
in Asheville, N.C. He was 91. By Michael T. Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-TRENDS (Undated) _ Online holiday shopping is
increasingly gnawing at the business of traditional retailers this
year, with preliminary indications that seasonal Internet sales may
nearly triple over last year. A New York Times/CBS poll Dec. 17-19
found that 17 percent of Americans said they have bought gifts over
the Internet this holiday season or planned to do so. Only 7
percent said they had shopped for holiday gifts online last year.
By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   BANKS-VENTURE-CAPITAL (Undated) _ Since 1996, major commercial
banks have tripled the money they devote to venture capital, the
high-risk, high-return world of financing companies before they go
public. The appeal of venture capital is obvious. Banks are happy
to get 8 percent interest on a typical loan, while the average
venture capital investment in a new company almost doubled this
year. But as banks move deeper into venture capital, they face some
risks. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   INDEXES-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ This is a tale of two
economies and of the intertwined stock markets that track them. The
more exciting of the economies is the Internet-driven
high-technology model. That is the economy that has caused the
Nasdaq composite index to leap 48 percent in 10 weeks. But the
other economy _ the old non-Internet one that still accounts for
most economic activity _ is starting to slow, and many of the
stocks in it are weak. By Floyd Norris.
