<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STANFORD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CARDINAL RULES OFF THE FIELD, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's known as Quarterback U, but a list of Stanford football
heroes who went on to greatness after graduation might include
names other than Jim Plunkett, John Elway and John Brodie.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the accomplishments of doctor Joe St. Geme, businessman
Hilary Shockley and attorney John Sande III. The truth of the
matter is that while the list of prominent former Stanford players
includes a Heisman Trophy winner, Rose Bowl MVPs and All-Americans,
it also includes doctors, lawyers and bankers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Stanford tradition,'' said Cardinal quarterback Todd
Husak, whose team will face Wisconsin in the Rose Bowl Jan. 1.
``When they recruit you they tell you that academics are going to
play a big part in your college life here.''
</P>
<P>
   The academic tradition is so powerful it once threatened to kill
the now-vibrant football program, Plunkett recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best proof that academic and athletic traditions can
stand hand-in-hand is Cardinal receiver Troy Walters. A 1999
first-team Academic All-American, Walters will graduate Stanford
with a 3.2 GPA. He chose to attend Stanford in large part because
of its reputation as one of the most prestigious universities in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was very important to me and to my parents,'' Walters
said. ``There are skills and talents that you need in life not only
in football, but in the classroom too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sande III, a prominent Nevada attorney who was Stanford's center
in the 1971 Rose Bowl, said he came to the university for an
education first, and to play football second.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I went there,'' he said. ``I always had it in the
back of my mind that academics was important. You could get
injured, or you might not be as good in college as you were in high
school, so getting a degree was important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   After his graduation in 1971, Sande attended Harvard Law School
before returning to his hometown of Reno. His son, John Sande IV,
is the Cardinal's long snapper this season.
</P>
<P>
   Several Stanford players have gone on to impressive careers in
the law. James Urkopina, a Stanford letterman in 1957 and 1958, is
now a member of the university's Board of Trustees. Rodney Gilmore
practices law in the Bay Area and works as a television commentator
for ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   As for doctors, Don Bunce, who helped lead Stanford to a Pac-8
championship and the 1972 Rose Bowl, is a graduate of the Stanford
Medical School and works as an orthopedic surgeon at the Palo Alto
Medical Foundation. St. Geme, a member of the 1980 Cardinal squad,
is an assistant professor of pediatrics at the Washington
University School of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Shockley, a member of the 1971 and 1972 Rose Bowl teams, is
president of his own company A/R Capital. Randy Vataha, an
all-conference receiver in 1970, earns his living as chief
executive officer of Game Plan Inc., an investment banking company
for professional sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take away from other teams,'' said Cardinal head coach
Tyrone Willingham, ``but Stanford is probably the premier
university in combining quality athletics and quality academics.
This is a program that has the ability to be the best... the
members of this team have traversed a very difficult terrain and
persevered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 0123EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
