<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-ADVICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOSE OF BUDGETING CURES HEADACHES FROM HOLIDAY SPENDING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Jason Takenouchi  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The average holiday shopping binge only lasts a
few weeks, but the financial baggage can stretch well into the next
millennium if you aren't careful.
</P>
<P>
   Credit counselors agree that smart spending is the key to
getting your financial house in order and keeping out of the red.
But for erstwhile overspenders who are already in financial straits
-- with a pile of overdue bills alongside those nicely wrapped
gifts -- more extreme steps may be in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing for the after-holiday spending blues is to sit
down and work out a budget,'' said Dave Matheny, public relations
director for the nonprofit Credit Counseling Centers of America.
``The biggest thing is to focus on where the money is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Your budget should include all your expenses, including food,
transportation, utilities and movie rentals.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive budget is only the first step, though. Further
debt management measures recommended by credit counselors include:
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!Find out how much you owe.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might seem obvious, but often people don't want to open
up their bills and face them,'' said Jennifer Root, public
relations director for the nonprofit Consumer Credit Counseling
Service of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!When you write your budget, be sure to include obligations
that only come once or twice a year. That will help prepare you car
registration payments, taxes or other big expenses down the road.
</P>
<P>
   !bbox!If you have a lot of credit card debt, try to make more
than just the minimum payments.
</P>
<P>
   According to CCCS-LA, it can take more than 16 years of minimum
payments to pay the average household's $840 in holiday spending.
Even a sturdy plastic Santa won't last that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people feel like if they're paying the minimum, that's
good,'' Root said. ``In reality, that really isn't OK.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Find places to cut back until your finances recover. Brown
bag lunches may not be prestigious, but they will save you money.
</P>
<P>
   -- Get help if you need it. Several nonprofit agencies offer
free credit counseling, and most are listed in the phone book. Be
sure to ask if the agency is accredited.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you're having problems making payments, talk it over with
your creditors. They probably don't want you to go bankrupt,
either, and they may be willing to alter your payment schedule or
interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   -- Don't expect instant results. If it took you a few years to
amass your debt, that same debt won't go away overnight.
</P>
<P>
   But budgeting doesn't have to be all doom and gloom.
</P>
<P>
   ``As part of your budget, just like you pay utility bills of a
mortgage, pay an amount to yourself,'' Matheny said. After your
finances are in order, that money should be used as a reward --
such as a vacation or special purchase -- that will make all the
austerity worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the idea of holding off now for something bigger or
better in the future,'' Matheny said.
</P>
<P>
   Once your finances are in a semblance of order, you can get to
work on repairing your credit.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are that if you missed payments or paid bills late, your
credit report will reflect that for several years. Those black
marks could hurt your chances to get a loan or finance a major
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   You can improve your credit with a little discipline, though.
Some advice from the experts:
</P>
<P>
   -- The best way to boost your credit is by proving your
worthiness. Bring your payments up to date and pay your bills on
time.
</P>
<P>
   -- In general, avoid credit repair companies. Credit counselors
say most of the services offered by such companies are available
for free elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   -- Build an emergency fund. If disaster strikes, you can draw
down the fund instead of getting into deeper debt. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
