<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-SIXERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS DEFEAT 76ERS, 99-94 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Kendall Gill is one of Don Casey's
favorite players in the National Basketball Association. Gill is
also a close friend to Casey, the New Jersey Nets' coach. But that
did not stop Casey from wincing, praying and crossing his fingers
when Gill received a pass from Kerry Kittles with 14 seconds left
in Thursday night's game against the Philadelphia 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets were holding on to a slippery 2-point lead, and Gill
was clearly about to hoist a wide-open 21-foot jump shot from the
right corner. With Gill being far from a great outside shooter and
Philadelphia's Allen Iverson playing phenomenally, the chances of a
miss and subsequent heart-wrenching loss to the hated 76ers were
good. And Casey knew it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't been shooting well and I was saying to myself, `If
there's a God and he's fair and let us assume that he came from
Africa or Egypt, it will go in,''' Casey said moments after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The shot indeed went in and gave the Nets the cushion they
needed to pull out a 99-94 victory over Philadelphia, the team
coached by the dreaded Larry Brown and John Calipari and led by
Iverson's dazzling 42-point performance.
</P>
<P>
   There was great symbolism in Gill's hitting the final shot,
particularly from a spot just a few feet in front of Brown. In
preseason comments about Calipari's firing last season as head
coach of the Nets, Brown, a longtime friend of Calipari, implied
that Gill was unprofessional and a problem player who conspired
with Jayson Williams, General Manager John Nash, the team president
Michael Rowe and Casey to have Calipari ousted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was apropos,'' Casey said of Gill's shot. ``The guy blasted
him in the paper, and he shoots a game-winner right in front of
him. It's very dramatic. For that, I feel good for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Casey also felt good for himself. He had not been left
untouched by Brown, who was ejected in the 76ers' first trip to the
Meadowlands on Nov. 20 only to have Calipari take over and lead
Philadelphia to a humiliating 100-96 victory. At the time, the Nets
were foundering at 1-9, and Casey seemed on the verge of being
fired. While both Brown and Calipari denied planning that turn of
events, almost everyone associated with the Nets believes it was
staged. So after hitting the final shot tonight, Gill yelled some
choice words at Brown while walking toward the Nets' bench during a
timeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you what I was saying, but it was in the heat of
the moment,'' Gill said. ``It wasn't Merry Christmas or Happy New
Year.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Nets broke the huddle, Gill and Casey shared a few
words, a smile and a hug on the sideline before Gill returned to
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time they were here, we thought that Larry Brown got
thrown out of the game on purpose so that Cal could coach them,''
Gill said in explaining his impromptu chitchat with Casey. ``They
knew that we were struggling at that time. So this time, I told
Case that that was his Christmas present from me. He bought me a
money clip, and I got him a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill's success in the clutch epitomized his improved play
lately. While struggling earlier in the season, he missed a similar
wide-open jumper in the closing moments of a 96-92 loss at
Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I had the opportunity to hit the shot,'' said Gill,
who had 10 of his 11 points in the second half. ``Everybody thinks
I can't shoot, but you can't score 10,000 points in this league
without being able to shoot. This was the biggest shot for me all
year and this was our biggest win because we beat the guys that
smashed us in the newspapers. I think we have sort of a rivalry
going with them now, since we're so close and Cal is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this was the best victory for us this year, period.
Scratch all the rest of them. This one really meant something to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nets started with playoff intensity and effectiveness,
leading by as many as 14 points in the first half and taking a
53-43 lead at halftime. They headed into the fourth quarter ahead
by 74-64 when Philadelphia began its charge.
</P>
<P>
   With Iverson, who made 11 of 26 field-goal attempts and 17 of 20
free throws over all, scoring 6 points, the 76ers moved within
82-81 with six minutes left. But Jamie Feick nailed a 21-footer,
then followed a layup by Keith Van Horn (25 points, 12 rebounds)
with a great midair assist to push the Nets' lead back to 89-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kendall's shot, Feick's pass and Feick's rebound were the
three biggest plays of the game and every game, you have to have
three big plays and those were them,'' said Stephon Marbury, who
joined Kerry Kittles with 21 points for the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   But the 76ers would not die quickly. They pulled within 96-94 on
two free throws by Iverson with 1 minute 14 seconds left, and
seemed ready to crush the Nets again until Gill received the pass,
made the shot and ruined their plans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
