<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-WIZARDS-ROCKETS-H     12-24 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WIZARDS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Cuttino Mobley heard those words again, and after so many nights of
profanity, he sought to clean up the locker-room language.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rockets stared into the face of their biggest problem and
whipped it, pulling away down the stretch for a 105-89 win over the
Washington Wizards on Thursday before 14,841 at Compaq Center.
Mobley keyed the late run and finished with 20 points, his third
consecutive night of scoring 20 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, there was one last bit of unfinished business.
</P>
<P>
   ``How about let's just stop talking about the fourth quarter?''
he said. ``How about that? Then you won't have to think about it.
Is that better?''
</P>
<P>
   But with a few more games like Thursday's, those ugly words went
from vulgar to poetry. The final quarter went from weakness to
strength. And there was little doubt what was different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I forgot all about it,'' Rockets guard Steve Francis said. ``I
didn't even think about the fourth quarter until way into it.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their other problems in the calamitous early season, the
Rockets had fallen 10 games on the wrong side of .500 largely
because of their inability to win the fourth quarter. In the
previous four games, the Rockets had averaged just 16.5 points on
30.5-percent shooting in the fourth quarter. They had managed just
11 points in two of their previous three fourth quarters, their
worst scoring periods of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game on the line Thursday, the Rockets took command
down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Francis said of the fast finish. ``I was
really excited and happy we had a chance to do that. It started at
the beginning of the fourth quarter _ we recognized we just have to
continue playing the way we've been playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Matt Bullard nailed a 3-pointer, his fourth of the game,
to push the lead to seven. Suddenly, shooters who had been missing
were on target. Tough fast-break drives that in previous games had
produced blown layups were successful Thursday. And when the
Rockets needed to come up with the stops to take control of the
game, they held the Wizards to one field goal in a 5:17 stretch of
the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Francis had made four of 14 shots when Bryce Drew passed to him
at the top of the key. Francis immediately nailed a trey. Drew
pulled up for a jumper and a nine-point lead. Mobley hit a pair of
free throws. Kenny Thomas added another. And when Mobley stripped
Mitch Richmond, he took off on a fast break, drawing a foul from
Michael Smith for a three-point play and a 90-78 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley found Kelvin Cato inside for a dunk, and the Rockets had
their largest lead, 93-78, with 4:49 left, completing a 13-4 run.
But the Rockets maintained they were better down the stretch
because they had executed more expertly all game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been practicing well on this,'' Cato said. ``We're
getting time to practice and practice. We ran the plays it took to
win the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did not shoot well most of the night. They made just
43.8 percent of their shots. But the Rockets, the most
turnover-prone team in the NBA, had just 13. Of their 35 field
goals, 25 came on assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is stuff we've been working on, but I think we're getting
better at running all the different sets that we now have and it's
really helping our offense,'' Bullard said. ``We were able to get a
big win tonight _ win by a lot of points _ and I think guys are
getting into the offense. They're getting into the right places
earlier, and we're running the plays a lot crisper.''
</P>
<P>
   The best example might have been the last play of the decisive
fourth-quarter run, when Mobley drew a defender to him inside, then
found Cato. One game after Mobley was so critical of himself for
failing to effectively pass in traffic, he had five assists, three
on penetrations that ended with a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just basketball,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.
``That's reading the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullard had a season-high 16 points, making six of 11 shots and
four of six treys. Cato had 20 points in 39 minutes off the bench
and matched his career high with 12 rebounds. Thomas had 10
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Francis, struggling with his shot much of the night _ he made
one of his first nine attempts _ had 11 assists without a turnover
and came on late to finish with 16 points. He left the court in the
final two minutes when his back stiffened, but the problem was
considered minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bullard got us off to a good start,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I
thought the bench gave us a tremendous lift. A lot of guys played
well. I loved to see 13 turnovers for eight points. That's such a
big difference. I thought we did a pretty good job containing
(guard Rod) Strickland. Cato was active. Cuttino was outstanding.
And Steve, 11 assists. There were a lot of contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they ignored the arrival of the fourth quarter, they
played one worth remembering.
</P>
</TEXT>
