<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS DEFEAT KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With more creative shuffling of the deck than
usual, a fistful of jokers can beat three Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who historically provide more talk-show punch
lines than the Clinton administration, survived a three-pronged
assault from Chris Webber (33 points), Corliss Williamson and Jason
Williams to hand Sacramento a 97-91 defeat Thursday night before
14,315 fans at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (8-18) prolonged assistant coach Jim Todd's winning
streak (two) that began Wednesday night in Oakland when head coach
Chris Ford surrendered to lower back spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Hudson was their trump card against the Kings with 16
points, 10 assists and six rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the unofficial and typical conspiracy of
less-than-equitable officiating, the Clippers had to deal with
Lamar Odom jumping on the illness bandwagon. The rookie forward had
13 points, nine rebounds and four blocks, but accomplished these
numbers with rising flu symptoms. He attracted his second and
disqualifying technical foul at 7:48 left to play and the Clippers
juggling an 84-77 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Maurice Taylor, who missed the Golden State game with
an assist from the flu, returned at less than peak efficiency but
rallied for 14 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (14-10), who usually are more dangerous in transition
than Lon Chaney, almost did themselves in by coughing up 15
turnovers in the first half. Much of their technical difficulty was
registered by Williams, the flashiest thing we've seen out of
Sacramento since Jerry Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Williams seemed more interested in trotting out his considerable
razzle-dazzle than efficiently slicing through the Clipper defense.
And Williams, who may be a bigger defensive liability than your
cousin Vinny, was butchered by Clipper Troy Hudson (12 points and
six assists in the first half).
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's deadly subs the self-aware Bench Mob were
out-mobbed by the Clippers two-man gang of Keith Closs and Charles
Jones. Closs had nine points, six rebounds and two blocks in relief
of center Michael Olowokandi, while Jones had 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   With Webber spanking them for 13 points, the Clippers trailed,
29-22, after one quarter. But with Hudson smoking Williams and his
caddy former Clipper Darrick Martin the Clippers outscored the
Kings, 29-16, in round two and took a 51-45 lead at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento cut into the lead by two in the third quarter, but
the Clips endured another Webber salvo to grab the win, their
fourth in six games.
</P>
<P>
   CLIPPERS NOTES: Todd, when pressed Friday for an ETA on Ford's
return, said, ``I was hoping for tonight.'' Oh, he doesn't mind the
responsibility of being in charge, but also appreciates the
expectations. ``It's a little different sitting in that seat. But
really, my job is to be an extension of the head coach.'' ... Since
Ford has been in L.A., Closs by poor choices on and off the court
has held down the job of heating up the bench. But Wednesday night
in Oakland, the 7-foot-3 backup center took advantage of the
diminished roster to earn 20 minutes, producing 10 points and eight
rebounds. ``It felt great being able to get up off the bench and
made positive contributions on the court ... get in the other
team's way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
