<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SHOPLIFT-HOLIDAYS-SFC     12-24 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPLIFT-HOLIDAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. STORES SAY HOLIDAYS ARE BOOM TIMES FOR SHOPLIFTERS  
 
 
 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID LAZARUS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ 'Tis the season for sticky fingers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   While San Francisco retailers are enjoying robust sales as
Christmas fast approaches, they also say that shoplifting is
rampant in their stores.
</P>
<P>
   And, with varying degrees of resignation, they say there's
little they can do to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to assume that everyone who walks into the store
is a potential shoplifter,'' said Angela Coffey, merchandising
manager at the J. Crew outlet in the downtown San Francisco
Shopping Centre. ``You try and watch them all, but it's not always
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to pick your battles,'' she said. ``You're not going
to worry about $10 hair accessories when you have $200 cashmere
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then _ and this is something most retailers don't want you
to know _ the unwritten rule is that if a shoplifter makes it out
the door with an item, it's pretty much history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told not to chase,'' Coffey said. ``It's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, shoplifting has been in decline in recent years.
According to the San Francisco Police Department, there were 2,996
reported incidents in 1996, 2,788 in 1997 and 2,467 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, merchants, business groups, the district
attorney's office and even the police say shoplifting is on the
rise. The only thing that is down, they say, is the number of shops
actually reporting thefts to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many retailers have made the determination that it's not cost
effective to seek prosecution,'' said Bruce Van Kleeck, vice
president of the National Retail Federation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to pull people off the job for court
appearances and paperwork,'' he said. ``It's a business decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchants also say that in some cases stores fear being hit by a
lawsuit if the suspected shoplifter insists that an honest mistake
was made.
</P>
<P>
   For many merchants, a certain degree of theft _ or ``inventory
shrinkage'' in retail-industry parlance _ is simply accepted as the
price of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   It is the flip side of the booming U.S. economy. More money in
circulation compels merchants to place more items on the floor to
attract shoppers. But more items on the floor also make for a more
tempting target for those disposed to take a five-finger discount.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Johnson, a spokesman for the San Francisco district
attorney's office, said shoplifting is ``way up'' this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it up, the shoplifters are getting bolder,'' he
said. ``They're walking out with bigger and bigger items. There's
no attempt to conceal. They just grab them and walk.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager of one store in the San Francisco Shopping Centre,
who requested anonymity, observed that shoplifters are growing
bolder because they know that the consequences of being caught are
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shoplifters know the laws better than the merchants,'' he
said. ``They know that even if they get arrested, they'll be out in
two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   He glanced around his own shop, an outlet for a national
clothing chain. There was no guard on duty, no cameras visible on
the walls or ceiling. There weren't even security tags on the
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had guys who took things, got caught, and three hours
later they were back,'' the store manager said. ``You just can't do
anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on whether the store is interested in
cooperating,'' said Jim Deignan, a spokesman for the Police
Department. Some retailers, he said, have declined to pursue
arrests even when a shoplifter has been caught red-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be running from store to store all day if shoplifting did
get reported,'' said Officer Al Melendez, who patrols Union Square.
``But it doesn't. The actual amount of shoplifting going on _ I
can't even imagine the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Melendez cited the example of a repeat offender that he called
``Pockmark Face.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy goes to Brooks Brothers three times a week,''
Melendez said. ``Each time, he grabs a stack of shirts and runs out
of the store. The salespeople never report it.''
</P>
<P>
   All merchants interviewed said stores in downtown San Francisco
are hit more frequently by slick ``professional'' shoplifters as
opposed to teenagers making off with small items.
</P>
<P>
   They said shoplifters will typically case a store several times
to gauge the level of security. ``If the shoplifter sees a lot of
new faces among the staff, they'll feel more confident,'' one store
manager said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also see more of them working in teams, where one will make
a distraction while the other takes items,'' she said. ``Or they
come in with an entire family and pass the items to a child. We're
not going to accuse a 5-year-old child.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Wallace, president of the Bay Area Better Business Bureau,
agreed that shoplifters are growing more sophisticated in their
methods as stores struggle to keep pace by adopting more advanced
security measures.
</P>
<P>
   While the Bay Area bureau has yet to study shoplifting in
detail, the nationwide Council of Better Business Bureaus points to
a recent study commissioned by the Louisville, Ky., branch.
</P>
<P>
   It found that U.S. businesses lose an estimated $16 billion a
year to shoplifting, and that one-third of all new enterprises fail
because of retail theft (often committed by employees).
</P>
<P>
   It also found that while adolescents account for nearly half of
all shoplifting, they make off with only a third as much as their
adult counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Mattingly, president of the Louisville Better Business
Bureau, said many stores are responding by investing in additional
cameras, electronic sensors and security personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these things are expensive,'' he said, ``and consumers end
up paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattingly estimated that as much as 3 percent of an item's
retail cost reflects the store's security expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of stores at the San Francisco Shopping Centre
employ their own guards. Most rely instead on salespeople keeping
an eye out for potential shoplifters.
</P>
<P>
   At American Eagle Outfitters on the ground floor, a display
table full of colorful fleece pullovers sits just inside the
entrance. A thief could be out the door with one in just two steps.
</P>
<P>
   Cheyenne Santos, whose blue blazer and gray slacks instantly
mark him as a security guard, said he watches customers' eyes and
hands, ``and the way they come in and touch things.''
</P>
<P>
   But if one of those customers suddenly grabbed an item and
bolted for the door, he said, he would probably do little if
anything to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to let people go,'' Santos said. ``If I go after
them and they get hit by a car, my company would be liable.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Crew's Coffey essentially conceded that if a shoplifter is
determined to walk out of a store with stolen goods, he or she will
probably get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, some thieves add insult to injury by coming back to
return unwanted items.
</P>
<P>
   ``The professionals take things into the fitting room and use a
garden tool to remove sensors,'' Coffey said. ``They come back
later with the same things. Then they try and get store credit for
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   She shook her head. ``It's frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
