<HEADER>
A8293 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-OSTLER24-COLUMN-SFCHR     12-24 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER24-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESOLUTIONS FOR A NEW MILLENNIUM  &HT;     
   
  
</HEADLINE>
   By SCOTT OSTLER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's been a good millennium. Some of man's greatest achievements:
<P>
   The Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   The Industrial Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Catch.
</P>
<P>
   If I left out anything important, contact me at the Column
Correction Hotline. Sorry about giving out the wrong number last
time. My bad.
</P>
<P>
   Operators are standing by to misdirect your call or sell you
infomercial items that Steve Garvey guarantees will shrink your
waistline and/or shine your car.
</P>
<P>
   If you are put on hold, please enjoy ``Ravi Shankar's Greatest
Hits Volume III,'' and be assured that your call is very important
to us (and to Ravi, who gets royalties).
</P>
<P>
   The operators have been swamped with calls from readers who
caught my recent reference to ``pasta pazool'' in the Dean Martin
song ``That's Amore.'' It turns out that Deano was actually singing
about pasta  &LR; fazool,  &LR; which is slang for pasta a fagioli, which is
pasta and beans.
</P>
<P>
   A pasta pazool, of course, is the edible festive hat worn by
Italian Shriners.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BY THE WAY,  &LR; Merry Fill-in-the-Blank.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't everyone wear a badge during this season, indicating
his or her Big Holiday of choice? Save us the agony of selecting
the appropriate greeting.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it's Merry Christmas and Happy Hanukkah, but what is
Kwanzaa's favored adjective? Have yourself a kooky little Kwanzaa?
</P>
<P>
   The beautiful thing is, although we all go our separate
ethnic/cultural/religious ways to celebrate our holidays, Sunday we
will all be re-united as the Family of Man in the gift-return
lines, praying together that we brought the right receipts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THEN COMES Y2K,  &LR; which will be even more festive than the other Big
Holidays, because computer glitches will wipe out all your credit
card debt.
</P>
<P>
   You would be foolish not to max out all your credit cards, trust
me. If you don't do it, don't come to me on January 2 begging to
borrow my new Maserati.
</P>
<P>
   The new millennium scares me a bit, though. You can't treat it
like just another new year. You can't make New Year's resolutions,
you have to make New Millennium resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   I will lose so much weight that when I cut in a theater line, a
guy behind me will shout, ``Hey, Gandhi, get your bony ass in the
back of the line!'' I will cure a major disease, or catch one,
whichever comes first. I will play shortstop for the Yankees. I
will vacuum under the back seat of my car.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WE ALL  &LR; feel compelled to celebrate this New Year's extra hard. We
will wear gaudier and more festive lamp shades. Many of us will
stagger into the new millennium as Pukemon.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us won't make it. Reportedly, members of one doomsday
cult are coming to San Francisco to commit mass suicide by using
crosswalks.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, if you drink too much on New Millennium Eve, when it's
time to go home, stand on a street corner and hail a cab. You won't
get one, but your efforts will provide a lot of hilarious
entertainment for the rest of us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ALREADY  &LR; I miss the old millennium, and some of the stuff that will
get left behind due to limited space in the lifeboats.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Macarena. Not the Macarena as performed by drunken fat
guys at basketball games, but the slinky, sensuous real thing. My
wife could do a mean Macarena.
</P>
<P>
   I worry that the new millennium, despite all the hype, will be a
disappointment, that it will be the old millennium with a coat of
cheap paint that we won't notice until we lean against it.
</P>
<P>
   What if we wake up on Jan. 1 and we don't have buns of steel and
a new Harley and a boss who suddenly understands our quirky genius?
</P>
<P>
   What if the rich are still way too rich, and the busiest hotel
in town is still the Market Street Sidewalk Inn?
</P>
<P>
   What if, despite shock therapy and a new regimen of
pogo-stick-aerobics, the same nonsense continues to flow from these
very fingertips on this very keyboard? Another long millennium with
no Pulitzer?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; THERE'S GOOD REASON  &LR; to celebrate the New, Improved Mil, of course:
</P>
<P>
   Because we can. We're here. Assuming, of course, that turns out
to be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, we have survived a half century in which hundreds of
reality-challenged, power-crazed, thin-skinned world leaders sat
with twitching index fingers poised over red buttons. By all
rights, the planet should by now be a lump of smoking coal.
</P>
<P>
   In America, we have created a nation that annoys a lot of
people, including many Americans. We have rubbed many people the
wrong way, and now they want to rub back. So be careful. If a
stranger asks you to hold what appears to be a bowling ball with a
sizzling fuse, you'll know you've watched too many cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm taking the rest of the century off (not counting this
column). I plan to climb to the top of a Himalayan mountain and do
some deep meditation and soul searching, but of course I will still
be receiving cell calls, e-mail, voice mail, faxes, beeper
messages, telegrams and bills.
</P>
<P>
   And to you, dear reader _ loyal, devoted, accidental or
otherwise: My best wishes for a wacky Whatever, my profound and
groveling gratitude, and a tip of the old pasta pazool.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Scott Ostler's column appears Monday through Friday. You can &LR; 
 &LR; reach him at (415) 777-7031, fax him at (415)896-1107 or send &LR; 
 &LR; him an &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; e-mail at ostler &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 0252EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
