r a BC-HERO-FIRE-LADN     12-24 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERO-FIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD SAVED AS NEIGHBOR DOUSES FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Lisa Van Proyen  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A suburban Los Angeles man is being hailed as a
hero after he saved a 3-year-old boy's life by racing into a
smoke-filled apartment to douse a Christmas tree fire with buckets
of water.
</P>
<P>
   Gerardo Perez said he heard a child's screams Wednesday night
and saw 15-foot flames leaping from an upstairs apartment. An
electrical short in Christmas lights had sparked a fire that
consumed the tree, presents and living room, overwhelming the
toddler with smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking. I was just trying to get the child out and
at that moment, you don't think, you just react,'' Perez said,
nursing a burn to his shoulder on his own without medical
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, 33, deflected the praise, saying instead that many people
from the apartment complex worked to extinguish the blaze. He also
noted that 11-year-old Daniel Garcia had returned to the apartment
to rescue his 3-year-old brother, Arturo Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of the Garcia family credited him with saving the
children and the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the one who saved him. My aunt tried to get him out, but
the smoke was too intense. He took his shirt off and went in with
buckets of water. We're glad that he did this for us,'' said Carlos
Ontiveros, a cousin of the two injured boys.
</P>
<P>
   The toddler was not burned, but was overcome by smoke and
remained in critical condition Thursday afternoon with
life-threatening injuries to his lungs at Valley Presbyterian
Hospital, a hospital official said.
</P>
<P>
   His brother was also under treatment for smoke inhalation and in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The Garcias had lived in the second-floor apartment in the 8800
block of Langdon Avenue for six months and at the time of the fire
were readying for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very sad for them,'' said Daniel Pomposo, 12, who lives
below the Garcias.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said they plan to buy the Garcia family gifts, things
they need most due to losses in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could probably try to make up for their Christmas. Having
two kids in the hospital at Christmas is traumatic ... We will try
to make their Christmas more meaningful,'' said a neighbor,
Josefina Fuentes.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal began about 8 p.m. when the tree burst into flames.
As Perez made his way up to the apartment, he said he heard,
``Mommy! mommy!''
</P>
<P>
   The toddler was in the middle of the living room next to a
Christmas tree, but Perez couldn't see him through the thick smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Perez furiously grabbed buckets from neighbors, who filled them
from a pool as others called 911.
</P>
<P>
   About halfway inside the living room, Perez dumped the water
near the tree, getting within a few feet of flames, burning his
shoulder. As the flames consumed the tree, the Christmas presents
at its base, and the rest of the living room, about 15 neighbors
battled the blaze, grabbing fire extinguishers and using a hose
from the first floor to douse flames through the window, witnesses
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a woman screaming that her son was trapped inside. I
felt helpless,'' said Ricardo Recinos, who was baby-sitting his
1-year-old nephew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Christmas lights were popping. I could feel the heat way
over here. It was pretty intense for a small house fire,'' Recinos
said.
</P>
<P>
   The older brother managed to escape from the burning apartment
with his mother, Angeles Garcia. But minutes later, after Perez and
others had put out most of the flames, the older teary-eyed brother
grabbed a flashlight out of a neighbor's hand and rushed into the
smoke-filled apartment to rescue his younger brother, family and
neighbors said. ``He pulled my flashlight out of my hand and ran
inside looking for his brother. I believe it was him who brought
him out,'' Fuentes said.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing neighbors knew, the two brothers were outside the
apartment with their mother by their side. And the firefighters
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes and at least a dozen other neighbors praised one another
for their quick actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never underestimate what kind of neighbors you have.
Today, it's for you, tomorrow it will be for me,'' Fuentes said.
``I feel real proud of my neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
