<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING THE RIGHT STAINLESS STEEL SINK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 26, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are looking at stainless steel kitchen sinks and other
kitchen items for our house. One store said that the differences in
stainless steel sinks for sale is the amount of nickel in the
steel. Another store said the difference is in the weight. Who's
right?
</P>
<P>
   GALE BATSIMM, North Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think I am on the side the store that mentioned nickel
content as an indication of stainless steel quality. It is the
quality of the steel, not its weight, that counts, although a heavy
sink is better than a light one.
</P>
<P>
   More important, there are two types of stainless steel. One day
recently the handyman got himself into a mess by declaring that if
stainless steel rusts, it is not stainless steel.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Two readers pointed out that there are two kinds of
stainless steel. Here is how Arthur Rosen of Randolpoh put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two series (groups) of stainless steels; the 300 and
400 series. Although both are considered stainless steel, their
materialscontent and method of manufacture are different. One
easily identifiable difference between the two series is that the
300 series is non-magnetic and will not rust whereas the 400 series
is magnetic and can rust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although most `stainelss steel' sinks are made of the
non-rusting 300 series stainless steel, it is possible that some
sinks have been made with the 400 series. I suggest you have your
reader check the sink with a magnet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible to make even the 300 series stainless steels
magnetic under cartain circumstances. Improper welding techniques
and/or mechanical work with, say, a grinder, will make the area of
the sink that was welded and/or ground become magnetic.''
</P>
<P>
   So, with this information, the handyman suggests you opt for a
300 series sink. And, the heavier and more expensive, the better,
but it does not necessarily have to be the top price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My shower pads (floors of the stalls) are made of some kind
of stone and binder, very smooth and shiny. Parts of them are
turning black. They are OK dry, but when wet, they are black, but
only where people stand in the shower. How can I clean up that
black?
</P>
<P>
   BRUCE TRUESDALE, Nantucket, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Those shower floors are most likely terrazzo, a ground stone
with binder, then smoothed and polished. I think the finish is worn
just a bit where people stand, enough to get dirty. The dirt is
ground in and looks worse when the floor is wet.
</P>
<P>
   To fix it, make a strong solution of Spic and Span and water,
add a cup of household bleach to the solution, soak the floor with
this solution and let it stand for 5 or 10 minutes (so it can do
its work), then scrub and rinse. When it dries, apply one or more
coats of a masonry sealer or tile sealer; repeat this once a year.
This will make the terrazzo water resistant, and may correct the
problem. If nothing seems to work, you could tile the floor with
glazed ceramic tile, using a thin-set mortar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My problem is with a second-floor balcony, one that sticks
out of the wall with no support under it. Water comes in
over/under/around the door threshold in driving rain, leaking to
the bathroom below. We removed the flashing under the threshold and
noticed that there was no caulking. We then caulked that area, and
the problem is about 90 percent better, but still water is coming
in. What can we do?
</P>
<P>
   MELISSA BUOYMANN, Machias, Maine
</P>
<P>
   A. The balcony is sturdy, set on lookout joists, which are
simply an extension of the floor joists through the wall to as far
as the balcony edge, which in your case is four feet. I will bet
that the threshold is just an inch or so above the balcony floor,
and therein lies the problem. A door entering onto a balcony should
have a full step down from threshold to balcony floor, which is
about 7 1/2 inches. This step will allow flashing to keep out
windblown rain.
</P>
<P>
   Anything less is inadequate, although you could raise the door 7
1/2 inches; that is fussy work, but possible. Adding to your
problem is the possibility of rain going through the balcony floor
and running down the wall between the joists, causing more leaks.
</P>
<P>
   A possible cure, if you do not raise the door: For the
threshold, caulk the joint directly under the threshold and
anywhere else you think water is coming in. Nail copper or aluminum
flashing on the wall immediately under the threshold (sill), and
fold it so a bit of it is lying on the balcony floor. This will
allow water that hits it to drip down onto the floor and drip
harmlessly away, windblown or not.
</P>
<P>
   And, check the outside wall under the balcony, between those
lookout joists; that wall should be weatherproof to resist
windblown rain, which is frequent since your house, as you said,
faces the ocean, right on the coast.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of water is the bottom of the door. Make sure it
is well sealed. If not, install a moving threshold, one that pops
up when the door is opened and pops down to form a tight seal when
it is closed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
