<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPROVING THEIR WORLD IS BACK `IN' AT TUFTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 26, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fruits of liberty that Americans enjoy, and help spread
across the planet, were planted and flourished in the rich soil of
democracy. But history has recorded the decay of democracies as
well as the blissful ripening of ours.
</P>
<P>
   As the millennium beckons, more people are looking forward
rather than back. But on the campus of Tufts University in Medford,
the doleful pronouncement of Edward Gibbon over ancient Athens, the
America of its day, is not only heard but heeded.
</P>
<P>
   As recounted by professor Brian O'Connell, Gibbon's ``Decline
and Fall of the Roman Empire'' gave this epitaph for once-mighty
Athenians after they became corrupted by indolence, greed, and
immorality: ``In the end, more than they wanted freedom, they
wanted security. They wanted a comfortable life, and they lost it
all _ security, comfort and freedom . . . when the Athenians
finally wanted not to give to society, but for society to give to
them, when the freedom they wished for most was freedom from
responsibility, then Athens ceased to be free.''
</P>
<P>
   Could it happen here? Without question.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is now the longest-running democracy in
history, as well as the richest and most powerful, and with the
most widely shared prosperity. But how do we keep it? John
DiBiaggio, the president of Tufts, is convinced you make a down
payment on preserving democracy by educating college kids as to
what it takes. Now the university's board of trustees has embraced
the notion, voting to launch the loftily titled University College
of Citizenship and Public Service. The idea is to promote the
notion of ``giving back'' and ``a desire to make the world a better
place,'' according to the trustees' minutes.
</P>
<P>
   And because DiBiaggio (eight years at Tufts, 14 years as
president at the University of Connecticut and Michigan State) is
currently head of both the American Council on Education, higher
ed's largest umbrella group of 3,500 colleges, and the Campus
Compact, a group of 700 schools committed to community action,
there's a chance that the bonfire lit at Tufts may catch on
elsewhere. The goal is to imbue in every Tufts student _ each of
the 4,800 undergrads plus the graduate students in various
disciplines _ the ethic of citizen involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts has mounted a good start; 1,000 students already take part
in a broad array of community activism ranging from AIDS to
environmental causes. But the new scheme envisions two or three
years of run-up to the hoped-for goal of commandeering $35 million
in new gifts to launch a university-wide, full-court press on the
philosophy of active citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Do not count DiBiaggio among those who see the 1960s through
rose-colored glasses. In a recent interview he ticked off the
excesses of that era: ``Kids had no input in decision-making then,
and no due process. For the kids in the '60s and '70s, it was not
just about civil rights or the Vietnam War. We put nonsense courses
in their curriculum and we inflated their grades.'' That triggered
cynicism and disengagement, he argues. ``Then they became very
apathetic and focused on themselves. Now, there's a rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   So citizen involvement will become ``a hallmark of Tufts
education across all our degrees,'' said Dean Robert Hollister.
``Our focus on civic leadership and our across-the-curriculum
commitment sets this initiative apart from the efforts of other
colleges and universities.''
</P>
<P>
   DiBiaggio reckons sensitivity to civic concerns can be fragile
and expire easily. ``In the '80s, the first time we saw homeless
people in the streets since the Depression, we were shocked. Now,
we brush by them, don't even know they are there.'' What Tufts can
do about that, and about the erosion of all sorts of democratic
bulwarks, is recommit its campus to the ethic of citizenship, of
responsibility to a meaning larger than one's own paycheck or
401(k) plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only 15 percent of the 18- to 25-year-olds voted in the last
election,'' he said. So it will take more than just some subtle
pushing in the direction of more volunteerism, he said. ``We can't
let it just be that. There's got to be some meaning in it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the redrawn game plan, students in every course
and discipline will be steered to the relevance of what they are
learning to real life in real places. Engineering students studying
environmental remediation, for instance, will be assigned real
chores in cleaning up a brownfields site. ``They have to translate
what they're doing,'' said DiBiaggio, from the classroom to the
community.
</P>
<P>
   There are successful examples aplenty. There are 25 students in
the Tufts Literacy Corps. Others go on ``Volunteer Vacation''
during spring break to build housing for Habitat for Humanity.
``Our medical students are more altruistic, less materialistic;
it's a wonderful shift,'' he enthuses.
</P>
<P>
   This is student-driven, Hollister said. Two-thirds of incoming
students in a survey asked that community service be a structured
part of their university life. O'Connell sees the shift as a return
to notions of citizenship that were more deeply ingrained at
midcentury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 50 years we've pretty much phased out anything
like civics or citizen education from schools and colleges,''
O'Connell said. When the Department of Education surveyed high
school students, 4 out of 10 flunked even the basic concepts, he
said. ``A hundred years ago, one of the primary goals of a college
education was to prepare them to be community leaders and active
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   But we began trimming back, to load up on science and vocational
courses. ``We're forgetting that democracy depends on the degree to
which citizens are prepared.'' This is why Plato took a dim view of
democracy, when the lowest common denominator of the rabble could
elect leaders who promised them the easy life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now the longest-lived democracy in the history of the
world,'' O'Connellsaid. ``It's provided us more liberty and
opportunity than any nation known, and no institution can presume
that preserving this democracy for those who come after us is
someone's else's business.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
