<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETIREEE WITH MINIMAL FINANCIAL NEEDS IN GOOD POSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 26, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am married, age 64 and would like to retire about midway
through next year. I will have income of $74,400 from pensions and
$25,600 from two rental properties. I would also like to have
income of $20,000 a year from my investments, which would be used
to accelerate mortgage payments so my home mortgage and those on
the rental properties would be paid off in six years. The
investments include a $260,000 410(k) plan, from one employer, a
$125,000 401(k) with another employer, and a $30,000 account in
four mutual funds. Nearly all of the accounts are in stock funds or
stocks. How would you suggest I consolidate the portfolio either
for early payment of the mortgages or payment over the traditional
mortgage course, which would take 10 years? How might I make the
transition from pre-retirement to post-retirement assets?
</P>
<P>
   K.K., San Diego,
</P>
<P>
   A. I think youre in a good position to make no transition at
all. Since your pensions and rental income stream are sufficient to
supply all the money you need to live on, you can treat the entire
investment portfolio as long-term reserves. You would require a
total return of only 4.82 percent to support withdrawals of $20,000
a year during the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   Although I consistently look down on the idea of drawing an
income stream from a stock-dominated portfolio when the investor is
counting on stock market gains to support the withdrawals, in your
case your needs are so small and your savings sufficiently large
that assuming the risk seems very sensible to me.
</P>
<P>
   So my suggestion would be to simply draw the funds evenly from
your various accounts as needed to meet the mortgage prepayment
schedule. You could begin by taking the actual portfolio yield,
although that probably represents less that 1.5 percent of the
portfolio balance. It doesnt seem to me that there is any
particular imbalance in the portfolio, assuming you agree that you
are in a sufficiently strong financial position to be almost fully
invested in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   One strategy you might employ would be to assess your market
performance at the end of each year, and if you find that the
market performance of the previous year did not support the 4.82
percent withdrawals, you could defer prepayments during the
following year, meaning you would stretching out the mortgage
prepayment schedule, but also meaning that you would not be selling
stock positions into a weak market.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you feel that upon retirement your
portfolio should be more conservative, you could swap your $95,000
position in Investment Company of America for shares in a sister
fund, Income Company of America. The latter is a balanced fund with
its investments about evenly divided between stocks and
fixed-income holdings. Similarly, you could transfer some of the
funds in your second 401(k) to the balanced account, where your
current position represents a token participation in the
fixed-income markets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm a 36-year-old stay-at-home mother of three boys -- aged
six, two and 11 months. My husband is 38 years old and has 12 years
in the U.S. Navy. After 15 years he has the options of receiving a
$30,000 bonus and a pension representing 40 percent of his basic
pay, or of taking a pension representing 50 percent of his base
pay. Right now, our investments total $37,000, with Roth IRAs in
Janus fund and Janus Overseas, and accounts in Neuberger Berman
Guardian, Acorn fund, and savings bonds. We fully fund each of our
Roth IRAs each year and add $100 per month to each of the other
three accounts. I am thinking of replacing the Neuberger fund with
Vanguard Index Value and the savings bonds with Vanguard Total Bond
Market Index. Which option do you suggest for the pension -- taking
the bonus and investing it, or taking the higher pension? If we
were to take the bonus, how should we invest it?
</P>
<P>
   A.M., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. My guess is that the reasoning behind the idea of the bonus
is to supply retiring servicemen with a pool of cash to tide them
over until they establish themselves in a second career. But I
think you would be much better off in the long run if you went for
the higher pension. You dont cite the estimated base pay for your
husband at the time of his retirement, but lets work out an
estimate based on a $40,000 earnings level. If you took the bonus
and a pension of $16,000 a year, you would have to achieve average
investment levels of 13.33 percent to bring in the $4,000 which
would represent the equivalent of the 50 percent pension. If your
husbands base pay is higher, then the level of returns needed to
make the bonus-plus-pension deal match the pension-without-bonus
package would be even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Recent stock market years notwithstanding, I dont think that
expectations of long-term market returns in excess of 13 percent
are reasonable, so I would definitely go for the higher pension.
</P>
<P>
   But I also suggest that you make a change in your savings
pattern to insure that you will be in a position to turn down that
bonus. You will doubtless need some extra cash during that
change-of-careers period, and the time to start saving it is now.
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion would be to curtail your monthly contributions to
both mutual funds and to the savings bond program and to put that
$300 a month into a money market fund. In three years, with a
presumption of average returns of 5 percent from the money fund,
you would accumulate $11,609, and with any luck, that should be
sufficient to fund you through the transition. If it is not, you
could at that point liquidate some of your savings bond
accumulation. If the transition turns out to be smooth and requires
little or none of your savings, at that point you could restore the
cash you would have saved to your mutual fund accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I agree that it would be wise to swap the position in
Neuberger Berman Guardian for shares of Vanguard Index Value. Index
Value has outperformed the Neuberger fund consistently in recent
years, and its low expenses seem to me to augur continued better
performance in the large-cap value market segment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am 55 and my husband 59; we plan to retire in two years. We
have $137,000 in various bank CDs, $24,000 in six taxable mutual
fund accounts, and IRA and 401(k) accounts with $270,000 in CDs,
$30,000 in a fixed annuity, $25,000 in a Fidelity Advisor Balanced
account, and $31,000 in 10 additional mutual fund accounts. How can
we better diversify our investments so that we can beat inflation?
We will need $24,000 a year from our investments when we retire.
</P>
<P>
   K.K., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. This is one of those tough situations to advise in, since Ive
always assumed that when a person has built an ultra-conservative
portfolio, it hasnt happened by accident. Thus with my estimate
that you have 91.3 percent of your portfolio on the fixed-income
side, I've guessed that you are very risk-averse.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly coming up with the $24,000 will be no problem; the
yields on your CD accounts alone should be sufficient to bring you
that income stream. But your remaining investments are too
conservative to give you a good shot at countering the effects of
inflation in your later years. Your broad array of mutual funds
don't give you much in the way of diversification, since the
positions in the funds which might give you the kind of long-term
growth you need are too small. These are funds such as Fidelity
Growth and Income, Barclay S&AMP;P Midcap Stock and Barclay S&AMP;P 500
funds. My suggestion would be to pare the portfolio down so that
you have about $75,000 in such funds, and the remaining in your
choice of the many balanced or asset allocation funds. This would
still leave you with more than 80 percent of your savings in
fixed-income investments, but it would be a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
