<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FATMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAN IN A MIDDLE SEAT' KNOWS ALL, TELLS ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FAT MAN IN A MIDDLE SEAT 
Forty Years of Covering Politics 
By Jack W. Germond 
Random House, 284 pp., $25.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On numerous occasions in his memoirs, covering 40 years on the
political-reporting beat, Jack Germond takes us on an almost Hunter
Thompson-esque journey of caloric and fermented excess.
</P>
<P>
   One 1966 night on the town with a Richard Nixon aide, for
example, consisted of 13 Irish coffees in a cocktail lounge and
beers in an after-hours club. As Germond wistfully notes, today's
generation of clean-living reporters drink white wine instead of
whiskey and eat salads instead of steak.
</P>
<P>
   That's the core point of ``Fat Man in a Middle Seat'': Things
sure have changed in politics. Not only the lifestyles of
journalists but the rules of the game and the relationships between
the media and the pols.
</P>
<P>
   Germond _ a political columnist for The Baltimore Sun and TV
pundit best known as the mildly cantankerous liberal on ``The
McLaughlin Group'' _ has traded toasts with many of the nation's
leading postwar pols. And the book is at its most engaging when he
delivers his personal critiques of those figures.
</P>
<P>
   George Wallace was a political animal whose racism represented
more a campaign tool than heartfelt conviction. ``Clean Gene''
McCarthy, the saintly darling of the left in the 1968 presidential
race, showed an uglier side in private, carping about the press and
even bad-mouthing the loyal students who fueled his insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Germond didn't click personally with Richard
Nixon, who comes across as the kind of tortured soul portrayed in
Oliver Stone's movie ``Nixon.'' The author soured on Jimmy Carter,
eventually coming to view him as fatally weak. (The epiphany comes
in 1979 when Carter, angry at the negative columns Germond is
writing about him, invites him for drinks at the White House and
fails to give the columnist a sufficiently fearsome tongue-lashing.
``If this were Lyndon Johnson, I'd be afraid my barn would be
burning at this very moment,'' he writes.)
</P>
<P>
   Germond portrays Ronald Reagan as a distracted dolt and assails
Clinton for being ``the most selfish and egocentric politician I
have ever seen.'' Germond seems to anoint Bobby Kennedy as his
favorite pol, and saves his greatest disdain for George Bush, whom
he calls ``the most vacuous man to occupy the Oval Office in my
time in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbled throughout ``Fat Man in a Middle Seat'' are clear
examples of how the politics/journalism equation has changed.
Germond recalls, for instance, how he once talked Robert Strauss
out of running for president in the 1980s. That's the kind of
too-cozy relationship between reporter and source that would earn
Germond a tongue-lashing from Brill's Content today. The author
admits he didn't maintain proper ``detachment,'' but brushes the
issue aside by saying, ``I couldn't help but go into the tank for
Strauss; he was too good company.''
</P>
<P>
   In another telling passage, Germond recounts sitting in a hotel
while a woman who had just emerged from a tryst with George Wallace
bragged about it. ``It never occurred to me to report it,'' he
writes. ``These days it could be Page One stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Germond is clearly no devotee of the introspective,
self-flagellating brand of journalism. And it's refreshing to read
a book about the media that doesn't lecture on how to restore
faltering public trust in the Fourth Estate. He even has the
temerity to admit his preference for what ``politial scientists
disparage as horse race journalism, which means putting the
emphasis on winners and losers rather than the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Germond imparts his most serious message in the book's final
pages, warning that political journalism's ``most egregious
weakness'' is the tendency to transform a candidate's minor gaffe
into a major story without ``any sense of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Germond recalls a 1979 Maine GOP straw poll
that Howard Baker lost to George Bush by 20 votes after delivering
a bad speech. Baker was instantly buried by the press, which
trashed his political skills without asking what Germond deemed to
be the crucial question: ``Why in the world should a public
official of the quality of Howard Baker be eliminated as a
presidential candidate on the basis of this one episode?''
</P>
<P>
   On the plane back to Washington from Maine, Germond sat with a
top Baker adviser who gamely tried to spin the defeat while
``swill(ing) down six Jack Daniels.''
</P>
<P>
   Readers will find that such Germond moralizing is relatively
rare. His encyclopedic recall of the tippling habits of Baker's
aide is much more typical of the breezy style of the book.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 0959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8320 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NO FORGIVENESS IN MCAS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The titles of the senior humanities portfolios collected last
week by Eileen Shakespear at Fenway High School were impressive
enough: ``The Chilean Military Coup of 1973,'' ``The Vietnam War's
Effect on Veterans,'' ``The Persecution of Homosexuals During World
War II,'' ``Kurt Vonnegut and the First Amendment,'' and ``What
Made Hitler So Powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   Other subjects included the Tuskegee experiment of untreated
syphilis on African-American men, the Milgram experiment on how far
people would follow orders against their personal conscience,
genital mutilation, busing in Boston, Salvador Dali, and Thomas
Jefferson's fathering of a black woman.
</P>
<P>
   Just as interesting were the students who were not finished.
About 15 students were in a computer lab, typing so hard that their
pecking filled the air like jackhammers. Their fingers were
seemingly so loud because their mouths were so quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so amazing is that they are working so hard, but most
of the kids flunk the portfolios the first time around,''
Shakespear said. ``Some of them will cry. They will all feel real
bad. But it shows they care about their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as if on cue, some ninth-grade boys walked down the
hallway. Unlike the quiet focus of the seniors, they walked in a
more sloppy swagger, talking loudly. ``That's how many of them come
to us when they start here,'' Shakespear said. ``I become angry
when I hear that Fenway does better because we get better kids. Our
kids come in like ninth graders everywhere, with hoods over their
heads. A lot of them come without a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The students end up finding a purpose in a way that should make
the state think far more carefully about its myopic mission to
judge students solely on the basis of standardized test scores.
Fenway is a school where scores do not predict success.
</P>
<P>
   The poverty rate of the school is 60 percent. If the MCAS were
required for graduation right now instead of 2003, 56 percent of
Fenway students would fail in English, 85 percent would fail in
math, and 74 percent would fail in science. Taken together, the
categories of ``failing'' and ``needs improvement'' take in 88
percent of Fenway 10th graders in English, 99 percent in math, and
93 percent in science.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Director Larry Myatt walks the halls with an electric step
and infectious pride. The reason is simple. He said, ``Ninety
percent of our students come in here with scores that are failing.
Ninety percent of our kids go on to college.''
</P>
<P>
   Myatt, given the powers of a pilot school, has crafted an
environment where teachers like Shakespear can tap into the
potential of students. Unlike the horrors of larger high schools
where one teacher may have several classes of 25 to 35 students
each, Shakespear has only 45 students, split into two sections,
with a teaching intern and a twice-a-week volunteer who can reduce
her student-to-teacher ratio to as low as 7-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks your heart to keep hearing about teachers with 150
students,'' said Shakespear, a former middle school teacher. ``I
might not be here teaching today if I had that load.''
</P>
<P>
   In technology, Fenway has far more superior access to the
Internet than most Boston public schools. All its classroom
computers are on the Internet, compared with 40 percent for the
city and 66 percent for the state. While the state's ratio of
students per computer is 6.3-to-1 and the Boston system's ratio is
5-to-1, the ratio at the Fenway is 2.2 students per computer.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Myatt has made the rewards for learning
tangible. Few Fenway students score above 1,000 on the SATs, but he
has developed relationships with colleges that search for potential
beyond one-shot tests. Graduates go on to Wheaton, Brandeis, Tufts,
Tuskegee, Hampshire, Suffolk, Bradford, and public institutions in
Massachusetts. Myatt said two graduates have gone on to become
class presidents at Wheaton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still struggle,'' Myatt said. ``They still have catching
up to do because they are now with more affluent kids. But they're
on their way. If these kids were to have been judged solely on the
MCAS, they may have never gotten the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   That disturbs Myatt, who was involved in the early discussions
of what would become the Massachusetts Comprehensive System
Assessment. He had hoped it would be a tool to identify problem
schools and districts in order to improve them. Now he says it has
become a tool more for punishing students and blaming parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no forgiveness in MCAS,'' Myatt said. ``There is no
hunger, no thirst, no intellectual gratification you can measure in
these tests. These scores send a message to our kind of students
that `You failed by a long shot.' I fear so many kids will see it
as a such a long shot, they will drop out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that the MCAS can't be useful as an organizing
tool for curriculum. But there are plenty of kids who test well who
can't critically think their way out of a paper bag. The more you
use this as the single instrument to judge our kids, the more kids
you leave to the side. As far as I can see, all the MCAS is doing
is turning into a real estate indicator.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
