<SLUG> BC-EARLY-ADMISSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING INTO TOP SCHOOLS IS EASIER THAN IT SEEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, in addition to their Christmas presents, tens of
thousands of high school seniors will be opening a far less
satisfying seasonal item: rejections or deferrals on their early
applications to college.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news will likely have their parents grousing at holiday
parties about how difficult it must be to get into college.
</P>
<P>
   And it is, right?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the nation's 2,044 four-year colleges and
universities _ indeed, the majority of those in the US News and
World Report Top 50 _ accept fully half the students who apply.
Many more schools, including some among the Seven Sisters and the
country's top public universities, accept two out of three, or even
three out of four, of their applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The happy little secret of college admissions is that a very
large percentage of students get into one of their top choice
colleges,'' said Richard Zeckhauser, a professor of political
economy at Harvard's Kennedy School of Government, who studies
college admissions. ``But the colleges won't tell you this, because
it's in their interest to say this is a very competitive process.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that schools like Harvard, Brown and Stanford,
all of which accepted just more than 10 percent of applicants last
spring, are tough to get into. But those schools, trendsetters in
so many ways, have come to shape _ and hype _ popular perception of
college admissions, making parents and students think that colleges
are much more choosy than they actually are.
</P>
<P>
   This year promises to heighten the hype. The number of early
applications has gone up sharply, but the percentage of acceptances
has stayed about the same, so a greater number of students will
receive rejection notices or deferrals this month. A deferral
pushes an applicant into the regular pool of candidates who will
not find out if they are accepted until April. And it may also make
it seem like colleges have become that much more selective.
</P>
<P>
   Several indicators, though, offer a reality check.
</P>
<P>
   Consider last spring's acceptance rates at several top schools,
as indicated by the colleges for the annual US News rankings. Smith
College took 56 percent of applicants, Mount Holyoke 64 percent.
The University of Chicago accepted 61 percent of applicants,
Brandeis, 57 percent. Two top ranked public universities, The
University of Michigan at Ann Arbor and the University of Wisconsin
at Madison, accepted 59 percent and 73 percent of applicants,
respectively. Carleton College and Macalester College, both top
liberal arts schools, accepted 56 percent of applicants, and
Vanderbilt, the 20th-ranked national university, accepted 59
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's generally written about is how hard it is to get into
these schools, that less than one in four people are accepted, that
all schools cost $120,000. But that's only a small percentage of
the schools,'' said Robert Morse, who compiles the US News
rankings. ``Outside of the Top 10, Top 25 schools, it's rare to
find schools that accept less than 50 percent of students.''
</P>
<P>
   Another measure is the acceptance rate at the 500-odd schools
that offer some kind of early application programs. According to a
survey by the National Association for College Admission
Counseling, about half those schools say they admit between 60 and
79 percent of total applicants, whether they apply early or
regular. About 20 percent admitted 80 percent or more. Less than 5
percent admitted less than 20 percent of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   And in April of each year, at the end of the admissions cycle,
executive director Joyce Smith points out, the association
publishes a list of 300 to 400 schools that are still willing to
consider applications. The Ivies aren't on the list, but some
renowned schools are: Lesley and Simmons colleges, Fordham
University, the flagship campus of Pennsylvania State University,
Dickinson College, and Temple University.
</P>
<P>
   High school guidance counselors say it's rare that they have to
resort to using that list. But that's only because most of their
students get into their top choice schools.
</P>
<P>
   Milton High School, for example, each year surveys how many of
their seniors get into their first or second choice school. That
rate has held steady at about 80 percent for several years. While
other high schools say they don't do similar checks, they believe
the rates are about the same.
</P>
<P>
   The message guidance counselors want to convey? Plan ahead, but
relax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, we live through this whole thing with early
decision, then we live through the wait list, but overall it works
out,'' said Vincent D'Antona, director of guidance and counseling
for the Arlington schools. ``We hype this college stuff, but in the
end, they're all going to be OK. Most are going to get their first
choice or maybe their second choice, and in a rare few, it might be
their third.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is the perception one of a process so exclusive?
</P>
<P>
   Colleges want to look as selective as possible so they can
ultimately attract a better and better pool of students.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions officers privately concede that some schools will try
to encourage applications, even from students they know don't meet
their standards, so they can reject more students, and look more
choosy. Less scrupulous schools may count half-completed
applications, or students who had the College Board send SAT scores
but did not apply, as requests for admission, Zeckhauser said, so
they can say they rejected more students.
</P>
<P>
   The more selective the colleges are, the more appealing they
become. They start to attract the attention of students with better
SAT scores and grades, which sends their rankings, and desirability
even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions specialists argue that this is the principal reason
so many colleges now use the common application, which allows
students to use the same form to apply to dozens of schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scarcity is where it's at,'' said Bill Mayher, a former
guidance counselor at top private schools outside New York and
Boston, and the author of ``The College Admissions Mystique.''
``Improving the product isn't going to bring in more customers,
selectivity does. The way kids perceive it, if a college is hard to
get into, it's good. If it's less hard to get into, it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   The frenzy feeds the frenzy: high schools say that seniors are
applying to 10 or 12 schools now, up from four or five just five
years ago. More applications mean more rejections and thus the
perception of greater selectivity.
</P>
<P>
   Mayher says early applications have made the whole cycle even
more vicious: ``The letters come out in the high point of American
communication, which is the preholiday cocktail party, office
party. When the parental rumor mill is operating full-tilt,
everybody is talking about which first rate students have been
deferred. Stoking those fires has been an incredibly successful
move for colleges, because they don't even get caught marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   But selectivity is also in the interest of students.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always want to be part of a group they can't get
into,'' Zeckhauser said. ``Can you imagine if the college wrote to
every kid saying, `Congratulations, you got in, do you realize that
70 percent of applicants got in?' Instead, the president welcomes
them opening day, saying `You're very lucky to be here, we had an
incredibly strong pool,` and everyone looks around and feels
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution, college and high school admissions advisers say,
is to get students to focus on what school is best for them, not
simply the best school.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to go to elite schools, even if they're not
elite kids,'' said Jim O'Loughlin, a guidance counselor at
Groton-Dunstable (Mass.) Regional High School. ``Those are the
schools the kids figure they have to go to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
