<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK BISHOP MAY CALL AN OPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Think of your own child. You see wonderful
potential. You have big, elaborate plans for him or her. You want
him or her to be a doctor or a CEO of a Fortune 500 company, but
then you find out he or she really wants to do something completely
different. You're exasperated. Then, after the initial shock,
you're happy.
</P>
<P>
   Well Patriots fans, such might be the case with your favorite
son, Michael Bishop, perhaps the most celebrated third-string
quarterback since Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   You have big plans for Bishop as a quarterback in the NFL, but
your collective hearts may be broken. ``My first love is
baseball,'' he said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Whoa.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball?
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. This is a the kid who some believe should replace
Drew Bledsoe for the final two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is my No. 1 sport,'' Bishop said. ``A lot of people
didn't know that. I think I'm a better baseball player than I am a
football player. You're always better at your first love.''
</P>
<P>
   This might be good news for the Cleveland Indians, who drafted
him. Bishop last played baseball at Blinn Jr. College, a
baseball/football factory in southern Texas. One said, ``Good
tools. Good speed. He has a gun for an arm, but he's raw. He'll
have trouble hitting the curveball at different levels, but he's a
determined, hard worker who could make himself into a player.''
Bishop is a third baseman, who would probably be moved to the
outfield to take advantage of his speed.
</P>
<P>
   Could he be a good player?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is given,'' said Bishop. ``You have to work for it.
You can't promise anything. I still have to work hard at what I
have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some thought Bishop should have been utilized this season to
take advantage of his athleticism. But Pete Carroll and his
offensive coaches thought Bishop should learn to play quarterback
first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have caught the ball or run the ball or . . . I have a
good-enough arm to get the ball to the receivers,'' Bishop said.
``I would have been glad to do whatever they wanted me to do to get
on the field. They wanted me to learn to be the best quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the Patriots brass constantly mentions NFL Europe,
which has become a steppingstone for many NFL quarterbacks,
including St. Louis's Kurt Warner, Washington's Brad Johnson, and
Seattle's Jon Kitna.
</P>
<P>
   When Bishop speaks to Patriots' vice president of player
personnel Bobby Grier at the end of the season, he will likely hear
that Grier has an offer for him to play for the Frankfurt Galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't changed my mind about it,'' said Bishop. ``I've been
asked about Europe since the season was halfway over. I just want
to concentrate on these two wins and then go home to Texas and do
some thinking. Even if I did go to Europe and play well for 10
games, I'd be in the same position I am now. It's a no-win
situation. I don't want to fight battles that I have no chance of
winning. I just want to stay here, lift weights, run.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that the exposure in Europe might spark interest from
another team, Bishop said, ``That's a good point, but if that
doesn't happen, and I'm in the same situation, I don't want to go
there and get on top of my game and then come back and have to
watch everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll is a huge fan of Bishop's, but he hasn't found the
proper time to fit him into the game. Carroll envisioned the
Patriots' offense being so powerful that he would be able to play
Bishop late in games, but it hasn't turned out that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way this guy plays football,'' said Carroll. ``I've
never seen a guy with such a fire on the field. I am very strong
about this, I have no reservation he can play in this league. From
what I've seen he can be a factor. I've based that on seeing some
of the other young guys who have come into the league this year and
seeing them on the field. I look for us to get in a position where
he can play. If he had to play, I wouldn't hesitate in putting him
in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, a seventh-round pick from Kansas State, was also the
runner-up for the Heisman Trophy. Starting all 25 games at Kansas
State, he finished with a 22-3 record and 36 touchdown passes in
two seasons. He rushed for 748 yards on 177 carries with 14
touchdowns and threw for 2,844 yards in his senior season. He was
24-0 at Blinn and won two NJCAA titles.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop, according to team sources, hasn't been the most studious
of players, spending little time going over film and the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   He has a basic understanding of the offense so that if he had to
play, the Patriots would simplify the offense to its base level
(which is not such a bad idea for Bledsoe), and Bishop would also
add his freelancing ability to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know everything they've wanted me to learn,'' he said. ``I
can run the exact same plays as Drew and John (Friesz) if I had the
chance. I'm always doing all I can. I feel like I put myself in a
situation where my teammates have confidence in me. I learned a lot
by watching. Not being able to play has been a setback. I learned
some good things and some bad things. I've just tried to keep
myself focussed to be the best athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing he will not do is beg for playing time. ``I'm not
going to put myself in the situation where I'm going to ask them to
play,'' Bishop said. ``If they want me to go out and help the team,
I'll do the best I can. But otherwise I'll just sit back and learn
from Drew. I'm not going to beg to get into a game. If you prepare
yourself well, you know what's going on and you have confidence,
you can get the job done. With me I know I'll come in and put
points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite having a completely different style than Bledsoe, Bishop
said he's learned from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just learned from hearing some of the things he's said,''
said Bishop. ``He's struggled this year, but he's still one of the
best in the league. He's always talking about what he's doing wrong
or what he's doing right, and if you listen hard enough, you can
begin to understand some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said that while Bishop's athleticism could carry him
through a game, his inexperience is cause for reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand the lack of time he's had at playing
our system at our level,'' said Carroll. ``He hasn't had that. I
think he's a regular first-year guy. He thinks he can do anything.
No challenge is too much for him. He has a tremendous competitive
attitude, but it doesn't mean he's ready to run the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead, maybe he's ready to run the bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
