<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-CRADLE-BOS &LR;      12-24 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-CRADLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRADLE WILL ROCK' BRINGS THE '30S VIVIDLY TO THE SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
CRADLE WILL ROCK 
Written and directed by: Tim Robbins 
Starring: Hank Azaria, Bob Balaban, Ruben Blades, Joan Cusack, John
Cusack, Cary Elwes, Philip Baker Hall, Cherry Jones, Angus
MacFadyen, Bill Murray, Vanessa Redgrave, Susan Sarandon, Jamey
  Sheridan, John Turturro,  Emily Watson 
Running time: 133 minutes 
Rated: R (some language and sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Cradle Will Rock'' is film's most gratifying piece of time
travel since ``Shakespeare in Love.'' It's not just that Tim
Robbins so richly evokes the most invigorating decade of the
American century _ the 1930s _ when art, passion, and politics came
together in populist ways that continue to energize artistic
endeavor today. Robbins doesn't just throw everything he knows into
``Cradle Will Rock.'' He throws everything he is into it. It isn't
perfect, but there isn't a film this year that's more alive with
heart, richness, and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of what Robbins calls a mostly true story is the
musical Marc Blitzstein wrote for the Federal Theater in 1936.
``The Cradle Will Rock'' (why Robbins dropped the article I don't
know), aflame with idealism, depicted steelworkers fighting back
against owners downsizing them into the Depression before the word
downsizing was invented. Today, of course, the steel mills mostly
have been moved to other countries. Even in its own time, ``The
Cradle Will Rock'' probably would have joined most earnest agitprop
in being quickly forgotten. But it got a great boost from its
enemies.
</P>
<P>
   When Red-baiting right-wing politicians succeeded in locking the
troupe out of its theater on opening night, the company, with its
ranks swelled by a sympathetic public, marched 21 blocks uptown to
another theater. Forbidden by their own union from appearing
onstage, the actors performed from their seats and other places in
the auditorium while Blitzstein, who was not a member of the
musicians union, accompanied from an onstage piano. The result was
an electrifying evening of musical theater history. Using the event
as his centerpiece, Robbins fashions a rousing evocation of a
cultural landscape that much American art can still call home.
</P>
<P>
   Although the film is not without some broad political
cartooning, Robbins adroitly and virtuosically echoes both the
structure of Blitzstein's folk opera and another famous collision
of a few years prior. In 1932, Nelson Rockefeller commissioned
Mexican artist Diego Rivera to paint a mural in the then new
Rockefeller Center lobby, only to have it destroyed when Rivera
insisted on featuring in it both Lenin and a stream of syphilis
bacteria soaring out over the heads of capitalists. In a sense,
this film is Robbins's own version of that mural. It's also a
provocative continuation, metaphorically speaking, of that march
through the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Blades is an enlivening presence as the mischievous
Rivera. John Cusack transcends caricature to actually arrive at
moments of sympathy as Rockefeller, who finds that his appreciation
of art has its limits. Cusack's Rockefeller is the kind of guy who
can dance in Rivera's studio with a reluctant Frieda Kahlo and two
nude models, yet still utterly lack the capacity to appreciate the
rich irony in Rivera's mural sitting above the altar in one of the
great temples of capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   But the main event is the Federal Theater episode, and Robbins
fleshes it out with delicious theatricality, For the most part, it
is wonderfully realized by a cast that somehow refrains from
smacking its lips over the juicy parts Robbins has written for
them. It's essential to put a believable Orson Welles on screen and
Angus MacFadyen flails and billows and bellows in an unwavering
state of high dudgeon as the then boy-genius, who saw no conflict
between his self-appointed role as proletarian spokesman and
recipient of liquor-laced luncheons at the 21 Club, that
speakeasy-turned-posh-eatery. Cary Elwes provides droll
counterpoint as his snooty and mismatched colleague, John Houseman.
We can believe that however ill-suited they may have been, they
were amazingly productive.
</P>
<P>
   Working the up-market end of Robbins's canvas are Vanessa
Redgrave, as a dithery but well-intentioned patron of the arts,
Philip Baker Hall as her steel magnate husband who at least doesn't
pretend to be a deep soul, and Susan Sarandon, as Mussolini's
smooth ex-mistress and current emissary, offering the plutocrat a
da Vinci as a bribe to keep exporting steel to Il Duce. In
deliberate and effective contrast that leaves no shred of doubt
about the dialectic Robbins is after, John Turturro shines as a
poor but principled actor who turns his back on the security
offered by members of his family because he won't endorse their
tolerance of fascism. Hank Azaria is another plus as Blitzstein,
haunted by visions of his big influence, Bertolt Brecht.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Watson burns with pale fire, too, as unemployed Olive
Stanton, who played the key role of a prostitute in the musical,
then disappeared from view. With her expressive button face
dominated by eyes that dare not be anything but pragmatic as she
contemplates the source of her next meal and a plan for getting
through the night, Watson's performance effortlessly hits the right
note of Depression-era poignancy that would never dream of
descending to self-pity. Watson is the soul of the movie. The
others talk a lot about the masses and the bread stolen from the
mouths of workers. When Watson's blue eyes go dead, we know she's
the one who has actually gone hungry.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Cusack and Bill Murray make emotional poverty piercingly
poignant as pinched, damaged people who give more comfort to the
enemies of the Federal Theater than to each other.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to pick a favorite performance, it would be that of
Cherry Jones, as that indefatigable warrior, Hallie Flanagan, who
not only convinces as the rock upon which the theater is built, but
as the angel of theater itself. Long after the Federal Theater and
its comrade in arms, The Group Theater, dissolved, they continued
to catalyze the best in taboo-shattering American theater, with a
spirit of insurrection built into its ethos.
</P>
<P>
   Working the other side of the street, Sarandon is scarcely less
wonderful as Mussolini's press agent, drumming up good will and a
steel deal. Not that ``Cradle Will Rock'' is without a few missteps
in its rush to line up its dialectics. I wish, for instance, that
more care had been taken in the casting of William Randolph Hearst,
who just four years later was to clash famously with Welles over
``Citizen Kane.'' But Robbins and ``Cradle Will Rock'' are on the
side of the angels here, and their shortfall is the result of
overreaching ambition. Although downsizing and homelessness have
hardly vanished, ``Cradle Will Rock'' is virtually alone in
reigniting the activist torch as grandly as it does and recapturing
the sizzle of the '30s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
