<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 89, HE HAS DONE IT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you tried to figure out which New Englanders got the most
fun, adventure, and zest out of the century nearing its end, you'd
be hard pressed to do better than settle upon Bradford Washburn and
his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he sweet-talked the former Barbara Polk into a life
of mountain-climbing and exploration to spice up the routine of
museum work, the wiry 89-year-old and his spouse have been up and
down more often than Jack and Jill.
</P>
<P>
   Explorer, cartographer, climber, and photographer of the
planet's wildest and most remote places, Washburn's life unrolled
like an endless script of an adventure novel from the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Mt. Everest, Mt. McKinley, and the Grand Canyon have all fallen
under his eye, lens, and mapmaker's pencil. And the fruits of a
remarkable life are gathered in an exhibition at Boston
University's Department of Special Collections in the Mugar Library
off Commonwealth Avenue. There's a picture of his father, Henry,
dean of the Episcopal Theological School, riding a white horse
along an unpaved Brattle Street in Cambridge in 1910, the year
Bradford was born.
</P>
<P>
   A collection of the family letters and photographs, astonishing
for their freshness and cheerful affection, detail a childhood that
seems scripted for a simpler, more idyllic era. When Brad became
captain of the Groton School baseball team, father weighed in with
a manly letter of congratulations, leavened with Victorian-era
advice useful to this day:
</P>
<P>
   ``Watch the way your men play . . . be particularly careful to
find out which boys are the best heads, that is the boys who are
calmest and make the quickest and best decisions as to what plays
to make, and then find out where they play the best. And be just as
strict with yourself as you are with the others.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a crude but serviceable childhood map of Squam Lake in
New Hampshire, with colored shading indicating best spots for
pickerel and bass fishing. A typed manuscript from the boy
naturalist later made it into print in ``The Churchman'' magazine.
Brad sternly admonishes piscators: ``I have fished to eat, it is
not good to fish for fun and after you have a great many fish to
throw them away or give them to the cat. God never intended them to
be thrown away, he expects them to swim around and chase their
tails.''
</P>
<P>
   At 17 he climbed Mt. Blanc, Western Europe's tallest peak, and
wrote about it. In Alaska, he climbed down a tricky crevasse at the
end of a 100-foot rope to rescue three fallen sled dogs, a perilous
business that qualifies him as dog lover of the century.
</P>
<P>
   His honeymoon with Barbara included ``bringing along eight
college kids,'' says Tom Winship, the retired Boston Globe editor
who photographed the couple atop Alaska's Mt. Bertha in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I recall,'' Washburn deadpanned the night of his BU exhibit
opening, ``I set the camera up, handed it to Tom, and told him just
to push the button.'' Mt. Bertha was named for a famed local
prostitute, a landmark in her own way, Washburn chortled, a fact he
learned only later.
</P>
<P>
   Winship said the 1940 party included a European ski instructor
``who turned out to be a spy; the SOB had been a leader of Nazi
youth in Salzburg. He was arrested after we got back from the two
months on the glacier.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit displays a cautionary letter from Gilbert Grosvenor,
the gray eminence of the National Georgraphic Society, and warns of
an upcoming Alaska trek when Brad was, at age 24, appointed chief:
</P>
<P>
   ``Yours is the first expedition we have trusted to a man as
young as yourself . . . The ascent of previously unscaled mountains
is always attended with considerable uncertainty and peril . . .
The fact that you have, in your few years of active work, made a
really remarkable record of achievement in Europe, the United
States, and Alaska, which is good evidence of your ability to
prepare beforehand, might very naturally lead you to be a little
over-confident and to take risks in this summer's expedition that
an older man might not venture to take.''
</P>
<P>
   But it all ended well, as did most of his jaunts, including
hanging out of a plane over Mt. Everest with a camera.
</P>
<P>
   Photos of Washburn's astonishing landscapes are in a concurrent
exhibit at the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Do not count Brad Washburn among those who look back with more
fondness than they contemplate the road ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you pass 80, one must spend every single minute looking
ahead,'' he said in a speech in Switzerland five years ago. ``We
are living today in an ever-more-thrilling world.'' Between
adventures, he led the Museum of Science to ``keep the public,
young and old alike, abreast of this marvelous world of change _ to
open eyes, to broaden horizons, to stimulate the curiosity and
creativity of our citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Dr. Howard Gotlieb, who heads BU's Special Collections,
``Brad has done everything, been everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad way to pass the century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
