<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GODSMACK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GODSMACK'S MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aerosmith is headed out of town _ and so is Phish and the J.
Geils Band, the other area giants that have played many New Year's
Eve shows around town. That leaves newly crowned stars Godsmack to
fill the local concert void with ``Smackfest 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you heard it right _ ``Smackfest 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an ambitious, hard-rock event coming to the unlikely
setting of Boston's Bayside Exposition Center, which more typically
has car shows and flower shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed some room, and we're going to try to make it as much
of a festival atmosphere as possible,'' Godsmack's Sully Erna says
of his band's New Year's Eve bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have vendors in the crowd, psychic readers, and
a Harley-Davidson exhibition _ stuff like that. And we'll have two
stages. We're hoping between 7,000 and 10,000 people show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Godsmack will perform late (``we have a special surprise at
midnight,'' says Erna), capping a high-decibel, sonic slugfest that
includes Staind, Tree, and Reveille. And if all goes well, then
``maybe every year we'll have a Smackfest. I don't see why not.''
</P>
<P>
   Erna and his mates are an ambitious bunch _ and their ambition
has been rewarded this year. The band's self-titled album sold 2
million copies _ the most for any Boston act this year. Its twin
radio hits, ``Whatever'' (core verse: ``I'm doing the best that I
can _ now go away!'') and ``Keep Away,'' have made the band this
year's most-played group on active-rock radio stations in the
country, according to trade magazine Radio &AMP; Records.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's awesome considering that Metallica is mandatory on
every rock station,'' says Erna, whose group likewise beat out Limp
Bizkit and Rage Against the Machine for airplay.
</P>
<P>
   Godsmack also was on the summer Ozzfest tour and had a major
coming-out show at Woodstock '99, where its intense, hammer-down
set ranked among the best of that crazy weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great year. We've grown at a really good pace,''
Erna says from Birmingham, England, where Godsmack is finishing a
European tour with Black Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of good times, we've been seeing all different
kinds of countries, the album's been selling well, and we put out
three videos. We're building our fan base every day. It's just been
an amazing year. In one sense it's a surprise, but in the other
sense, we're very glad that we're being rewarded for all the hard
work we're doing on the road. We are definitely pounding away out
here, and everyone is just super-fried at this point. This is our
14th month in a row that we've been out and we're just tired and
want to go home and rest and recharge our batteries. But at the
same time, at least while we're going through this kind of work and
exhausting ourselves, it's paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the European tour with Sabbath, Godsmack, which first won
fame by being played on local station WAAF-FM (107.3), did its own
autumn headlining tour of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had such a high demand for it that we built a stage and
added crew members and we had lights and riggers and sound
technicians and all sorts of people working for us,'' says Erna.
``We had two 18-wheelers and two tour buses and we took the show on
the road. We nearly sold out everywhere we played and everyone did
a really good job. But it was hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The group has kept plowing ahead _ and Erna hasn't lost his
voice, a rarity for a hard-rock belter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, it just hangs in there with me,'' he says
of his instrument. ``I don't really have that much of a problem
with losing my voice. Sometimes I get tired, but a lot of that is
self-induced pain, because I drink too much the night before. All
in all, I've had really good luck with my voice and I don't know
what to attribute that to. I wasn't ever trained, or anything like
that. Whatever I'm doing, I'm doing fairly right.''
</P>
<P>
   He has suffered, however, through a bout of insomnia, which
struck him on several recent nights of the European tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's because my body didn't get used to Europe time
and I am still on Eastern time,'' says Erna, whose band has been to
Europe twice this year, but will take next month off and then start
a new album in February. ``It's also because I'm anxious to get
home and I have so many things to do for Christmas, it just keeps
my mind running at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of home were noticed in recent gigs in the German cities
of Munich and Stuttgart, where fans held aloft WAAF shirts for the
band to see. ``I thought: Either someone is here on vacation or
they've been doing their homework,'' says Erna.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Godsmack was treated by the headlining Black
Sabbath, Erna replies, ``They're pranksters! When we did the show
in Munich, it was in this old warehouse building, and above the
left-hand side of the stage is this catwalk where you walk over the
crowd. So if you open the dressing room doors, you can look over
the catwalk and down below, where they are serving beers. Me and
Robbie (Merrill, a Godsmack bandmate) are standing out there,
leaning against the railing, and right below us were three or four
girls cracking beers for everybody. Suddenly, Ozzy and Tony
(Osbourne and Iommi, respectively, of Sabbath) come flying out of
the room and Ozzy throws down two stink bombs and runs back into
their room, so we were blamed for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that was my Ozzy story for the tour. And the funny thing
is, when we first met his son Jack at the Ozzfest, we met him the
same way. He came around the corner in a golf cart and threw a
stink bomb at everyone. Now I know where he gets his personality
from! But, really, they're funny guys. They're just having a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   One final note about the Smackfest: It will be taped as part of
a future home video. ``We have been shooting since the Ozzfest,''
says Erna. ``So we have a lot of pretty funny footage. And
Smackfest will be the climax of the year. We will definitely get it
on film.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
