<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONADVERTISING-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MERCHANT SELLS THE HOPE OF SMARTER KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For late 1999, the advertising formula for e-commerce retailers
has been pretty straightforward: Raise a bunch of money, then throw
most of it at a big television ad campaign that drives customers to
the retailer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com Inc. employs a different kind of marketing
strategy, one that relies on everything from plugs on McDonald's
lunch tray liners to e-mail solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Like many others, SmarterKids.com sells toys on line. A rival is
eToys Inc., which has spent an estimated $40 million on ads over
the holidays, as it aims to become the top on-line toy store.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when education reform is a hot issue, SmarterKids.com
looks to differentiate itself from the competition by targeting
educational toys.
</P>
<P>
   At its Web site, parents can fill out questionnaires about their
children, entering age, personality traits, and scores from such
standardized exams as the MCAS in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   After processing this information, a program on the Web site
presents users with a list of toys, games, and educational products
that is intended to meet the individual needs of the child.
</P>
<P>
   This capacity makes SmarterKids.com's Web site the equivalent of
``a smart sales clerk,'' says chief executive David Blohm from the
company's Needham, Mass. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Other Internet toy stores are mere ``catalogs on line,'' he
said. But SmarterKids.com ``takes e-commerce to the next level,''
Blohm said.
</P>
<P>
   When parents make repeat visits to SmarterKids.com, its
storefront software takes into account past purchases and what
parents have told it about their children. In other words,
different parents see a different mix of products when they visit
the site.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to inspire customer loyalty by ``creating a private
store for every child,'' Blohm says.
</P>
<P>
   On-line toy stores have been put to the test this holiday
season. In some cases, big television ad campaigns have driven more
traffic to some of these Web sites than they can handle. One site
that's struggling belongs to Toys ``R'' Us Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it has done far less television advertising,
SmarterKids.com can make the claim that it's had no big problems
with site crashes and bungled orders.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings groups have given high marks to SmarterKids.com's site,
but investors remain wary. In its first day of public trading last
month on Nasdaq, SmarterKids.com stock traded at 14. Thursday its
shares closed at 8.
</P>
<P>
   EToys has seen an even more dramatic swing. In three months, its
stock has fallen from 80 to just over 30. Perhaps investors fear
that a post-holiday shakeout will inflict heavy casualties on the
crowded on-line toy retail category.
</P>
<P>
   One challenge ahead for SmarterKids.com: It outsources its
warehouse operations and may soon outgrow its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Hambrecht &AMP; Quist LLC, the lead manager of the initial public
offering for SmarterKids.com, projects fourth-quarter sales of $4.3
million and next year's sales at $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com may need fewer television ads because it refuses
to sell television-hyped toys such as Pokemon and Furby.
</P>
<P>
   Many on-line toy merchants have been devoting 75 percent of
their marketing budgets to television ads, said Al Noyes, a
SmarterKids.com executive. His company, in contrast, is spending
only about a quarter of its marketing dollars on television.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed at working mothers and created by the Wenham ad agency
Mullen, a SmarterKids.com television ad campaign has been airing
for the past few weeks. The ads show children at play. ``Open
minds, open worlds'' is part of the message.
</P>
<P>
   SmarterKids.com declines to disclose how much it spends on
marketing, but a chunk of its money goes to buying customer lists
from other Web sites, such as Coolsavings.com, which promises
consumers all sorts of discount coupons and rebates in return for
some personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Once in possession of one of these lists, SmarterKids.com
behaves like a company sending out a mass mailing. But instead of
snail mail, SmarterKids.com uses e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Potential savings may be enormous. It costs about 70 cents for a
direct marketer to send out a piece of mail, Blohm says. An e-mail
can cost less than a dime, and consumers tend to respond to e-mail
faster than other direct marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to reach a broader audience, SmarterKids.com recently
paid McDonald's Corp. to print some SmarterKids.com literature on
the fast-food company's tray liners. The liner copy makes a claim
that SmarterKids.com can help turn children into better readers.
</P>
<P>
   Another marketing effort has SmarterKids.com operating boutiques
for so-called content Web sites, such as LightSpan.com, a sort of
on-line community of teachers.
</P>
<P>
   While such boutiques boost revenues, another goal is to raise
the visibility of SmarterKids.com with educators. The hope is that
when parents ask a teacher how to help their child improve in
school, one piece of advice might be: ``Check out
SmarterKids.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Such initiatives are aimed at customer acquisition, Blohm says,
while radio and television advertising will mostly be reserved for
building the SmarterKids.com brand.
</P>
<P>
   Says Blohm, ``TV can only be part of an overall strategy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
