<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GALAXY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE SPOOF HITS ITS TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GALAXY QUEST 
Directed by: Dean Parisot 
Screenplay by: David Howard, Robert Gordon 
Starring: Tim Allen, Sigourney Weaver, Alan Rickman, Tony Shalhoub,
Sam Rockwell, Daryl Mitchell, Enrico Colantoni, Robin Sachs,
Patrick Breen, Missi Pyle, Jed Rees, Justin Long 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Rated: PG (some action violence, mild language and sensuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Galaxy Quest'' isn't the first film to goof on ``Star Trek,''
but it may be the first to include a role for Trekkies. That's part
of what makes it a clever, affectionate, and entertaining holiday
snack for sci-fi fans. Falling somewhere between slick and cheesy,
it wrings levity from a mischievous concept _ TV stars of a
canceled series spacejacked by naive aliens in need of protection.
They think the actors are real space heroes. The stars, meanwhile,
are stars no longer. The series was canceled 20 years ago. They
grumpily appear in costume at conventions of die-hard fans called
Questarians, but only so they can pay their bills by signing
autographs at $15 a pop.
</P>
<P>
   It won't do to push the correspondences too far, but there's
something of William Shatner's Kirk in Tim Allen's Commander
Taggart. Alan Rickman's Dr. Lazarus looks a little like a Klingon,
but he's obviously the Spock figure. And Sigourney Weaver's
Lieutenant Tawny Madison is at the opposite end of the spectrum
from her Ripley character in ``Alien.'' Much is made of her
abundant cleavage, but the space bimbo stuff is offset by the fact
that the actress she's playing, Gwen DeMarco, is the most sensitive
and perceptive among the group. Rickman gets the most mileage out
of their communal gloom as a Shakespearean actor steeped in
melancholy.
</P>
<P>
   The good aliens are amusingly conceived too. Looking like
tutti-frutti octopuses, they're able to alter their appearance to
seem sort of human in a stoned way. They suggest cousins of Brent
Spiner's Data on helium, as they blissfully wait for the heroics to
start once they've beamed the actors aboard the real spaceship they
modeled on the bare-bones sets they saw on reruns they picked up in
space. Enrico Colantoni, the photog of ``Just Shoot Me,'' is
sweetly goofy as the trusting leader of the dwindling race known as
the Thermians. He's ably abetted by Missi Pyle's intergalactic
Betty Boop, who falls for Tony Shalhoub's faux engineer.
</P>
<P>
   The bad guys, led by Robin Sachs, suggest a gang of angry and
heavily armed lobsters. The action, especially on a sandy planet,
has the primitive feel of vintage TV. The special effects are good
enough, and the creatures include one original _ a monster made
entirely of boulders. Insofar as the film has a message, it's about
being nice to your fans, because you need them more than you think.
This is borne out when the actors don't know how to make the
spaceship work, and have to phone one of their maniacal devotees on
Earth to get help. What's funniest, apart from Allen's riffs on the
has-been's ego, are the sweetly loopy aliens, tottering a la C3PO
up and down this or that very functional, very bare corridor.
``Galaxy Quest'' is a savvy little side dish of a movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
