<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-AFFAIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AFFAIR' SHOWS ITS CRAFT, BUT WASHES OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE END OF THE AFFAIR 
Written and directed by: Neil Jordan (based on Graham Greene's
novel) 
Starring: Ralph Fiennes, Julianne Moore, Stephen Rea, Ian Hart,
Jason Isaacs, James Bolam, Samuel Bould 
Running time: 105 minutes 
Rated: R (scenes of strong sexuality) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The End of the Affair'' is that most heartbreaking of artistic
endeavors _ the immaculately crafted film that just sits there and
refuses to come to life. Or at least not the extraordinary kind of
life it asks of itself. Maybe it's all the rain. It seems to be
raining all the time in Neil Jordan's downbeat take on Graham
Greene's semi-autobiographical World War II love story. Actually,
it's really more about the cost of love than about love itself,
although there are more than a few really sexy scenes between Ralph
Fiennes's novelist and Julianne Moore's appetite-filled but
unsatisfied wife of a diplomat. When they make love as the air raid
sirens howl, it's sometimes the Luftwaffe that makes the earth
move.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we can believe in the liberating sexiness, we also can
believe in the novelist's fulminating jealousy when after one
particular bomb blast the woman named Sarah inexplicably ends the
affair. The mystery of what made her do so is what occupies most of
the story, with copious flashbacks and no small amount of irony,
that begins just after the war, in the omnipresent drizzle, when
the husband asks the novelist, whom he met but never suspected was
cuckolding him, to trail his wife because she's been behaving
mysteriously. This sends the novelist into a much more agitated
state than the husband's. If she didn't end the affair to go back
to her husband, then who is her new love interest? It's consuming
him.
</P>
<P>
   If Greene saw himself in the novelist, it can't be said that he
painted a flattering self-portrait. Not all of Fiennes's acuity can
overcome the fact that the novelist is more than a bit of a pill.
Julianne Moore of the alabaster skin _ having herself quite a year,
what with ``An Ideal Husband'' and ``Magnolia'' _ fills the screen
with genteel anguish as well as a quite believably earthy side.
Yet, filled with grace as some of them are, the pieces never really
add up here, and the answer to the mystery, when it is revealed,
falls short of amazing us.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been scrupulously faithful to Greene's novel and this
film at least is miles ahead of a 1955 version with Deborah Kerr
and Van Johnson. Longtime Jordan collaborator Stephen Rea does a
heroic job of projecting understated decency and thus is seemingly
sympathetic as the husband. Never is he merely a boring cuckold,
even if he apparently doesn't know enough to come in out of the
rain. Still, ``The End of the Affair'' falls stubbornly short of
making a serious bid to enter the pantheon of star-crossed lover
films. This waterlogged ``End of the Affair'' recalls ``The English
Patient,'' but with rain instead of sand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
