<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CLICK BEFORE CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, Virginia, there is an Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   'Twas the night before Christmas, and all through the house,
</P>
<P>
   not a creature was stirring, not even the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Its duty was done _ click, click, click, click.
</P>
<P>
   And now we no longer needed St. Nick. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The packages were stacked near our doorstep with care.
</P>
<P>
   Like a cyberspace miracle, they landed there.
</P>
<P>
   All we must do is wrap them with glee
</P>
<P>
   and put them under our Christmas tree. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, out on the porch there arose such a clatter,
</P>
<P>
   we looked outside to see what was the matter.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mike down the street, with a problem, you see.
</P>
<P>
   He had nothing to put under his Christmas tree. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He ordered on line for Robert, who's 5.
</P>
<P>
   But, for some unknown reason, things never arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``What should I do?'' he said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just say Santa's late,'' we smugly said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As he scampered off quickly, in search of a mall,
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the Christmas lists we used to scrawl.
</P>
<P>
   There were no videos, Nintendo or special Game Boy _
</P>
<P>
   just books, a doll, and a favorite toy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We handed our list to Mom and to Dad;
</P>
<P>
   then just hoped Santa would make us real glad.
</P>
<P>
   The stores were special, filled with delights _
</P>
<P>
   garlands and ornaments, red and green lights. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They went up in December _ not early fall _
</P>
<P>
   and the mood was as bright as a winter snowfall.
</P>
<P>
   It was a treat, way back then, to go to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   We'd go at Christmas and have quite a ball. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But then, something happened, I'm not quite sure why.
</P>
<P>
   It was no longer fun; the stores made us cry.
</P>
<P>
   The parking, the lines, the unfriendly clerks.
</P>
<P>
   The people around us, they were always such jerks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make even an old-fashioned girl,
</P>
<P>
   think the new-fangled Net could be worth a whirl.
</P>
<P>
   I clicked on a Web site, and it hit like a bomb:
</P>
<P>
   There was Land's End and J. Crew and eToys.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just give up your credit card, click on the mouse,
</P>
<P>
   and wait for the goodies to fill up your house.
</P>
<P>
   At first, I was nervous. Was it a safe bet?
</P>
<P>
   Could I shop til I drop and not break a sweat? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of course, said my husband, with manly disdain.
</P>
<P>
   You can run up our debt in sun or in rain.
</P>
<P>
   I did the clothes and he did the toys.
</P>
<P>
   Even in cyberspace, boys will be boys. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We filled up our carts and clicked once to send.
</P>
<P>
   And simple as that, our spree came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   No crowds, no headaches, no hassles, no fuss.
</P>
<P>
   Just a purring PC _ and the two of us. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's scary how simple it could be to spread joy
</P>
<P>
   to a 6-year-old girl and a 10-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   Laying a finger alongside my nose,
</P>
<P>
   I shut down the computer and walked off on tiptoes. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The kids were asleep as I said with delight:
</P>
<P>
   Merry Christmas to all and to all a good night.
</P>
<P>
   As for Mike down the street _ well, things are not yet quite
right.
</P>
<P>
   He still needs a miracle this Christmas night!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(End poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to Clement Moore &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
