<HEADER>
A8375 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MOVIE-RIPLEY-BOS &LR;      12-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RIPLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RIPLEY' A SEDUCTIVE LOOK AT DEVIOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY 
Written and directed by: Anthony Minghella (based on Patricia
Highsmith's novel) 
Starring: Matt Damon, Gwyneth Paltrow, Jude Law, Cate Blanchett,
Philip Seymour Hoffman, Jack Davenport, James Rebhorn, Sergio
Rubini, Philip Baker Hall 
Running time: 160 minutes 
Rated: R (violence, language and brief nudity) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is a slick, twisty, top-of-the-line
crime thriller with gorgeously sensual textures and a screenful of
wickedly faceted performances. But mostly it's the film's avoidance
of simplistic good guy-bad guy labeling that sets it apart. It
grabs us as gradually as temptation grabs Matt Damon's have-not
with his smiling face pressed up against the lifestyle he'd love to
make a permanent part of his life. ``The Talented Mr. Ripley''
knows how corruption works. That's what makes it such an
entertainingly seductive and then unsettling carnival of
deviousness.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Highsmith, who wrote the novel on which the movie is
based, believed that crime, even murder, was not the product of
intrinsically evil people, but of one thing leading to another.
That's the way it happens here as Damon's impoverished 1958 college
grad gets a job playing piano at a rich man's party, is mistaken
for a guest, then is mistaken for a college buddy of the rich man's
playboy son who is knocking around Europe spending the old man's
money, much to the latter's annoyance. So James Rebhorn's grumpy
tycoon hires Damon's Tom Ripley to go to Europe and bring the
spendthrift home. Almost immediately the deviousness starts.
</P>
<P>
   Before he even lays eyes on Jude Law's golden boy, Dickie
Greenleaf, Ripley has a shipboard encounter with Cate Blanchett's
slightly out-of-it socialite, whose yearning parallels his in ways
she'll never know. Not wanting to present himself to her as her
social inferior, he introduces himself as Dickie Greenleaf. She
buys the lie. For a moment, they're soulmates in yearning, sharing
a communion that only he's clued into. She has money, but not the
entree she thinks Dickie can give her. He has neither money nor
entree, but his mind starts racing after both.
</P>
<P>
   It's at that point that Ripley's smile changes. His toothy grin,
initially boyish and open, starts looking like the root of all
evil. We wouldn't feel the evil if we didn't first feel the
yearning. And the yearning in Ripley's case is nothing more than
good old American ambition and social climbing. We also sense that
the corruption begins in Ripley's rejection of himself because he's
poor. Part of the reason he's such a chameleon is that he feels
empty inside. He feels he has no identity worth asserting. From
there, it's the shortest of leaps to his belief that it's better to
be a fake somebody than a real nobody.
</P>
<P>
   He begins by co-opting Dickie as soon as he meets him, becoming
a double agent by telling Dickie of his father's scheme, proposing
to subvert it by joining forces to spend even more of the old man's
money. Then he begins charming Dickie, bonding with him by feigning
an interest in jazz. He also gets on the good side of Dickie's
girlfriend, Marge, played by Gwyneth Paltrow. They become a
pleasure-seeking threesome, tooling around the warmer precincts of
Italy when la vita was still dolce for rich Americans. The film
would quickly capsize if Law's privileged Dickie wasn't so
believably charismatic, so convincingly cavalier. Next to him,
Ripley, in his specs and corduroy jacket, seems a bit of a dork.
Marge, pressuring Dickie for a commitment, seems brittle.
</P>
<P>
   Bookending Blanchett's deb on the periphery of the story is
Philip Seymour Hoffman's arrogant boor, using his money and
position like a truncheon on poor Tom. Where Blanchett's Meredith
is dense but good-hearted, Hoffman's Freddie is into social
thuggery. If anyone is to die, and you can feel the slippery slope
steepening, you want it to be him. Sure enough, there is a killing.
It happens in an unplanned way, but once it does, everything starts
accelerating, including Ripley's improvisational giftedness, a
surprising revelation of emotional depth in Marge, and the
realization of just how deadly the oedipal war was that Ripley
stepped into between the son on the run and his disapproving
father.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is filled with enlivening detail and specificity.
Damon, revealing a much more explicit and explicitly ruinous
revelation of Ripley's gay crush on Dickie, with this single role
in this singular film impressively extends his reach as an actor.
The others compel as much respect, too. As he showed in ``The
English Patient,'' director Anthony Minghella has a real talent for
conjuring up a sense of place, in this case the seductive
languorousness of the Italian Riviera, where the temptation to
drink a late breakfast in a rented villa with history in every
stone, then sun yourself on the deck of a rented cabin cruiser, is
so irresistible that you can all but feel it dragging Ripley into
its gravitational field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is ``The Great Gatsby'' of crime
capers, as Ripley tries on Dickie's clothes and wonders what it
would be like to try on his life as well. The sun gives way to the
grave clarity of gray skies after Dickie seduces a local woman to
dire effect and we begin to feel the whole charmed interlude slip
away. The emotional jolts, when they come, hit harder than the
proverbial blunt instrument. Minghella's changes most notably
involve, in addition to more overt displays of Ripley's homosexual
attraction to Dickie, a string of male betrayals sustained by
Paltrow's Marge. The film falters in its ending. But Ripley never
does, and neither do any of the players. Like Ripley, the film
takes its cue from jazzy riffs, enjoying the danger of hurtling to
parts unknown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
