<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, Dec. 24, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Saturday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6320,
   
 (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (''a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COPS-TRIAL (Albany, N.Y.) _ The judge picked to preside over the
trial of four white New York City police officers charged with
murdering a West African immigrant in the Bronx is a tough jurist
known for running an orderly courtroom. State Supreme Court Justice
Joseph C. Teresi has served six years as a judge. Earlier, he spent
more than 20 years as an assistant public defender who represented
hundreds of criminal court defendants in Albany County. By CAROL
DeMARE.
</P>
<P>
   REINDEER (Albany, N.Y.) _ We hear about them once a year. They
have Teutonic names like Donner, Blitzen and Rudolph, and lead a
sleigh from the North Pole, delivering presents throughout the
world. That's fine for Hollywood. But in the cruel, sub-freezing
chill of the arctic, the truth is not so glamorous. The North Pole
part is accurate enough; reindeer predominate in Lapland, on the
polar fringes of Scandinavia. The sleigh-driving days are fading,
however, as the Lapps (who like to be called Sami), herd the
domesticated beasts with snowmobiles and all-terrain vehicles. Cute
to children at Christmas, reindeer are food and business to these
herdsmen. Think pelts. Think shoes. Or a variety of delicacies from
smoked reindeer heart to reindeer strips on mashed potatoes with
reindeer gravy and lingonberries. By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-AMNESTY (Albany, N.Y.) _ Four prison inmates serving time
under New York's harsh Rockefeller Drug Laws have been granted
clemency in a yuletide gesture of mercy by Gov. George Pataki. By
LARA JAKES.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
