<P>
   Eds: No new items. All stories except developing stories have
moved. With questions, please page Paul Foutch at 888-782-8655.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CHRISTMAS _ BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Following Christmas
Eve in Bethlehem, the centerpiece of the millennium milestone the
world marks this year. Will include color from the day, from the
crowds gathering at the mosque for noon prayers at one side of
Manger Square, to the Midnight Mass in the Church on the other side
and the Protestants in the Shepherds Fields nearby. Developing.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 6:30 p.m. EST. (Israel is 7 hours ahead
of EST.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR _ ATLANTA _ Rosalyn McCrary had a bad case of the
Millenium jitters. The banquet server at the Marriott Hotel at
Lenox was scheduled to work New Year's Eve but feared leaving her
young son at home alone. So she approached her boss about the
problem. That discussion set into motion a novel way to help
workesrs cope with being sepArated during the holiday. The hotel
management has set aside 50 rooms _ that go for mroe than $200 a
night _ for employees and their families. The hotel will pay the
costs of the room and food for the night. It's a small price to pay
for their peace of mind, said the hotel's GM. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHOPLIFTING _ It's a gangbuster holiday season for retailers,
but it's also one for shoplifters. The more shoppers in retail
stores, the greater the chance that the employees will be
distracted. Thieves are lifting everything from athletic shoes to
CD's, which rank among the nation's most stolen items, according to
a 1998-1999 study conducted by Loss Prevention Specialists, a
consulting group in Winter Park, Fla. (Degross, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-TODAY _ It all began with the birth of Jesus, but
today Santa, Xmas trees, presents and eggnog seem to be the focus
of Christmas. We explore how the holiday has changed in the last
century, focusing on the recollections of people who touch on both
the spiritual and commercial side of the holiday. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTIAN-MUSIC _ DAYTON, Ohio _ James Lloyd looks at the top 10
artists who helped the Christian music explosion in the 1990s. It's
now the No. 5 most popular musical genre, ahead of jazz, metal,
classical and Latin music. Do not use before Dec. 26. (Lloyd,
Dayton Daily News). 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The following package on the truth behind Jesus and his
story has moved through the week and is moving again for today:
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-APPEARANCE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jesus Christ is
worshiped as the human incarnation of the son of God, and his
likeness has been reproduced for hundreds of years by thousands of
artists. But they've all been making it up. The Apostles were
assiduous in copying down Jesus' message, but no one bothered to
write about his appearance. We know some things he said, but not at
all how he sounded. And though Bible readers are given vague hints
about the visage of the Prince of Peace, even those are
contradictory. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-CRUCIFY _ The spikes nailed through Jesus' wrists and
ankles did not kill him. The crown of thorns that cut into his brow
was little more than a nuisance, and the whipping he endured before
he was crucified was almost an act of mercy. (Belkin, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-LIFE _ Jesus may have been the Prince of Peace, but if his
life was at all typical of his fellow Nazarenes in the first
century, he didn't live like royalty while he was growing up.
(Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-MISTLETOE _ The mistletoe you're trying to get caught
under this Christmas season wasn't always the semi-parasitic plant
it is today. According to an old French folk story, mistletoe used
to be a tree in its own right until it was caught in the wrong
place at the wrong time. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JESUS-GIFTS _ It takes a little of the magic away from the Magi
to be able to buy frankincense and myrrh for $2.95 in the incense
department at just about any New Age bookstore. But in their day,
the Three Wise Men had a different set of circumstances with which
to deal. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
