<HEADLINE>
REINDEER IN LAPLAND AREN'T JUST FOR SLEIGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ We hear about them once a year. They have
Teutonic names like Donner, Blitzen and Rudolph, and lead a sleigh
from the North Pole, delivering presents throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for Hollywood. But in the cruel, sub-freezing chill
of the arctic, the truth is not so glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   The North Pole part is accurate enough; reindeer predominate in
Lapland, on the polar fringes of Scandinavia. The sleigh-driving
days are fading, however, as the Lapps (who like to be called
Sami), herd the domesticated beasts with snowmobiles and
all-terrain vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Cute to children at Christmas, reindeer are food and business to
these herdsmen. Think pelts. Think shoes. Or a variety of
delicacies from smoked reindeer heart to reindeer strips on mashed
potatoes with reindeer gravy and lingonberries.
</P>
<P>
   These were among the observations of a group of University at
Albany researchers who visited Finnish Lapland in June under a
3-year, $205,000 National Science Foundation Grant to explore 4
arctic locales. Their purpose was as rooted in '90s values as
reindeer tales are mired in Christmas past: to look at gender roles
among reindeer herders, and show that women in indigenous societies
play an active role in the hunting and processing of food.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Jarvenpa, chair of the UAlbany anthropology department,
sees it as filling in the blanks in the anthropological record,
where women have often been kept on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional view is that women are attached to the home
and hearth,'' he said. ``But if you're actually on the scene,
looking at how these people actually make a living, that view
breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvenpa and Hetty Jo Brumbach, associate curator of
anthropology and co-investigator on the grant, found that even
though men are usually dispatched to kill large animals, women play
a huge role in scouting the game, butchering and processing the
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The pair have traveled to the polar nether-regions of Northern
Canada and Alaska and will go to Siberia this summer to complete
their review.
</P>
<P>
   These unexplored regions, rich in oil and mineral reserves, have
been relatively untouched by industrialization, Jarvenpa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area of the world was contacted rather late by Europeans
and industry is a very recent phenomenon there,'' he said. ``It's a
very unpopulated part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the reindeer population (roughly 700,000 in
Scandinavia) far outnumbers the human population.
</P>
<P>
   Jarvenpa said he didn't hear much about the Christmas-notion of
reindeer in his travels, although much of the story _ including
Santa Claus' elves and their pointy hats _ derives from the dress
of the Sami people and their small frames.
</P>
<P>
   The yuletide lore largely derives from the 1822 poem by Clement
Clarke Moore, known today as ``'Twas the Night Before Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph and his red nose didn't appear until 1939, as a
promotional gimmick by an American retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Such ideas seem remote when reindeer is your daily sustenance,
Jarvenpa said. He sampled a wide variety of reindeer cuisine on his
trip, including reindeer soup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tasty,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
