<SLUG> BC-COPS-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE IN TRIAL OF POLICEMAN HAS REPUTATION AS TOUGH JURIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CARLE DeMARE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Judge picked to preside over the trial of
four white New York City police officers charged with murdering a
West African immigrant in the Bronx is a tough jurist known for
running an orderly courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Joseph C. Teresi was named Thursday
to preside in the trial of officers Kenneth Boss, Sean Carroll,
Edward McMellon and Richard Murphy. The officers are charged with
second-degree murder and reckless endangerment in the Feb. 4
shooting of Amadou Diallo. They are accused of firing 41 bullets,
hitting the unarmed victim 19 times.
</P>
<P>
   The Diallo case is Teresi's most high-profile assignment in his
six years as a judge. Earlier, he spent more than 20 years as an
assistant public defender who represented hundreds of criminal
court defendants in Albany County.
</P>
<P>
   The move by Chief Administrative Judge Jonathan Lippman, head of
the administrative arm of the state court system, ends a week of
speculation over which Albany judge would get the controversial
police brutality case.
</P>
<P>
   The case was moved from the Bronx because of widespread
publicity and anti-police protests after the fatal shooting. The
cops maintain they believed Diallo, a street vendor who had never
been in trouble with the law, was reaching for a gun. The incident
occurred while police were searching for a rape suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi will be in the spotlight because critics see Albany as a
conservative community with a smaller minority population than in
the Bronx. The appointment has already drawn criticism from New
York City activists.
</P>
<P>
   The choice came down to Teresi and Supreme Court Justice Thomas
W. Keegan, the administrative judge in this area. Keegan was viewed
as too busy. As police court judge in 1988, Keegan sentenced the
Rev. Al Sharpton and folk singer Pete Seeger and 10 others to 15
days in jail after a protest here. Sharpton is a key figure in the
Diallo protests, but it is not known whether that sentencing had
any impact on the Teresi assignment.
</P>
<P>
   No date has been set for the start of the trial, although it
could begin as early as Jan. 31, sources said. The Office of Court
Administration may announce a date next week, spokesman David
Bookstaver said.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City appellate court last week moved the case from
the Bronx to Albany to ensure the officers a fair trial. The court
agreed with defense lawyers that widespread news coverage of the
incident and public sentiment, which erupted in demonstrations,
would make it impossible to seat an impartial jury in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi, 53, a Democrat, has handled several criminal proceedings
since becoming a judge, although most of his cases have been civil
matters, the primary focus of the Supreme Court in upstate
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Teresi, who had long sought a judgeship, was easily elected in
November 1993, running with the endorsement of Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an excellent trial judge, and I'm sure he'll do a fine
job,'' Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed as a tough but even-handed jurist, Teresi takes charge of
the courtroom and expects lawyers to proceed in an orderly fashion.
He has been stern, sometimes to the consternation of trial
attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   He is well-versed in the penal code and criminal law procedure,
having worked as a part-time assistant Albany County public
defender between July 1972 and Dec. 31, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   From 1973 until his judgeship, Teresi was an associate and later
a partner with the Albany law firm of Ainsworth, Sullivan Tracy,
Knauf, Warner and Ruslander. As a trial attorney, his emphasis was
on defense litigation in torts, products liability, malpractice,
civil rights violations and industrial accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of Teresi's assignment, dissidents in New York City
were crying foul. Randy Credico of the William Moses Kunstler Fund
for Racial Justice said he had been researching both Teresi and
Keegan, expecting either to be named. The agency focuses mostly on
trying to achieve justice for defendants convicted under the strict
Rockefeller drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   Credico said he doesn't believe that Teresi or Keegan would be
impartial. He said he is forwarding his research on Teresi to
Sharpton who has denounced the moving of the trial to Albany.
Credico is attempting to research Teresi's record regarding
sentencing of minority defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I categorically believe that under no uncertain terms this man
(Teresi) will be pro-defense in this case,'' Credico said. ``When
you become a Supreme Court justice in a conservative city like
Albany _ and even though there are a lot of Democrats, I call them
southern Democrats _ you have to become more pro-prosecution and
pro-police.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, on Thursday at the same time Teresi was being named,
inmate Elaine Bartlett was granted clemency by Gov. George Pataki.
She was sentenced to 20 years to life in Albany County in 1984
under the Rockefeller laws while represented by Assistant Public
Defender Teresi, Credico said.
</P>
<P>
   If the Office of Court Administration ``thinks they gave us the
soft one, someone to mollify the protesters down here, they're
wrong,'' Credico said. ``Judge Teresi is going to be met with just
as much resistance as Thomas Keegan.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresi declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bookstaver defended the choice. ``This was not a quick
decision,'' he said. ``Judge Lippman has been deliberating for
several days. It was an important decision.'' Lippman consulted
with Judge Joseph J. Traficanti Jr., the deputy chief
administrative judge for courts outside of New York City, and
Justice Anthony V. Cardona, the presiding justice of the Appellate
Division in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Taken into consideration was availability, Bookstaver said. ``We
had to find a judge available to take this case right now. Keeping
the case on track was an important factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Expertise was considered, he said, although all the judges
considered were certainly qualified. Demeanor was looked at, along
with fairness, he said. Also it was decided to not choose a county
judge so as not to create a backlog of felony cases in that court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
