<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Saturday, Dec. 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-POPE (Rome) _ In a moment he has been waiting for his
entire papacy, John Paul II on Friday night will open the Holy Door
to Saint Peter's basilica, ushering in a Holy Year that is intended
to set the tone for the entire third millennium. Before celebrating
Christmas Midnight Mass, John Paul II, following a 500-year-old
ritual, will push open wide doors that are kept bricked up until a
Holy Year begins, and sink to his knees in prayer while a choir
sings a Latin acclamation. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-BETHLEHEM (Bethlehem) _ Christmas Eve/Christmas Mass
in the little town where it all began. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israel-Syria-Lebanon developments:
The Israeli government approves expansion of two settlements on the
Golan Heights; a secret Israeli cease-fire with Hezbollah allows
the U.N. to recover guerrilla bodies in southern Lebanon; Prime
Minister Barak appoints a team to negotiate with Lebanon. By Joel
Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-HIJACK (Dateline to kum) _ Developing. An Indian Airlines
plane carrying about 180 people from Nepal to New Delhi was
hijacked today and flown to Pakistan. Hijackers demanding fuel and
food. India says 4 people have been killed on the plane. The
hijackers have not been identified.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Developments in the Chechyn war. By
Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BOULDER-HOMELESS (Boulder, Colo.) _ Overwhelmed by homeless
people, Boulder decides to open a municipal building to the
homeless for the holidays. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-WORKERS (Undated) _ For many Americans, the dawning of a
new millennium is going to mean another day, or night, on the job.
By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-BABIES (Houston) _ So far this year, 13 babies have been
abandoned here. So the city is mounting, a campaign to discourage
such behavior. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-YOUTH-CORRECTIONS (Los Angeles) _ The director of the
California's youth corrections agency has been forced to resign
following an investigation that revealed a pattern of brutality at
one of the state's facilities. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Houston) _ The shuttle astronauts finish up their
repairs to the Hubble space telescope and head home. By Warren E.
Leary. (500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The millennium may turn out to be a
bust, but Christmas 1999 was swinging. Official data will not be
available until early January _ and many of the biggest shopping
days are still to come with post-season sales _ but already retail
analysts are saying the nation's largest stores are right on track
to see a rise in purchasing well in excess of 6 percent. That would
make 1999 the strongest Christmas season since 1992, a fitting, and
not unexpected climax to a year where Americans _ encouraged by a
soaring stock market and rising wages _ have indulged in a
sustained shopping spree. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-BEER (Cairo) _ When the Egyptian government put the
national beer company up for sale a few years ago, nobody was
buying. But Ahmed Zayat, a 30ish Egyptian wheeler-dealer who had
worked for Wall Street firms, saw a gold mine. Nearly three years
after taking control of the company, Al Ahram Beverages, Zayat has
turned it into one of the best performing companies in Egypt. With
the help of consultants from Carlsberg, the Swedish brewer, he has
begun turning out first rate beer. And he has discovered that the
real gold may be in a line of non-alcoholic beers _ some with
apple, lemon and strawberry flavors. Zayat's success has been a
catalyst for a new wave of investment in Egypt. The beer company
was just one of more than 300 state-owned companies that the
government had been hoping to sell as Egypt took the lead in a
shift across the Middle East from centrally planned economies to
free enterprise. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-RATES (Undated) _ For much of this year, the question had
been: What happens if there are real computer generated problems at
the turn to the Year 2000? But as the year wound to a close _ and
as the fears of Year 2000 faded _ the question has changed to: What
if there are no Year 2000 computer problems? That switch in
sentiment, prompted in part by the Federal Reserve's efforts to
assure that financial markets function as smoothly as possible at
year's end, has already helped push Treasury interest rates higher
as investors have decided that they do not need the safe harbor of
the Treasury market. And Treasury interest rates could move even
higher in early January if, indeed, Year 2000 turns out to be not
much more than a computer blip. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   KODAK-FISHER (Rochester, N.Y.) _ George M.C. Fisher, Eastman
Kodak's chief executive, talks about his turnaround effort, as he
prepares to say goodbye. A Q&AMP;A by Claudia H. Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-TOBACCO (Undated) _ The California state treasurer imposes
a moratorium on state investments in tobacco stocks and asks the
state's big public employee pension fund to consider divesting its
shares. By Milt Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-Y2K (Sao Paulo, Brazil) _ With less than a week to go, no
one is quite sure what the fallout will be from Latin America's
approach to dealing with the Year 2000 problem. Some of the
region's poorest countries, like Paraguay, are drastically
ill-prepared, while other nations, like Chile and Mexico, planned
ahead and budgeted funds to sufficiently adapt their government
computers. Nevertheless, there appears to be a consensus emerging
among the people who have been rushing to prepare the region: The
parts of Latin America most at risk are also the most
technologically advanced, while the most underdeveloped regions,
while they will almost surely also be affected by the problem, are
not likely to suffer as much as the pockets of wealth. By Simon
Romero.
</P>
<P>
   Editors, U.S. markets are closed for the long holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
