</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC VIEW: VIRGINIA GOVERNOR LEADS CHARGE AGAINST TAXING
INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To listen to Virginia Gov. James Gilmore, a
conservative, tax-cutting Republican, the escalating debate over
whether to make the Internet a permanently tax-free shopping zone
is no contest.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside concerns that state and local sales tax revenue
would dry up as shoppers fled the malls for the Web. He suggested
that traditional retailers should stop whining about unfair
competition from the Internet and start viewing the technology as
an opportunity to build new markets. And he said the best economic
strategy is to nurture the Web's potential to preserve the
competitive advantage that is the basis of the America's current
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the slightest interest in destroying the tax base
of cities, states and counties,'' said Gilmore in an interview.
``But there is an interesting philosophical debate going on here.
Some politicians are basically saying that you have to have
fairness and a level playing field. Since we're going to have a
sales tax, we have to apply it to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Gilmore said, is precisely the wrong approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government is entitled to the revenue it needs to provide
services, but it is not entitled to reach into new areas to get
revenues it doesn't need,'' he said. ``Government is not entitled
to a taxation windfall just because a new industry has emerged.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts that the Internet is reshaping the
economy in fundamental and far-reaching ways, they were dispelled
this year, as dot-com stocks drove Wall Street, as the stodgiest of
corporations embraced the power of the Web and as technology-driven
enhancements in business efficiency startled Alan Greenspan and his
colleagues at the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   But economic policy-makers are only beginning to respond, and
the political parties are just starting to recognize the potency of
technology-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   No issue has had a higher profile in recent months than tax-free
cybershopping, a perk (or quirk) of electronic commerce that
millions of consumers enjoyed for the first time this holiday
shopping season. Online shoppers usually must pay for shipping, but
rarely pay any sales tax on goods bought from companies that do not
have physical presence, like a store or a warehouse, in the state
where they live.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has come up regularly in the presidential campaign.
Both Al Gore and George W. Bush have said they favor extending the
current moratorium on Internet taxation while the matter is
studied, but are concerned about the fallout for state finances and
traditional retailers. Most of Bush's Republican rivals want to
make the moratorium permanent.
</P>
<P>
   It is a tough issue, raising questions of fairness and ideology
without providing much middle ground on which a compromise can be
built, and there are passionate voices on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But no one argues the case against Internet taxation more
vociferously or with greater certitude than Gilmore. He has built
his political identity on tax cutting, and the state he governs is
home to one of the most successful technology corridors outside
California, with America Online among his many Internet-dependent
constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore was chosen by Republican leaders in Congress to be
chairman of a national commission studying the issue. Its latest
meeting, this month in San Francisco, reached a deadlock between
members who think applying sales tax to electronic transactions is
both proper and technically feasible and those, like Gilmore, who
think it would be a mistake and would anyway be too complicated to
enforce.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Gilmore said, there is no sign that online sales
are coming at the expense of traditional retailers or are eating
into state and local tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statistical data will have to come later,'' he said. ``But
at this point you only have to look into the stores and the malls
and ask, `How's business?' Business is booming. There is no
evidence I can see that sales tax revenue is down or that commerce
in traditional bricks-and-mortar retailing is down.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's message to traditional retailers, especially
local stores, is to stop fighting the Internet and embrace it:
``It's wonderful for small business. It's a dynamic development
that gives small-business people the ability to broaden their bases
and compete with big business.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore acknowledged the importance of ensuring Internet access
for the poor, so online commerce and its benefits will not flow
only to those who can afford computers and monthly service fees.
</P>
<P>
   His bottom line is that because no one can foresee precisely how
electronic commerce will develop or what its economic effects will
be, the best policy is to bar the door to Internet sales taxes. But
that same uncertainty might equally argue for a more flexible
approach, one that does not prejudge where technology will drive an
economy now changing in ways no one yet fully grasps.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1509EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
