<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8429 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-PROFILE-LOVEMAN-A     12-24 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PROFILE-LOVEMAN-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HARVARD TO HARRAH'S, IN SEARCH OF FREQUENT GAMBLERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Gary Loveman, chief operating officer of Harrah's
Entertainment, thinks gamblers are promiscuous. ``We have customers
who play around with everybody,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He is referring not to bedroom habits, but rather to gamblers'
lack of loyalty to any particular casino company. Loveman, a former
Harvard Business School professor, is trying to change that. If he
succeeds, he will have created a new model for growth in the casino
business.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's has invested more than $100 million in computers and
software to develop what is widely regarded as the industry's most
sophisticated ``frequent bettor'' program. Like airline
frequent-flier plans, Harrah's ``Total Rewards'' program awards
participants with perks _ in this case, rooms, meals and other
benefits _ and bombards them with promotional mail.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to grow by getting more business from Harrah's
existing casinos and customer base. That is in contrast to the
strategy of other companies: building splashy new casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a huge margin for profitable growth without having to
build ever more elaborate and sophisticated facilities,'' said
Loveman, wearing a pullover shirt at Harrah's headquarters here,
where everyone else seemed to be in suits. It is, he said, ``the
triumph of software over hardware in gaming.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, analysts say, the strategy is working. Harrah's and its
chief executive, Philip Satre, have received praise from trade
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Coccimiglio, an analyst with Prudential Securities, said
Harrah's has had greater revenue growth in most markets than the
industry as a whole, despite having casinos that are far from the
fanciest. In the third quarter, he said, Harrah's grew nearly three
times as fast as the overall market in Laughlin, Nev., and twice as
fast in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Even rivals have praise for the initiative. ``Harrah's has done
far better than anyone at that, and they've developed a brand in an
industry that's brandless,'' said James Murren, chief financial
officer of MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   But Harry Curtis, an analyst at Robertson Stephens, cautioned
that it was too early to tell how much of the success stemmed from
Harrah's strategy and how much from the overall strength of the
gambling business.
</P>
<P>
   Loveman, 39, received his doctorate in economics from the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology and became an assistant
professor at the Harvard Business School, writing papers or books
on topics from technology to East European economic reform.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught a popular course in the management of service
companies. ``That was his real obsession,'' said Thomas DeLong, a
professor of management at Harvard. He said it was not unusual for
professors there to go into consulting or investment banking, but
that gambling was a bit of a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Loveman taught a training course at Promus
Cos., predecessor to Harrah's. He was smitten by gambling _ as a
business and as an academic challenge, though not as a pastime.
``It's a data-rich industry,'' he said, ``and analytically it's
quite sophisticated,'' making it an ideal place to test his
theories.
</P>
<P>
   Loveman wrote an unsolicited letter to Satre offering ideas on
how the company could grow. He was hired as a consultant. Later, in
May 1998, though he had never held a full-time corporate job,
Loveman was hired as chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Satre said an outsider was needed to carry out Harrah's
marketing effort.``If there's an analogy, it's Lou Gerstner going
into IBM,'' he said, referring to Gerstner's move from RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Harrah's started its rewards program, in which
customers are issued a card that they insert into slot machines and
that keeps track of how much they gamble. Other casinos have
similar programs, but Harrah's offers it on a national basis, with
the points valid at any of its 19 casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``This works because we have the broadest distribution of
properties,'' Satre said. To expand its empire, Harrah's in the
last two years has bought the Rio Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas and
the Showboat chain and has agreed to acquire Players International
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that generally develops its talent internally,
Loveman has hired data-mining and marketing experts from companies
like American Express. New software has been developed that not
only keeps track of how much customers gamble but predicts who
might be induced to gamble more. The database, which includes
anyone who stays at a Harrah's hotel, now contains more than 18
million names, of which about 9 million are card holders.
Sixty-five percent of the gambling in the company's casinos is now
done by its 9 million card holders, and the revenue from
cross-market customers _ people who play in more than one Harrah's
casino _ has risen more than 30 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   While such databases raise privacy issues, Loveman said the
company does not sell the list to other companies. He dismissed any
concerns that constant promotions could be creating problem
gamblers, saying the company removes anyone from the mailing list
who requests it.
</P>
<P>
   Officially on a two-year leave from Harvard that ends in June,
Loveman spends weekends with his wife and three children at his
home in Wellesley, Mass. But he said that when his leave expires,
he will resign from the ivory tower to stay at Harrah's. ``It's
been certainly the most exciting period of time I've had in my
professional life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
