<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8430 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-INVEST-BROADWAY-ART-2     12-24 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-BROADWAY-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADWAY ANGELS, WITH SMALLER WINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the dance show ``Swing'' opened on Broadway in
early December, the audience had an unusual component: about 50
people in the packed theater had turned up not only to see the
show, but also to see how their investment in it had turned out _
and to celebrate afterward at a new dance club called Exit.
</P>
<P>
   As the song from ``Cabaret'' says, ``Money makes the world go
around.'' That goes for Broadway, too.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance on the Great White Way may be booming, but those
willing to put money into what remains a high-risk, low-return
investment are still hard to come by. As mounting a show becomes
more expensive _ musicals now cost $5 million to $12 million _
producers have been forced to rethink how they finance their
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations like SFX Entertainment, Walt Disney and Cablevision
_ which have produced shows like ``Jekyll &AMP; Hyde,'' ``Beauty and
the Beast'' and ``The Scarlet Pimpernel,'' respectively _ are
digging deeper into their own pockets to mount the splashy
productions that attract big audiences _ and to sustain those that
need time to build an audience after bad reviews (read
``Footloose'').
</P>
<P>
   Some longtime producers are toying with a structure _ similar to
that of a mutual fund _ in which they would establish a pool of
money from investors to support several productions, rather than
raising money project by project.
</P>
<P>
   And the producers of ``Swing'' _ Steven Baruch, a onetime real
estate developer, and his partners Richard Frankel, Thomas Viertel
and Marc Routh _ continue to finance Broadway and off-Broadway
shows as much as possible by shaking the trees for $10,000
increments from a multitude of individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   What's in it for investors? Potential profit, first of all;
investing in theater is by no means an altruistic endeavor. And
there are a few perks: prime tickets to opening night, the
occasionally star-studded party afterward, and other extras like
framed posters, cast recordings or souvenir books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backing a show is different than just going to the theater,''
said Andrew Benerofe, a real estate investor and developer who said
he had never turned down the opportunity to put $10,000 into one of
Baruch's productions. ``You live with the construction and building
of a show.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors, however, have reason to be cautious. Despite the
strong economy and the revival of Times Square, theater remains a
risky investment. With only one of five shows breaking even in the
average year _ let alone making a profit _ big investors in the
shows that fail still stand to be burned.
</P>
<P>
   David Richenthal, who produced last season's hit revival of
``Death of a Salesman,'' said he warns his investors with a
standard speech: ``It's like drilling for oil. There can be two or
three dry holes, but if you stay with it, you can hit a gusher.''
(The critically acclaimed ``Salesman,'' of course, qualifies as a
gusher.)
</P>
<P>
   Because oil drillers are hard to come by, the producers of
``Swing'' raise money one modest investor at a time. Baruch said
the strategy has paid off: if someone had put $10,000 into every
show he and his colleagues have produced since they started 15
years ago, that investor would have seen an internal rate of return
of about 41 percent a year. ``I dare say I doubt anybody has a
better track record,'' Baruch said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for ``Swing,'' which cost $5.6 million, the Baruch group
raised only about $1.5 million from individuals. Baruch said it was
impossible to mount a big musical today with only small investors.
Assuming that ``Swing,'' which opened to mixed reviews, builds an
audience, it will need 28 weeks to recoup its investment at 70
percent capacity _ or 21 weeks at 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most Broadway producers say the Baruch method is too cumbersome.
``When plays _ forget musicals _ cost $1 million to $2 million on
average, it becomes simply too much,'' Richenthal said. ``I find
producing hard enough without having to deal with a group of 50
investors. It would drive me bananas, and I think most of us feel
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Weissler, who with his wife, Fran, has produced Broadway
shows like ``Chicago'' and ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' said cobbling
together small increments takes too much time. ``If you're going to
do a production today, you have to move quickly,'' Weissler said.
``It doesn't allow you two years to raise your capital. Your
financing has to be in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Baruch acknowledges that his job has become more difficult over
the years. In 1985, it took 17 people to raise the $175,000 needed
to produce his first show, ``Penn and Teller,'' off-Broadway. Now,
with shows much more expensive, he has had to build a pool of 200
to 300 investors from which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Penn and Teller,'' Baruch's team made a name for itself
by producing classy off-Broadway shows like ``Frankie and Johnny in
the Clair de Lune'' and ``Love Letters.'' Then it tried its hand at
Broadway and, all told, has backed 35 shows in full or in part,
including the long-running ``Smokey Joe's Cafe'' and a
shorter-lived show, the revival of ``The Sound of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his investors, Baruch said, have stayed active because
they can afford to play around with $10,000 year after year.
``People would not commit suicide if we failed,'' Baruch said.
``And it isn't all that hard to find $10,000 players, given our
track record.''
</P>
<P>
   Benerofe said he made money investing in shows with Baruch like
``Driving Miss Daisy'' and ``Love Letters.'' And although Benerofe
said, ``you go into each one with the idea of making a profit,'' he
added that ``the investments are modest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's not terribly serious if it makes it or it doesn't make
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To update investors on a show's progress, Baruch said, he
inundates them with paperwork _ including all the reviews (bad as
well as good), press clippings from all over the country and
statistics on financial performance.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Producers say investors look for strong track records. Because
of his past successes, Richenthal said he had three times as much
capital offered to him for ``Salesman'' as he needed. And it was
doubly easy to raise money for ``The Price,'' also by Arthur
Miller, which opened this season, because ``Salesman'' was such a
hit. Nevertheless, Richenthal said ``Death of a Salesman,'' which
starred Brian Dennehy as Willy Loman, cost him $2 million to
produce, compared with the $48,000 it cost originally in 1949. The
play closed at a profit after an extended, nine-month run.
</P>
<P>
   But large investors, producers say, can come with their own
baggage. They often want a credit in the program. Sometimes they
fancy themselves as part of the creative team and hold forth with
unsolicited notes on the show (which, producers say, they rarely
pass along to the creative team). And if a show fails, Richenthal
said, some investors will call to complain, ``Why didn't you take
out a bigger ad?'' or ``Why did you take out such a big ad?''
</P>
<P>
   ``They can second-guess whatever you do, and they have a right
to,'' Richenthal said. ``That's why I would rather have a group of
fewer investors and pay proper attention to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Richenthal said he usually gathered 5 to 15 investors for a show
_ each of whom puts in a minimum of $25,000 _ and that he is the
only general partner in what he produces. ``I think there needs to
be one decision maker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors' focus on getting credit can be distracting, he added.
``There are times when those of us who truly are there, stepping on
the grapes 12 hours a day, find the work we do seeming to be
diluted by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Possibly as a result, producers have toyed with the idea of
trying to make themselves more independent of investors. Producers
say that the promise of a public company that is focused on
Broadway productions died last year, when Livent, the producer of
``Ragtime'' and other shows, declared bankruptcy and was later
acquired by SFX. They predicted that it would be a long time before
someone ventured down that road again.
</P>
<P>
   But Richenthal said he was considering identifying a few
specific projects over two or three seasons and raising money for
all of them at once _ the way a mutual fund gathers money to invest
in a portfolio of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   SFX Theatrical chairman and chief executive Miles Wilkin said
his company, along with Jujamcyn Theaters, is considering a similar
venture. ``We have discussed it earnestly over the last 12
months,'' Wilkin said. ``Not only researched it, but structured
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's stopping them? Wilkin said he and his colleagues would
``have to get comfortable with'' having enough projects in
production to make prospective investors feel secure. He likened it
to trusting your fund manager: ``You give up being able to pick
stocks for a predictable rate of return.''
</P>
<P>
   And is there ever such a thing as a predictable rate of return
in the unpredictable world of theater? ``You have to average out
those peaks and valleys,'' Wilkin said.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, old habits die hard, producers say. And theater
investors are used to backing specific shows that interest them,
not simply putting their money and trust in producers.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Roth, who counts ``Wit'' among the many shows she has
produced, said people who support her off-Broadway shows ``have a
different investor mentality,'' less angel than savior. ``They tend
to think, `Gee, this is a good project, and if I don't help it
happen, it might not happen,''' Ms. Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Ms. Roth, who has teamed up with the Baruch group
on several projects, said the multiple-investor approach was not
for her. ``It's tedious,'' Ms. Roth said. ``I give them credit for
being so tenacious.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that his strategy is labor intensive, Baruch
said it has kept him and his colleagues in business. ``When you're
dependent on big players, after a flop or two, you can lose them,''
he said. ``We always have people who will come back for more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
