<HEADLINE>
THE INCREDIBLE DISAPPEARING UNLOVED LUXURY-CAR TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (bl)  
 By WENDY WARREN KEEBLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If buying a Mercedes-Benz S500 or a Cadillac DeVille is on your
list of Y2K resolutions, Congress brings you New Year's cheer. When
the ball drops in Times Square, the luxury-tax rate will fall,
too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As of Saturday, car buyers will pay a 5 percent tax _ down from
6 percent this year _ on the amount by which a vehicle's
transaction price exceeds $38,000.
</P>
<P>
   That $38,000 threshold is more good news: Since 1997, the
federal government has imposed the tax on vehicles costing $36,000
or more. Exceptions are vehicles with loaded weights of more than
6,000 pounds, including large sport utilities like the Cadillac
Escalade, Chevrolet Suburban, Lexus LX 470 and Lincoln Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the luxury tax on automobiles is being phased out on a
schedule that is to culminate in its demise on Jan. 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The changes for 2000 are being toasted by groups like the
American International Automobile Dealers Association, whose
members sell vehicles from foreign manufacturers. The group, which
accounts for a lot of luxury-car sales, has led an industry effort
to eliminate the tax, which took effect in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Even at lower rates, and even among wealthy buyers, the tax can
be a sticking point in negotiations, dealers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people who have incomes that let them afford these cars
have those incomes because they're smart,'' said Walter Huizenga,
president of the dealers group. ``They're good negotiators. It's
not, `I can't afford that tax,' it's `I don't want to pay that
tax.'''
</P>
<P>
   So the tax's decline is good for buyers and sellers. ``It's a
tax that needs to go away, and it is going away,'' Huizenga said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
