<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8433 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO-ART-     12-24 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-VOLVO-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL YOUNG AMERICANS ADOPT A BABY VOLVO? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (bl)  
 By LEONARD M. APCAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, an automaker doesn't want to be caught offering a
dull, me-too product in the heart of the market. The $25,000 price
range is a predatory jungle inhabited by best sellers like the
Toyota Camry and Honda Accord, American favorites like the Ford
Taurus and Buick LeSabre and sporty imports like the BMW 323i and
Audi A4 _ not to mention a battalion of minivans, well-regarded
sedans like the Volkswagen Passat and Olds Intrigue and sporty
coupes like the Toyota Celica.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is also the Volvo S40, a compact sport sedan priced
just below $25,000 that is aimed at the young buyers who have long
eluded, or even ignored, Volvo. This will be a very tough market
for the Swedish company to crack. If things aren't crowded enough
now, Lexus and Jaguar have new small cars in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo, known for its extensive safety features, has generally
catered to older buyers (average age, 45) who didn't mind trading a
little flair in the styling department and a little sizzle under
the hood for big, boxy, even boring designs. Big, boxy and boring
aren't my words _ they rolled off the tongues of 20-to-35-year olds
when Volvo asked them to describe its cars.
</P>
<P>
   With the S40 sedan _ and a wagon version called the V40 _ Volvo
is trying to attract younger buyers with a few coins jangling in
their pockets. The auto marketers call this the ``entry-level
luxury market.'' In fact, it is a big-growth, high-profit business
where every luxury brand worthy of its burled wood inserts and
heated seats is trying to make a splash.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo wants buyers who are under 35 and don't mind the limits of
a smaller car, who want some European panache but might not have
the cash for an Audi, BMW or a Saab, all of which can easily barrel
through the $30,000 level.
</P>
<P>
   The S40 and the V40 are the latest in a string of new models
that Volvo has brought to the United States. By next fall, the
automaker _ which was bought by Ford this year _ will have
completed a three-year overhaul of its entire American lineup. Last
year, its most significant change was the S80, a new flagship sedan
with front-wheel drive and nary a square corner on its skin.
</P>
<P>
   The S40 echoes that look. With a nicely raked front end and a
swooping rear roofline, this curvy little Volvo is attractive. It
feels small inside, but the space is cleverly used. The rear seat
is surprisingly roomy, for instance, thanks to a design trick: The
rear seats are angled back more than usual to put extra space
between the front and rear passengers and increase the headroom.
</P>
<P>
   The S40 comes well-equipped, especially in comparison with the
hot-selling BMW 323i, a car with a starting price $4,000 higher. On
its base model, BMW skimps on touches that buyers have come to
expect: front and rear armrests cost extra, the visors do not have
lighted mirrors and the rear seat does not fold to add cargo space.
</P>
<P>
   The S40, which is built in the Netherlands in a joint venture
with Mitsubishi, comes with all those trimmings and more. While BMW
offers a powerful 2.5-liter six-cylinder engine, Volvo uses a
1.9-liter in-line four that is turbocharged and intercooled to perk
up acceleration. The engine certainly delivers reasonable pickup
and handling for a sport sedan, but it does not have the power
surge of BMW's six. Volvo has tried to reduce the lag time before
the turbo kicks in, but I still noticed a slight hesitation before
the car raced ahead.
</P>
<P>
   With its balanced suspension, precise steering and firm ride,
the BMW 3-Series has long served as the ride-and-handling benchmark
for sport sedans. Volvo cannot match BMW in that respect, but it
does not fall far off the mark. I did not feel as confident in the
S40 on parkway cloverleafs and twisting country roads as I did in
the BMW or, for that matter, in the Audi A4. The Swedes can still
learn something from the Germans about suspensions and handling.
</P>
<P>
   And Volvo might even consult its countrymen at Saab, whose 9-3
and 9-5 cars have the most impressive turbocharged four-cylinder
engines I have yet encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Volvo does excel in safety features. If you want to feel safer,
you might consider an armored personnel carrier. There are two huge
air bags in the dashboard and two in the sides of each front seat
that provide extensive protection to heads and torsos. The
passenger compartment has been substantially reinforced, in case of
a rollover, and the side pillars and door beams were engineered to
absorb the brunt of the impact if the car is struck from the side.
</P>
<P>
   The headrests, though they don't offer much comfort in highway
cruising, are supposed to provide elaborate whiplash protection if
the car is struck from the rear.
</P>
<P>
   For all the focus on safety, however, the S40 does not have a
headrest in the center of the rear seat, something one finds on
less expensive European cars like the Volkswagen Jetta. The S40
does have a three-point belt for the middle rear passenger.
</P>
<P>
   There are also pockets in the backs of the front seats and small
side pockets in the rear doors. The rear seat is split in a 70-30
configuration, and both parts flip down to swallow cargo that the
trunk cannot contain. There was but one cup holder for the rear
passengers (and just one more up front), and the rear windows did
not fully retract.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest annoyance was the placement of the power window
buttons on the center console, next to the mirror controls. With
the armrest down, those buttons are difficult to reach. Time and
again as I approached a toll booth, I groped for the window buttons
and ended up moving the mirrors out of place or accidentally
lowering the passenger window. Volvo says it has heard similar
complaints and plans to redesign the center console on 2001 models.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Volvo was cozy but comfortable. The seats
delivered pleasant support and included adjustable lower-back
support. Wind noise was minimal. The four-speed automatic
transmission has three shift modes: sport, economy and winter. A
five-speed manual transmission is not available, but Volvo says it
is thinking of adding one. Sporting drivers can shift for
themselves with the A4, 323i and Infiniti G20.
</P>
<P>
   In a crowded field, the S40 certainly stood out for its safety
and for its value. Compared with the three cars I drove for
comparison's sake, the S40 was less expensive than the BMW and the
Audi and not much more than the G20. As for the curse of being big,
boxy and boring, Volvo has definitely overcome the first two. It is
making progress on the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
