<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV26-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE (ONLY) THE TALL CORN GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 26, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the flap last fall about Edmund Morris' biography of
Ronald Reagan? Morris invented a fictional first-person narrator in
order to make more readable his ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald
Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   The book has sold briskly, according to Random House: well
enough, but not nearly as well as it might have if it hadn't been
savaged by most historians, journalists, and every self-interested
interpreter of Reagan's reputation on the political landscape. It
has fallen off the best-sellers lists.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked in the fracas was the story of another biography of a
Republican president. George Nash's life of Herbert Hoover took the
opposite tack from that of Morris: scrupulous, lengthy, objective,
scholarly.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's reward was to have the plug pulled on his project halfway
through by his backers, who complained of the cost and the length
of the project.
</P>
<P>
   With three volumes down, and another four or five to go, the
story was beginning to get really interesting. ``The Engineer
1874-1914,'' ``The Humanitarian 1914-1917,'' and ``The Master of
Emergencies 1917-1918'' had been published, heavily subsidized by
their sponsors, the Herbert Hoover Presidential Library
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Another thousand pages had been written on the year 1919 alone,
during which Hoover served as a kind of one-man Marshall Plan in
charge of US aid to Europe and Russia at the end of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   Next would come his years as Secretary of Commerce under Warren
Harding and Calvin Coolidge, his single term as president during
the years in which the Great Depression settled over the industrial
world like an unnatural winter, then the long period of
post-presidential influence among conservatives around the world.
Hoover died in 1964, the year Barry Goldwater was the Republican
nominee for President.
</P>
<P>
   Nash even took a year off to write a monograph on Hoover and
Stanford University. The Quaker-raised youth was a freshman there
when the fledgling university opened its doors in 1891, Nash points
out. He's still there in spirit, in the form of the Hoover
Institution for War, Peace and Revolution, a peculiar research
institute whose great stone tower dominates the leafy campus.
</P>
<P>
   It was all too much for the Iowa businesspersons and Hoover
friends and family members on the board of the Library Association
in the cheerful little farming community of West Branch, Iowa,
where Hoover had been born. By the mid '90s, they were running out
of the money they had to keep Nash writing.
</P>
<P>
   They were reluctant to raise more, impatient to see the end of
the saga, unwilling or unable to find some other GOP moneybags to
take over the project. The president's grandson, Herbert Hoover
III, known as Pete, turned 71 this year. Nash's 80-year-old mother
joked that her son wouldn't finish the project in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1995, after nearly 20 years of supporting the biographer,
the Library Association gave Nash his walking papers. A committee
headed by former Senator Mark Hatfield (R-Oregon) parceled out
assignments for the three remaining volumes of the original plan to
university-based Hoover experts. And George Nash, whose very visage
had come to resemble that of his subject as closely as if he had
been Hoover's son, put down what he thought had been his life's
work and started casting about for another task.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the following question: if the community that
howled at Edmund Morris for the liberties he took popularizing the
Ronald Reagan story cannot support a single superb scholar doing
the definitive life of the other great Republican innovator of the
20th century, just how sturdy are the intellectual underpinnings of
the current wave of conservatism, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   (What about Theodore Roosevelt, president from 1901 until 1909?
He's probably best understood as belonging to the ``long'' 19th
century. Dwight D. Eisenhower was more an interpreter of traditions
pioneered by the Democrats than a GOP original.)
</P>
<P>
   Nash was a freshly-minted Harvard PhD in intellectual history
when he answered an ad from the friends of the Hoover Library in
1974. They were seeking a historian to make use of newly-opened
material at the presidential archive in West Branch, Iowa, not far
from Iowa City. It was a bad year for 20th-century American
historians in the job market. Nash wasn't anxious to leave the
Connecticut River valley where he had been raised (South Hadley,
Mass.) and educated (Amherst College.)
</P>
<P>
   Nash's first book, ``The Conservative Intellectual Movement in
America Since 1945,'' was nearly complete. (It appeared in 1976.)
So rather than sign on as a teacher in a university where he did
not want to be, Nash agreed to write a six-volume life of Hoover,
the contract extending into the mid-1990s. He became an independent
scholar.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the United States was just entering its Turn to
the Right _ then, as now, very little understood. Nash's book
fairly quickly was recognized as a work of profound historical
imagination _ a thorough examination of the intellectual roots of a
phenomenon that had been dismissed nearly univerally in
universities as irrelevant only a few years before.
</P>
<P>
   Here was not just William F. Buckley, the conservative whom
everybody already knew, but Ludwig von Mises, Richard Weaver, Leo
Strauss, Friederich Hayek, Eric Vogelin, Willmore Kendall, Peter
Viereck, Russell Kirk, and a raft of other serious thinkers who
labored far from the media spotlight in the years before the
conservative resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   Yet by the time Ronald Reagan was in the White House, Nash had
shunned the heavily-endowed policy ``think-tanks'' that swept to
prominence with the Republicans in order to spend much of each year
at the presidential library in West Branch. In Hoover's lifetime,
busloads of schoolchildren had been delivered annually to the
presidential homestead, there to sing the state song to the Great
Man (``Iowa! Iowa! That's where the tall corn grows. . .). Now 60
years later a trio of Harvard historians (Richard Norton Smith,
Steven Kesselman, and Nash) labored over his papers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Cato Institute libertarians, American Enterprise
Institute ``paleo-conservatives,'' Hudson Institute
``supply-siders'' spent money like water. Nash bore down in Iowa on
topics as remote from the present day as Hoover's experiences as a
mining engineer and his adventures as a young husband in Beijing
during the Boxer Rebellion of 1900. It was an act of seeming
self-abnegation of astonishing proportions.
</P>
<P>
   As the years rolled on, however _ as Reagan gave way to George
Bush, who in turn was upset after a single term by Bill Clinton on
the strength of a short and mild recession; after Ross Perot, Pat
Buchanan, and Steve Forbes launched an angry revolt _ the Hoover
biography project began to take on significance and charm.
</P>
<P>
   What, after all, were the roots of the man Joan Hoff Wilson had
called ``the forgotten progressive?'' How did Hoover cope with the
strains within the Republican party between cosmopolitan
corporatists and populist isolationists, beginning in the 1920s?
What was the effect on ``liberal Republicanism'' of his eclipse?
</P>
<P>
   It is a truism that each generation must rewrite history in the
light of its own experience. In this sense Nash was the
indispensible historian of the generation of the 1960s _ well into
the task of reinterpreting intellectual experiences that had been
distorted, inevitably, by triumphalist interpretations of Franklin
Roosevelt's New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   Tt was, alas, too good to be true. Arthur S. Link's life-long
preoccupation with Woodrow Wilson (60-odd volumes of edited
papers!); Dumas Malone's six-volume life of Thomas Jefferson; John
Simon's laborious attention to the career of Ulysses S. Grant: all
magnificent obsessions supported by day jobs in universities. The
Hoover Library Association shared no such lofty motives. No other
sponsor could be found. And unlike the Edmund Morris episode,
hardly anyone in the vast conservative opinion-making apparatus
breathed a word.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nash is looking for another commission. Perhaps a full
length sequel to ``The Conservative Intellectual Movement in
America Since 1945?'' ``That is one of the ideas I have been
considering,'' says the historian. At least that book is back in
print, in a handsome 1996 edition, thanks to the Intercollegiate
Studies Institute in Wilmington, Del. Too bad a similarly generous
sponsor couldn't have been found for the rest of the Hoover
project.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
