<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Least E-Tailing Works in High Places
</P>
<P>
   Even President Clinton, for the first time, shopped online this
holiday season. Not surprisingly, he hasn't reported the delivery
problems that some constituents have had.
</P>
<P>
   From his antique wooden desk in the Oval Office, using a Compaq
laptop, the president ordered gifts last Monday from two Web sites,
said Nanda Chitre, a White House spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   He bought horsehair bracelets from a Web site,
www.lakotafund.org, that benefits the Oglala Lakota Nation in South
Dakota. And he bought a book, ``Children from Australia to
Zimbabwe,'' which invites children to experience what it is like to
grow up in other countries, from www.world2market.com.
</P>
<P>
   The gifts were sent to the White House, Ms. Chitre said, using
the special ZIP code that routes mail to the presidential
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Washington, Vice President Al Gore (who once
claimed to be the father of the Internet) also bought gifts online
this holiday season. But a spokesman declined to disclose details,
saying that Gore did not want to look as if he were endorsing
specific sites.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, shopped the
old-fashioned way this year, according to a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Help With That Perfect Gift  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even deep-pocketed executives stumble in buying the right
Christmas gift for their spouses. Al Piergallini, head of worldwide
consumer health at Novartis in Summit, N.J., acknowledges having
even more trouble than most. ``I always try to to find out what my
wife really wants,'' he said, ``but it is very difficult for me to
buy Christmas presents for women.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. On a recent trip to Fortunoff, Piergallini's
wife, Lorraine, spotted a piece of antique silver and asked him to
flip open his wallet. Piergallini obliged, but he still is not sure
what he bought. ``It's hard to say about those antique silver
pieces,'' he said. ``It goes in that category as the silver stuff
you put in your dining room.''
</P>
<P>
   Going Home, After the Holidays  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Clough, chief investment strategist for Merrill Lynch,
hasn't been wild about American stocks lately, but he is bullish on
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Clough, 57, was living and working in the Boston area when
Merrill hired him 14 years ago. He still lives there, commuting to
Merrill's Manhattan headquarters almost every week. Soon, he will
be back in Boston full time _ well, as soon as Merrill decides who
will succeed him. It may take two people.
</P>
<P>
   People at Merrill say David Bowers, the firm's European
strategist in London is in line for the job _ at least the global
part. Bowers, who is British, said decisions would be made after
the holidays. But, he added, ``I'd be very surprised if the U.S.
equity strategy was run by anybody other than an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoting Bowers would reflect Merrill's move from a domestic
firm to a global one. ``The function changed a lot while I was
here,'' Clough said. In recent years, he has spent much time
studying foreign financial markets (racking up more than 3 million
miles on airplanes). He is very proud of his call last year urging
investors to put more money into Japanese securities, which paid
off handsomely. Indeed, he remains bullish on overseas markets,
predicting they will beat the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
next year. His bearish views on domestic investing have been more
controversial, especially among the firm's 14,000 brokers. But
Merrill officials say Clough's departure is unrelated to that
stance.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Merrill, he will set up shop managing money for
charitable foundations and some wealthy families. And he will spend
more time on his other calling. He is a deacon in the Roman
Catholic Church, authorized to marry and baptize people. And, of
course, he helps the Archdiocese of Boston manage its money. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping an Eye on a Rival?
</P>
<P>
   The competition in Brazil's Internet industry is getting really
heated, thanks to Bob Wollheim, president of the Brazilian
subsidiary of StarMedia Network, the New York-based Internet
company that focuses on Latin America. He recently rented the side
of an apartment building near the Sao Paulo headquarters of its
largest rival, Universo Online, for a monster billboard of
StarMedia's logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now when those guys stand up from their desks to look out the
window, they'll be reminded of the competition,'' Wollheim said,
chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Caio Tulio Costa, UOL's managing director, was not amused.
``It's a waste of their investors' money,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
