<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Saturday, Dec. 25, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-HIJACK (Dateline to kum) _ Hijackers on Friday seized an
Indian Airlines plane with 189 people on board, made stops in India
and Pakistan, tried unsuccessfully to land in Afghanistan and then
touched down in the United Arab Emirates. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-POPE (Rome) _ In a moment he has been waiting for his
entire papacy, John Paul II was to open the Holy Door to Saint
Peter's basilica, ushering in a Holy Year that is supposed to set
the tone for the entire third millennium. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-BETHLEHEM (Bethlehem, West Bank) _ In this little town
where Jesus was born, Palestinian police stood guard on the
rooftops of Manger Square Friday as Italian nuns prayed with
clasped hands, American gospel choirs belted out carols and
Filipina immigrants wearing Santa hats boogied on plastic chairs.
By Deborah Songtag.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ After weeks of trying to persuade
Grozny's civilians to flee, Russian officials said Friday that
residents had missed their chance to leave and should hide in their
shelters until Russian forces have secured the city. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-WORKERS (Undated) _ George Fernandes was planning to
throw a big party on New Year's Eve. But he learned many of his
guests could not come. They had to work. ``A couple work for
utilities,'' he said. ``Some are involved with computer systems.
Some work in hospitals.'' The more he thought about it, Fernandes,
an electrician foreman for the city of Cambridge, Mass., decided he
should probably be working too. For many American workers, the
dawning of a new millennium is simply going to mean another day, or
night, on the job, as employers gird for any problems that arise
from Y2K glitches. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON-BABIES (Houston) _ They found the first baby in a
hospital bathroom, a crying newborn whose mother had disappeared.
Five days later a family awoke to find another baby, still bloody
from birth, on the front porch. A third baby turned up a month
later, and then a fourth was found abandoned on a city street. The
cases kept coming until the number reached 13: Three babies were
left outside hospitals. A newborn wrapped in a stained towel was
found at a Holiday Inn. A baby boy only 20 minutes old was
discovered on the grounds of an elementary school. Three babies
were found dead, including a newborn dropped in a Dumpster behind a
high school. Without any apparent pattern, the Houston metropolitan
area has experienced an unprecedented rash of abandoned babies in
the past year. The problem has baffled local officials, who say an
ordinary year might bring two or three cases. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The millennium may turn out to be a
bust, but Christmas 1999 was swinging. Official data will not be
available until early January _ and many of the biggest shopping
days are still to come with post-season sales _ but already retail
analysts are saying the nation's largest stores are right on track
to see a rise in purchasing well in excess of 6 percent. That would
make 1999 the strongest Christmas season since 1992, a fitting, and
not unexpected climax to a year where Americans _ encouraged by a
soaring stock market and rising wages _ have indulged in a
sustained shopping spree. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-RELIGIONS (Undated) _ Studying new religions is a growing
field, attracting psychologists, law anthropologists and literary
critics. Many say we're seeing a spurt of intense religious
activity, comparable to last century when the Mormon and
Seventh-day Adventist churches began. By Gustav Niebuhr. (1350
words)
</P>
</TEXT>
