<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8445 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-DALLAS-ARTS-ART-$     12-24 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-DALLAS-ARTS-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS' DEEP ELLUM: REVITALIZED, FOR WORK AND PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
Joel Kotkin is a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute for
Public Policy. His column on the Main Street economy appears the
fourth Sunday of each month. E-mail: grassrts(AT)nytimes.com.  
 (bl)  
 By JOEL KOTKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In 1986, when Brady Wood came here as a teen-ager from
New Orleans, he thought something was missing in the city _ like a
soul. ``This place was a great cultural void,'' he said. ``Too
clean, too much glass and steel.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Wood, now 32, says Dallas finally has ``a place
that's cool'': the Deep Ellum neighborhood, just across the Central
Expressway from downtown. And he had a hand in transforming it.
</P>
<P>
   Once a jumble of half-abandoned industrial buildings and the
site of the city's largest homeless encampment, Deep Ellum is now a
magnet for young professionals, stylish stores and the city's
growing Internet industry. It has a proliferation of retail
businesses selling most everything from trendy furniture to
tattoos, and dozens of places to eat, drink, dance and socialize.
``This neighborhood,'' said Wood, who owns two nightspots and two
restaurants in the district, ``could be the next Melrose or Soho.''
</P>
<P>
   There is more to the comparison than a developer's enthusiasm.
The evolution of Deep Ellum into a thriving entertainment and
creative business center reflects a broader national trend. Growing
populations of single people, young couples without children and,
more recently, empty nesters are recolonizing near-downtown
districts in New York, San Francisco, Seattle, Chicago and other
cities, and creative businesses like design studios, ad agencies
and Internet start-ups are following them in.
</P>
<P>
   Against this backdrop, Deep Ellum provides noteworthy evidence
that the same dynamic is at work in a new category of cities, like
Dallas, that did most of their growing after World War II and never
before possessed neighborhoods that many people would call hip.
</P>
<P>
   Characteristically, the emergence of Deep Ellum started with two
ingredients: cheap rents and old buildings. In its first heyday in
the 1930s, Deep Ellum was a center for African-American
entertainment, but by the 1980s it had withered to a handful of
restaurants and bars and little else. One of the rare parts of this
thoroughly modern city untouched by large-scale redevelopment, Deep
Ellum had blocks of old warehouses and factories ideal for
conversion into artists' lofts.
</P>
<P>
   When a few art galleries and nightclubs moved in, attracted by
the cheap rents, real estate investors like Wood and Don Blanton
saw possibilities. ``I did a lot of traveling in the country, and
Dallas didn't have anything like that for people,'' said Blanton,
who now owns 35 buildings in Deep Ellum. ``We had no Greenwich
Village or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly two decades for the vision to become reality, but
the rewards have been great for the pioneer investors. Buildings
that changed hands in the 1980s at $5 a square foot now attract
offers in the range of $100 a square foot. Yet Blanton, a West
Texas native who lives and works in Deep Ellum _ his spacious loft
is a short walk from his office on Commerce Street _ thinks it is
not yet time to sell. In fact, he is looking for more properties in
the district.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone: corporate real estate interests are appearing
on the scene. A major developer, Joseph Beard of Westdale Asset
Management, plans to refurbish an old building at the western edge
of Deep Ellum as part of a $90 million hotel-retail complex.
</P>
<P>
   Beard, whose firm specializes in condominiums and apartment
complexes, is impressed by the return of a residential population
to the district. According to Barry Annino, 42, a longtime local
real estate agent, the number of apartment and loft dwellers in
Deep Ellum has risen to more than 2,000, from 200 a decade ago. And
based on projects already announced, Beard estimated that the
number would more than triple again in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   With the new residents has come a surge in interest from
Internet businesses. In the past, Dallas' technology companies
tended to cluster in suburbs like Richardson and Plano, but Deep
Ellum is rapidly becoming a preferred home for dot-com concerns
like Broadcast.com (now part of Yahoo), which announced a move into
an 80,000-square-foot warehouse, with 700 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Annino, a former tennis pro from Queens who came to Dallas in
1985, leased Broadcast.com its first 3,000-square-foot building
here five years ago. Regarded as the unofficial mayor of the
neighborhood, Annino sees Yahoo's decision to keep the company in
Deep Ellum as validation of the district's emergence as a prime
location for Internet businesses. Many smaller companies that have
leased space there, he said, have told him that they were attracted
by the new ambience of the district, in much the same way as their
analogues have been drawn to Tribeca in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This location is perfect for a business like mine,'' said
Brett Strauss, 33, the president of Third Stone, an eight-person
Web design studio on Canton Street that counts Broadcast.com among
its customers. ``You have to be near the heart of things, near the
talent pool. This is young industry and this is a young part of
town.''
</P>
<P>
   In many eyes, one cloud hangs over Deep Ellum's future.
Experience elsewhere teaches that a neighborhood that is newly
fashionable is also newly vulnerable: Longtime residents like Brady
Wood worry that the boom times that are following Deep Ellum's
so-called discovery will wind up obliterating the character of the
place that has made it so attractive.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Soho first gained cachet as an artists' haven, but
rising rents have driven many of the artists away even as galleries
and restaurants have thrived. If not monitored carefully, Wood
said, the same dynamic could play out in Deep Ellum, snuffing out
the neighborhood's spontaneity as its one-of-a-kind shops are
overwhelmed by national chains and as local bohemians are
supplanted by well-turned-out young lawyers and stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this neighborhood,'' he said over coffee at Cafe
Brazil, a local late-night hangout. ``It's a great place to work,
and it keeps me in Dallas. But if it lost its character and became
like everywhere else here, I'd have to go back to New Orleans.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
