<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Dec. 26, will move Saturday, in the `a' category unless
otherwise noted.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-TIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ This New Year's Eve feels
different, no matter how arbitrary the date announcing the new
millennium may be. But the big round number about to invade our
lives has an undeniable symbolic force. Is this mere superstition?
Perhaps not entirely, for while our systems for measuring time may
be arbitrary, they are also necessary. We live suspended in
infinite time and space. But humans are mortal and finite, and we
need borders and markers to grasp the world in our minds. By Eva
Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   EXCESS-REVIEW (Undated) _ There is so much money sloshing around
that it seems to have overwhelmed the last vestiges of Puritan
guilt over spending it. As the stock market and corporate profits
continue to rise, charities nationwide report that donations from
both individuals and companies are donating have fallen this year.
The very idea of wretched excess, of buying as vulgar and wealth as
morally dangerous, has given way to a display-and-play ethos. By
Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inside the section:
</P>
<P>
   ENUFF-EHYPE-REVIEW (Undated) _ E-nuff already. It is the surest
sign that the Internet is totally mainstream: Everyone is tired of
it, not just the sleep-starved workers at dot-com startups, but
everyone _ man and beast alike. Turn on the television and you are
assaulted by an endless parade of jabbering advertisements for
e-commerce companies. Newspapers are so bloated these days with ads
for dot-com marketers that dogs across the nation must be loosening
their teeth and straining their necks to fetch them. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARRIAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Vermont Supreme Court seemed
to drop a bombshell last week when it ruled that gay couples must
either be allowed to marry or get the same benefits as heterosexual
couples. As gay rights advocates and their opponents squared off
over the decision, some of them agreed that the real battleground
will take place not in legal courtrooms but in the court of public
opinion. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DEBATES-ADS-REVIEW (Des Moines) _ Vice President Gore's
proposal to scrap all 30-second television spots in favor of
twice-weekly debates with former Sen. Bill Bradley is an indirect
approach to a spending curb. It would forswear the most costly way
to spend campaign cash: the 30-second TV ads, whose price rises
sharply each election cycle. If nobody bought 30-second spots
praising or condemning candidates like competing brands of laundry
detergent, campaign costs would drop dramatically _ and the level
of political discourse might rise. But nobody expects that to
happen. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-HEALTH-REVIEW (New York) _ Public policy on treating
mental illness often gets made in strange, circuitous ways.
Ultimately it is the states, not the federal government, that are
responsible for providing funding and treatment. In New York, major
changes are in the works come courtesy not of the president nor the
surgeon general, but thanks to one schizophrenic who pushed a woman
into the path of a subway train. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.S. (United Nations) _ The Clinton administration has
finally retreated from a policy of making the United Nations the
focal point of policy on Iraq _ and, indeed, from making Iraq a
focal point of policy. Now fixed on the glittering prize of a
broader Middle East peace among Israel and its neighbors, the
administration has let Iraq slip into the middle distance, where it
is likely to remain for the last year of the Clinton era unless
President Saddam Hussein does something very foolish and
provocative. By Barbara Crossette. (Moving in the `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   NEWYEAR-WARNINGS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The air is filled with
apocalyptic warnings tied to the turn of the millennium. But there
is plenty more to worry about than serious threats like terrorism,
doomsday cults and Y2K calamities. A sampling of alarming bulletins
culled from recent press releases and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   PREDICTIONS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A historical overview of
gloom-and-doom predictions, millennial and otherwise, followed up
with specific forecasts for the final week of 1999. By Jenny Lyn
Bader.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
