<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8448 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-MALLS-BECKER-ART-     12-24 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MALLS-BECKER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A FAMILY OF ENTREPRENEURS, THE GENERATIONAL TABLES TURN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 was sent Dec. 23 to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Far from contemplating retirement, as many men of 66
would do, Gordon Becker is setting out, again, to reinvent the
business he has been building for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Becker Group of Baltimore, the dominant player in a niche
business that it more or less invented _ providing seasonal
decorations for shopping malls _ is now throwing itself into the
world of ``shoppertainment,'' the creation of entertainment events
and attractions at malls to keep shoppers from defecting to the
Internet. It's risky, as Becker knows all too well: in the 1970s,
losing focus on his core business led to a Chapter 11
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, he says, growth is being supercharged by two
people _ a venture capitalist who has taken a large position in the
company and a successful entrepreneur with a stellar record in
building public and private service-sector businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Those two wise men also happen to be his sons, Eric, 37, and
Doug, 33.
</P>
<P>
   The Beckers offer an unusual case study in deep-rooted family
entrepreneurship. When the boys were growing up, their father was
their adviser in a string of teen-age businesses. Now the sons,
whose various ventures have grown into businesses worth more than
$750 million, are the advisers, stepping in to help take Dad's
business to a new level. Along the way, the Beckers have found ways
to keep the business partnership civil to the point that the
families even vacation together.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be a model for how you create next generations for
family enterprises,'' said Fredda Ferz Brown, managing partner of
the Metropolitan Group, a consultant to family-owned companies that
is based in Leonia, N.J..
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Becker's father was an entrepreneur of sorts himself, a
nightclub owner and violinist with his own big band that once
featured Tommy and Jimmy Dorsey. No one was surprised in 1947 when
Gordon, then 14, came up with an idea for drawing more customers
into a children's clothing store owned by a cousin. When he dressed
as Santa and sat in the front window for 75 cents an hour, sales
took off. After college, he started a Santa school to supply St.
Nicks to stores around Baltimore and Washington. That business
evolved into a company that dressed malls for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Becker often took his boys along to work, where giant
Christmas ornaments for his mall clients were made. ``I think our
early entrepreneurial interest comes from this,'' Eric Becker
recalled. ``We would bring our friends there, and it's where
everyone wanted to go play _ `My dad's just a brain surgeon; yours
is Santa Claus!'''
</P>
<P>
   A smart move, Ms. Brown said: ``Rather than just hearing Dad
moan and groan at the end of the day about what went wrong, they
get to participate in the fun of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys developed their own business interests when they were
as young as 9 or 10 _ Eric was selling garden seeds and greeting
cards, running a for-profit rocketry club and selling painter's
hats when they were in vogue with preteen-agers, while Doug
tinkered with various inventions. Their father gave advice when
asked, but didn't insist that the boys accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``His approach was, `Good luck, and if you stumble, get up and
keep on going,''' Eric Becker said. ``There was no `I told you so.'
He would ask us what we learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Becker had his own share of stumbles, and found himself
having to reinvent his business every 7 to 10 years. A frequent
mistake: holding on too long to low-profit operations, tying up
resources that could have been better employed. ``It was typical
small-business thinking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After one too many cases in which a mistake by a $300 Santa
soured relations with a $10,000-a-year client, he shut down the
Santa school. And he scrapped a promotional-events business that
booked talent like Igor the Great, who allowed himself to be shot
from a cannon across a shopping center parking lot _ but only when
the wind was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars were lined up and horns were honking; people were really
tired of waiting and he was saying: `Igor no go! Flag is flying,
Igor no go,''' Gordon Becker remembered with a shake of his head.
He would plead and negotiate and eventually get Igor launched. But
after a while the distractions and frustrations of the events
business persuaded him to focus on Christmas instead.
</P>
<P>
   By 1974 the Becker Group had revenue of $2 million a year but
was making very little profit. A consultant told Gordon Becker that
installing and repairing the mall decorations had become too
costly, so he made plans to close that part of the business.
Somehow his employees found out, he said, and sabotaged him in 1975
by purposely sending decorations to the wrong malls.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting the decorations sorted out and re-shipped put the
company in Chapter 11 bankruptcy-court protection, Becker said: ``I
lost close to $1 million. I was broke.'' But his clients and
suppliers rallied behind him, and he emerged from Chapter 11 in
just five months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Becker rebuilt his business ``by millimeters,'' he said,
his sons were developing their own business ideas. Along with two
friends, they put together several pieces of existing technology to
create LifeCard, a plastic card with a patient's entire medical
history. Eric quit college in 1984, one semester shy of graduation,
to pursue the idea, and Doug decided not to enroll at the
University of Pennsylvania, where he had been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Neither son remembers any complaint from Dad. ``He let me use
his office for meetings,'' Doug said. ``When we needed a lawyer, he
provided his. He was very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers sold LifeCard to Blue Cross Blue Shield of Maryland
at the end of 1985 for an undisclosed sum in the millions and used
the proceeds for new ventures. Eric is now chief executive of the
Sterling Group, an investment company with stakes in a dozen
companies in fields from food brokering to audio-visual supply,
plus real estate interests and a venture capital fund with $100
million in assets. Doug is now co-chief executive of Sylvan
Learning Systems, an education and training company with a $643
million capitalization and third-quarter revenues of $136.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   The generational tables began turning about four years ago. At
first Gordon Becker's approach was indirect. ``Dad didn't come and
say, `I'd like your advice,''' Eric Becker said. ``It was more
like, `Can you come to this meeting, I'd like to know what you
think.'''
</P>
<P>
   That changed suddenly last year. ``Dad turned 65,'' Eric said,
``and called me on the phone and said: `It's time. This business is
going to be you boys' one day, so it might as well be sooner rather
than later.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brown saw merit in the choice to wait until then to broach
the succession issue. ``He never pushed,'' she observed. ``It
wasn't a legacy, it was an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   And a good one, the brothers say. The Becker Group has about
1,000 malls in the United States as customers, along with 500 in 26
places from Brazil to Hong Kong to Spain. In addition to
longstanding licenses to use copyrighted characters and imagery in
holiday-theme mall events like Beatrix Potter Easter and Walt
Disney Christmas, it has added arrangements with Major League
Baseball and with Universal Studios for its classic movie monsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking for more ways to reach customers with
important messages,'' Doug Becker said. ``My father's business is
in a unique place to present these messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have seen the same trend, and the Becker Group's new
events unit, called Barnstorm, will be up against substantial
competition. The Simon Property Group, a leading mall operator, has
announced a partnership with the Turner Broadcasting unit of Time
Warner to produce mall events, and smaller operators like the
11-mall Mills Corp. are also putting together entertainment groups.
Doug Becker said Barnstorm would concentrate on carving a niche
rather than trying to be the biggest in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Becker said one idea the company was pursuing is a
mini-circus that would perform throughout the mall, with
opportunities for shoppers to participate. ``Your kid could learn
clowning, and actually perform with a clown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be Igor the Great all over again? ``We need to meet the
clients' needs, and the needs have changed,'' Gordon Becker said.
``Malls now consider themselves media. They sell advertising space
on trash cans, on railings, on windows.'' And that thinking extends
to promotional events, with malls sharing the cost with corporate
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   How has father taken to having the boys planning the course of a
company from which he has no intention of retiring? ``I love it,''
he said. ``My mother and father thought I was a rocket scientist
because I took a Santa suit and built a multimillion-dollar
business. Doug didn't go to college and Eric didn't graduate, and I
think they are rocket scientists.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
