<HEADER>
A8452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CHRISTMAS25-C     12-24 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CHRISTMAS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BETHLEHEM DRAWS WORLD'S FAITHFUL FOR CELEBRATION
 &HT;    770&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ In a land known for conflict, people from
different nations and faiths joined Friday night in the town where
Christianity was born to celebrate the last Christmas of the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Manger Square, the small stone plaza in front of the
1,500-year-old Church of the Nativity, displayed a panorama of
religious and international ritual throughout the day. There were
the solemn Friday prayers of kneeling Muslims and the jubilant
tones of a gospel choir from Houston, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The day culminated with a midnight mass attended by Palestinian
President Yasser Arafat and a handful of leaders from European and
African countries. The mass was shown on a large screen on a
high-tech stage.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of American pilgrims and tourists set aside official
U.S. warnings about millennial terrorism and turned out for the
event. The day was overseen by a heavy Palestinian security
presence _ 3,000 police in navy blue uniforms, under cover in
civilian garb or wearing blue camouflage paramilitary outfits and
carrying Kalishnikov rifles.
</P>
<P>
   For local Christian Palestinians, who make up about a third of
the city of 50,000, the day was a salve for wounded egos. Intensely
proud of sharing their birthplace with Christ, they have seen their
numbers overtaken by an influx of Muslim refugees and their city
suffer decades of Israeli occupation and Palestinian uprising.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Eve celebrations took place here even before control
was transferred from Israeli occupation to the Palestinian
Authority in 1995. But this was the biggest observance, and comes
amid nearly $200 million of improvements in the city. New hotels
are being built, roads and sewage systems upgraded, and Manger
Square has been converted from a bus parking lot to a tree-lined
piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Christians are gathering, more than in other years.
They are more united,'' said Nadia Ghattes, 25, who was strolling
the city's remodeled Star Street with her husband and daughter.
``They are trying to show that we are here. That there are
Christians here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were born here, we are going to live here and we are going
to die here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For the foreign religious pilgrims and tourists who came to the
city, just five miles south of Jerusalem, it was a chance to see
how the new Bethlehem stands up to the biblical one.
</P>
<P>
   They found themselves surprised, moved and overwhelmed. The
marching bands and bagpipe troupes, a staple of Palestinian
celebrations, caught some off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to see the nativity scene,'' said Barbara Mosher, 68,
a retired acrobatic pilot from Waynesville, Ohio, near Dayton.
``The parade was unexpected. I didn't know it would be so
carnival-like, but I enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin Harlamert, a retired judge from Oakwood, Ohio, said he had
come here before but was awakened this time to the Christian
Palestinian presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are wearing crosses on their necks and that
surprised me,'' he said. ``It's good to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of Middle Eastern turbulence were on hand Friday. In
the Israeli city of Netanya, police set off a controlled explosion
what they said was a powerful pipe bomb found in a crowded street.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, scars of old conflicts remain. The city suffers
from high unemployment and is bordered by refugee camps. Christians
have emigrated in large numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Stone remnants on the wall of the Byzantine-era Church of the
Nativity show that the door has been lowered twice to keep out
pillaging intruders. Now, the faithful must bow to enter the small
passage.
</P>
<P>
   It was in a grotto atop which this cavernous church was built
where Christ was believed to have been born at midnight on a cold
desert evening about 2,000 years ago. Pilgrims kneel there to touch
and kiss the stone. A handful of shepherds still graze their flocks
on the rocky hillsides nearby, between Palestinian development and
Jewish settlements on land captured by Israel in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, however, offered high-tech entertainment and
nationalist overtones for a people yearning for statehood.
</P>
<P>
   At least 6,000 Christians, Muslims, Palestinians and foreigners
watched the midnight mass under a light drizzle. One speaker called
the unusual rain in the desert town ``our Christmas present.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, other sides of the square offered other
cultural samplings. Hundreds of Muslims, the majority faith in this
Palestinian town, knelt in the square for noon prayers as onlookers
stood by with mylar Santa Claus balloons and the smell of shwarma
lamb barbecue wafted overhead. Palestinian flags were paired with
flags of states from around the world on the buildings of the
square.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A spot underneath those flags saw another landmark, if much less
momentous than the end of a millennium. Workers rushed to open a
Checkers restaurant, the first big-name American franchise to find
a place at the doorstep of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a quarter of those attending the nighttime show were
local Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   There have been simmering tensions in Bethlehem as the
demographics have shifted from a Christian to a Muslim majority.
Some Christians complained that even on Christmas Eve, the call to
pray from a mosque on Manger Square drowned out the festivities.
</P>
<P>
   But many Muslims say they also took pride in the attention
Bethlehem derives as the seat of Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to see people of all lands and nationalities
here,'' said Ala Moh'd(cq) Mustafa, a Muslim medical student born
in Bethlehem. ``All my friends are Christian, I have to celebrate
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
