<HEADER>
A8456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      12-24 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE INJURY BOOSTS WILLIAMS' COURT TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Early in the season, Eric Williams was most active and
most entertaining on the sideline. Always a cheerleader, the
6-foot-8-inch forward shouted encouragement from his seat. He stood
to applaud his teammates when they returned to the bench for a
timeout. His expressive face often served as a barometer of the
Celtics' streaky play; he would smile widely one minute then become
contorted with frustration the next.
</P>
<P>
   But for the last seven games, the sideshow has been dramatically
shortened. Williams no longer has much idle time to cheer. Now,
fans must catch his act on the court.
</P>
<P>
   With Paul Pierce on the injured list for the last seven games,
Williams has recorded six starts at small forward while Adrian
Griffin has shifted to the backcourt. During that time, Williams
has shown that he can contribute. In Pierce's absence, Williams has
averaged 31.4 minutes and 8.4 points per game. His best performance
of that stretch came against the Lakers, when he posted 12 points,
3 steals, and 4 rebounds in 38 minutes off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real unfortunate thing for our team when Paul was
injured because he's a real big part of our success this year,''
said Williams. ``But it gave me a better chance to get some
awareness on the court for myself. It gave me some more
opportunities to play and get a feel for the court with some of the
starting unit guys that I might not usually get a lot of time with.
I think it's going to be good in the long run because they have the
confidence that they can insert me at any position at any given
time no matter what the situation is.''
</P>
<P>
   The extra time on the floor does not surprise Williams, but he
believes more minutes were exactly what he needed to improve his
game. The forward says his defensive skills helped coach Rick
Pitino decide to play him more. His defensive presence against
Atlanta helped keep Isaiah Rider and Jim Jackson in check. He used
his height advantage and quickness to guard the Hawks' top scoring
threats and limit their productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of our better defensive players,'' said Pitino. ``He
scores well. He's very unselfish. He's improving his shooting. So,
if you can look for a silver lining, which is certainly not in wins
and losses, it's Eric Williams getting more playing time and
emerging into a better basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   But Pitino would not be offering praise if injury had not taught
Williams to make the most of every opportunity. Williams's outlook
on his career changed when he collided with Karl Malone four games
into the 1997-98 season. Williams suffered a torn right ACL as a
result. It took reconstructive surgery and a year and a half of
rehabilitation before he felt he had returned to his pre-injury
level of fitness. Time away from the game gave Williams a chance to
reflect.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my fifth year now,'' said Williams, who was drafted
14th overall by the Celtics in 1995, traded to Denver in 1997, and
returned to Boston in an early August trade this year. ``I was
injured three years ago for a whole year and I had some time to
assess what was going on in my life and my career. I'm more
professional now. If Coach P or any of the coaches need me to do
something, then I'm going to step it up. That may mean being a
cheerleader on the sidelines or coming out like I did in the second
game of the season and scoring 18 points. Now, I'm out there being
an integral part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pitino: ``I wish everybody's attitude could be like Eric
Williams and Walter McCarty. Regardless of how they play, they give
you 100 percent and they root their teammates on.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was Williams's attitude and sideline enthusiasm
that first impressed Pitino. Although the 27-year-old did not play
in the season-opener against Toronto, he led the cheering during
and after Boston's road victory. The next night in the Celtics'
home opener, Pitino rewarded Williams with 14 minutes of playing
time. He responded with 18 points, 5 rebounds, and 1 steal.
</P>
<P>
   With Pierce on the mend and Danny Fortson scheduled to return
against the Clippers Sunday, Williams likely will see fewer
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine with him. He'll take his act on the road or back to
the bench. And when another opportunity presents itself, Williams
will be more than ready to take the main stage again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
