<HEADLINE>
ELLISON COMFORTABLE WITH SPECIAL TEAMS ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Jerry Ellison does not expect to continue in
his role as the Patriots' secret weapon.
</P>
<P>
   First, because other teams certainly must know about Ellison
after he caught four passes for 50 yards in a 24-9 loss at
Philadelphia last Sunday. Second, because he plans to return to his
place as special teams specialist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I played well when I got in there and, hopefully,
I'll continue to do that,'' Ellison said while preparing for
Sunday's game against Buffalo. ``It's been a while since I've had a
chance to do that. But I know my role. I was brought in to play on
special teams and I am comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, who turned 28 last Monday, showed flashes of
explosiveness in his first two seasons at Tampa Bay in 1995 and
'96. But Ellison made his mark on special teams as the Bucs
qualified for the playoffs in '97 and has made a career as a
dependable player on kickoffs and punt situations and as a reserve
running back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every player is ambitious and I want to continue to be able to
contribute on offense,'' Ellison said. ``A couple of guys got hurt
and I jumped at the opportunity. But I've still got a job to do.
You can't get overexcited that you're not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Can Ellison make similar contributions on a regular basis?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can, but it remains to be seen,'' he said. ``I have
to take it one game at a time. I've still got to prove myself. You
have to get the confidence of the coaches and of the players around
you. If you don't perform, of course, they are not going to put you
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison entered the game in Philadelphia before the Patriots'
cause was completely lost. He caught a 23-yard pass from Drew
Bledsoe, then a caught a 7-yarder at the Philadelphia 13-yard line
to revive some hope. But that would be Bledsoe's last completion
until the Patriots' final possession of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison performed on that final possession, but likely will
return to a lower-profile status against the Bills, though the
Patriots could use a spark after having failed to score more than
two touchdowns in a game since a 27-3 win at Arizona Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``All teams that win championships have good special teams,''
Ellison said. ``At first, when I started playing, I didn't pay
attention to the importance of special teams. But that was a major
factor in our success at Tampa Bay. We had a couple of guys who
could return the ball, but sometimes it was just getting the team
good field position so the offense could control the ball and put
it in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little things that happen on special teams can decide the game
_ a slip-up by one guy and the other team can score or block a
punt. And you saw the importance of special teams with Green Bay a
couple of years ago with Desmond Howard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison said he always wants to play more but is confident in
his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``My motto is that I will do anything to help the team win,
whether it's special teams or whatever they want me to do,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1733EST &QL; 
