<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORKPLACE-DATING-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIETLY, DOT-COMS REWRITE RULES ON OFFICE ROMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (bl)  
 BY ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A date. That's what Kate Hayes wants for New Year's Eve. Someone
to clink champagne glasses with. Someone to kiss at the stroke of
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   So Ms. Hayes has been doing something she had vowed she would
never do: She is actively pursuing a mate through work. For the
past few months, she has told everyone she meets _ clients,
colleagues, her superior _ that she is available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so in the millennium-date fret mode,'' said Ms. Hayes,
who is 25 and a director at Hireminds.net, an Internet and Web
staffing specialist in Cambridge, Mass. ``Some of my colleagues
interview people who are prospective clients, and if I'm not
representing them, then I think I can date them. I feel out the
situation: `Hey, I heard about this party, why don't you go, it
would be a great way for you to meet people.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hayes is among many young people at Internet and high
technology start-ups using the workplace as a launching pad to find
love. Not content with redefining other aspects of workplace
culture, dot-com companies, often populated by the young and
dedicated, are throwing out corporate rules that discouraged dating
and fraternization among employees. But they are finding that
writing the new conduct codes, which often allow relationships
between a boss and an employee, is not so easy.
</P>
<P>
   People have always found romance on the job. In a 1999 survey
conducted by Careermag.com, an online job and career Web site based
in Boulder, Colo., 20 percent of 10,000 respondents said they had
had an affair with another worker. According to a 1988 report by
the Bureau of National Affairs, a private research group in
Washington, one-third of all relationships begin in the office. And
in a 1994 survey of of 485 managers and executives from Fortune 500
companies, the American Management Association found that 74
percent said it was all right to date a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dot-com set, workplace dating is almost de rigueur.
</P>
<P>
   ``For such a long time people would discourage any social
interaction at work, but a lot of corporations are realizing that
this is a dedicated work force, extremely hard workers,'' said
Tiffany Shlain, 29, founder and director of the Webby awards, the
Oscars of the Internet. Saying she was ``a bit old-fashioned on a
lot of things,'' Ms. Shlain added that she could see why allowing
dating was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always cared to make sure my staff enjoys their work
environment,'' she said. ``You have to cater more to the needs of
the people working for you. It would be cold-hearted and
nearsighted not to create an environment they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Mara Engel, a senior public relations manager at Excite(AT)home,
in Redwood City, Calif., agreed. ``Dating isn't encouraged here per
se, but it's definitely a social environment,'' she said. ``It's
not exploited _ people aren't running around holding hands and
making out in the bathrooms _ but it exists. You really get to know
people and you're working toward the same goal and it fosters
romance. People work 10 hours a day in some cases. Your work
becomes your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Like their forerunners in Silicon Valley, many Internet
companies hold happy hours or keg parties at the end of the week
attended by both upper management and underlings. Partly because
most people in such companies are around the same age, the
boundaries of behavior can be blurry.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie  &QL; 
Armistead met his wife, Katherine, at Interactive Planet Inc., a
privately held Internet development company in Atlanta. He was the
senior account manager; she was an account manager. They sat about
10 feet apart. ``Technically, I was her boss,'' Armistead said.
</P>
<P>
   The company had only about 15 employees, ``so there was some
sensitivity to dating in the office,'' he said. The couple kept
their romance secret until it became clear that it was becoming
serious.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they went to lunch with their boss _ Armistead's former
college roommate _ and came clean. ``I expected to lose my job,''
Armistead recalled. ``It was his company, and he cared a great
deal. His concern was being able to portray a professional work
environment to our core client base. He didn't want us to work on
the same accounts in case we had personal problems. It could have
gone either way, but he said, `Well, you're both very
professional.' But he made it clear that we wouldn't be working on
the same project.'' (Both have since moved to other companies.)
</P>
<P>
   According to Ethan Winning, a management consultant in Walnut
Creek, Calif., who specializes in employee handbooks, policies and
procedures, only about 10 percent of companies have written
policies on dating and fraternization. But most employers, worried
about sexual harassment claims, discourage managers from dating
subordinates. They may also separate couples, transferring one
person to another part of the company, requiring one to report to a
different manager or even asking one to resign _ especially if they
marry.
</P>
<P>
   At Internet start-ups, where there are often fewer than 30
employees, such moves can be impractical. And some employers have
another rationale for allowing dating: they believe that happy
employees are productive, too.
</P>
<P>
   But some workers and companies have found that the new attitude
can cause problems. Lori Park and Lisa Bongiorno each recently
filed a $10 million lawsuit in New York state Supreme Court against
Juno Online Services of Manhattan and a senior manager. Each woman
contended that the company allowed a sexually hostile environment
and that she had been sexually harassed by a manager.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Park, 25, who was a software engineer at Juno, said she
dated Matthew Battles, a senior vice president, for the year and a
half she was there. Ms. Bongiorno, 28, who was an account
executive, said she was romantically involved with the senior vice
president for strategic marketing, Jordan Birnbaum.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got there, I didn't want to be involved with
dating in the office,'' Ms. Bongiorno said. ``But I was told that
once I got used to the Juno environment, I would soon see that
dating was acceptable and encouraged.'' She worked at Juno from
February 1997 through February 1999, when she was dismissed. She
blames Birnbaum.
</P>
<P>
   Birnbaum and Battles declined to comment last week, according to
the company's public relations representative, Howard Rubenstein
Associates. In a statement, Juno general counsel Richard Buchband
denied all accusations in both suits. He said that Ms. Bongiorno's
case was dismissed in October on technical grounds and that it was
without merit. He said Ms. Park had been treated in a
``professional and lawful'' manner; Ms. Park's suit is pending.
``Our firm has strict policies and procedures to protect our
employees against any mistreatment in the workplace,'' Buchband
added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bongiorno is appealing her suit's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Park, who now works at another Internet company, said she
had been terrified to break up with Battles for fear of losing her
job. ``A lot of people were dating within the company, and it's a
bad idea because people treat you differently,'' she said. ``I felt
that everyone was trying to get on my good side or say things to me
to get to Matt. You can't legislate workplace dating, but I
wouldn't do it again. It makes your private life totally public and
if your lover is more important than you, you never know what
they're going to do to you. And it's your livelihood and your
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning, the management consultant, called dating within an
office ``the worst idea you can possibly come up with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies, in general, don't want to talk about this,'' he
added. ``They'd rather talk about their salaries than dating.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning, who has written behavioral guidelines and rules of
conduct for dot-coms and high-technology companies, wishes that
more young companies would adopt written employment policies.
``They think they're very progressive in Silicon Valley, Boston,
New York or Minneapolis,'' he said. ``They're all very young and
they don't care what their employees do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said couples should be aware of the pitfalls of intra-office
dating. ``You can always say that a dating relationship interferes
with the work flow,'' he said. ``You know how catty people are,
what the rumor mill is like. And the breakup of a relationship _
marriage or not _ can tear an organization apart. The company does
have a right to protect its interest, even without a written
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, however, there are other things on the minds of many
young people _ like the more pressing issue of a New Year's date.
``I go to tons of Cyber Brew parties and I always mention that I'm
single,'' Ms. Hayes said. ``I can put a spin on it that makes it
business-related, so it's also business-motivated for me, because
when I go to a party I'm socializing but also networking. Even if
it's a bum date, I still get work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1735EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
