<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8461 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BO     12-24 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME CATCHING UP WITH AGELESS RAY BOURQUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ultimately, there will be a line drawn beneath Ray
Bourque's career. Father Time eventually corners every player,
ordinary and extraordinary, and has yet to lose that little
one-on-one battle between the eternal and the mere mortal.
</P>
<P>
   As great as Bourque has been for 20 1/2 National Hockey League
seasons, he, too, will face that inevitable tap on the shoulder,
the calling out, the realization that it is time to stop. For
Bourque, who will turn 39 Tuesday, the end may come at the end of
this season. For now, though, he remains on the Boston blue line,
his skills still ranking him among the game's elite defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to leave the game where you've got guys saying,
`Get out, you can't do it anymore,' '' Bourque said not long ago,
contemplating the day his career will end. ``I don't want to be
dragging. That's not the way I want to go out. I'd love to go out
still playing a good, solid brand of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what history records beneath Bourque's name _ and it
appears inevitable that it won't show a Stanley Cup _ he will be
remembered not only for his endurance and longevity, but for the
blend of consistency and quality he brought to the ice for two-plus
decades. He won the Calder Trophy as the league's top rookie in
1979-80. He has five Norris Trophies as the NHL's best defenseman.
He has been voted a first-team All-Star a dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades in the Hub, Bourque has been the
Rolex, not the Timex. For nearly 1,500 games and nearly as many
points, he has been the most consistently superior performer ever
to wear the franchise's spoked B. There have been those blessed
with greater talent and acclaim (Bobby Orr) and those with more
flash (Phil Esposito) and certainly more showmanship (Eddie Shore),
and many (some faceless) with more Cups. But Bourque, Cup or no
Cup, has become the franchise standard for doing the best for the
longest period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be remembered just as a guy who showed up every
night and played his heart out,'' said Bourque. ``Just a guy who
was there, game in and game out, and was there for his teammates.
That's pretty much what I've tried to bring, and what I expect from
others, and I hope (as captain) that I get from others. I think
I'll be remembered for that, just as a guy who was there, every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque was 19 when the Bruins made him the eighth selection
overall in the 1979 entry draft. Raised in St. Laurent, a
working-class suburb of Montreal, he and his two brothers refined
their shooting skills by taking aim at a makeshift hockey net that
their father propped against the cellar wall in their apartment
building. To this day, Bourque remains one of the game's most
accurate and hardest shooters, always the one to beat at the NHL
skills competition during the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, the whole wall cracked and water came in,'' said
Ray Bourque Sr., recalling how sons Raymond, Richard, and Normand
endlessly fired pucks in the basement. ``We were renting the place.
I had to fill the wall with special cement, some kind of crack
filler, before we moved out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Creighton, new on the job as Don Cherry's replacement, was
the Bruins' coach upon Bourque's arrival in Boston. By the end of
the '79-80 season, Creighton had been dismissed and Bourque, with
65 points in 80 games, had played well enough to be the first Bruin
named the league's rookie of the year since Derek Sanderson a dozen
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's first contract was worth $100,000 a season, about the
going rate for highly touted picks at the time. These days he earns
$6 million a season, almost $75,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been fortunate, that I've been able to touch both ends of
it,'' said Bourque, reflecting on the salary inflation every pro
sport has experienced in the last 20-plus years. ``I've seen the
old players that really didn't earn all that much, but went out and
really had a passion for the game, and now the kids who are coming
up are a little different in how they look at it. It seems like
their knowledge of the history of the game isn't as sharp, or it
isn't there as much. And their thinking process is a little
different. They hit the jackpot right off the bat, a lot of these
kids. They're trained like that at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played, I just thought about playing. You just wanted
to play, and you weren't thinking about all the other stuff that
was going to be there for you if you did make it _ kind of this pot
of gold. But that's the way it is now. That's reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Bourque's ninth year in Boston before the Bruins finally
made the Cup finals in 1988. He already had one Norris Trophy by
then, was about to receive his second, and he collected 21 points
in 23 playoff games that year before the Bruins finally succumbed
to the powerful Edmonton Oilers. Two years later, on his way to
winning a third Norris, he helped the Bruins again reach the final,
where they once more were rubbed out by the Oilers, who by then
were without superstar Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   If ever Bourque was going to win the Cup, it was that spring of
'90. But even with Gretzky gone, essentially sold to the Los
Angeles Kings only weeks after the Oilers defeated the Bruins in
'88, the Oilers still finished off the Bruins in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes (it's a matter of being) in the right place at the
right time,'' said Bourque. ``Obviously, there are some guys who
are a big part of (Cup-winning) teams and you've got to have them.
You look at guys like Gretzky and (Mark) Messier, all these guys
that have won many Cups, and they're huge. But you also look at
their teams, and many times they played on great teams. I've played
on really good teams. How many great teams have we had here in
(20-plus) years?''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's last great teams won the Cup in 1970 and '72, the Big,
Bad Bruins of Orr, Esposito, Gerry Cheevers, John Bucyk, et al. It
was but a kernel of a dynasty, one that quickly eroded under the
influence of the higher-paying World Hockey Association and, to a
degree, the lack of self-discipline that was inherent in the era.
If only a handful of those players had been as loyal and as
physically disciplined and conditioned as Bourque, his career
likely would have dovetailed with a championship-caliber run that
could have endured through the '70s and perhaps lasted through the
great Oilers teams of the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't have enough,'' said Bourque, reflecting on
competitive gaps during his career. ``There are a few things that
come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Two nights during Bourque's career stand out above all others.
</P>
<P>
   One came Dec. 3, 1987, when he showed an uncharacteristic flair
for the dramatic, surprisingly surrendering his No. 7 sweater the
night Esposito's No. 7 was retired to the Garden rafters.
Esposito's jaw dropped, a tear came to his eye, and the old
building's foundation shook when the beaming Bourque shed his
sweater to unveil the No. 77 he would wear from that day forward.
</P>
<P>
   Some 2 1/2 years later, on April 17, 1990, in the first round of
the playoffs, the Garden was the stage for even greater Bourque
drama. Pitted against their New England rivals, the Hartford
Whalers, the Bruins were pushed to Game 7 and faced with the
unenviable prospect of taking on the Whale without Bourque. Hobbled
by a hip injury and unavailable for Games 3-6 of the series,
Bourque was not thought to be capable of playing in the decisive
game.
</P>
<P>
   But to the amazement of even his teammates, Bourque made a
valiant return, and helped set up Boston's first goal in a 3-1
victory. When his name wasn't listed as a scratch in the pregame
public address announcment, the sellout crowd of 14,448 roared, and
it bellowed again when Bourque took his first shift with 52 seconds
gone in the first period. It was as if he were a returning war
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't hacker tennis or a jog around the park,'' said
then-coach Mike Milbury, shocked that Bourque could play at such
high efficiency after being unable to skate for 10 days. ``This is
big-league hockey. I don't know how he got through it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if ultimately his career ends without his name etched in the
Cup?
</P>
<P>
   ``So? That ain't gonna change my life,'' he said. ``I mean, the
game's been so good to me. I appreciate the game. I respect the
game. I know what it's all about. I know how hard it is to win a
Cup. I've been through it. But, you know, I'm going to walk away
from this game, whenever that day is _ with or without a Cup _ and
it ain't gonna change anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
