<HEADER>
A8463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ASIAN-AMERICAN-WRITER     12-24 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-AMERICAN-WRITERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORKSHOP NURTURES ASIAN AMERICAN WRITERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT WADDELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It started in a Greek-owned diner eight years ago,
with a half dozen Asian-American writers talking about what seemed
to be an explosion of literary efforts around them. What better
place for the conversation, since much of the writing dealt with
the struggle of Asian immigrants and their children to come to
terms with the quirks and textures of American life.
</P>
<P>
   The publication of novels like ``The Woman Warrior'' by Maxine
Hong Kingston in 1976 and ``The Joy Luck Club'' by Amy Tan in 1989
profoundly influenced many young writers. But those at the diner
table felt that a more active hand was needed to nurture those who
were struggling with their own work.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the Asian American Writers' Workshop, whose
membership has grown to 600, more than 100 of them writers, and
whose mailing list has grown to 7,000. Operating from a basement
under the Gap store on St. Marks Place and Second Avenue, the group
helps members in many ways.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a year it publishes both literary anthologies and The
Asian Pacific American Journal, which features short stories,
poetry and essays, and it has a magazine, Ten, with articles about
writers and writing. It also awards grants to struggling writers
and runs educational programs and groups for writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``By supporting the writers, we're supporting the future,'' said
Quang Bao, managing director of the organization, which has a
$450,000 annual budget supported with donations and government
grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each story builds a collective history and increases community
visibility,'' he said. ``There are a diverse group of people who
tell their stories in diverse ways. We want to tell as many stories
as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his hope was that the work would be considered purely on
its quality and not more sociologically as a from of ethnic
expression. He said he wanted to move to the point where ``we can
call it literature and not go into these hyphenated categories.''
</P>
<P>
   Members range from established authors to neophytes. In the last
two years many have published works and received generally positive
reviews. Among the books are Lois-Ann Yamanaka's ``Heads by Harry''
(Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux), Ruth Ozeki's ``My Year of Meats''
(Viking), Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni's ``Sister of My Heart''
(Doubleday) and Bino Realuyo's ``Umbrella Country'' (Ballantine
Books).
</P>
<P>
   Kyung Cho, a literary agent at Jane Dystel Agency who is writing
a historical novel, ``The Encyclopedia of Korean Culture,'' said
that many Asian-American writers have relied heavily on biography
and autobiography to tell individual stories and historical
narratives. As younger writers begin to define themselves and their
art, fiction, often emerging from factual situations, is being used
by a growing number.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Hagedorn, author of ``Dogeaters,'' which was nominated
for a National Book Award in 1990, said: ``We're not just writing
about our grandmother and a bowl of rice anymore. It's a very
healthy movement, a growing movement since the 1970s.''
</P>
<P>
   The workshop has a program for more than 50 students from 15 New
York City high schools with writing classes, discussions on race
and identity, and instruction in making videos. The group has a
bookstore at their office at 37 St. Marks Place with more than
2,000 titles by Asian-American writers.
</P>
<P>
   But it helps writers most by publishing their works and making
grants. Each year since 1993, three writers under 30 who live in
the city have received $5,500 Van Lier Fellowships. At least 150
writers have been published in workshop anthologies or in its
magazines. The anthologies generally focus on one segment of Asian
society like gays and lesbians, Filipinos and Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Bao said that although the anthologies each have a theme, ``at
our writing workshops anything goes, it's a lab for artistic
experimentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Bao said, the group hopes to move to a larger office
and give special attention to the 25th anniversary of the mass
movement of Vietnamese refugees to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very inspiring and supportive environment,'' said
Andrea Louie, the Chinese-American author of ``Moon Cakes''
(Ballantine, 1995) ``I've enjoyed the diasporaic experience of
different groups. Even though it's different, we're very much the
same.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
