<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Saturday, Dec. 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ Federal officials are refining
their strategies to obtain drug coverage for the elderly through
Medicare. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CREW-SEARCH (New York) _ With frenzied speculation already
underway about potential successors to Schools Chancellor Rudy
Crew, members of the Board of Education and officials in Mayor
Giuliani's administration remained focused Thursday on the more
immediate question of who would actually carry out the search for a
new schools chief in an atmosphere that is expected to be even more
politically charged than usual. By David M. Herszenhorn.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-CHRISTMAS (Darien, Conn.) _ The meteorologists may say
that there hasn't been any snow this winter in this quaint and
affluent town. But don't to one resident's 11 grandchildren. Come
Christmas morning, they will discover a hill on their grandparents'
property blanketed with snow, giving them the perfect place to test
out the sleds and toboggans they will receive as presents on
Saturday. What's more, they will also see that they'll be the only
ones for miles and miles with a patch of winter in a landscape of
green and brown. But it's not Santa or even Mother Nature who
created their private winter wonderland. Instead, they can thank
the latest indulgence of the go-go 90s: a man-made, made-to-order
white Christmas. By David W. Chen.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-HIJACK (Dateline to kum) _ Hijackers on Friday seized an
Indian Airlines plane with 189 people on board, made stops in India
and Pakistan, tried unsuccessfully to land in Afghanistan and then
touched down in the United Arab Emirates. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS-POPE (Rome) _ In a moment he has been waiting for his
entire papacy, John Paul II at midnight is to open the Holy Door to
Saint Peter's basilica, ushering in a Holy Year that is supposed to
set the tone for the entire third millennium. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN-PRESS (Portsmouth, N.H.) _ Among political reporters, the
extraordinary access that John McCain provides has become the stuff
of instant legend. For hour after hour, he takes on all comers on
the bus his staff has christened Straight Talk Express. In fact,
this maverick Republican conservative will spar and ruminate,
banter and cajole, kick back and hold forth for as long as anyone
with a pad or a microphone cares. And sometimes, even longer. The
result: an unusually tension-free detente between the press and a
candidate from a wing of a party that often has viewed journalists
as the enemy. Indeed, some in the conservative movement are so
deeply resentful of McCain's clubbiness with the press and
incredulous at the huge amount of attention he has garnered _
earlier this month, for instance, Time ran his photo on the cover
and a package of five stories on his candidacy _ that they detect a
strong whiff of favoritism. By Peter Marks.
</P>
</TEXT>
