<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8465 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-MEMBERS-ONLY-CLUBS-AR     12-24 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMBERS-ONLY-CLUBS-ART-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOCKING THE STUFFY OUT OF PRIVATE CLUBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JAMES COLLARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to Home House could be forgiven for supposing that they
are crossing the hallowed portals of a traditional gentlemen's
club, one of those temples to upper-class masculinity that have
played a key role in London life since the 17th century.
</P>
<P>
   It is a suitably grand building, built in 1777 for the Countess
of Home. A rather austere lobby leads to grand reception rooms
elaborately decorated with gilt, stucco, rich furnishings and
glittering chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   Home House is a members-only club, but that is where the
comparison pretty much ends. At lunch in its dining room,
overlooking Portman Square in the fashionable West End of London,
handsome young staff members serve ``modern European'' food to an
eclectic mix of people: men, women, black, white, straight, gay, of
all ages. But all are uniformly chic. They are as up-to-the-minute
as the art on the walls (vast contemporary canvases hung amid
18th-century detail), with their mobile phones at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   Opened this year after an $18 million makeover, Home House has
all the see-and-be-seen theater of a boutique hotel. The Britpack
actor Sean Pertwee and Zach Goldsmith, a socialite, both held their
wedding parties there. Madonna and Whitney Houston have been guests
in the beautiful bedrooms upstairs, while the bar, with its video
screens, fashionable cocktails and music graduating from mellow to
lively as the night progresses, has something of the buzz of a
nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Home House is the latest, grandest and arguably most ambitious
of a new generation of members' clubs to open in the last two
decades _ places like the Groucho, Black's, the Academy, Soho House
and the Cobden. Rather louche, in some cases almost seedy compared
to the grand old clubs of St. James', these newcomers don't fit the
term ``gentlemen's club'' _ women are welcome as members, and most
of the men would view the word ``gentlemen'' as anachronistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can bring a business client to lunch, and I can bring my
boyfriend, which I'd hesitate to do in other clubs,'' said Ian
Scott, a regular at Home House, who is also a member of three
traditional clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can also take my mother to lunch here, and she'll love
it,'' added Scott, a managing director of an advertising agency.
``It's less formal perhaps, but the food is excellent, and it's
completely pukka.'' (That is, first-class.)
</P>
<P>
   Traditional clubs _ where to this day men in Savile Row suits
and bespoke shoes, many sitting alone and reading a newspaper,
order meals of roast pheasant washed down with claret _ were
designed as one more way in which the leisured classes could enjoy
their leisure.
</P>
<P>
   Their rule books discourage the discussion of business (with the
exception of politics in those two great political rivals of the
19th century, the Reform and the oh-so-Tory Carlton Club), which is
certainly not the case in this new generation of London clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Based mostly in Soho, an area of London roughly equivalent to
its namesake in New York and home to many of Britain's
media-related businesses, the new clubs are primarily places to
entertain clients, to table hop, to network and to socialize with
one's peers, akin to power-lunch spots like the Four Seasons or
Michael's in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But in London, ``networking in clubs is more likely to mean
dinner or drinking in the evening,'' said Matt Seaton, a
contributing editor to British Esquire and a member of the Academy
Club.
</P>
<P>
   There is no real equivalent in New York to the current London
scene, where everyone seems to be angling to get in somewhere. The
private clubs fulfill the weeding-out role performed by
list-keeping doormen at New York City night spots, or by publicists
in control of parties for stores, films and some charity events.
</P>
<P>
   Soho is also the center of London's rather raucous night life, a
district filled with bars, restaurants and nightclubs, and it's no
accident that at clubs like Soho House, with many members in the
film business, or the Groucho, a literary club, business is
combined with some serious drinking, particularly as clubs evade
English licensing laws, which force most pubs to close at 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a member of Soho House for two reasons,'' said Amanda
Posey, an independent film producer. ``First, because of my work _
it's perfect for meetings, entertaining, screenings. The other
reason is that it's great to have somewhere central where you can
drink after 11 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   The Groucho, founded by writers and editors, is a place for
publishing industry lunches, but by night it becomes a thoroughly
raffish, boisterous, rather boozy venue filled with a heady mix of
journalists, publicists and television folk, with the likes of
Damien Hirst and Robbie Williams thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Soho House has recently explored opening a branch in New York,
but has been stalled by local laws prohibiting for-profit,
members-only clubs. ``I think the laws about clubs are old, and I
think they're holding New York back in this area,'' said Jonny
Ohlson, the director of Soho House.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is often assumed that London clubs were formed by
like-minded individuals for the pure pleasure of one another's
company, the new ones in particular tend to be profit-making
ventures, and even some dating from the 1700s were organized by
entrepreneurs or chefs.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Clivaz, an entrepreneur, who came up with the idea for
Home House, said he identified ``a gap in the market for a club
where you could enjoy grand surroundings with a relaxed atmosphere;
a club where it didn't matter about your origins, your gender, your
background, your sexuality and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly a workers' paradise, though. The fee to join is
$2,000 (less for those under 30 and for overseas members), plus
annual dues of $2,000. There is now a six-month waiting list to
join, except for overseas members.
</P>
<P>
   Members must be elected, and election to all London clubs runs
along similar, traditional lines. An existing member proposes you,
another seconds, and you hope not to be vetoed or blackballed by
other members. Membership signals status of a distinctly modern
kind _ connectedness _ and as power ebbs away from the traditional
ruling classes in Britain, it has flowed toward places like Soho
House, where Gordon Brown, the chancellor of the exchequer, lunched
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about belonging to the old Establishment anymore,''
Seaton said. ``It's about being connected to the media industries,
which New Labor sees as political tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Labor Party, entrenched in power, has stepped up a
campaign that seems aimed at sidelining the old gentlemen's clubs
and all they represent. The party recently floated plans to ban
men-only clubs on ``equal opportunities'' grounds, causing
consternation in St. James'.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Coming on top of Prime Minister Tony Blair's blistering attack
on ``the forces of conservatism'' three months ago, his reform of
the House of Lords (formerly described as the best and the most
exclusive club in London, with a largely hereditary membership) and
a proposal to ban fox hunting, it seems almost as if Labor is no
longer bent on bashing the rich, but on outright persecuting the
posh.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional clubs, formed partly so men could drink, eat and
gamble to their hearts' content, out of sight of wives and mothers,
remain thoroughly masculine worlds. Women are sometimes admitted
for lunch, or for parties (or as an ``honorary man,'' which is
Margaret Thatcher's status at the Carlton).
</P>
<P>
   But the idea that women are thereby excluded from
power-brokering _ the justification for ending single-sex policies
_ is pooh-poohed by Anthony Lejeune, the author of a history of
London clubs and a member of White's (one of the oldest of all).
</P>
<P>
   He argued for the status quo based on the very decline of the
old-line clubs' importance. ``Thirty years ago, I'd say pretty well
every Conservative MP was a member of the Carlton,'' he said.
``Today, I'd estimate about 30 or so are. MPs are simply not those
kind of people anymore.'' The belief that excluding women means
that they are missing out on major business deals is mistaken, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   If the Carlton is out in the cold in the Britain of New Labor,
Blair's name for his reinvented party, so the Travelers Club,
founded in 1814 by Lord Castlereagh, then the foreign secretary,
and Talleyrand, and reputed to be the haunt of powerful Foreign
Office mandarins, diplomats and the upper echelons of MI6, now
seems equally a backwater. It is no longer a place from which
treaties are brokered and gunboats dispatched.
</P>
<P>
   But while the traditional clubs' influence in world affairs may
have waned, the clubs have worked hard to attract young
professionals, and some have succeeded by cannily extolling their
ancient charms _ leather armchairs, faded carpets, portraits and
busts of past members. Some of the traditional clubs now have
seven- or eight-year waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Victor, an American-born, London-based literary agent, is a
member of both the venerable Garrick Club, the haunt of actors,
lawyers and writers, and a founder of the Groucho, and he finds
merits in both. ``I helped found the Groucho partly because I
wanted a club where men and women were on an absolutely equal
footing,'' he said. ``I took a woman to lunch at the Garrick today,
and she was made absolutely welcome, but there are rooms she can't
go into and so on. That's a very big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are great places for entertaining,'' he continued. ``The
Groucho is somewhere I'd go to when I've arranged to meet someone
for a drink or for dinner, but the Garrick has many of the
qualities of home. I can step into this wonderful old building,
leaving the noise of the city behind me, have a cup of tea, read a
newspaper, write a letter. Or you can also just sit down to lunch
at the members' table there, start talking to the person sitting
beside you and perhaps have some wonderful conversation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
