s l BC-NITEOUT-ROCKETTES-$AD     12-24 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-ROCKETTES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ROCKETTE'S, A SORORITY OF SINGING REINDEER AND TOY SOLDIERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Okla.)  
 (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)   By DAVID HANDELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To our day off!'' said Jaime Windrow, raising her
cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Amy Krawcek, raising hers. ``A much-deserved and
needed day off.''
</P>
<P>
   They clinked glasses with Kristin Tudor and Jacqueline Collins
in the unison one would expect from four Rockettes stepping out for
the night.
</P>
<P>
   These are not your grandfather's Rockettes. Variously sporting
leather pants, fake fur, feather cuffs, pashmina scarves and cell
phones, these women, all in their 20s, hit Veruka, a downtown club,
on Monday night to replenish calories lost during their grueling
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can't believe we have to work on the holidays,'' Ms.
Windrow said, ``but the holidays are what we're all about.''
(They're only employed full time from October to early January.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Krawcek added, ``we are all so tired of Christmas
music!''
</P>
<P>
   Over eight brutal weeks, two 36-Rockette teams (plus four
substitutes) split as many as 32 weekly performances of ``The Radio
City Christmas Spectacular.'' They have to whip through multiple
costume changes, from '20s flappers to toy soldiers to
white-antlered reindeer.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think we're so glamorous,'' said Ms. Krawcek, a
spirited brunette from Wisconsin, ``but we're in the dressing room
between shows with ice wrapped around our bunions saying, `Please
don't make me put my shoes back on!' or napping in sleeping bags.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krawcek pointed out that they had just performed 17 shows in
one week, while a typical Broadway dancer does 8.
</P>
<P>
   These four Rockettes, who have been with the company two to four
years, share a dressing room with eight other dancers. Ms. Windrow
likened it to ``a big sorority _ a therapy group.'' Since the
troupe is organized by height, these four, all 5-foot-8 or
5-foot-9, are positioned near one another onstage, and they all
work the late shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go out after the shows and wind down,'' said Ms.
Windrow, a redhead who grew up in Rhode Island, danced at Busch
Gardens, Disney World and MTV and will become a Knicks City Dancer
after the show on Jan. 5.
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on and the cosmopolitans kept flowing, the
women were easily prompted to re-enact the ``Marshmallow World''
number from the show, accompanying themselves on air ukuleles. And
they began to spill some secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tudor, a blond Oklahoman, turned out to be married. Two of
the women showed off pierced navels, though they are against
official Rockette policy. Why? Because during the toy soldier
routine, when the dancers do a domino-like fall into each others
arms, there's concern that the rings might rip out.
</P>
<P>
   After a few last turns on the nearly empty dance floor, the
dancers grew famished. On Mondays, Veruka's kitchen is closed, so
they went in search of food, first to the Coffee Shop, which was
closed for a Christmas party, and then to Joe's Pub, where a weekly
event called Slag was in full swing. But it was 1 a.m., and the
kitchen had just shut down. Exasperated, Ms. Tudor, the team's
dance captain and unofficial den mother, ducked out to forage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Windrow and Ms. Collins, a black-haired Long Island native,
took to the dance floor until Ms. Tudor returned with bags from
McDonald's. Ms. Tudor, a vegetarian, ate a Filet-O-Fish. Ms.
Krawcek removed her burger from the bun, firmly declaring, ``No
carbohydrates!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Windrow was reinvigorated. ``We have a day off tomorrow!''
she reminded everyone as she gobbled fries. ``I'm not a reindeer _
I'm a human!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
