u f BC-HOLIDAY-MERCHANDISE-B     12-24 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-MERCHANDISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME RETAILERS, HOLIDAY IS ALWAYS WHERE IT'S AT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Scrooge's mandate from the spirits _ keep Christmas in
your heart all year round _ also happens to be a business plan for
John Svenson and Tom Baldwin, operators of two distinct retail
chains that traffic almost exclusively in holiday merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   The Svenson family runs The Christmas Dove, and Baldwin is a
cofounder of Christmas Corner. While they sell similar merchandise,
each has a different strategy.
</P>
<P>
   With four stores and a retail Web site, The Christmas Dove is
open for business all year long. But though it is a 52-week
operation with a full-time staff, Christmas Corner opens most of
its 40 stores only in the months leading up to Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   At Faneuil Hall Marketplace, the recently refurbished Christmas
Dove sells just about anything a holiday home decorator could want,
from $9 Snoopy ornaments to $220 wooden figures inspired by the
Nutcracker ballet. For those who would deck the halls with a Tiny
Tim theme or a Wizard of Oz motif, there's plenty of product.
</P>
<P>
   As the store's $600,000 redesign suggests, business is booming,
and among the reasons why are a chap named Christopher Radko,
licensed goods from the likes of Disney, and the insatiable
appetite of tourists for year-round Yule gewgaws.
</P>
<P>
   According to Svenson, collectibles are the biggest thing to hit
his business this decade, and Radko gets much of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to collectibles, his Christmas tree ornaments are
as prized as Millennium Barbies or the latest Beanie Baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one rock star in our world, it's Radko,'' says
Garth Svenson, one of two sons in the family business.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Svensons, Radko's grandmother festooned the
Christmas trees of his youth with hand-blown glass ornaments from
Eastern Europe. But when the adult Radko went to buy his own
ornaments, he found that no US retailers carried them. So he
started his own business, and the rest is merchandising history.
</P>
<P>
   At The Christmas Dove, ornaments that bear his name can fetch
anywhere from about $25 to just over $200, and each season's new
designs are eagerly awaited by the affluent middle-age women who
make up a large part of Radko's following.
</P>
<P>
   Radko ornaments aren't the only items being hoarded. Collectors
also buy tiny Victorian villages made by Department 56. And for
those who want more than a simple creche, a nativity line from
Fontanini offers a full range of accessories. Buying a few pieces a
year, a collector can build a miniature Bethlehem that has
everything but a Lionel toy train running through it.
</P>
<P>
   Licensed products are nearly as big as collectibles. Teletubby
ornaments sold out quickly this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had Pokemon,'' Mark Svenson says wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   If collectors drive the high-end of the business, it's tourists
who make the cash registers ring 52 weeks of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the season, an ornament that evokes a vacation
spot makes a perfect tourist memento, says Garth Svenson.
</P>
<P>
   Already the store offers a line of Christmas mice collectibles,
and some day Boston tourists may be able to buy mice dressed up
like Paul Revere and Revolutionary War patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Because many ornaments are cheap and portable, they make good
gifts for a vacationer's house-sitter or for ``Aunt Mary who
watered the plants while you were gone,'' John Svenson says.
</P>
<P>
   With tourists in mind, he and his wife, Linda, have sited
several of their stores along routes traveled by vacationers.
</P>
<P>
   There's a Christmas Dove in Ogunquit, Maine, that does a brisk
trade in the summer. But because so few vacationers visit Maine in
the winter, the store is closed in December.
</P>
<P>
   At Christmas Corner, Baldwin employs a different strategy. His
Albany, N.Y. company leases vacant mall space for stores that open
around September and close around New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the chain is operating temporary stores in about 40
locations.
</P>
<P>
   With permanent space, The Christmas Dove can attempt to be a
holiday showcase.
</P>
<P>
   But because Christmas Corner stores can be in different space
every year, ``we skew toward the traditional and what people are
used to,'' Baldwin says of his merchandising strategy.
</P>
<P>
   According to Baldwin, better mall locations and a strong economy
have led to improved sales this year. But like The Christmas Dove,
Christmas Corner is a privately owned business and does not
disclose earnings or revenues.
</P>
<P>
   While most Christmas Corners are temporary, there is a
year-round staff and two permanent stores in tourist locations, one
in Atlantic City, N.J.; the other in Lake George, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   It was the tourist traffic that lured the Svensons to Boston in
1980, a few years after they opened their first Christmas Dove in
Barrington, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The Svensons located their store in Faneuil Hall Marketplace,
which had recently reinvented itself as a new kind of urban
shopping center that featured food courts and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Unique and wildly popular at first, the marketplace partly
became a victim of its own success. New malls copied its
innovations and lured away some customers. Then the ongoing Big Dig
project encroached on its space, disrupting the pedestrian traffic
that helped the marketplace boom in its first decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the willingness of the Svensons to invest in a remodeled
store, marketplace general manager Skip Coppola sees more signs of
a rebound. When the Big Dig is finished, Faneuil Hall Marketplace
will recapture much of its past glory, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The new two-level Christmas Dove is certainly impressive.
Designed to evoke a Dickensian village, it's more than four times
larger than the old store it replaces.
</P>
<P>
   If The Christmas Dove is full of Victoriana and Radko objets
d'art, Christmas Corner stores stick to a more basic approach.
</P>
<P>
   After all, says cofounder Baldwin, ``Santa Clause and little red
balls have been popular for hundreds of years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
