u f BC-BOND-RATES-NYT &LR;      12-24 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOND-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY RATES RISE AS THREAT OF YEAR 2000 PROBLEMS DIMINISHES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For much of this year, the question in financial
markets has been: What happens if there are real computer-generated
problems at the turn to the Year 2000? But as 1999 closes _ and as
the fears of Year 2000 fade _ the question has changed to: What if
there are no Year 2000 computer problems?
</P>
<P>
   That switch in sentiment, prompted in part by the Federal
Reserve's efforts to assure that the markets function as smoothly
as possible at year's end, has helped push Treasury interest rates
higher. Investors simply have decided that they do not need the
safe harbor of the government securities market.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury interest rates are likely to move even higher in early
January if, indeed, Year 2000 turns out to be not much more than a
computer blip. That means the yield on the 30-year bond, which was
at 6.49 percent Thursday, should easily shoot past 6.50 percent,
the highest it has been since September 1997. (Financial markets in
the United States were closed Friday in observance of the Christmas
holiday.)
</P>
<P>
   The main force driving all interest rates higher recently has
been a growing consensus among investors that the Federal Reserve
will be forced to raise its short-term interest rate target a
quarter of a percentage point at least twice early next year to
slow economic growth to a noninflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   That fear has helped push the yield on the 30-year bond up
almost half a percentage point since mid-November. The yield on the
two-year note, which is more sensitive to Fed rate moves, is at
6.23 percent, the highest it has been since May 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed has already raised its short-term interest rate target
three-quarters of a percentage point in three quarter-point moves
this year. But the 5 percent growth rate of the nation's gross
domestic product in the last six months is still well above the
central bank's speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve officials made their worries about the pace of
growth clear in the statement they issued after their policy-making
meeting Tuesday. Though they left their short-term interest rate
target unchanged, at 5.50 percent, and did not indicate that their
next move would be a rate increase because, they attributed that
stance to ``market uncertainties associated with the century date
change.''
</P>
<P>
   They said that they still remained ``concerned with the
possibility that, over time, increases in demand will continue to
exceed the growth in potential supply, even after taking account of
the remarkable rise in productivity growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Such trends, the statement continued, ``could foster
inflationary imbalances that would undermine the economy's
exemplary performance.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recent performance of corporate bonds and riskier
high-yield junk bonds, in comparison to the Treasury market, shows
that investors are also getting back some of their appetite for
risk, a signal that they are less worried about Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Since Nov. 5, when the yield on the 30-year bond was 6.05
percent, it has risen 44 basis points, or hundredths of a
percentage point. In that same time, the yield on junk bonds is up
just 12 basis points, while corporate bond yields are up 35 basis
points.
</P>
<P>
   According to Robert J. Barbera, chief economist at Honeig &AMP; Co.
in Rye Brook, those numbers show that investors are selling
government notes and bonds and buying corporate bonds because they
do not think they need the protection that the essentially
risk-free Treasury market provides.
</P>
<P>
   The selling adds to the pressure on Treasuries. If there are no
bad computer glitches at the turn of the year, the probability of
problems ``goes from small to zero, and you have to conclude that
the last vestige of Y2K hedges will be unwound,'' Barbera added.
That would mean more selling and even higher Treasury yields.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Treasuries have more to give up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve should get just as much credit for this
relaxation of Year 2000 fears as it gets for the fears that it will
raise its interest rate target next year.
</P>
<P>
   Central bank officials have been aggressive in their efforts to
assure that financial markets would not seize up near the end of
1999 and the start of 2000. Officials were worried, in part, that
just the fear of computer problems _ even if they never occurred _
would force many corporations and financial institutions out of the
market at year-end and leave others without the ability to raise
cash to meet ordinary needs.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed's reassurance campaign was capped in October, when the
central bank announced the sale of a form of Year 2000 insurance.
In seven separate weekly auctions, the Fed sold options that would
guarantee the availability of billions of dollars in ready cash
between Dec. 23 and Jan. 12. In the seven auctions, the Fed sold
$481 billion of insurance, easily enough to make a lot of investors
feel comfortable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1744EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
