<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8470 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-NY-CENTURY-EVENTS-ART     12-24 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CENTURY-EVENTS-ART-$ADV26-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP 10 PARTIES OF THE CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Parties run off affluent times,'' said Ann Douglas,
a historian and chronicler of that endless and great party,
Manhattan in the 1920s. ``This is when excitement is high and
society can express itself by wasting things.'' Her apercu explains
why a list of New York's most talked-about hosts of the 20th
century does not contain the name Brooke Astor. Rather it includes
Leonard Bernstein, Steve Rubell, Gayfryd Steinberg, Malcolm S.
Forbes and Puffy Combs.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to memorable parties, success is in direct
proportion to the outrage produced. Nothing, that is, succeeds like
wretched excess. Parties are to be measured by the column inches of
ritualized contumely printed by newspapers, including this one,
tsk-tsking over the frivolity of the privileged classes.
</P>
<P>
   With this guideline in mind, your correspondent combed through
the shelf of cocktail-party literature (the journals of Edmund
Wilson, the columns of Liz Smith) and compiled a party canon. Here
are 10 of the most famous, and infamous, celebrations by New
Yorkers in the last 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Cult of the Magazine, Part I: Fund-Raiser for The Masses,
Webster Hall, 1913. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Masses was a radical socialist magazine, the flower of the
new bohemia that had taken root in Greenwich Village. It published
short fiction by John Reed, as well as humor and general
intellectual rabble-rousing. Even though none of its contributors
were paid a dime, the magazine gasped for funds, so its desperate
editor, Max Eastman, organized a fund-raiser at Webster Hall. (Yes,
the same Webster Hall on East 11th Street where drag go-go dancers
later shimmied.) Admission was $1 with costume, $2 for plain
clothes. Drunkenness ensued, followed by nudity as the costumes
inevitably came off.
</P>
<P>
   Nudity on dance floors was thus established as ``something of a
trend,'' Terry Miller wrote in ``Greenwich Village and How It Got
That Way'' (Crown, 1990), echoing down to this day. Thanks to the
ball, The Masses was able to continue publishing into the early
days of World War I, known chiefly for its antiwar, front-line
reports by Reed. By 1917, its editors had been indicted for
sedition (all were later acquitted), and the magazine folded,
prompting a snide epitaph: ``The Masses, a magazine that didn't
give a damn, and got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Downtown, Uptown: Opening Party for the Dark Tower, 1928.  &LR;  At
the peak of the Harlem Renaissance and Prohibition, a
hair-straightening heiress named A'Lelia Walker Robinson opened her
136th Street mansion, christened the Dark Tower, as a literary
salon and dining club. It was the perfect site for discovering, as
Ann Douglas put it, ``the potent combination of stimulants and
strangers.'' Rothschilds, rebels and writers, including Langston
Hughes and Countee Cullen, drank Ms. Robinson's exquisite
Champagne, ignored her reportedly banal conversation and generally
``stretched themselves to be as sophisticated as New Yorkers have
since casually become,'' said David Levering Lewis, author of
``When Harlem Was in Vogue'' (Penguin, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``If modernism is the metaphor for the 20th century, you
couldn't think of a better site for it, for the new mix of things,
than Harlem,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Robinson, a daughter of Mme. C.J. Walker, one of the first
black millionaires, hoped her Georgian-style double town house,
with its bow front and French interiors, would be a haven for
writers and painters. But soon after the Dark Tower opened,
something went awry. The place was fabulous, but so were the
prices, Lewis wrote, and there was too strict a door policy,
effectively shutting out the very people Ms. Robinson had seemed
intent on welcoming. In their place were mainly ``the rich, the
prominent and the striving,'' Lewis wrote, adding, ``The artists
left hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Block Party and an Angry Mayor: Seventh Avenue, V-E Day, May
7, 1945.  &LR;  ``Unofficial'' news of Germany's surrender set New
Yorkers to dancing in the streets. They were throwing paper from
windows in Times Square. In the Garment District down Seventh
Avenue, they threw fabric, bales and bales of it. ``Every
conceivable remnant, in every possible shade and hue, turned and
squirmed in the thin morning sunlight,'' Meyer Berger reported in
The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``Then the very garment workers who had set it all
adrift on the morning wind were released by their employers, or
simply went AWOL, to wade and dance in this weird confetti of their
own making.''
</P>
<P>
   They drank and sang and congaed, while planting lipstick kisses
on passing servicemen. But then the disapproving voice of Mayor
Fiorello H. La Guardia boomed over a public-address system,
exhorting the revelers, Berger quoted, ``who had thoughtlessly left
their jobs, to go home or return to their jobs, and I want to beg
of them again, that having taken time off, not to do it again.''
Abashed, the crowds dispersed. Berger added, ``New Yorkers, in most
cases, went to bed at a decent hour, virtually certain that they
would awaken in a new day to be greeted by the official V-E
announcement.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Blockbuster: Premiere Party for ``Around the World in 80
Days,'' Madison Square Garden, Oct. 17, 1957. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe rode in on an elephant. Elizabeth Taylor played
host to what was probably the first over-the-top premiere for a
blockbuster movie. It was given by her husband of the time, Michael
Todd, the P.T. Barnum of Hollywood, and the event arguably ushered
in the modern Hollywood era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Todd's party signified what the 50's were all about:
bigger, better, elephantine,'' said Neal Gabler, author of ``Life
the Movie: How Entertainment Conquered Reality'' (Knopf, 1998).
``It was kind of prescient. He took one theme of the film industry,
the party, and commercialized it: the public was invited, tickets
were given out, and it was covered by everybody. He really got
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the Mix: Truman Capote's Black and White Ball, the Plaza,
Nov. 28, 1966. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first large party that contained these three very
different worlds,'' said George Plimpton, author of ``Truman
Capote'' (Doubleday, 1997), meaning politics, high society and
literature. It was also probably the purest example of what can be
called the Irwin Allen-``Towering Inferno'' theory of party-giving:
cram as many bold-face names into as large a space as will hold
them. ``Truman was very clever to make Kay Graham the focus,
because that allowed him to bring in Washington,'' Plimpton
continued. ``Anyway, you had the political world, the social world
_ the swans, as he called them, Jock Whitney and everybody _ and
the literary world, and then all those detectives from `In Cold
Blood.' And everybody in New York knew about it, even the
doormen.''
</P>
<P>
   In Plimpton's book, the novelist John Knowles remembered: ``I
felt as if we were in Versailles in 1788. People were applauding us
in the street as we walked in. We had our masks on. I thought, next
year it'll be the tumbrels taking us out to Herald Square, but at
the moment we were the last of the aristocrats. I remember arriving
at the side entrance of the Plaza. There was a solid phalanx of
news media. I forget exactly what group I was with but no stars
were with us. We arrived and the klieg lights went on because we
were masked. They turned on the lights and looked at us. Nobody.
The lights went off again.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Radical Chic: Fund-Raiser for the Black Panthers at the Park
Avenue Apartment of Leonard Bernstein and Felicia Montealegre, his
Wife, Jan. 14, 1970. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I dig absolutely,'' Leonard Bernstein said in response to a
Panther field marshal's call for Marxist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't dig, not really. How could he know that the little
fund-raiser he'd organized for the Black Panthers in his duplex
would unleash such a torrent of scalding ink, most famously
``Radical Chic,'' the social satire by Tom Wolfe first published in
New York magazine. (It included a long and delightfully wicked riff
on the hors d'oeuvres.)
</P>
<P>
   In another tasty exchange from the evening, detailed by
Charlotte Curtis in The Times, Cynthia Phipps, ``a member of one of
the country's wealthier aristocratic families,'' was introduced to
Henry Mitchell, a ``Harlem Panther defense captain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Phipps tentatively raised the subject of Nigeria, which
Mitchell said he really didn't know too much about,'' Ms. Curtis
wrote. ``She asked if there were any good capitalists. Mr. Mitchell
said he didn't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Last Days of Disco: Bianca Jagger's Birthday, Studio 54,
May 1978.  &LR;  It was just another night at the club that made
Halston, Liza, Andy and Bianca the Peanuts gang of the demimonde.
They even had their own magazine, Andy Warhol's Interview, in which
you could thrill to the chiaroscuro portraits of a 54 busboy or
Fran Lebowitz or Jerry Hall.
</P>
<P>
   This party had a baby theme, so the beautiful busboys wore
diapers, and Bianca _ that's what everyone learned to call her _
wore a baby-doll dress. There were bowls of Cracker Jack.
</P>
<P>
   The male model Sterling St. Jacques, naked and drenched in
silver glitter, led a white horse onto the dance floor. Astride was
another model, a glittery Godiva. And then Bianca and Godiva
changed places, and that picture, said Bob Colacello, then editor
of Interview, made the front pages of tabloids all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled, ``Baryshnikov and Mick Jagger were dancing
together, and everybody realized, `Hey, we can have a good time
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wretched Excess, Parts I and II: The Birthday Parties of Saul
Steinberg in Quogue, N.Y., and Malcolm S. Forbes in Tangier,
Morocco, August 1989. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Lordy, what a to-do for a couple of oldish rich guys: there were
tableaux vivants of the Flemish paintings collected by Steinberg in
Quogue and a cavalry charge in Tangier. Forbes, celebrating his
70th birthday, wore a kilt and staged a kiss with Elizabeth Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   And the costs! Steinberg, a financier, spent $1 million, and
Forbes, the patriarch of Forbes magazine, spent $2 million.
Columnists all managed to work the name Thorstein Veblen into their
copy, proclaiming the last chapter of the greed-is-good decade.
</P>
<P>
   All, that is, but Liz Smith, who cast herself as billionaire
apologist. She went so far as to print her estimate of Gayfryd and
Saul Steinberg's charitable contributions to date: $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Malcolm was just trying to give everybody a good time, and
people were so ungrateful,'' Ms. Smith said the other day. ``Parts
of it were taxing. Like the hotel, which they'd just painted, and
there was no air-conditioning, and so everybody had to sleep with
the doors open, and it smelled like paint and fish, and the
sleeping arrangements _ Gayfryd and Arnold Scassi in a room
together, and Mrs. Graham with somebody or other. I'm sure she'd
never had to sleep in a room with someone like that. And then, when
we got back, Malcolm asked me, `Why are they so ungrateful?' And I
said, `They're just rich people, and they're not used to hardship.'
The Steinberg party was just a good party. I don't care what
anybody says. It's just that the headline was `Wretched Excess.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rapper's Delight: Puffy Combs' 29th Birthday, Cipriani Wall
Street, Nov. 4, 1998. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was the night that Puffy Combs, an indifferent rapper but a
gifted music executive and entrepreneur, simultaneously arrived and
peaked in one four-hour period. Hideously oversubscribed, thanks to
a battery of publicists, and buffeted by more than 3,000
gate-crashers, the party boasted guests like Muhammad Ali, Donna
Karan and Sarah Ferguson, all of whom had to wait in the cold
behind police barricades, while Martha Stewart and Naomi Campbell
snuck in through a back door. Combs was four hours late.
</P>
<P>
   The price tag was $600,000, and it included $50,000 for a lucite
dance floor with the initials P.D. (for Puff Daddy), and go-go
girls with spangled pasties, in cages. A fiasco, yes, but since
then Combs has become a sort of paradigm of the so-called '90s mix,
a melange of young Hollywood, hip-hop musicians and the ubiquitous
Ms. Stewart, all linked by one insidious thread, a seemingly
insatiable appetite for shopping.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Cult of the Magazine, Part II: Debut Party for Talk,
Liberty Island, Aug. 2, 1999.  &LR;  Eight hundred celebrities _ from
Madonna to Al Sharpton _ and 2,000 Japanese lanterns twinkled
gamely at Tina Brown's last party of the decade as the fog rolled
in from the sea, a dank curtain ringing down on a show that had
gone on just a little too long. The mist grew thicker, until all
you could see was the boxed dinner in your lap and the back of your
seat mate's head, craning for a look at Demi Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just picnic food, and Queen Latifah screaming at us,''
said Michael Musto, who has covered parties for The Village Voice
since 1985. ``But over all, I gave it a thumbs up. I mean,
everybody was there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
