<HEADER>
A8474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-MILITIA-BOS &LR;      12-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-MILITIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN-BACKED MILITIA SET FOR FINAL ASSAULT ON GROZNY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND DMITRY SHALGANOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ As Russian planes and artillery pounded
Chechnya's capital Friday, Moscow said it was counting on a force
of pro-Russian Chechen militia to crush separatist fighters
defending the ruined city.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-Russian Chechens are led by Beslan Gantamirov, a
convicted embezzler and former mayor of Grozny who spent four years
in prison before he was pardoned and freed from jail in October by
Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin so he could take part in the
offensive against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Gantamirov said 1,500 of his loyalist militia were
already fighting in Grozny, and predicted the capital would come
under Moscow's control by the end of the year. Friday, Moscow's top
envoy to Chechnya, Nikolai Koshman, said parts of Grozny were
already under Russian control and that the complete capture of the
city was a matter of ``two, three, four days.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, speaking as his heavy artillery and cannons boomed,
Russian commander Col. Gen. Viktor Kazamesev told the Globe that
local Chechen militia _ not Russian troops _ would make the final
assault.
</P>
<P>
   But Moscow has underestimated the rebels many times before.
Another pro-Moscow Chechen leader, Malik Saidulayev, cast doubt on
predictions of a quick takeover, calling the Russian military
strategy in Grozny ``incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that any assault on the city would put thousands of
civilians who had ``no chance to leave'' in harm's way. And he
predicted the estimated 5,000 rebel fighters defending the city
would hold out for longer than Gantamirov and other Russian
commanders had predicted. ``I doubt Grozny will be taken in the
next few months,'' Saidulayev said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin is trying to avoid a repeat of the disastrous
1994-96 war Chechen campaign, this time moving cautiously and
methodically, pounding the city with artillery and bombs, then
sending special forces, and presumably, Gantamirov's militia, to
test the defenders. The results have been costly _ one such
reconnaisance group was surrounded and attacked by rebels last
week. Western news agencies reported that 115 Russians died,
although the military denied any attack.
</P>
<P>
   Koshman, repeating his confidence that Grozny would be in
Russian hands by New Year's, said civilians remaining in the city _
whom he estimated at 37,000 to 42,000 _ would be safe if they
stayed in the bomb shelters where they have been hiding since
Russia launched its offensive in October.
</P>
<P>
   Koshman's remarks to journalists in Moscow Friday seemed to
indicate that Moscow had fully backed away from eariler threats to
level the city. Koshman also stepped back from his previous
statement that Grozny was no longer fit for reconstruction, saying
instead that experts would assess the capital after the fighting
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Koshman also said an investigation was still under way to
determine if Russian soldiers killed as many as 41 unarmed Chechen
civilians in a village outside the capital, as human rights
organizations and Chechens reported.
</P>
<P>
   A federal prosecutor said Friday that nothing of the kind
happened, and the Defense Ministry denied reports that a Russian
commander of the troops had been fired over the incident. The
ministry said instead that Major General Vladimir Shamanov would be
awarded a Hero of Russia medal.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny's warren of concrete ruins and Soviet-era bunkers make it
easier to defend than the lowland towns and villages Russian forces
have conquered in three months of fighting. After last week's
resounding victory, Prime Minister Vladimir Putin may have decided
to pursue a quick military victory in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Gantamirov comes in. The Russian logic is that
loyalist Chechens know the city as well as the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to put things in order here ourselves, and the federal
army should stand in our rear and provide us support,'' Gantamirov
said recently in his hometown of Urus-Martan, 12 miles south of
Grozny, which his forces helped capture from rebel fighters earlier
this month.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke after his cortege, an armored black jeep equipped with
a big safe in the trunk and an armored personnel carrier with
faulty breaks, roared up to this ruined village 12 miles south of
Grozny, to recruit fighters and hand out uniforms. Russian
commanders, he said, had been unwilling to arm too large a force of
Chechens. But their faith in Gantamirov's fighters had grown after
a small group of about 300 militia had helped take Urus-Martan
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels deny Gantamirov played a role, saying their forces
had left Urus-Martan a day before the Russian forces moved in.
Gantamirov's troops fought on the Russian side in the first
conflict, but without great success.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with Gantamirov is that he was part of Moscow's
unpopular puppet regime during the first war, during which time he
was arrested and convicted for misuse of federal funds intended for
the reconstruction of Chechnya. Russia has ruled out talks with
Chechnya's popularly elected separatist leader, Aslan Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   During the trip to Urus-Martan, Gantamirov chatted amiably with
journalists, led toasts and served up shiskabob. But his aides
warned not to ask any questions about his conviction or time in
jail.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, officials say choosing to ally themselves with
Gantamirov is merely Chechen realpolitik.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what if Gantamirov took money _ everyone did,'' said Kim
Tsologov, Russia's deputy minister for ethnic affairs. ``Besides _
were the accusations against him as serious as the political role
he will play now? Or course not.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsogolov could not say what Gantamirov carried in that safe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Filipov reported from Moscow, Dmitry Shalganov reported from
Urus-Martan.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
