<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8475 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-SURVIVAL-B     12-24 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-SURVIVAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM SPOOKED STOCKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LifeTabs, vanilla-wafer-sized discs of concentrated food that
take the place of meals: 125,000 jars sold, at $19.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Survival pack for two _ a year's supply of dried fruits,
vegetables, margarine, milk, and seeds for planting sprouts: 60,000
packs sold, at $1,695 each.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium has been good to Sam Andy Inc., a Texas survival
food company that traditionally sells its wares to campers and
civil defense groups. Y2K has pried the market open wide, said John
Sauer, company CEO. By the start of 1999, sales had risen by 1,200
percent; the company started running round-the-clock shifts and
opened new factories in three states.
</P>
<P>
   And after a summertime lull, Sauer said, sales have climbed
again in the last few months. The procrastinator market, he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Though a survey indicates most Americans will make some minor
preparations, and mainstream retailers are stocking more staples in
anticipation, most consumers are facing the end of the millennium
with a collective yawn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, and a core of wary souls across the country has been
taking Y2K more seriously, pouring their fears _ and their cash _
into supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Sauer divides them roughly into two groups. There are the
regular stockpilers, who view food storage as a sort of insurance
policy. And there are the Y2K-watchers, from paramilitarists to
professionals, who are paying close attention to their cupboards as
the millennium nears.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Middelkoop, an industrial engineer in Amherst, Mass., counts
himself in the latter group. He doesn't expect a major crisis _
though, in engineer-speak, he says there's a ``non-zero chance of
Armageddon'' after Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Middelkoop said, he works closely enough with computers
to know what could go wrong. That's why he came up with his own Y2K
plan, which he posted on his Web site early last year.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with figuring out where to spend New Year's Eve and
ends with making sure he has ``marginal food sufficiency'' six
weeks after the Big Event.
</P>
<P>
   Middlekoop downgraded his plan slightly over time _ deciding,
for example, not to buy a Coleman portable stove. But over the
months, he has met most of his goals.
</P>
<P>
   Hoard food _ check. A friend found Canadian Army rations at a
surplus store.
</P>
<P>
   Buy batteries _ check. In a drugstore a few months ago, he found
24-packs on sale for $4.99.
</P>
<P>
   Acquire ``water storage device'' _ check.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those office water coolers?'' he said. ``One of them
disappeared from the office.''
</P>
<P>
   It's best to be safe, agrees Mike Woodard, a Sam Andy
distributor in St. George, Utah. He started to think about
potential Y2K problems last year, he said, when he scanned the
Internet and came across tales of serious preparations.
</P>
<P>
   After he read about a man who had purchased a cave and was
planning to subdivide it, Woodard decided he needed a disaster
blueprint of his own.
</P>
<P>
   After a year's worth of reassuring news reports, Woodard doesn't
fear widespread chaos anymore. Still, he fully expects a recession,
which he belives will start with Third-World countries and
breakdowns in the supply chain.
</P>
<P>
   To ready himself, he has stocked up on supplies, and plans to
withdraw all of his money from the bank just before the new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that everybody would at least be prepared to feed
their family and kids for at least 90 days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While three months' planning might be rare, researchers expect a
steady flow of people to head to automatic teller machines and
supermarkets this week _ and many government officials are urging
residents to fill their pantries for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   A September poll by the Gartner Group, a New York consulting
firm, found that 55 percent of Americans plan to withdraw two to
six weeks' worth of cash, and 67 percent plan to store enough food
for a week.
</P>
<P>
   That stockpiling impulse, some feel, could be a catalyst for
good works.
</P>
<P>
   Shaunti Feldhahn, a devout Atlanta churchgoer with a background
in risk management, decided last year that preparing seemed wise,
but was dismayed with what she viewed as an un-Christian trend
toward hoarding. So she started the Joseph Project 2000, a national
organization that urges churches to collect supplies to help the
community.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-area businesses and aid groups have been making modest
preparations of their own, on the off chance that disaster strikes
next week. Area hospitals have reported that they're stocking up on
generators and dry ice. Some ``Meals on Wheels'' programs plan to
give their clients extra food, water and flashlights for the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And several mainstream retailers are making sure their shelves
are fully stocked, to accommodate last-minute Y2K fears. Many
supermarket officials say they expect the approaching new year will
be like the best kind of winter storm: the one you know is coming
three years in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no different than a northeaster, or a blizzard, or a
hurricane,'' said Bernie Rogan, spokesman for Shaw's Supermarkets.
It's a matter of stocking the shelves, he said, with food that
``time and time again, our customers seek out when a low-pressure
area is approaching.''
</P>
<P>
   At Shaw's, that means tapping into long-tested storm preparation
plans and providing steady supplies of bottled water, canned goods
and batteries. And white bread, which seems to sell out during
every storm, Rogan said. He figures it serves as a companion piece
to peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   Rhode Island-based CVS drugstores aren't stocking their shelves
any more than usual, said spokesman Mike DeAngelis; December, he
added, is always a big month for batteries. And the chain is
confident it won't face a run on prescription drugs because
pharmaceutical companies typically keep 90-day supplies in the
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis said he doesn't expect much panic, because of the way
customers have behaved so far.
</P>
<P>
   When NBC aired its made-for-fear ``Y2K'' disaster movie last
month, he said, the CVS customer service office braced for
thousands of nervous callers. They didn't get one.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most mainstream stores and businesses aren't seeing much
interest in stockpiling Y2K survival goods, and aren't benefiting
from a millennium boost, said industry forecaster Kurt Barnard,
president of the Barnard Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   Even hoarders won't bring in new retail revenues, he said.
They'll be bringing home goods they usually buy _ just a few weeks
or months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're buying 20 boxes of cornflakes today, you certainly
have enough cornflakes to last you several months,'' Barnard said.
``Unless you're a cornflake freak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
