<HEADER>
A8478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CANADA-TERRORISTS-BOS     12-24 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-TERRORISTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTED TERRORISTS LONG A TARGET OF CANADIAN INTELLIGENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Individuals linked to an apparent conspiracy to
smuggle bombmaking materials and suspected terrorist operatives
into the United States had been monitored for years by Canada's
intelligence service _ and in October were at the center of a probe
by French counterterroism investigators concerned that Montreal is
becoming a new capital of Islamic radicalism.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Canadian police Friday issued an arrest warrant for
yet another Algerian national with possible links to a terrorist
conspiracy that may be planning millennium attacks on the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police are seeking Abdel Majed
Dahoumane, 32, of Montreal on two charges of illegal possession of
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Dahoumane is an associate of Ahmed Ressam, also 32, the
suspected terrorist arrested in Washington state last week trying
to smuggle explosives and other bombmaking material into the US.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the most massive cross-border investigations in
US-Canadian history continued to swirl around Quebec province, New
England and other parts of North America, officials confirmed that
Ressam had been under surveillance by the Canadian Security
Intelligence Service from the day he arrived in Canada in February
1994 carrying a false French passport and claiming to be fleeing
political persecution in his native Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   The monitoring was ordered, officials close to the Canadian
intelligence agency said, because of suspicions he was affiliated
with Algerian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   But the Canadian spy agency apparently lost sight of Ressam in
the crucial weeks before he travelled to British Columbia earlier
this year. It was while living at the Motel 2400 outside Vancouver
that Ressam and an associate _ who the RCMP believes was Dahoumane
_ are thought to have assembled the explosives and timing devices
with which he was caught by US Customs inspectors in Port Angeles,
Washington Dec. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Police and intelligence services fear the thwarted smuggling
attempt may have been part of a larger conspiracy by terrorists to
attack targets in the United States as Americans prepare to
celebrate the turn of the millennium. Those fears were heightened
by this week's arrests in Vermont of a man and woman from Montreal
with ties to violence-prone Algerian radical groups.
</P>
<P>
   French investigators earlier this year became keenly interested
in Ressam and his onetime Montreal roommate, Karim Said Atmani,
another Algerian living in Quebec with links to radical Islamic
terrorist organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In October, a special French investigation team arrived in
Montreal seeking more information on Ressam. But by then, to the
embarrassment of Canadian intelligence officials, he had dropped
out of sight _ apparently bound for British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Globe and Mail newspaper &UR;  &LR; in Toronto, the
Canadian spy service lost track of Ressam because government budget
cuts made surveillance too expensive to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe and Mail also quoted an unidentified senior
intelligence official as saying Ressam is linked to the the
notorious international terrorist Osama bin Laden, a Saudi
millionaire, now living in Afghanistan, thought to have
masterminded the 1998 bomb attacks against US embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania that killed more than 220 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, who has a Quebec record of theft convictions, is also
suspected of affiliations with the Armed Islamic Group _ often
known by its French acronym, GIA _ a violent Islamic radical group
whose terrorist operations have largely been confined to Algeria
and France. But Montreal police say Algerian gangs using the GIA's
trademark fundraising technique of robbery and extortion are on the
rise in Canada's second-largest city, which has an Algerian ethnic
community of 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorist experts say this reflects a trend of Islamic radicals
becoming increasingly active in North America, although using the
United States and Canada mainly as a source of money, not as
terrorist targets.
</P>
<P>
   However, said Gavin Cameron, senior research associate with the
Monterey Institute of International Studies in California, ``the
GIA, in the last year in particular, has become less predictable.
It's splitting. That may mean there are factions who are more
extreme, more willing to target...the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the counterterrorist investigation widening across the
United States and Canada is focused on establishing what links, if
any, exist between Ressam and two individuals arrested Dec. 19 at a
remote border crossing in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   US prosecutors say Lucia Garofalo, 35, and Bouabide Chamchi, 20,
both have ties to Algerian terrorist groups. The couple have been
in federal custody in Burlington, Vt., since a search of Garofalo's
car revealed trace amounts of explosives. So far, however, they
have been charged only with fairly minor violations of immigration
law.
</P>
<P>
   Garofalo is a Montreal welfare mother whose Algerian husband,
Yasim Rachek, was deported from Canada in 1993 for various crimes,
including use of a false French passport. He has been repeatedly
denied permission to return, which _ given that his wife is
Canadian, and willing to sponsor him _ suggests Ottawa has strong
reason to consider him dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler Neon Garofalo drove into Vermont, and a cellular
phone in her possession, belong to another Algerian in Montreal,
Brahim Mahdi, whom US intelligence officials say is a member of a
Swiss-based Islamic group founded by arms dealer Mourad Dhina, an
Algerian living in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Less is known about Chamchi, who showed up in Montreal in June
1997 as a stowaway aboard a ship from Europe. He is an Algerian
national who was carrying a fake French passport at the time of his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Susan Milligan of the Globe's Washington Bureau contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
