<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEANIE-BABY-REFERENDU     12-24 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEANIE-BABY-REFERENDUM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY PUTS FUTURE OF BEANIE BABIES TO A VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four months ago, Ty Inc. shocked children and other collectors
with a terse announcement that it would kill off its wildly popular
Beanie Babies line come Dec. 31. But Friday, just in time to spread
some extra Christmas cheer _ and, perhaps, stoke the ebbing flames
of the toys' popularity _ the privately held company said it would
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, what Ty said, in an announcement on its Web page
(www.ty.com), was that it would let the public vote on whether it
should keep churning out new Beanie Babies in the new millennium.
``After much thought, I am willing to put the fate of Beanie Babies
in your hands,'' Ty Warner, the company's owner, wrote on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers and collectors had little doubt about the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been deluged with calls and letters from children,
hospitals, charities and collectors, all begging them to
reconsider,'' said Mary Beth Sobolewski, an avid Beanie Baby
collector and the editor of Mary Beth's Bean Bag World Monthly,
which covers all kinds of bean bag collectibles. ``There's no doubt
in anyone's mind that people will overwhelmingly vote to keep the
line going.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner's abrupt change of heart has led many people to wonder
whether he ever intended to discontinue Beanies. The company did
not answer its telephones Friday, but toy industry experts suggest
that Warner was never about to kill a goose (or duck or swan) with
so many more golden eggs to lay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did exactly what a company should do, which is create
more frenzy for their product,'' said Stevanne Auerbach, who runs
Dr. Toy, a nonprofit concern in San Francisco that evaluates toys
for educational and play value.
</P>
<P>
   That frenzy has reached across the ocean. Toy experts say Beanie
Babies are even hotter sellers these days in Great Britain than in
the United States, where Pokemon and other products elicit the
fervor among children that Beanie Babies did a year or two ago. In
August, Ty set up its first distribution center in Japan. Ms.
Sobolewsky said the company had plans to step up marketing for
Beanie Babies in France, Portugal and Finland next year.
</P>
<P>
   While the death scare may have frustrated collectors, retailers
say it sent Beanie Babies flying off their shelves. ``It was all
promotional stuff, a way to make the product more in demand,'' said
Lorraine Papania, a co-owner of George's Games and Collectables in
Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   There may have been more going on than that. The market has been
swamped with counterfeit Beanies this year, while many authentic
Beanie Babies have wound up being sold through unauthorized
channels.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sobolewski said that Ty recently fired many of its
independent sales representatives in an attempt to attack the gray
market problem. She suggested that Warner may have used the
kill-them-off announcement to pave the way for a redesigned line of
Beanie Babies that are more difficult to counterfeit. ``I'm sure
he's taken that into consideration,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The telephone and Internet referendum will begin at 6 a.m. EST
on Dec. 31 and end at 6 a.m. on Jan. 2. Each life-or-death vote
will cost 50 cents, charged to a credit card. The company said it
would donate all proceeds to the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS
Foundation _ and expected to raise millions of dollars even at that
price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
