<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8488 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-     12-24 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKING UP ON ROSES, CONFIDENT OF SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(lh) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roses, like dogs, have tended to follow me through
the 20-some years of my nomadic gardening, from the ruins of a
stable yard on the North Shore of Long Island to the backyards and
roofs of Brooklyn to the old chicken yard of the family farm in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen a lot of roses by now, everywhere from botanical
gardens and the intimate private spaces of friends, to
Sissinghurst, where Vita Sackville-West gardened, in Kent, and
Mottisfont Abbey, in Hampshire, where Graham Stuart Thomas planted
his private collection of 350 varieties of old roses.
</P>
<P>
   It was there, looking at a Complicata, a single pink rose with
yellow stamens winding up an old apple tree, and feeling the
rain-drenched weight of Madame Hardy, a white hybrid damask rose,
heavy in my hand, that I must have taken one of those emotional
snapshots.
</P>
<P>
   The old brick walls covered with climbers; the pale yellow
foxgloves and chartreuse lady's mantle punctuating that sea of
purple, pink, white and red; the dark green leaves of the rugosa
roses and their heady scent.
</P>
<P>
   I could see it all again last weekend as darkness fell by 4 in
the afternoon and I ordered about a dozen old roses for the old
barnyard at the farm. This is my Mottisfont waiting to happen. The
stone walls _ built by my great-grandfather from rocks picked out
of his fields _ beg for roses and clematis to tumble over the top.
Sheltered by the barn and the abandoned pig house (another
picturesque ruin), the space suggests a few fruit trees, like
apricot, peach, quince and plum, that will make sturdy trellises
for climbers.
</P>
<P>
   I want to plant a little history here, too, beginning with Rosa
gallica, a low sprawling shrub with lightly scented, single pink
flowers. A native to southern Europe and farther east, it fathered
one of the first gallica hybrids, Gallica officianalis, the
apothecary rose, said to have been brought to England by the
Crusaders, where it was named the Red Rose of Lancaster. Its deep
pink, 3-inch, semidouble flowers with golden stamens open in June
and produce fat red hips in fall.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Rosa Mundi, or R. gallica versicolor, whose pink
and white striped flowers Sackville-West described as ``red cherry
juice generously stirred into a bowl of cream.'' I want Tuscany,
too, a semidouble, deep purple gallica that Thomas, a stickler for
detail, insists is not purple at all, but ``murrey,'' the color of
mulberry juice. And Belle de Crecy, another fragrant gallica, with
tones of cerise and purple.
</P>
<P>
   It's wise to order roses now, before nurseries run out of their
best stock and while there's plenty of time to get them to your
door by early spring. Roses grown on their own roots tend to be
hardier creatures than grafted roses, which may succumb to a hard
winter. If only the rootstock survives, the roses that bloom the
next spring will be a lot different from the previous year's.
</P>
<P>
   Many old roses make good climbers, like Madame Hardy, which
completely covers a 10-foot pillar at the Cranford Rose Garden at
the Brooklyn Botanical Garden, and Gloire de Dijon, a China rose
with Bourbon blood, which covers itself with large, fragrant
quartered roses that are a buff-apricot. Quartered roses are
usually flat, and full, with twisty petals that appear to be
divided into four sections.
</P>
<P>
   Frau Karl Druschki, a hybrid perpetual bloomer developed in
Germany in 1901, will also thrive as a climber or if trained on a
pillar. Its snow-white flowers start as pink buds and open four
inches across. But be warned: it is susceptible to mildew.
</P>
<P>
   I've ordered others that stand up well to the heat, like Graham
Thomas, a fragrant, lemony yellow English rose that starts as an
apricot-pink bud and opens to a cup of swirling petals three inches
wide. It's a tall shrub type that can easily grow to nine feet tall
and five feet across, so give it space.
</P>
<P>
   Named in honor of the venerable plantsman who brought so many
old roses back from oblivion, Graham Thomas is one of many English
roses developed by David Austin. They combine the voluptuous shape,
color and fragrance of old roses with the vigor and perpetual
flowering of modern ones.
</P>
<P>
   Other heat-tolerant beauties on my list are Othello, a very
fragrant, deep red English rose that darkens to near-purple and can
be trained on a pillar or fence, and Zephirine Drouhin, a deep pink
Bourbon rose developed in 1868 that makes a good climber and blooms
all season. It's very fragrant and has few thorns. Experts warn
that these two have a tendency to mildew, but I'll take the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Dortmund, a bright-red single with a white center, stands up to
both heat and cold. It's hardy to 30 below, so I forgive its scant
scent.
</P>
<P>
   Other climbers include Souvenir de la Malmaison, named in honor
of the Empress Josephine's garden at Malmaison, with fragrant
pink-white quartered blossoms that open wide and flat, and the
yellow, lightly scented Lady Banks rose, Rosa banksiae Lutea, a
rambler (a climber with long, flexible canes). Lady Banks' canes,
which are thornless, can grow 20 feet, and they have exfoliating
bark the color of cinnamon. This one is great for growing over a
porch roof.
</P>
<P>
   Fruehlingsgold, a shrub rose with fragrant, near-single,
butter-yellow petals and golden stamens, also crept onto my list,
somehow. So did Madame Gregoire Staechlin, a large-flowered pink
climber with silken petals.
</P>
<P>
   It breaks your heart because it blooms so briefly in the spring
and then again in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Following are nurseries that offer roses grown from their own
roots.
</P>
<P>
   Antique Rose Emporium, 9300 Lueckemeyer Rd., Brenham, TX 77833;
(800) 441-0002; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Creek Nursery, P.O. Box 411, Northport, WA 99157; (509)
732-6219; free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom Roses, 24062 Riverside Dr. NE, St. Paul, OR 97137;
(503) 538-1576; catalog is $5.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Own-Root Roses, 6 Sheffield Rd., Nashua, NH 03062; (603)
888-2214; catalog is $3.
</P>
<P>
   Roses Unlimited, Route 1, Box 587, Laurens, SC 29360; (864)
682-7673; free listing with stamped self-addressed No. 10 envelope.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Gardens, 2833 Old Gravenstein Highway South, Sebastopol,
CA 95472 (707) 829-2035; catalog is $10, applied to order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
