<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8490 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-3TAKES     12-24 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-3TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S LIGHT DIMS IN SOUTHEAST ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
 (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are being sent to NYT photo and graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ When Nakamasa Okamoto arrived in the mid-1980s from
Kyoto, Japan, and opened the Naniwa restaurant in a shopping center
here, Japanese contractors building Singapore's subway lined up to
get in. Over the years, karaoke lounges and other Japanese
restaurants filled the building, serving legions of Japanese
bankers and traders who arrived to do business from this hub of
Southeast Asian commerce.
</P>
<P>
   With its racks of sake bottles and decorative fans, the Naniwa
prospered, a cozy retreat in a Japanese mercantile empire that
Western investors overlooked until recent years. Okamoto added a
karaoke room and hired three chefs from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But the financial crisis that rocked Southeast Asia in 1997 and
1998 also pummeled Japan, the region's largest foreign lender and
investor. So, already suffering from recession at home, Japan
rushed to cut its exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the shopping center around the Naniwa is much quieter.
Where once 120 businessmen a night would visit Okamoto's restaurant
and spend up to $90 each, now only about 35 come to spend half as
much. Okamoto has had to close the karaoke room, lay off his chefs
and start cooking himself. ``All my regular customers went back to
Japan,'' Okamoto said. ``It's getting hard to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Southeast Asia claws its way back to economic health,
Japan Inc. still appears to be retreating. In the first half of
1999, Japanese banks pulled nearly $10 billion in loans from the
region, part of a rollback that has sucked $108 billion out of
Southeast Asia since 1995 and cut Japan's share of foreign lending
here from more than half to less than one-third. Last year,
Japanese investment fell by almost half; Japan has been displaced
by Britain, which has also reduced its interests in Southeast Asia,
atop the list of the region's largest foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Southeast Asia's bureaucrats and industrialists
have slowly been abandoning a model of economic and corporate
management that they learned from Japan _ one in which the state
steers the economy and channels people's savings to a core of
powerful banks and conglomerates to develop manufacturing exports.
Instead, they are struggling to adapt to a British-American vision
of free and transparent markets, a shift that seems increasingly
inevitable because of the advance of the Internet and its free flow
of information.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult transition, one that pits Asia's political
establishment against the demands of a new global marketplace.
Asian politicians accustomed to decades of economic control now
preach the gospel of commercial upheaval: free enterprise,
entrepreneurship, deregulation and competition. Beneath the
rhetoric, however, economic recovery and swollen public coffers are
allowing them to proceed deliberately, even haphazardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a bit of experimentation going on right now,'' said
Mark Hansen, a consultant at Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton in Jakarta who
has lived in the region for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   That has not escaped notice in Tokyo. Despite the increasing
popularity abroad of Japan's high-technology wizardry and animated
emissaries like the Pokemon characters, the country's financial
muscle in Asia is waning, part of a broad decline in its economic
power. Western companies, according to a recent report by Japan's
Nomura Research Institute, ``may replace Japanese companies'
dominant position there in the next few years.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But Western investors are not filling the void just
yet. For one thing, Asia doesn't need to replace all that Japanese
money: it was part of the capital overexpansion that set the stage
for the crisis in the first place. And most investment bankers in
the region say their customers back home still consider Asia too
risky. ``There's still a big gap between offshore investors'
appetite for risk and Asia's credit fundamentals,'' said Stephen W.
Berger, managing director of J.P. Morgan's investment banking unit
here.
</P>
<P>
   So in large part, the region itself is picking up the slack.
With their own banks paralyzed by bad debts, Asian companies are
repaying Japan by selling stocks and bonds to investors at home.
That, in turn, is promoting more sophisticated and transparent
capital markets, while reducing Southeast Asia's reliance on
fair-weather funds from abroad and the political strings that are
attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're regaining the upper hand over the political
environment,'' said William C. Belchere, head of fixed-income
research and strategy at Merrill Lynch in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   All of this appears likely to alter irrevocably a relationship
that dates to the early part of this century, when a rapidly
industrializing Japan ventured into Southeast Asia for oil, rubber
and other raw materials. In return, Japan promised to liberate the
region from European rule and establish what it called the Greater
East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
