<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8491 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IVORY-MUTINY-BOS &LR;      12-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVORY-MUTINY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMY MUTINEERS SAY THEY CONTROL IVORY COAST GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Ivory Coast, long a bastion of stability in
turbulent West Africa, was shaken Friday as army mutineers claimed
to have overthrown the government in what would be the nation's
first such takeover since independence.
</P>
<P>
   A day after angry soldiers marched through the streets of the
capital, Abidjan, protesting over pay and living conditions, former
army chief of staff Robert Guei declared on state television that
``from this instant, President Henri Konan Bedie is no longer
president of Ivory Coast.'' Guei suspended the country's courts,
parliament, and constitution, and imposed a nighttime curfew from 9
p.m. to 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the mutineers' control remained uncertain early
Saturday. Military loyalists said Bedie was still in command, but
diplomatic sources said he had taken refuge at the French Embassy.
Meanwhile, the world community condemned the coup.
</P>
<P>
   The unrest in Abidjan marks a sour end to the year in Africa,
when many leaders express hope that the dawning century will be
witness to widespread renewal and progress on the continent, and
comes at a particularly delicate time for West Africa. Nigeria is
in the middle of a tense transition from military role to
democracy. Sierra Leone was torn apart this year after troops
rebelled against the government _ protesting, among other things,
inadequate pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivory Coast is an important test case,'' said Roger Berry, an
Africa specialist at GPC O'Neill and Associates, a public affairs
consulting firm in Boston. ``It is basically coming out of a
20-plus year benign dictatorship. The country was taking steps to
modernize its economy. Democracy was trying to break through. Now
the past is rearing its head, and it will be interesting to see if
the center holds.''
</P>
<P>
   The overthrow recalls a warning made by South African President
Thabo Mbeki last year after a coup in another West African country,
Togo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year 2000 is upon us,'' Mbeki, the chief visionary of an
African Renaissance, told African leaders in 1998. ``To achieve an
African renewal in politics, in economics, in social life and in
culture we have to act together as Africans. As Africans we must
get together and say it is incorrect for anyone of us to steal a
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest cocoa producer, Ivory Coast was under
one-man rule from independence from France in 1960 to the death of
its first president, Felix Houphouet-Boigny, in 1993. Its trademark
stability masked underlying cleavages, including a deep rift
between Bedie, who was elected president in 1995, and Guei, who was
appointed military chief by Houphouet in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bedie sacked Guei shortly after coming to power after the
military chief criticized the new president for using soldiers to
quell student riots in 1995. Guei joined Bedie's Cabinet a year
later as minister of sports, but was fired again for unknown
reasons after the 1996 Olympics. In 1997, he faced a final
humiliation when Bedie ordered him removed from the military
entirely in the wake of unsubstantiated allegations that Guei had
tried to plan a coup two year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Political sources say that rivalry between Guei and Bedie dates
back to the death of Houphouet-Boigny, when former Prime Minister
Alassane Ouattara briefly challenged Bedie, the constitutional
successor, for the presidency. Ouattara had planned to challenge
Bedie in an election next October,
</P>
<P>
   Guei demanded Friday that all political prisoners be released,
including 11 leaders of Outtara's party. ``Power is in my hands,''
Guei said. ``I will take care of everybody. You should not be
worried.'' The strength of Guei's movement is, however, uncertain.
He appears to have fewer than 500 soldiers out of a 7,000-strong
army backing his plot, according to diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   Military sources, meanwhile, told Reuters that Bedie had given
the order to loyalist forces to counterattack but that he and his
commanders were debating how best to crush the revolt without
civilian casualties. Initial orders called for a low-key approach.
</P>
<P>
   Friday opened in Abidjan with sporadic gunfire, and mobs of
youth spread out, hijacking cars and mugging commuters.
</P>
<P>
   UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan condemned the coup, saying
``violence to disrupt a country's political process is
unacceptable.'' And France, which still has troops inside its
former colony, issued a statement calling for the ``immediate
re-establishment of order and security in Abidjan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
