<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8492 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-2NDTAK     12-24 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SINGAPORE: Co-Prosperity Sphere.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is just what Western observers said Japan had finally
achieved by the early 1990s. Japanese companies, expelled during
World War II, returned to Southeast Asia in the 1950s with
Washington's encouragement. By the mid-'60s, Bangkok was glowing
with neon signs advertising Japanese products. Japanese motor
scooters choked the streets of Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's financiers were close behind. ``Banks followed, first
lending to Japanese companies, then countries and then companies
down there,'' said Koji Yamashita, a credit officer at the
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan who spent 13 years in Southeast Asia
for the bank.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of yen began in earnest in 1985, when the Plaza
Accord, an effort by the Group of Seven industrialized nations to
devalue the U.S. dollar, sent the Japanese currency surging. As
their goods became more expensive overseas, Japanese exporters
hurried to build factories in Southeast Asia, where land and labor
were cheaper. Matsushita Electric Industrial, for example, now has
58 factories around Southeast Asia, 14 of them in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   The strong yen helped finance Asia's so-called miracle. It also
created an asset bubble in Japan that the Japanese central bank
finally punctured in 1989. High and then record low interest rates
both worked to drive Japanese banks deeper into Southeast Asia,
where they became a ready source of cheap funds. By 1995, Japan
accounted for more than half of all foreign loans to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economic stature in the region is also reflected in
trade figures. Despite Southeast Asia's latest troubles, Japan
racked up a trade surplus of 854 billion yen with the region in its
most recent fiscal year, which ended on March 31; the year before,
the surplus stood at 2.1 trillion yen.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of Japan's economic brawn still abounds, from its cars
(9 of 10 vehicles in Thailand are Japanese) to its tourists (Japan
is Southeast Asia's largest single source of visitors). The biggest
shopping mall on Singapore's Orchard Road is anchored by the
Japanese department store Takashimaya. Isetan, Seiyu, Parco and
Sogo all have department stores here, each a commercial aircraft
carrier in a Japanese retail flotilla and a lifeline for the more
than 30,000 Japanese residents of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Daimaru's grocery in Singapore, for example, offers all the
tastes of home: dried seaweed, $2 pears flown from northern Japan
and, most important to Daimaru's largely Japanese clientele,
Japanese beer by the case. In the same shopping center are a golf
store, a Japanese bookshop and a school for Japanese tea
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Americans largely ignored Asia's yen-driven
metamorphosis. ``U.S. investors really weren't
internationalizing,'' said Jesper Koll, an economist at Merrill
Lynch in Tokyo. ``Even people who were investing in Japan were
considered madmen.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the United States decided that it was time to get in on
the region's boom. Under Robert Rubin, then the Treasury secretary,
the department worked to open Asian capital markets. At the same
time, the Group of Seven agreed to push up the value of the dollar
against the yen _ the Plaza Accord in reverse.
</P>
<P>
   As European banks joined their U.S. counterparts in cashing in,
the Japanese were cashing out. In 1995, $47 billion in Japanese
loans drained from Southeast Asia, an amount almost equal to what
all the other foreign lenders combined were pumping in.
</P>
<P>
   But what has sent Japanese banks running was not the $77.5
billion in loans they still have in Southeast Asia. It is the $272
billion in bad loans they still have in Japan. Of the 1.13 trillion
yen in problem loans at Sanwa Bank, for example, only about 12
percent are in Asia outside Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is at home, not here,'' said Akio Takeuchi,
general manager of the Southeast Asian operations of Fuji Bank.
</P>
<P>
   As banks pulled back, Japanese investment in Southeast Asia also
evaporated. Direct investment by Japan fell last year to its lowest
since 1993; in Indonesia, for example, it dropped 75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese investment in the region may never be the same. Osamu
Hosokobu, director of the venture capital firm Japan Asia
Investment in Singapore, says Japanese manufacturers already have
enough factories in the region. Most future investment, he says,
will probably be for upgrading operations, not building new ones.
``Japanese investment in Asia is almost done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Japanese worry that Japan has lost respect as an economic
role model. Among them is Kazuo Sugino, secretary-general of the
Singapore Japanese Association, a private club for Japanese
residents. In a room adorned with photographs of Japanese naval
vessels and Japan's emperor, Sugino recalled Singapore's founding
prime minister, Lee Kuan Yew, holding up Japan as a model. ``These
days,'' he said, ``I never hear Singapore's leaders praise Japan's
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said J. Mark Mobius, president of the Templeton
Emerging Markets fund, ``most of these countries have begun to
reject the Japanese model.'' Singapore is leading the trend,
fostering an entrepreneurial class and a bond market, deregulating
its financial markets and opening its banking industry to foreign
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand's central bank recently prohibited senior bank
executives from holding more than three company directorships, a
move intended to break up the links between lenders and borrowers _
a hallmark of Japan's system. Minority-shareholder rights are
gaining ground, too, and freewheeling, Silicon Valley-style venture
capitalism is the rage.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8493 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-3RDTAK     12-24 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASEAN-ECON-ART-3RDTAKE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SINGAPORE: the rage.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors like Mobius yearn for even faster change, but
nationalism is a powerful obstacle. Many Southeast Asians, see the
changes as a new imperialism. In their eyes, the opening of capital
markets means accepting foreign ownership and management of
national icons.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in Indonesia and Thailand, efforts to settle billions of
dollars in unpaid corporate debts often stumble over the likelihood
that doing so would mean selling out to Western investors, who,
unlike their Japanese predecessors, refuse to be silent partners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps furthest from rejecting its tutor to the north is
Malaysia. When Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad came to power in
1981, during an economic recession, he urged Malaysians to ``look
East'' to Japan; today, he remains one of the region's most vocal
opponents of what he calls Western market fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia was one of the few Southeast Asian countries to survive
the latest crisis without having to accept money from the
International Monetary Fund. And the country's apparent success
emboldens those who, while conceding that slumping investment may
cost Japan some influence, say the Japan example has not been
discredited. ``I don't think there was any proof that the Japanese
financial model failed,'' said Takatoshi Ito, an economics
professor who this year took over as Japan's deputy vice finance
minister for international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Ito and his predecessor Eisuke Sakakibara share Mahathir's
disdain for the wrenching economic changes that the IMF made
prerequisite to the $118 billion in emergency financial aid it
administers to the region. Instead, they argue that what small
nations need is insulation from global financial shocks.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, the Japanese suggested an alternative, a $100
billion Asian Monetary Fund led by Tokyo. The United States
Treasury shot down the proposal, saying it would undermine the
IMF's authority. Revive your own economy first, the Americans told
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   So Japan came up with a more palatable alternative: a $30
billion Miyazawa Plan, which along with other loans, credit
guarantees and contributions means up to $80 billion in financial
assistance from Japan to Asia, more than any other nation has
provided for the region's rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the IMF weakened by accusations that its policies
worsened some countries' plight, Asian officials have renewed calls
for an Asian fund. Many would also like to see Sakakibara take over
from Michel Camdessus, the outgoing managing director of the IMF, a
seat traditionally filled by a European.
</P>
<P>
   Japan continues to advocate an Asian fund, though only as the
IMF's sidekick. ``We don't want to establish a regular organization
that will be seen by the U.S. government as antagonistic to the
international financial order,'' said Hiroshi Hashimoto, Japan's
ambassador to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Hashimoto, a cousin of Ryutaro Hashimoto, Japan's sword-fighting
former prime minister, has been busy parrying critics _ including
some from Singapore's government _ who say that Japan has done too
little to help Asia.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, Japan has long felt misunderstood and hamstrung
in the region. A pacifist constitution, regionwide mistrust and
American ascendancy relegated Japan to a back-seat role during the
Cold War, silently bankrolling Asia's wobbling dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   The investment brought considerable backlash. Japan acquired a
reputation among some in Southeast Asia as an economic opportunist.
Riots erupted when Japanese Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka visited
Jakarta in 1974; thousands of Toyotas burned in the streets as
crowds protested links between Japanese investors and cronies of
Suharto, then the president.
</P>
<P>
   With its enormous trade surplus, Japan has been accused even by
admirers like Mahathir of maintaining a one-sided relationship,
hesitating to hire local managers in its Southeast Asian operations
or to transfer technology.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, critics have accused Japan of tying Miyazawa Plan money
to the purchase of Japanese goods or the payment of Japanese loans.
Hashimoto says most of the aid comes without strings; rather, he
said, the plan demonstrates Japan's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The continued economic influence of Japan is guaranteed to some
extent by the roughly $1.7 billion in development aid it lavishes
on the region every year, not to mention the nearly $100 billion in
annual trade between the two.
</P>
<P>
   And Japan's banks still have potentially huge power: As the
region's biggest lenders, they dominate the committees deciding
what to do when companies stop repaying. But unlike American
bankers, who learned during the Latin American debt crisis that the
fastest path to recovery is to reschedule debt quickly, even if it
means taking losses, the Japanese prefer to dig in, said James
Fiorillo, an analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy has cast them as obstacles to Asia's recovery.
When the Indonesian automaker Astra International told bankers last
August that it needed to reschedule $1 billion in debts, for
example, it took Japanese bankers 11 months to agree to a deal _
and then only after Astra agreed to pay back its loans in full.
``The Japanese have unrealistic expectations,'' said one European
banker who serves with Japanese counterparts on several
restructuring committees.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese bankers say they need to be mindful of the $180 billion
in taxpayer money they were given to recapitalize. ``If there's a
way to minimize our loss, we have to do it,'' said Takeuchi of Fuji
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorillo of ING Barings predicted that Japanese banks would
continue to retrench in Asia, in part because they need to fend off
increasing threats at home from the likes of Fidelity Investments
and Merrill Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities are opening for Western financiers in Southeast
Asia, too. Citigroup and ABN Amro Holding, the biggest Dutch bank,
are among the handful of Western banks expanding their retail
services in the region. ABN Amro has also been moving its Singapore
staff to offices around Asia to reflect a shift toward borrowing in
local currency instead of in dollars or yen. Western bankers also
dominate another growing business _ advising Southeast Asian
governments and companies how to fix the mess left by the economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, the private money for rebuilding Asia's
economies is coming not from abroad but rather from a mountain of
domestic savings. When Siam Cement of Thailand, for instance,
decided in April to sell 50 billion baht ($1.3 billion) in bonds to
help pay off $2 billion in foreign debt _ mostly to Japanese banks
_ it sold them to Thai banks and local investors, said Bunn
Kasemsup, the company's assistant corporate treasurer.
</P>
<P>
   That would very likely please Alan Greenspan, the Federal
Reserve chairman, who recently urged Asia to reduce its reliance on
bank lending. Bank loans represent only about 20 percent of assets
in the United States, according to J.P. Morgan; they account for 74
percent of assets in Indonesia and 84 percent in Thailand. A more
developed bond market, economists say, would help bring
transparency to the region and reduce foreign investors' concerns
about Asian risk.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese money will find its way back to Southeast Asia,
economists predict, though the form and the mechanisms may not be
the same. The megamergers seizing Tokyo lately are part of a
revolution in the way Japan's huge savings are invested. In the
future, ``a Japanese bank could be lending to a foreign bank in
Tokyo that ends up lending through Hong Kong to an Asian bank that
ends up lending in Thailand,'' said Kenneth Courtis, an economist
at Deutsche Bank in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Ambassador Hashimoto, meanwhile, is trying to tap new sources of
Japanese investment for Southeast Asia. In August, he met here in
Singapore with a delegation from small and midsized businesses from
Osaka. He has even suggested that Asian cities try to lure Japan's
growing number of pensioners as long-term visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is not finished,'' Hashimoto said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
