<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     12-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS NOT WORRIED ABOUT Y2K  
 CLINTON AVOIDS FEUD OVER FLAG  
 COUNTING HURRICANE VICTIMS IN NORTH CAROLINA  
 SENATOR WANTS CLEAR POLICY ON CUBAN PRISONERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ What me, worry?
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the hype this past year about the Y2K bug and
widespread computer crashes, most lawmakers don't seem anxious
about the potential for problems come New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   An informal survey of House members and senators found few
making any extraordinary plans to prepare for a bumpy transition
into 2000. No one appears willing to celebrate the new year in a
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and I have prepared for Y2K like we would for a
winter storm,'' wrote Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., in a recent
column. ``While we need to prepare for potential Y2K related
disturbances, we need to remember not to panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards warned against senior citizens' falling victim to Y2K
scams, urging them not to give personal information, like credit
card numbers, to strangers over the phone.
</P>
<P>
   As for New Year's Eve, he plans to be in Raleigh with family and
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Sen. Jeff Session, R-Ala., said his millennium
celebration would be a low-key affair with close friends and family
in Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like things are going to go well, but there might be
some minor problems,'' he said of the potential for computer
glitches.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, computer worries seem to have taken a back seat to the
possibility of terrorist attacks during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   With the State Department issuing warnings for Americans
traveling abroad and local police departments urging citizens to be
cautious in large crowds this season, the threat of attacks has put
something of a damper on the holiday spirit in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most officials described themselves as optimistic that
any attacks could be foiled with heightened security measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not suggest that people significantly alter their
plans,'' Sessions said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., said the latest warnings about
terrorism threats must be kept in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a concern, but I have more concern about safety in
our schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NO RENAISSANCE MAN HE
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has a good excuse, but in ducking out on the
wonky annual Renaissance Weekend in South Carolina, he is also
avoiding a ticklish political subject.
</P>
<P>
   The president and first lady are staying in the White House for
the New Year, hosting millennium events on the mall and monitoring
any Y2K breakdowns or incidents of terrorism. But by skipping the
South Carolina confab, he is staying out of a feud over the state's
display of the Confederate flag. Civil rights groups have suggested
a visitor boycott of the state in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the president's views on the Confederate banner,
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said he has not run the issue up
the flagpole with Clinton. But he confirmed the president would not
be in Hilton Head for an event he almost always attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot going on here,'' Lockhart said of Washington.
``This is obviously a very important milestone the nation will
celebrate, the world will celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTER THE DELUGE
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eva Clayton, D.N.C., wants to make sure victims displaced
by Hurricane Floyd don't suffer again by not being counted in the
2000 census.
</P>
<P>
   Their participation is even more vital since federal aid is
distributed on the basis of population and failure to take part in
the census could cut federal funds needed for rebuilding. Many of
those who lost their homes to the storm are minorities, a group
typically under-represented in the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flooding makes the potential for undercounting in eastern
North Carolina even more likely now,'' Clayton said recently.
</P>
<P>
   While the Census Bureau plans a special effort in North
Carolina, Clayton urged the bureau to be more aggressive in
reaching out to flood victims. She called for community involvement
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort must be broad and comprehensive,'' she said. ``Much
is at stake for us.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKE NO PRISONERS
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., wants no repeat of the recent hostage
standoff in a St. Martin, La., parish prison involving Cubans
awaiting deportation after serving criminal sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux called on the Senate Judiciary Committee to hold hearings
next year on what to do about 2,400 Cubans remaining in other U.S.
prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not right that American taxpayers should continue paying
to feed, house and provide medical care to Cubans who have served
their time for their crimes,'' said Breaux. ``It's time to send
them home.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said that a clearly articulated policy would deter others
from rioting in prisons in an attempt to force the issue.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin are in the Washington bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1810EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
