<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-STOCKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH COMPANIES RIDING HIGH-TECH STOCK SURGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pre-Christmas buying spree that drove the Nasdaq briefly to
the 4000 market Thursday made telecommunications and high-tech
stocks the big winners. But it was also a big week for
biotechnology companies.
</P>
<P>
   One company, Genome Therapeutics Inc. of Waltham, Mass., say its
shares reach record highs amid optimism about breakthrough
medications.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Amgen Inc. and Genentech Inc., the world's two largest
biotech companies, hit records and led the group higher. The
American Stock Exchange Biotech Index climbed 19 percent during the
week, outperforming gains in the broader Dow Jones industrial
average and the technology-laden Nasdaq index.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Biogen Inc. saw its shares soar to 81 3/4 on Thursday,
up nearly 13 points since Monday. Shares of Vertex Pharmaceuticals
Inc. also soared nearly six points last week closing at 33, while
Alkermes Inc. stock reached its 52-week high of 53 5/8, up more
than five points since last Friday. All three are based in
Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the whole biotech universe, it's just exploded
in the last 10 days,'' said Marie Warburg, a fund manager with BB
Biotech, one of this year's best-performing biotech funds.
</P>
<P>
   She and other analysts say investors who profited from Internet
investments are moving money into biotechnology shares to catch the
next big boom. They have chosen companies that have made
breakthroughs in their drug discovery efforts, along with companies
such as Genome Therapeutics that use genetic information to help
big pharmaceutical companies develop new medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Genome Therapeutics, one of the nation's oldest
biotechnology-turned-genomics companies, saw its stock reach an
all-time high of 17 3/16 during the week _ more than four times its
price of 4 1/8 on Dec. 1. The surge follows a series of alliances,
milestone payments, and management changes that began in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which uses proprietary genetic databases to guide
drug development efforts for big pharmaceutical companies, this
week announced a potential $118 million agreement with Wyeth-Ayerst
Laboratories, the pharmaceutical division of American Home Products
Corp., to develop treatment for the bone-thinning disorder
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   That deal _ the largest in Genome Therapeutic's 38-year history
_ came two days after the company announced it had reached a
critical milestone in the development of a potential drug to treat
asthma for Schering-Plough Corp. The large Madison, N.J.-based drug
maker, a leading supplier of asthma medication, also has similar
research deals with Genome Therapeutics for antibiotic-based drugs
and antifungal treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The Schering-Plough and Wyeth-Ayerst deals, along with the Dec.
16 announcement that Richard D. Gill, an intellectual property
rights specialist, will become president of Genome Therapeutics
Jan. 3, convinced Wall Street that the 190-employee company was
making important strides in its development. Gill succeeds Robert
Hennessey, who will remain chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect announcements of further scientific and commercial
achievements, new partnerships and progress in established
partnerships . . . to raise Genome Therapeutics' profile with
investors over the next few months,'' noted Matt Geller,
biotechnology analyst at CIBC World Markets in New York, after the
company announced it had received the Schering-Plough milestone
payment.
</P>
<P>
   Genome Therapeutics, which originally was formed as
Collaborative Research in 1961 and changed its name nearly seven
years ago, competes for customers with its bigger genomics
competitor Millennium Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies, along with Lynx Therapeutics Inc., which
develops technologies for cloning and studying DNA, and Incyte
Pharmaceuticals Inc., both based in California, have seen their
shares rise this month over investor enthusiasm in genomics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from Bloomberg News was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
