<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8498 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV30-     12-24 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV30-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CHOICE OF HILLARY'S MAKES SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, Dec. 30.)  
(lh) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's so hard to get about Hillary choosing New York over
Washington? The air is fresher. Her New York house, while grand, is
almost cozy next to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Why not excuse herself early? The first lady thrill has been
gone for a while. She's put in seven years. So what's a few months
without her undivided attention, considering how much time the
president, himself, has allowed for distractions. Besides, no one's
paying much attention to the current tenants anyhow. It's all about
who moves in next January.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone had reason to look forward to a brand new century, it
has to be this woman. It is time to walk into her own house and
close the door, get into her sweatshirt and pajama bottoms and
crank up the music.
</P>
<P>
   I like that image of her. It perpetuates the way Emma Thompson
played her in ``Primary Colors.'' No crushed woman, making weepy
calls to friends at 3 in the morning. That's over. End of chapter.
She has a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Not to presume anything about the status of the first ovaries,
but Hillary seems to be displaying what some women know as
post-menopausal zest. Hillary, who has been an inspiration to many
women for how she juggles her multiple roles as deftly as she
coordinates a headband with a pearl necklace is now playing out a
middle age fantasy. That is, to make an about-face, do something
completely different. A lot of women describe it as ``my turn.''
</P>
<P>
   While others may happily lack the motivation of wanting to
distance themselves from a man who made them feel like dog meat
around the world, they can relate to suddenly thinking, ``I'll
study Greek.''
</P>
<P>
   For Hillary it's politics, which she can do in the very nice
state of New York where the weather is better than in Washington
and the lights are brighter than Arkansas. For another woman it's
quitting her teaching job to become a white water guide. For
Hillary it's butting heads with an old pol who sputters that she's
a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   I know a woman a little older than Hillary who decided to take
up the bass fiddle just because its sound fascinated her, and she
practiced enough that one night her singer-friend called her up
from the audience to play with her band. I imagine taking on a
blowhard mayor of New York requires the same kind of courage needed
to walk on stage in an Irish saloon and make your musical debut.
</P>
<P>
   Why not take an early out from D.C.? Chelsea seems willing to
fill in at the occasional White House dinner, and we know from
watching ``The West Wing'' that nobody gets much personal time
anyhow, so what's she going to miss?
</P>
<P>
   Hillary actually looks as if she's having more fun these days,
even when they jump on her for being too much a Yankee fan or too
kissy with Suha Arafat. Embarrassing moments to be sure, but at
least they're her personal blunders, not his.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has her champion moments too. She's allegiant to health
care and the poor, two issues that fell out of favor with her
husband's administrations even as homeless wanderers spread from
the cities to the suburbs and health care worries turned into a
crisis. Turned-off Hillary fans, of whom I know a few, got back on
board when she stood up this month for the homeless mentally ill
and then for gays in the military.
</P>
<P>
   She's the first first lady to have a career and the first to be
hounded for it. It's going to feel good to start making her own
money again, and if she doesn't make it to the U.S. Senate this
time she can try another time. We know the woman does not give up
easily.
</P>
<P>
   A Hillary biographer says that Hillary is a century ahead of her
time. Let's hope not. She may not have been a cookie-baker but she
knows enough about the kitchen to know when to get out.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
