<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL-SYRIA TALKS CREDITED FOR 3-DAY TRUCE IN SOUTH LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israeli troops and Lebanese guerrillas fighting in
southern Lebanon observed a rare and unannounced three-day
cease-fire that ended Friday, allowing the recovery of the bodies
of five guerrillas killed in the area in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   The lull was widely seen as a product of last week's resumption
of negotiations between Israel and Syria, which supports the
Iranian-backed guerrillas of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Although artillery exchanges resumed Friday, the cease-fire was
described by spokesmen for United Nations forces as the the
quietest period in southern Lebanon in more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross workers assisted by U.N. soldiers recovered five
bodies in the Israeli-controlled area of southern Lebanon during
the cease-fire, which quietly went into effect Tuesday morning. It
ended Friday when the guerrillas shelled positions of the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-fire was the second time that the fighting in southern
Lebanon has been curbed since the renewal of the Israeli-Syrian
talks, which are scheduled to resume Jan. 3. Last Thursday,
Hezbollah departed from its usual practice, refraining from firing
rockets into northern Israel in retaliation for the wounding of 15
Lebanese children in a schoolyard shelled by the South Lebanon
Army.
</P>
<P>
   Supplied and trained by Iran, Hezbollah is fighting the Israelis
with the support of Syria, which is the main power broker in
Lebanon and has thousands of it own troops in the country. The
guerrillas seek to oust the Israelis from a nine-mile deep strip of
south Lebanese territory that Israel says it is holding as a buffer
zone against cross-border attacks. The zone was carved out in 1985,
and is controlled by Israeli forces and its Lebanese allies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said the request
for the cease-fire, arranged by a five-nation group monitoring
events in southern Lebanon, had been made by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the atmosphere of the resumption of talks made the
conditions for a cease-fire more favorable,'' Sneh said. ``This
shows that a cease-fire in southern Lebanon is feasible, but the
interests of Hezbollah do not necessary correspond with Syrian
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have expressed hope that negotiations with
Syria, as well as planned talks with Lebanon, will produce an
agreement that will allow the withdrawal of Israeli forces from
southern Lebanon. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has vowed to
bring the troops home by July.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's office said Friday that he would head a five-man
steering committee that had been appointed for the talks with
Lebanon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even as he prepared for next round of talks with Syria and
Lebanon, Barak sent a message that he was not about to make any
immediate changes on the Golan Heights, captured from Syria in
1967.
</P>
<P>
   Syria is demanding a return of the land as part of a peace
agreement. But Barak's office said Friday that he had given the
go-ahead for the construction of 70 more housing units at two
Israeli settlements in the Golan Heights: Katzrin and Bnei Yehuda.
A spokeswoman for Barak said that he had confirmed existing
construction plans, and that as long as there was no deal with
Syria, the plans were likely to proceed.
</P>
</TEXT>
