<SLUG> BC-EARTH-LIKE-PLANETS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASTRONOMERS SEEK ELUSIVE EARTH-LIKE PLANETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By CARRIE MILLER   
 The Gainesville (Fla.) Sun  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ If there are other planets like Earth in our
galaxy, a team of University of Florida astronomers may have found
a way to divine them in the glowing dust that rings newborn stars.
</P>
<P>
   Their findings were published this week in The Astrophysical
Journal, a leading international astronomy journal.
</P>
<P>
   Although scientists have discovered 27 planets to date using
other means, those methods are only good for finding huge planets
that tend to be gaseous and uninhabitable, said Scott Fisher, a UF
graduate student. For example, astronomers have observed that some
stars seem to dim as large orbiting planets pass in front of them.
Another method, called the ``wobble method'' detects planets so
large that parent stars are disturbed by the gravitational pull of
the planets' orbits.
</P>
<P>
   But detecting the presence of smaller, rocky planets like the
Earth has been more elusive, said Mark Wyatt, who graduated last
week from UF with a doctorate in astronomy and was the lead
researcher on the UF team.
</P>
<P>
   If life did exist on other planets, Wyatt said, it would most
likely be found on a terrestrial planet like the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   He said observations of a young star in the constellation
Centaurus led the researchers to propose the new method. Unlike
most stars of its age, HR 4796 has a donut shaped ring of dust
particles orbiting it, which may or may not be left over from when
the star formed. The researchers noticed that one side of the
``donut'' was glowing more brightly than the other, leading them to
believe the gravitational pull of an unseen planet may have shifted
the dust cloud off-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the center of the donut is offset, one side is closer
to the star, so that side is hotter and brighter,'' Wyatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Because HR4796 is part of a binary or two-star system, it is
possible the companion star is shifting the dust ring as well,
Wyatt said. More detailed observation will be needed to confirm the
existence of the planet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most exciting part was when we worked out, with computer
modeling, that the size of the planet would only have to be 10
earth masses,'' Wyatt said, ``which is much smaller than all
previous methods.''
</P>
<P>
   The wobble method, by comparison, only detects planets at least
the size of Jupiter, or about 300 times larger than Earth. The
``dust-disk'' method is also different in that it can detect
planets much farther away from stars, Wyatt said.
</P>
<P>
   The HR 4796 planet could be as far away as 50 ``astronomical
units'' from its star, said Stanley Dermott, professor and chairman
of the UF department of astronomy. One astronomical unit, the
distance between the Earth and the sun, equals about 92.7 million
miles.
</P>
<P>
   Dermott was among the members of a joint UF-Harvard team that
last year announced the discovery of the dust disk around HR 4796
and its companion star. The astronomers said the disk, the first to
be discovered in a binary star system, had the right conditions to
be forming planets.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt, who spent three years on the research for his
dissertation, was supported in part by a Fulbright Scholarship. He
also received NASA funds provided to Dermott for work on the
dynamics of dust in the solar system.
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the research team are Dermott, Fisher,
Charles Telesco, a UF astronomy professor; Keith Grogan, a UF
postdoctoral research associate; and Robert Pina, a UF assistant
professor of astronomy.
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville Sun, in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
