<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8502 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-STUART-MOVIE-824(2TAK     12-24 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUART-MOVIE-824(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF MOUSE AND MAN: REBIRTH OF STUART LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ M. Night Shyamalan was sitting in a rest stop
restaurant on the New Jersey Turnpike having something to eat and
watching CNN on one of the television sets that give travelers
something to stare at while they chew.
</P>
<P>
   ``A story came on about this little boy who had ears so big that
his parents used to tape them back and how traumatic it all was for
him,'' said (pronounced shy-ah-MELL-inn). He stopped chewing. He
thought about it. And while he didn't shout ``Eureka!'' there was
an immediate sense of happy discovery.
</P>
<P>
   Shyamalan, who has since become famous as the writer and
director of ``The Sixth Sense,'' one of 1999s biggest box office
successes, was at the time an ambitious screenwriter hard at work
on finding a way to translate E.B. White's classic children's tale,
``Stuart Little,'' to the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The task had thus far stymied Shyamalan, as it had other
screenwriters who had taken a stab at adapting White's picaresque
tale of a mouse-child's adventures in the larger world. ``I
thought, hey, we could make this a movie about a person who doesn't
belong, who doesn't feel like they fit in,'' said Shyamalan, who
lives in a suburb of Philadelphia. ``I felt all kids could relate
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, but especially during the holiday season, when
Hollywood turns out most of its prestige, Oscar-yearning movies, a
significant percentage of which are almost always based on classic
books and recent best sellers, screenwriters like Shyamalan are
faced with figuring out how to translate the printed word into
images and sounds. In some cases, like ``Stuart Little,'' it is a
particularly difficult process because the work does not easily fit
into the fast-paced, neat-and-clean, an-arc-for-every-character
constraints of the mainstream Hollywood film.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Jordan, who transformed Graham Greene's most
autobiographical novel, ``The End of the Affair,'' into a bitter
romance starring Ralph Fiennes and Julianne Moore, was able to
follow the general structure of the novel. But he said he felt he
needed to shoot several of the crucial scenes more than once to
show them from the sometimes conflicting perspectives of the main
characters. ``My approach to the entire story was that none of
these characters actually knows the real truth of the pivotal
events,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Petersen, who has just completed principal photography
on his adaptation of ``The Perfect Storm,'' a best-selling sea
tragedy set off the New England coast, had an even more difficult
task. As the author, Sebastian Junger, acknowledges in the book, no
one can know what actually happened on the boat that is the story's
main setting, as none of the occupants survived the storm. So the
author offers the range of things that might have happened and then
indicates which he thinks was the most likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we are not able to do that,'' Peterson said of the
film, that which is to be released next summer. So each time the
book's author allowed uncertainty to creep into the narrative,
Peterson said, the filmmakers had to guess what made the most sense
to them, factually and dramatically. Did the lead character, the
boat's captain, played by George Clooney, twist the arms of his
shipmates to try to plow through the deadly storm or did he lay out
the facts and leave it up to majority vote? No one knows, beyond an
educated guess. In the screenplay, though, the captain and crew
make the fateful decision collaboratively. ``It's the nature of
movies,'' Peterson said. ``We had to make a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   That's always the nub of it: the choice.
</P>
<P>
   The choices that the filmmakers behind ``Stuart Little'' say
they were forced to make jettisoned much of White's story,
transformed almost all of the essential remaining scenes and
imposed characters and emotional crises on characters who are
little more than  in White's book, if they exist at all.
</P>
<P>
   White's ``Stuart Little'' is the story of a ``mouse-child'' who
is born into the Little family in an idealized New York City of
parks and intelligent animals. Some of Stuart's adventures in the
book, including a miniature sailboat race in Central Park, are
carried over to the film, but the context is entirely different; in
the film, the race is a bonding moment for Stuart and his brother,
George, while in the book George is a minor character who is not
even present for the boat race. And while the book's final third
sees Stuart leave home without a backward glance to find the
beautiful bird he loves, in the film the bird does not appear and
the story becomes a paean to family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I originally did a draft that was basically a faithful version
of the book,'' Shyamalan said. ``The general response from the
studio and everybody was, wow, it's so literate, but it's an
independent movie starring a mouse. So I decided I needed to be
more broad with it, to keep with the spirit but be more
contemporary.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At first, he said, he was daunted by the idea of adapting a book
that so many adults remember affectionately from childhood, until
he talked to a lot of people and came to believe that people didn't
really remember the book all that clearly. ``What I realized over
time is that everybody, everybody has mythologized the book,''
Shyamalan said. ``But it's not what they think it was. The book was
so fragmented and I think people filled in the gaps in their
imaginations over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   It was this fragmentation that posed the greatest dramatic
hurdle. ``Part of the problem was, the book was very episodic,''
said Douglas Wick, one of the film's producers. ``It was designed
to be read in installments to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Minkoff, one of the directors of Disney's ``Lion King,'' was
given the task of mixing live action with the computer-generated
image of Stuart, whose voice is provided by Michael J. Fox. ``The
problem is that the book is not like `Charlotte's Web,' '' Minkoff
said of White's best-known children's tale. ``That one really is a
novel. With Stuart, every chapter is its own story.''
</P>
<P>
   The main dramatic shortcoming, as far as a film adaptation is
concerned, the filmmakers said, is that while the character of
Stuart has a very definite voice and personality in White's story,
neither he nor any of the other characters go on a neatly defined
emotional journey that connects the book into a satisfying whole.
That had to be imposed on the story, they argued, and the defining
moment for Shyamalan came at that turnpike rest stop.
</P>
<P>
   First, the decision was made to make Stuart not a
``mouse-child'' who is literally born into the Little family, but
an actual mouse who lives in a New York orphanage and is adopted by
the Littles, who admire Stuart's pluck and see nothing odd about
bringing a mouse into their family. All the other changes made in
White's story are an outgrowth of that change. The emotional
connective tissue of the story, about Stuart's efforts to fit in
with his adoptive family, were born from that report about the boy
with the ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I write a script I ask myself, what fairy tale is
this?'' Shyamalan said. ``What myth is this fairy tale about? In
this case, it's the adoption myth, the orphan being adopted, like
Annie.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy Pascal, chairwoman of Columbia Pictures, which released the
movie on Dec. 17, said the result was ``in the same spirit as the
book but in a more movie-friendly story.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort appeared to be connecting with audiences. The movie,
which cost about $100 million, was in first place at the box office
in its opening weekend. It earned more than $15 million, a figure
which augurs well for the film surpassing $100 million at the
domestic box office, said Ed Russell, a spokesman for the studio.
He said Columbia is hoping that Stuart will be a recurring
character for the studio, with more films, television shows,
merchandising and other commercial outlets featuring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stuart Little is a franchise character for this studio,'' Ms.
Pascal said. ``We have more uses for Stuart beyond this movie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
