<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, Dec. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(lh) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tranquil weather will cover the nation on the last Christmas Day
of the millennium as a fast northwest-to-southeast jet stream flow
limits the influx of moist air from Pacific, Atlantic and Gulf of
Mexico. Winter chill will grip the Eastern Seaboard as breezes from
the northwest import Canadian air southward. Despite abundant sun,
daytime readings will hold in the 20s from Philadelphia to Boston.
Meanwhile, for the first time this season, the mercury will fail to
reach 70 degrees Saturday afternoon at Miami. The threat for a
killing freeze will be high across northern Florida Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Strengthening breezes from the southwest will direct milder air
into the Midwest and western Great Lakes. Sunshine amid patches of
clouds will cover the region. A few snow flurries will persist near
Lakes Erie and Ontario as winds gather moisture in transit across
the unfrozen waters. Little if any accumulations will occur,
however.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty breezes from the northwest warming on descent from the
Rockies will propel temperatures to much above normal levels from
central Montana to eastern Colorado. A stationary high-altitude
low-pressure system near New Mexico will cause overcast skies from
eastern Arizona to southwestern Texas. Scattered light showers will
occur beneath the clouds with some snow in New Mexico's San Juan
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Formidable high pressure will continue to sponsor dry weather
along the West Coast. California will be sunny, as warm, gusty
winds buffet southern areas. Farther north, fog will limit
visibility in much of interior Washington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Alaskan Chinook
</P>
<P>
   The word ``Chinook'' is an American Indian word that refers to
winds that warm on descent from mountain ranges, causing snow to
quickly melt and evaporate on their downwind sides. These chinook
or ``snow eater'' winds often occur east of the North American
Rockies. But during Wednesday, an Alaskan chinook gusting to 80 mph
careened down the northern slopes of the Alaskan Range, an
east-to-west horseshoe which houses Mt. McKinley. The Alaskan
version of a chinook caused snow to change to freezing rain and
rain in some areas north of the Alaskan Range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8506 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-XMAS-SALES-SFCHRON &LR;      12-24 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-SALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By CAROL EMERT &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
As the holiday shopping season drew to a close Friday, sales were
coming in higher than even the most optimistic expectations.
<P>
   ``This was the strongest season in recent memory,'' said John
Konarski, senior vice president of research for the International
Council of Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   Konarski had forecast a 4 to 6 percent increase in holiday sales
this year while other predictions ranged as high as 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be little bit higher'' than 6.5 percent,
thanks to the booming economy in the Bay Area and across the
country, Konarski said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at Kepler's Books and Magazines in Menlo Park are up 11
percent compared with last Christmas _ and shopper insanity in
Silicon Valley is up, too, said manager Karen Pennington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are so fatigued they're sucking their thumbs and laying
on the floor while their moms are in linnnington said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a well-heeled shopper ordered and paid for a book
over her car phone and asked Pennington to meet her in the parking
lot with the wrapped gift and a card.
</P>
<P>
   ``She slowed down as I passed it to her through the passenger
window,'' Pennington said. ``She said `Merry Christmas' and voom,
off she went.''
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce traffic slowed significantly by Christmas Eve _ in
fact, Web shopping has been on the wane since mid-December due to
shopper fears of late deliveries and shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic to gift sites, for example, jumped 32.5 percent between
December 5 and December 12 but then declined 20.9 percent the
following week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected (e-commerce sales) to continue to rise until a
week before Christmas, with people taking advantage of quick-ship
programs,'' said Tim Meadows, vice president at NetRatings, a firm
that tracks Web traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``People are cautious about waiting till the last
minute and taking the chance that merchandise isn't available,'' he
said. ``The challenge for online merchants next holiday season is
how to build a reputation for dependability.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, e-shopping got started earlier than expected,
with Net traffic starting to grow immediately after Halloween.
Meadows attributed most of the early bump to toy shoppers looking
for this season's hot items, such as Pokemon games, before they
sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Web sales are expected to double this year, but still remain
less than 2 percent of general merchandise sales.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Eve sales for Macy's West were up about 15 percent
compared with last year, said Jeremiah Sullivan, president.
Millennium-themed champagne flutes, dressy clothes, power beads and
fluffy slippers have been among the most popular items this year,
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   For the season as a whole, sales at Macy's West stores are
running about two percentage points higher than expected and will
tally a mid-single digit increase over the 1998 holiday season,
Sullivan said yesterday. He declined to give specific numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's flagship Union Square store, which finished a
remodel this year, is seeing double-digit increases compared with
to  &LR; 1998, Sullivan said. Sales at Macys.com, meanwhile are up 300
to 400 percent this holiday.
</P>
<P>
   As late as Friday, the Hearthsong educational toy store in
Berkeley was ``nutty'' and packed with shoppers, said assistant
manager Sanjay Kumar.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our science kits, games, puzzles, anything in the store
has been selling well,'' Kumar said. ``Every item at one time or
other has been sold out.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales at jewelry and home-entertainment stores have been
particularly strong this year, with both rising 10 percent or
greater, according to an International Council of Shopping Centers
poll of mall speciality stores.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel sales have also been strong, with weekly increases since
Thanksgiving ranging from 4.3 percent to 7.2 percent, according to
the council.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
