<HEADER>
A8507 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SUPPORT-TECH-SFCHRON &LR;      12-24 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPPORT-TECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By BENNY EVANGELISTA &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Getting your new Christmas computer to blast out the sounds of
gunbattles in Quake III could be a vexing matter of fixing an
improperly installed sound card. Then again, it could be that you
forgot to turn up the volume control on the speakers.
<P>
   Solving a problem with your new PC or gizmo could entail hours
of frustration _ or a simple call or e-mail to tech support. Even
though much of the world is on holiday today, several phone-in and
online help desks are staffed and standing by to answer consumers'
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of, `I just got a computer, but I don't know how
to run this thing,''' said Loc Ha, a help desk technician with the
new online help site Sykes AnswerTeam.com
</P>
<P>
   The AnswerTeam, a 24-hour service based in Tampa, Fla., is one
of several technical help sources available on the Internet this
Christmas to assist frustrated people who can't get that new
computer, DVD player, digital camera, handheld device or other
high-tech toy to work.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the services offer more than just prepackaged FAQs;
users can e-mail specific questions and real people will send
answers. Ha said that for complicated questions, he will walk users
through the problem by phone.
</P>
<P>
   Prices can range from free to $15 per call.
</P>
<P>
   Technical help is just a mouse click away from independent sites
like San Francisco's Cnet Inc., which has launched a service called
Help.com, or Sunnyvale's NoWonder Inc. Manufacturers like Dell
Computer Corp. and Palm Computing also have phone and online help
available today.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a site called Tech Support Guy, where the motto is,
``There's no such thing as a stupid question, but they're the
easiest to answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most basic one I got so far is the lady who forgot to turn
off the power on her computer and just turned off the power on her
monitor,'' Ha said.
</P>
<P>
   When she switched the monitor back on, she couldn't understand
why the computer was displaying a message that it was shutting
down, Ha said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a dumb question, but a lot of peopjust not
informed about what's going on,'' Ha said.
</P>
<P>
   And if the help desk still can't get that new electronic toy to
work, you could swap it for a surfboard, a collectible watch or
other item listed on a new site,  &LR; www.Intellibarter &LR;   &LR; .com &LR; , which
officially launches Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Intellibarter, a Santa Cruz startup, allows users to trade a
product straight up for another product without cash. The company
decided to launch today to draw people who received gifts they
don't want, but don't want to battle long lines at store return
counters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you received something that's not your cup of tea or
maybe you got five wallets, so you want to find out what you can
get for that item in trade,'' said Intellibarter founder Patrick
Tao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
