<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAEAST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NBA Eastern Conference
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Miami Heat guard Tim Hardaway has suffered a setback
in his recovery from a jammed right knee. At midweek, he said he
was at least 10 days from running again.
</P>
<P>
   That means Hardaway will end up missing at least 17 games from
an injury he thought would sideline him just a game or two.
Hardaway missed his 14th game Wednesday and will sit out the next
three _ today at Milwaukee; Tuesday against Minnesota, in the
Heat's final game at Miami Arena; and Wednesday at Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest Hardaway could return is Jan. 2 against Orlando in
Miami's first game in AmericanAirlines Arena. But Hardaway told TNT
he could miss another month.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway resumed practice last Friday, and coach Pat Riley
hinted that his return was close. But Hardaway said he experienced
Tuesday ``a little feeling that shows the knee is weak.'' As a
result,
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway will not run, practice or do anything to exert pressure
on the knee until at least Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee is not responding,'' Hardaway said. ``I'm going to do
nothing for 10 days and see if it comes around. There's still
weakness and a little bit of pain. Sometimes it takes longer than
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway reiterated that surgery is not an option, because an
MRI last month found no structural damage. Rest, he said, remains
the only option.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Jamal Mashburn, who has missed two games with a sprained
left ankle, remains out indefinitely. The injury is between a Grade
1 and Grade 2 sprain. Although the Heat is listing Mashburn as
``day to day,'' Riley sounded pessimistic about a quick return.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous amount of soreness,'' Riley said. ``I
watched him the past couple of days, and he could barely walk. ...
It's disappointing to
</P>
<P>
   have to go through (injuries) as a club that has high
expectations. Our plans this year were big. I'm concerned about it.
</P>
<P>
   MAGIC DECISION
</P>
<P>
   You'll know whether Orlando cares about making the playoffs by
what the team elects to do with forward Chris Gatling. With Gatling
playing well, the club has a winning record, but this was a season
when they were looking to go lottery. If Gatling is traded for cap
room, the team probably will suffer in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can be a most unpleasant decision,'' general manager John
Gabriel said about trading players from a potential playoff team.
``We're excited and perplexed over our success. But we're not
satisfied, either. ... We're leading sort of a double life, with
the best of both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   STAYING ALIVE
</P>
<P>
   You can walk up to the United Center box office and buy a ticket
before every game. So how do they keep that record sellout streak
going?
</P>
<P>
   They are using some creative accounting, which is not uncommon
in the NBA. For one thing, the Bulls have had attendance as high as
24,544, yet ``capacity'' is 21,711. They have sold 17,000 season
tickets and most of the 216 suites with four seats each, which
count into the total.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago ticket broker Eric Soderholm said: ``Their streak is
still alive? Are you kidding? Really? I can't give Bulls tickets
away. They went from the greatest ticket on the planet to the worst
ticket, just like that. Our business is going to be down 50 percent
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   BIRD SPEAKS
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird on the state of the NBA today and why he's had
enough:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Magic (Johnson) and Isiah (Thomas) hugging and kissing
before that game, (Game 1 of the 1990 Finals).
</P>
<P>
   ``That changed this whole league. That's all that goes on now.
It's a lovefest. It's like Woodstock in 1969, everyone huggin' and
kissin'.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell guys, `I know I'm a little different than you guys. But
I never could even speak to an opponent.'''
</P>
<P>
   PISTON TIME
</P>
<P>
   If the Pistons are going to assert themselves, now's the time.
They are 12-14, but 11 of their next 15 games starting today are
against teams with .500 records or worse. They will play three of
the four teams with above-.500 records at The Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 15 to 20 games are real important,'' Grant Hill
predicts. ``If we don't come out of it with a winning record, guys
could start to mail it in. The month of January is very important.
We cannot go into February thinking we are out of it. We are still
in the hunt, and we know we are a better team than we've shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
