<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8512 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKN-NBAWEST26-COX     12-24 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAWEST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking note of the NBA Western Conference
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the Rockets going nowhere, there would seem no
reason for Hakeem Olajuwon to rush back this season, if ever. But
Olajuwon said he still wants to play this season, has not given up
on this team and wants to finish his contract next season.
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon had approached the team in the offseason about the
Rockets buying out the last year of his contract and retiring after
the season. But Olajuwon and the team could not come to an
agreement about the remaining $16 million on his contract. Since
his Nov. 26 injury, Olajuwon decided he would like to keep playing
next season, to go out on a better note than this season is likely
to provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way I want to go out, not the way I want to
end my career,'' Olajuwon said. ``It hurts too much to see us
losing every night, and, after all that I have been through in 16
years and helped to accomplish with this team, it is not the way I
want people to remember the conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is rehabilitate my injury, get back into the
lineup as soon as possible and do anything I can to turn this
around and to play out my contract through next season with the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to end my career here in Houston. I cannot picture
myself being anywhere else or wearing any other uniform. This is
where everything has happened and where it should come naturally to
its conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon underwent hernia surgery Dec. 1 and was expected to
miss six weeks. Olajuwon said that until the injury, he was feeling
stronger than he had in three years and expected to become more
effective through the season. His decline in previous seasons, he
said, was the result of pain he no longer has.
</P>
<P>
   He told Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich at halftime of the game
against the Knicks on Dec. 14 that he wanted to return this season
and play out his contract. He went on to say that he still believes
the Rockets could make the playoffs this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' he said. ``It is December. I have never entered a
season in my career where I didn't think it was possible to compete
for a championship, and I have never been in a season where anyone
gave up this early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It disturbs me to hear talk of the future, of next year
already. It sounds like you don't want to compete. I know that to a
lot of people, making the playoffs looks impossible to accomplish.
But isn't that where Clutch City came from originally? Didn't
people think it was impossible in 1994 and 1995?''
</P>
<P>
   DENVER DEALING?
</P>
<P>
   Denver Nuggets coach Dan Issel won't deny the talk about Larry
Hughes and Ty Hill for Ron Mercer and Bryant Stith. He will only
say that he did not originate the deal. Mercer, looking for maximum
dollars, insists he has not ruled out returning to Denver. He told
the Denver Post that reports that he thinks Denver is too cold and
that he doesn't like it there were overblown and inaccurate. He
will test the free-agent market, but he said that it doesn't mean
he doesn't' want to be in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   SPUR SLOWDOWN
</P>
<P>
   The offense of the San Antonio Spurs is stagnating. Tim Duncan
has been dominating, but, if the Spurs run into a team with guards
quick enough to double and recover, they're in trouble. ``We have
the title,'' Robinson said, ``but we're still a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   NOTES
</P>
<P>
   Center Sean Rooks continues to slip further out of the Dallas
Mavericks' rotation. Rooks hasn't played a single minute in the
past three games. ... Don't look for Mookie Blaylock's name in
Golden State box scores for a while. He's out with a strained calf.
... In Sacramento, Jason Williams, nicknamed ``White Chocolate,''
is turning into the White Shadow. He's shooting 39 of 144 from
three-point range and averaging almost four turnovers a game. . . .
New Vancouver coach Lionel told Bryant Reeves he must shift his
focus to defense, and Reeves, who owns a $65 million contract isn't
happy. In Hollins' first two games, Big Country got a total of
eight shots; he has averaged 14 points for his career. ``It's
something I'm going to have to kind of learn to deal with,'' Reeves
said. ``I know I'm not going to get the touches anymore. I'm going
to become more of a screener. That's what (Hollins') head-coaching
philosophy is, and I've got to live with it. ... You just have to
play with it, that's all I'm going to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
