<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWLS-PLAYOFFS26-     12-24 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-PLAYOFFS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playoff system likely far down the road
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NCAA determines all of its championships through
playoffs _ except for major-college football.
</P>
<P>
   Only one sport conducts its postseason events outside of the
NCAA's domain _ major-college football.
</P>
<P>
   The unique system for Division I football results largely from
the universities' cozy, long-standing relationships with bowl
games. The bowls have confined any playoff to the drawing board.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the relationship survives, bowl committees
annually spend millions of dollars in lobbying efforts, according
to a review of bowls' tax records by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. The bowl games are rewards not just for the
players but also for the coaches and athletics administrators _ and
their spouses _ who are entertained by the host committee in the
days leading up to the game. A playoff would interfere with, if not
end, the arrangement, which dates back more than six decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl administrators are out-of-season fixtures at the NCAA and
major conference meetings, working crowded lobbies and huddling one
on one with key decision-makers to keep their games and the system
itself alive. A handful of bowls take hobnobbing to another level
by staging relaxed, fun-in-the-sun weekend packages to entice
coaches and athletics officials to their cities for golf and
tennis. Many offer prizes.
</P>
<P>
   If showered on a college athlete, such extravagances would cost
him his eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The most rec statements indicate that the Tostitos Fiesta
Bowl spent $108,227 on its Fiesta Frolic, a three-day event held
each spring in Tempe, Ariz. The FedEx Orange Bowl listed expenses
of $112,891 for its weekend entertainment, Summer Splash, in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   While coaches and athletics directors in increasing numbers are
supporting a playoff system to replace or alter the bowl system,
the bowls are banking on years of goodwill to maintain the status
quo. They sell the relationships, the pageantry, the parades and
vacationlike atmosphere of their events. They hope the schools
won't be able to say, ``Hey, it's been great, but we're moving
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Another impediment to a playoff, at least in the short term, is
the series of contracts that would keep the bowl format in place
halfway through the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the current playoff talk focuses on a 16-team system
being pitched to major conferences by Swiss-based marketing giant
ISL. It promises annual payouts to schools totaling $375 million,
two and a half times the $150 million that bowls are expected to
generate this year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Big Ten and Pac-10 conferences have contractual
obligations to the Rose, one of four bowls in the Bowl Championship
Series, through the 2005 season. The BCS title game rotates among
the four bowls _ Rose, Sugar, Orange and Fiesta. Conference
officials might start negotiations next month about extending the
BCS agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ABC has exclusive television rights to the game, being played
for the second time Jan. 4, in the Sugar Bowl. The game is designed
to result in a so-called national champion, although sometimes in
the past, bowl results wound up splitting the championship between
the two major polls.
</P>
<P>
   Two additional BCS championship games are scheduled, through the
end of the 2001 season. The contract includes an option for a
three-year extension with ABC and the BCS, which is run by
commissioners of the six major conferences _ Atlantic Coast,
Southeastern, Big East, Big Ten, Pac-10 and Big 12. ''The whole
playoff concept is flawed right now because ABC has a long-term
deal,'' said TV consultant Barry Frank, who negotiates rights deals
for major sporting events. ''I don't see ABC saying, 'OK, let's
just tear up all these contracts and start all over again and maybe
lose (TV rights).' Knowing the mindset over there, it would amaze
me if they allowed that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl did agree to free the Big Ten or Pac-10 champion
if either qualified for the BCS title game, but it would be
unlikely to tear up its own agreement before 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``To make a playoff work, you've got to have everybody in it,''
said SEC commissioner Roy Kramer, coordinator of the BCS. ``You
can't have a Penn State (of the Big Ten) sitting out there not
being part of it. ... So, it would be very difficult for anything
to happen as long as there's a Rose Bowl agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   If a playoff does arrive, Kramer said that he thinks ISL will
not operate it. ``It's not going to be run by a foreign marketing
company,'' he said. ``It might be outside the NCAA, but it'll be
run by the (schools and conferences).''
</P>
<P>
   When playoff talk heats up, the bowls react in unison to
describe the system as an unmanageable pressure cooker that would
deprive student-athletes of valuable class time. The playoff bug,
they argue, mainly afflicts athletics directors who once coached
basketball and are smitten with its system. They repeat the same
mantra _ ``bowls have never been healthier'' _ while tossing out
supporting facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
   A playoff involving 16 teams _ the ISL plan _ would destroy the
major New Year's bowls, except for one as possible host for the
championship game. Because early rounds probably would be played at
campus sites, to assure full stadiums, the bowl cities would suffer
lost tourist business. Whether some bowls would survive, perhaps as
football's version of the weakened postseason NIT basketball event,
is anybody's guess.
</P>
<P>
   The most enticing aspect of a playoff to university presidents _
who must approve such a system _ is the major payday.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is still some tradition with the bowls, but money
talks,'' Frank said. ``Michigan (football) lost $2 million (last
year), and Michigan has a 100,000-seat stadium and one of the
biggest programs. So, if Michigan loses $2 million, what is Ohio
University or Rutgers losing? I think there is always a need for
money in college athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   However, universities' financial needs were reduced recently
when the NCAA accepted an 11-year, $6 billion deal from CBS for
rights to its basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A football playoff would be even more lucrative.
</P>
<P>
   Former Oklahoma athletics director Donnie Duncan conducted a
study five years ago that concluded the ISL projections of $375
million annually for a football playoff are valid. But Kramer
dismisses the figure.
</P>
<P>
   `` I'm not sure that pot of money is as big as they say, once
you subtract other factors and the damage it might do to the total
system,'' Kramer said. ``But is it more money? Sure, it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
