<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-FEATURE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Francis' leadership helping Coyotes capture victory
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This man doesn't scare easily. As a youth, Bobby
Francis would sit in Madison Square Garden, watching the New York
Rangers and listening to the crowds' chants. The content varied,
depending upon the home team's standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the crowd chanting, `Emile, Emile,''' said the son
of former NHL coaching legend Emile ``Cat'' Francis. ``I also
remember when things weren't going so well and everybody was
chanting, `Goodbye, Emile.' I used to turn to my mom and ask,
`Where are we going?'''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Francis isn't going anywhere right now _ except, perhaps,
up. The new coach of one of the most unstable franchises in NHL
history, Francis has led the Phoenix Coyotes to a record of 20-12-3
going into the two-day Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes sit atop the Pacific Division, even though goalie
Nikolai Khabibulin has sat out the entire season in a contract
dispute; his recently acquired replacement, Sean Burke, has missed
11 games in a row with a torn ligament in his thumb; and the
Coyotes are playing a style opposite of Francis' predecessor, Jim
Schoenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld's conservative, defensive preachings and Phoenix's
continued post-season failures got the coach fired after two
seasons. General manager Bobby Smith's directive to Francis was to
open up the offense. The Coyotes' 110 goals after 35 games put them
on a season pace of 258 goals, 53 ahead of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of skill on this team, and I thought we could
improve our transition game and on the power play,'' Francis said.
``We've encouraged our defensemen to jump into the play more, and
they've helped us generate a lot scoring chances. You can't do that
without leaving yourself vulnerable on defense, but the results
have been positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody likes points. It helps come negotiation time.''
</P>
<P>
   The insecure life of an NHL head coach has been well illustrated
by the Winnipeg/Phoenix franchise. Francis is the club's fifth
coach since 1994 and 14th in 21 seasons. The biggest reason for the
turnover is playoff failures. The franchise last won a post-season
series when it was the Winnipeg Jets in 1987. The Jets/Coyotes have
lost nine consecutive series since.
</P>
<P>
   Francis was a surprise choice to replace the fired Schoenfeld,
but he was well-schooled. He coached successfully for several years
in the IHL and AHL, and for the last two assisted Boston's Pat
Burns. He also learned from Emile Francis, who coached in New York,
St. Louis and Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moral issues,'' Francis responded, when asked what he
learned from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I paid attention to the way he treated people, with respect
and honesty, and he expected the same in return. With him, a player
always knew where he stood. Nobody was blindsided.''
</P>
<P>
   Communication with players was a problem under Schoenfeld.
Presumably, it's not a problem anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
