<HEADER>
A8517 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWLS-MAIN26-COX     12-24 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-MAIN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Football bowls big game of money, tradition
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ College football bowl games are as much a part of the
holidays as eggnog and gifts. In the next 12 days, 19 games will be
played _ all on TV _ bringing the postseason total to 23, a record.
</P>
<P>
   Bowls are big business, and getting bigger each year. And here
is their little secret: While most bowls are set up as tax-exempt
nonprofit organizations and traditionally carry a charity-minded
image, the bowls pass along just a tiny portion of their revenue to
needy causes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the total that went to charity was less than $1
million. Rather, the ``charities'' that benefit most are the
colleges, which shared in at least $140 million. And the bulk of
the money went to salaries, facilities and equipment in the
athletic departments _ not to academics.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers were derived from an Atlanta Journal-Constitution
analysis of tax returns over the past three years of the nonprofit
bowls. (Four are considered for-profit and their returns are
private.) During that period, the bowls generated $393 million in
revenue, and their latest tax returns show they have a cumulative
war chest of $43 million.
</P>
<P>
   To earn NCAA certification, bowls are required to turn over 75
percent of income before expenses to the participating
universities. The Internal Revenue Service permits the practice of
designating college athletics as ``educational nonprofits'' for tax
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   So, like many other sports-related organizations, bowls enjoy
the same tax benefits as groups such as the American Red Cross and
the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can (say) that if a bowl is giving Notre Dame $5 million
to come and play, they're giving it to a charity,'' said Chuck
McLean, vice president for research with GuideStar, the largest
database on nonprofit organizations. ``Notre Dame is a public
charity in a very odd sense.''
</P>
<P>
   With so few dollars directed to charities, bowls have begun to
downplay their philanthropic efforts. Many say there is simply no
money left after the schools take their cut and pay their expenses,
which range from six-figure salaries for executives to millions of
dollars for entertaining guests.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the AJC analysis found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tostitos Fiesta Bowl, which has surpassed the Rose as the
wealthiest bowl with $11 million in assets, put $25.2 million in
university coffers last year while giving charities $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Rose Bowl, with a $10.2 million war chest, paid $25.5
million to colleges and less than $100,000 to charities.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl at the Georgia Dome paid out a
record $3.2 million to the universities of Georgia and Virginia,
while the WinShapes Home Program, a foster homes group that was
cited in promotional brochures as receiving a portion of ticket
sales, got $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ The FedEx Orange Bowl, which produced revenues of $34 million,
gave $12,000 to a local college assistance program.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Wells Fargo Sun Bowl paid teams $2 million last year,
while contributing $35,000 to El Paso area sports organizations.
</P>
<P>
   _ The COMPUSA Florida Citrus Bowl paid out $7.34 million from
revenues of more than $12 million, with $100,000 going to charity.
</P>
<P>
   Among expenditures found in the returns were $120,000 for
complimentary tickets (Rose), $206,000 for a halftime show
(Orange), $55,000 for lobbying for a car rental tax that benefited
the bowl (Sun) and $454,000 to lease stadium skyboxes (Citrus).
</P>
<P>
   ''We do give to other charities, but it's small in comparison to
the amounts we give to universities,'' acknowledged Stan Laybourne,
the Fiesta Bowl's chief financial officer. ''It's a bowl-by-bowl
situation. Some of the bowls that are just a football game _ the
lower-tier bowls _ have enough trouble just paying the minimum NCAA
requirement. As you go up the food chain of bowls, you do other
(fund-raising) events and then you can give to . . . other
charities.''
</P>
<P>
   The bowls have always worked with the host cities to help draw
tourism and business. The Peach, in Atlanta, is one of three
directly tied to its local chamber of commerce or convention
bureau, from which funding is received.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, we're all in this business to provide
something for our community,'' said John Fulmer, Sun Bowl chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, bowls are seeking to ``expand the brand'' by
conducting other events. The Nokia Sugar Bowl game, which this year
is for the national championship, is the highlight of a series of
events _ college basketball doubleheader, marathon, swim meet,
international junior tennis tournament, regatta, youth soccer
tournament and the National Invitational Flag Football
Championship.
</P>
<P>
   This year's kickoff between Florida State and Virginia Tech is
not until Jan. 4 _ three days after the traditional New Year's Day
bowl date _ so New Orleans hopes to lure people into town early and
induce them to stay longer. With so many activities planned around
the game, the economic impact should far exceed last year's figure
of $137 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bowl's entertainment budget just for parties representing
the participating schools is about $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three team functions that are required, plus two
spouse functions where we entertain the wives _ which has become a
big thing,'' executive director Paul Hoolahan said. ``We'll
entertain 300 to 400 women on two full days. A golf outing. All the
pre-game media stuff. We have the Gala, which is our signature
event. That is 1,500 people, from 7 (p.m.) to 1 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Kevin Ash, Rose Bowl game director: ``Team entertainment
used to be giving each player a deck of cards. Now it's lunch and
dinner, shows, clothing, gifts. It's not only the players; it's the
coaches, administration, coaches' wives.''
</P>
<P>
   The most famous event associated with a bowl game is the
Tournament of Roses Parade in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we look at it, we're a parade first,'' Rose Bowl
executive director Jack French said. ``Our volunteers are much more
enamored of the parade than they are the Rose Bowl game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rose is both the oldest bowl and the last to add a corporate
sponsor to its title. It is now the Rose by AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta organizers are favorably viewed as the Microsoft of the
bowl business. Two years ago, the committee took over what was then
the Copper Bowl, also in Arizona, and signed up title sponsor
Insight.com. Together they generated $22.2 million in revenue. Last
year, the Fiesta produced a $25.2 million payday for schools in the
first designated ``national championship'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is talk of the Fiesta organization moving across the
border and staging another bowl in Monterrey, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some real potential down there,'' said John Junker,
Fiesta Bowl executive director. ``Everybody says there are too many
bowls. Well, I think maybe there are too many fast-food
restaurants, or too many networks. That is a marketplace judgement.
If a bowl can pay the bills, attract teams and do the job of
rewarding teams, then that is what college football has wanted us
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
