</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-PEACH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peach Bowl no longer `just a football game'
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Talk about an image makeover. At the start of the
1990s, the Peach Bowl compared with the Cotton, Orange or other big
bowls the way Trump would fit with Bush, Bradley, Gore and McCain.
Teams usually played on an overcast or drizzly afternoon, in a
half-empty Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium, for a paycheck barely
covering expenses. The game flirted with bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Chick-fil-A Peach Bowl isspiffed up and financially
robust. It is playing to packed houses inside the
temperature-controlled Georgia Dome, with every game this decade
going down to the wire. Since 1995, only three bowls have attracted
larger average crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The Peach's bank account reflects its resurgence. An analysis of
federal income-tax returns for the last three years shows net
assets of $2.1 million, surpassed only by the traditional New
Year's Day big boys _ Rose, FedEx Orange, Tostitos Fiesta and Nokia
Sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia-Virginia game last December helped generate more
than $5.1 million in total revenue and had an estimated $35 million
impact on the local economy. The bowl's payout to participating
schools has increased 100 percent in the 1990s, with UGA and
Virginia splitting $3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's Clemson-Mississippi State matchup is expected
to generate as much as $3.6 million for the schools and have a
local economic impact of $45 million. The game sold out earlier
than ever, and the teams are expecting to bring a combined 50,000
fans to town.
</P>
<P>
   The turnaround took root in 1985 after Peach officials persuaded
the Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce and city business leaders to
take control of the game. The Peach had no title sponsor and was
strapped for cash. Ron Allen, then chairman of the chamber and head
of Delta Air Lines, accepted the challenge by writing a six-figure
check for his company.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Peach Bowl is set up as an affiliate of the chamber,
with offices in its downtown Atlanta headquarters. Key chamber
officials serve as trustees of the bowl. The event returns a small
portion of profits to the chamber for its past financial
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling was to get it to the chamber, because it was the
one group in the city that could get behind it and keep it alive,''
said former Peach volunteer Steve Hatchell, executive director of
the Orange Bowl. ``We didn't want to lose it and lose face that
Atlanta couldn't sponsor a bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the Peach secured Chick-fil-A as title sponsor, while
also signing on Coca-Cola, Texaco and NationsBank. It signed a
long-term broadcast deal with ESPN and expanded its crew of
volunteers from fewer than 10 to more than 400. A contract with the
Atlantic Coast and Southeastern conferences to provide teams for
the game clinched the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the No. 1 or No. 2 alumni base of most, if not all,
ACC and SEC schools living in Atlanta,'' bowl president Gary Stokan
said.
</P>
<P>
   That has given the Peach a regional flavor, but officials aren't
opposed to branching out.
</P>
<P>
   Stokan talks of elevating the game to a higher level, perhaps
moving into the Bowl Championship Series if a slot should open or
even bidding to host a national championship game if college
football goes to a playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   After putting last year's Peach Bowl to bed, Stokan led a
scouting mission to the first BCS title game in the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to their parades, to their festivities, just to
compare it to what we do,'' he said. ``Certainly, we can't go from
what we're doing now to a BCS game, but we can look at what the
expectations are and start to drive our committees to that point.''
</P>
<P>
   That means moving the Peach beyond just a postseason football
game to a series of events during the year.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Peach conducted the Office Depot ACC-SEC Celebrity
Golf Invitational at the Country Club of the South for coaches and
athletics directors. The bowl held a reception the night before
with ESPN football analyst Lee Corso as speaker. Proceeds benefited
Georgia Baptist Hospital, which this week will send through Atlanta
a mobile screening unit decorated as a peach.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Peach Bowl FanFest this week in the Georgia World
Congress Center features 40 games and exhibitions, ending with what
is being billed as the world's largest tailgate party on game day.
</P>
<P>
   The annual parade this year features Evander Holyfield as grand
marshal. Next year, the bol group has scheduled a women's
college-basketball doubleheader at Philips Arena, with Georgia,
Georgia Tech and national power Tennessee already booked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think we're just a football game,'' Stokan said,
``that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
