<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8519 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-BOWLS-REPS26-COX     12-24 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWLS-REPS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dealing to get the best bowl
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUSCALOOSA, Ala. _ During the week, Jack Oppenheimer is a
certified public accountant. But on football Saturdays, he turns
into something else _ bowl scout.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer loves the gig, which is college sports' equivalent
of being a globetrotting member of the International Olympic
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with a hunter-green COMPUSA Florida Citrus Bowl blazer
and a gift of gab, Oppenheimer pumps hands tirelessly like a
stumping politician as he works the press box at Bryant-Denny
Stadium, passing out Citrus stick-on patches. He is delighted when
an Alabama coed returns to ask if she could have another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those dirty jobs, and somebody has to do it,''
Oppenheimer says, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   For the bowl representative, life is good. Oppenheimer
volunteers his time, but either the host school or the bowl sends
him on weekend junkets to such football-crazed college towns as
Gainesville, Fla., Ann Arbor, Mich., and Knoxville, Tenn. He
schmoozes and boozes with athletics administrators, college
presidents and influential alumni _ all to build and maintain
relationships with schools if they wind up in Oppenheimer's New
Year's Day bowl in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's a lot of fun,'' says Oppenheimer, one of two
Citrus representatives assigned to Alabama's home game last month
with Mississippi State. ``If you go to Penn State's homecoming
weekend, who else can get a room in the Nittany Lion Inn and get
down on the sidelines late in the game? I had dinner at Joe
Paterno's house two years ago. How many guys can say that?''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Joe Pa, Penn State's legendary coach, served
lasagna and an assortment of other Italian dishes. ``What else
would you expect?'' Oppenheimer asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi State lured him to a game last fall by arranging a
two-day stay at the Old Waverly Golf Club, an exclusive
country-club community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still working on Augusta; I'm a softy for golf,'' says
Oppenheimer, who only wishes a college football team played in the
same town as the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The bowls spent more than $500,000 last year on travel alone for
its representatives, according to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's analysis of the bowls' tax records. Typical
of the major bowls is the Outback, which spent $60,000 on travel
and and an additional $367,814 on social functions.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, before conferences struck long-term deals with
bowls to lock in their member schools, many bowl reps were colorful
characters who often worked cloak-and-dagger style into the wee
hours so they could return home with a commitment from top football
schools for a marquee matchup. Then, most of the best teams had
several bowl options and were romanced throughout the season, much
as high school recruits were.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three years later, former Orange Bowl president Nick
Crane remembers how he lost Pittsburgh and Heisman Trophy winner
Tony Dorsett to the Sugar Bowl. ``It was as simple as ABC,'' Crane
said. The TV network promised Pitt it would televise a few of its
games the following season if it committed to the Sugar _ on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Crane staged parties at his Coral Gables home for NBC, which
carried the Orange, and for big-name coaches and their athletics
directors. A successful businessman, Crane was known to discuss
investment strategies with guests, many of whom remain friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of discussions you have over a beer,'' he said. ``I
talked to Sue Paterno 20 or 25 years ago about buying gold.''
</P>
<P>
   A University of Miami trustee, Crane phoned Joe Paterno to check
on his interest in the school's football coaching job before Butch
Davis was hired in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The king of the hobnob was Jim ``Hoss'' Brock of the Cotton
Bowl. His tactics are legendary, from finagling a halftime
interview on a major network to befriending a top player, such as
Dan Marino, Doug Flutie or Eric Dickerson, who might influence his
team's postseason choice.
</P>
<P>
   Brock would show up on campus, with a trademark unlit stogie in
his mouth, on a Thursday, one day ahead of the other bowl scouts.
Every preseason, he would throw a party for preseason All-America
players when their media tour came through Dallas. And the joke was
that he visited Notre Dame, the most coveted bowl team for many
years, often enough to be fitted for a priest's collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the fun is gone, the spirited competition,'' said
Brock, ousted by the Cotton Bowl in 1995 after 20 years as
executive director. ``The people today in charge of the bowls,
except for some of the old-timers, are running it more to make sure
the business level is there and the sponsorship. My No. 1 concern
was to try and get the best football player in the country. And
however we were going to do it, we would do it. They never fussed
about my expenses or anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your bowl guys still go to conference meetings and they go to
certain big games just to show up,'' Brock said. ``I think the
personal involvement is history, and you lose something when you
don't have those relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of the conference tie-ins to bowls, many of the
so-called scouts are little more than colorfully dressed greeters.
The Peach, for example, is locked into one team from the Atlantic
Coast Conference and one from the Southeastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But the revised system hasn't driven them off the road.
</P>
<P>
   Oppenheimer traveled to seven games this fall for the Citrus,
which was represented at every SEC and Big Ten game by someone from
its 120-member selection committee. Eleven scouts from eight bowls
attended the Alabama-Mississippi State game, including ex-Falcons
coach Leeman Bennett and software executive Rod Hovater from the
Peach. In their bright, batteries-not-included blazers, the scouts
are seated on the third row of the press box, hovering above the
50-yard line, looking like a human fruit salad.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, cocktails and hors d'oeuvres were plentiful at
an invitation-only reception in the Paul W. Bryant Museum that also
included the Crimson Tide's 1978 and '79 national championship
teams. Then, it was off to dinner with athletics officials and the
CBS broadcast crew at the Cypress Inn, a restaurant overlooking the
Warrior River.
</P>
<P>
   At the reception, the Fiesta's Mike Doherty, a Scottsdale, Ga.,
hotel manager, never wandered far from the bar as he worked on the
Alabama officials and ex-players. He was hard to miss in his
canary-yellow blazer.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many games left, so tough to call,'' said Doherty, whose
bowl has a ``soft'' tie-in with the Big 12 but can choose the other
team from any league. ``The Southeastern Conference, no question,
is the top conference for college football. The finest in terms of
travel teams, bringing fans to bowl games. If we got any one of
your teams, we'd be fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, the Crimson Tide radio network hosted a
brunch. Then several scouts huddled with Alabama's interim
athletics director Finus Gaston to assess their chances of landing
the Tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of eating,'' said Bennett, chairman of the Peach's
selection committee, almost two hours before kickoff. ``I've been
in locker rooms, and I've been in press boxes. For somebody who
hasn't done that, it might be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Hovater, who admitted to feeling a rush, distributed Peach Bowl
fliers and patches, then attended the coaches' post-game news
conference. He and Bennett wore conservative navy blue blazers, set
off by an orange Peach Bowl emblem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the schools to know we're here and interested, and
they want to let us know they're interested,'' Hovater said. ``They
don't mind being nice if you show up. It's a sign that they've had
a successful year.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the Peach wound up with Mississippi State as
its SEC team. The Citrus, which also has an SEC connection, landed
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on a November weekend in Alabama, Jack Oppenheimer made
some connections that might come in handy someday _ and he had a
good time besides.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
