<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-SULTAN-ART-400     12-24 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SULTAN-ART-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
500-YEAR-OLD PORTRAIT OF OTTOMAN SULTAN HELPS TURKS LOOK AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ The image of a long-dead sultan, bearded and
gazing impassively from beneath his ceremonial turban, has
captivated his former Ottoman capital.
</P>
<P>
   Although he speaks to Turks through the mist of their imperial
past, his message is thoroughly modern. To everyone's surprise, he
has become a symbol of Turkey's new turn toward Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Turks have long admired the sultan, Mehmet II, for his military
triumphs, especially his capture of Constantinople, now known as
Istanbul, in 1453. But at an extraordinary art show here, they are
seeing another side of him that perfectly fits the spirit of today.
</P>
<P>
   The show portrays Mehmet as a philosopher and linguist who
deeply admired European culture. By happy coincidence, it opened
just days before the European Union officially accepted Turkey as a
candidate for membership on Dec. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Together these events reflect and contribute to the pro-European
feeling that is spreading in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   The art show is distinguished not only by its timing, but also
by its size. It consists of only one painting: Gentile Bellini's
masterly portrait of Mehmet.
</P>
<P>
   Mehmet was the first sultan, and one of the first Muslims
anywhere, to defy religious tradition by allowing his portrait to
be made. Bellini's picture has become the best-recognized image of
the Ottoman era, a painting that virtually every Turk can instantly
identify.
</P>
<P>
   As the first and perhaps finest portrait of an Ottoman sultan by
a European artist, it also symbolizes Turkey's European dream. Some
who view it cannot help reflecting on how history might have
changed if later sultans had shared Mehmet's fascination with
European ideas and technology.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the painting's primal importance to Turkey, it had
never been shown publicly here until now. It is on loan from the
National Gallery in London for a one-month exhibition through Jan.
7, and it is drawing animated crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching the portrait itself, visitors pass a series of
panels describing Mehmet and his times. They portray the sultan as
a visionary who ``always looked westward'' and was fascinated by
science, literature and the wider world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so impressed by his thirst for knowledge,'' said Oktay
Dalibar, an engineer who visited on a recent afternoon. ``What a
personality, what an intellectual in that darkness of the Middle
Ages! A great role model for today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bellini's oil portrait, which is displayed behind a protective
plastic shield, shows Mehmet in a reflective aspect. He is wearing
a red caftan with a fur collar, and there is a pronounced hook to
his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Before him lies a chest adorned with jewels signifying his
empire's wealth. Six crowns over his head represent the six Ottoman
sultans who ruled before him. The Roman motif of the framing arch
may suggest his dream of ruling Rome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen this picture so many times, in so many
schoolbooks and on so many walls over so many years that it's
really imprinted on our brains,'' said Mehmet Onkal, a business
consultant. ``Now it's finally here, the real thing. Hard to
believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Sultan Mehmet had good relations with the Medici family and
other powerful Italian clans, especially in Venice and Florence,
and at his request they sent him artists and craftsmen by the
dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Bellini, who had been court artist to the Doge of
Venice. He arrived in 1479 and spent the next year and a half at
the Ottoman court, painting erotic scenes on interior walls as well
as the famous portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months after the portrait was finished, Mehmet died.
Some historians believe that he was slowly poisoned on orders of
his son, who succeeded him as Beyazid II. If this is true,
Bellini's portrait is of a dying man.
</P>
<P>
   Sultan Beyazid considered his father's art collection decadent
and ordered it sold at auction. The Bellini portrait is believed to
have changed hands several times before being bequeathed to the
National Gallery in 1916.
</P>
<P>
   In the years after Mehmet's death, the Ottomans lost their
enthusiasm for Western culture, eventually isolating themselves
from the outside world. But Mehmet remains a hero to many Turks.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Mehmet Pere, a newspaper editor from a provincial
town, stopped to see the portrait during a recent visit to
Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me feel proud and sad,'' Pere said as he emerged.
``I'm proud that we've been accepted as a candidate to join the
European Union, because we deserve it. But I'm sad because this
should have happened 500 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bellini painting, while an undoubted gem of 15th-century
Italian portraiture, is not considered a true masterpiece. But for
Turks it is a work of art in the fullest sense, because it helps
them define their collective identity. Today it encourages their
march toward Europe by asserting that Mehmet would have approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``With his ideas we could have participated in the
Renaissance,'' lamented Munever Eminoglu, manager of the Istanbul
gallery where the portrait is on display. ``Instead we had just a
short golden age for art and science. This painting is the most
direct link we have to that period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
