<SLUG> BC-BIODISCOVERY-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA FIRM FILES COPYRIGHT INFRINGEMENT SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a bicoastal legal battle, BioDiscovery Inc. has filed suit in
federal court in Los Angeles seeking $50 million in damages from
the former General Scanning Inc. of Watertown, Mass., claiming
copyright infringement of its ImaGene software.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week GSI Lumonics, which acquired General Scanning
in March, said it is seeking a declaratory judgment from US
District Court in Boston, claiming its software, called Quantarray,
does not infringe on BioDiscovery's product.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Quantarray is a reverse-engineered version
of ImaGene developed by BioDiscovery. Both programs work with
scanning devices made by GSI Lumonics to help biologists determine
the vitality of genetic material.
</P>
<P>
   The ImaGene software enables medical researchers to quickly
quantify and analyze the presence, strength, and/or weakness of
genes in a sample of DNA material. The software helps determine if
a gene is healthy by assigning it a color: red for an unhealthy
gene, yellow for a healthy one. The BioDiscovery software also
helps scientists plot this information and create pie charts,
grids, and other expression patterns.
</P>
<P>
   BioDiscovery founder Soheil Shams said he had a distribution
agreement with the former General Scanning, which was marketing
ImaGene software with its scanning hardware. However, Shams claims
the company, which did not have its own software, developed
Quantarray to sell with its scanning hardware. He claims Quantarray
is a ``copycat'' version of ImaGene and violates BioDiscovery's
copyright protection.
</P>
<P>
   GSI Lumonics sells a mix of products and services in the
consumer packaging, medical, aerospace, semiconductor, and
electronics marketplaces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
