u k BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN URGE TO GIVE SOMETHING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Newspaper ads frequently aspire to drama, but the
attention-getting presentation of one recent full-page was
striking. The word ``MONEY'' in a script evoking the Gilded Age was
a draw for almost anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted at the booming economy's new millionaires, the ad urged
them to do something with their money that may not have been the
first instinct of many of them: Give some of it away. Just write a
check to the nearest worthy cause and unload some of their wealth
on the less fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   It ran, appropriately, in the Globe's business section on Dec.
15. There was no name attached, no specific charity recommended, no
post office box or e-mail address. Just an open letter, paid for
handsomely by someone who didn't want anyone to know who he or she
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've received a wonderful gift this year,'' it stated.
``It's time to give some of it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The author tantalizingly threw out just enough detail to arouse
curiosity. ``I am one of you. I started with nothing, and I
remember just how sweet it was to make my first million. But I also
know the singular joy of giving some of it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as soon as the ad appeared, people began to wonder who
had placed it. The names of several civic-minded Bostonians were
floated.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe's advertising department said whoever had placed the
ad had gone to considerable lengths to keep his or her identity
private. It was placed through an agency, Hill Holliday, without an
individual's name attached.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, I called Jack Connors, Hill Holliday's CEO, to ask
who had placed the ad. I asked if he had placed the ad; some people
thought they detected his style behind both the message and the
prose. Connors chuckled and told me he'd check with his client on
whether he could reveal the identity.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, he told me his client preferred to remain
anonymous. He wouldn't say whether he was his own client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to the party and they would really like for us to
honor their request for anonymity,'' Connors said.
</P>
<P>
   I have my suspicions, but they don't matter. As people are
forever saying this time of year, it's the thought that counts. And
the thought behind that ad should resonate with a lot of folks.
</P>
<P>
   As the economy continues its overheated march to the millennium,
there are more well-off people than at any other point in our
lifetimes. There are also more people in need. We all know that.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just that need is greater; it's also that more of
those in need are invisible. Meanwhile, many people have more ways
to avoid seeing the everyday realities in which so many others are
trapped. Connecting with other different people seems to require
more conscious effort for those of us who are able to escape to our
suburban fortresses, luxury cars, and comfortable vacations. But
those are hollow rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, it was embarrassing to talk like this; I probably
would have been embarrassed to write like this. Any fool could see
that liberalism was dead, and good riddance; farewell to sappiness
and hello to success and meritocracy.
</P>
<P>
   But, for many surprised people, something interesting has
happened along the way to running the company or retiring at 40. A
lot of people I know have discovered an emptiness they never saw
coming, sitting in big offices they never thought they wanted to
occupy and wondering what the hell they were doing there. They have
become something they never expected: cliches.
</P>
<P>
   The holiday season is always the peak time for platitudes,
promises, vows of reform. Illusory better selves emerge, pledging
goodwill toward men, peace on earth. The promises come easily, and,
of course, we mean them all when we make them.
</P>
<P>
   The promise of Christmas _ of redemption and salvation _ is a
personal matter. You believe it or you don't; you understand human
destiny that way or you don't. But Christmas long ago took on
another meaning for many people _ as a time to remember others, to
step outside their own desires and do for others as they would have
done to themslves.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that this spirit is more important now than ever. The
tools that have made so many people more affluent than they
expected to become have made us even more isolated, even more than
usual.
</P>
<P>
   Writing checks is a poor substitute for human contact. But it is
a starting point for remembering how much of life there is beyond
the 401(k) balance and the next resort vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The step after that, now that could be the tough one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)Globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
