<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN CONGRESS IN DEADLOCK OVER BUDGET BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Infuriated opposition congressmen showered one of
their colleagues with pennies and trash on the floor of Congress
this week, accusing him of selling himself to the government after
he had voted for President Ernesto Zedillo's budget bill and
against one drafted by the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hands are clean!'' shouted the congressman, Armando Lopez
Romero of the tiny Workers' Party, seeking to defend himself above
a chorus of catcalls and obscene insults on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The outpouring of contempt was one of several incidents that
erupted after governing party floor whips had split a handful of
opposition lawmakers from their parties. The tactics blocked
passage of a budget drafted by four opposition parties whose
combined votes have since 1997 often controlled the 500-member
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the hardball tactics in a regular congressional
session that ended on Dec. 15 and in an extraordinary session on
Dec. 21 and 22, the governing party, known as the PRI, failed to
split enough votes from the opposition to pass its own $128 billion
proposal for next year. A second extraordinary session has been
scheduled, for Dec. 28. The budget has to be approved by Dec. 31 to
avert a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obviously corruption here,'' Vicente Fox of the
center-right National Action Party, the opposition's leading
presidential candidate, SAID. ``Deputies have obviously been
bribed. This is the same old PRI and the same old government,
trying to get its budget approved on the basis of corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Arturo Nunez, leader of the PRI congressional
delegation. The party relied on sound political arguments in
persuading the opposition lawmakers to vote with the government, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These deputies took a principled decision when they voted with
us against the opposition bill,'' Nunez said.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting has concentrated the energies of much of the
political elite for a month. The rancor grew so furious that
opposition parties refused to authorize Zedillo to travel to
Washington this month for a meeting with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The deadlock appeared to owe more to parties' frantic attempts
to position themselves politically as Mexico heads into a
presidential election than to differences over dollars and cents.
The gap between the government's bill and the opposition's was
tiny, just 30 cents out of every $100 authorized for spending.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition budget would have appropriated $478 million more
for social spending than the PRI proposal. The president of
National Action, Luis Felipe Bravo Mena, said the four opposition
parties were seeking to channel the additional money to workers'
pensions, farm programs and other programs that ``would help
flesh-and-blood Mexicans, and not just the country's macroeconomic
statistics.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issue that focused discussion this week was the
Congress' desire to control how to spend the appropriations,
Dolores Padierna of the center-left Party of the Democratic
Revolution said. Opposition legislators sought to insure that the
Zedillo administration could not use social programs next year to
buy votes for the PRI presidential candidate, Francisco Labastida,
Ms. Padierna said.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition also pressed longtime demands for increased
federalism, seeking to transfer control over some expenditures from
the federal government to states and cities, she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
