</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO LATE TO LEAVE, GROZNY CIVILIANS TOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After weeks of trying to persuade civilians to flee
Grozny, Russian officials said Friday that residents had missed
their chance to leave and should hide in their shelters until
Russian forces have secured the Chechen capital.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's warning was a fresh indication that the climactic
battle for the city is finally at hand. It was also a somber
reminder that Russia forces are determined to quickly subdue Grozny
even if it means fighting in a city still occupied by tens of
thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time to strike Grozny from the agenda is counted in
days,'' Nikolai Koshman, Russia's senior representative to
Chechnya, said at a news conference here Friday. ``It is better for
people to stay in Grozny while the operation is under way.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Grozny's civilians has become one of the most urgent
problems in Russia's military campaign against Chechnya's rebels.
With considerable fanfare, Russia established two escape corridors
for civilians to escape the besieged city.
</P>
<P>
   But the corridors, by and large, turned out to be a failure.
Only a fraction of Grozny's residents fled, and many who did found
themselves under fire in the escape routes.
</P>
<P>
   Koshman said that up to 50,000 civilians were still trapped in
Grozny and that only 8,000 had used the corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Russian television Friday showed thunderous artillery strikes
against Grozny as Russian forces have began to edge into the city.
Gen. Viktor Kazantsev, the commander in the North Caucasus, visited
troops on the outskirts of Grozny, another sign of the battle to
come.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how Friday's warning was being communicated to
Grozny's civilians, or whether any steps have been taken to reduce
the risk to them in the battle for the city. Most are living in
cellars, where they have been short of food, living in fear of the
punishing Russian bombardment and local marauders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing our best to avoid any strikes against the
districts where the civilians are located,'' Koshman said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees from Grozny have said in recent weeks, however, that
the Russian strikes have been indiscriminate and that houses and
markets have been hit. Many victims, they said, are ethnic
Russians, too old, too weak or too scared to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have said from the start that their plan is not
to ``storm'' Grozny, an allusion to the 1994-96 war, when Russian
forces raced into the center of the city and were roundly defeated
with enormous casualties on the Russian side. Instead, the basic
plan is to take Grozny neighborhood by neighborhood after pummeling
it with artillery and airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Ministry troops and a small number of forces controlled
by the former mayor of Grozny, Bislan Gantamirov, will reoccupy the
city. Gantamirov was imprisoned for embezzlement but rehabilitated
by Moscow, which is eager to find allies among the Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officials said that there were about 2,000
Islamic fighters in Grozny, and that they had thwarted several
efforts by the militants to break out of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny was not the only objective. Russian artillery and
aircraft also attacked targets in the Argun Gorge, hoping to
prevent the rebels from escaping to mountain sanctuaries.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said that SU-24 bombers, SU-25 attack planes
and Russian MI-24 helicopter gunships carried out 71 missions on
Thursday. Kazantsev said the Russian military hoped to subdue the
entire breakaway republic, including the mountains, within three
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
