<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETHLEHEM-2000-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIANS OF ALL STRIPES PACK BETHLEHEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ In the place where Jesus was born,
Christians of all denominations from around the world Friday
arrived to celebrate the Christmas that will usher in the third
millennium of the faith.
</P>
<P>
   Braving ominous warnings of millennial terrorism and a cold
drizzling rain, some 15,000 pilgrims _ including tour groups, heads
of state, and Palestinian families _ packed the ancient cobblestone
streets and newly renovated Manger Square for a Christmas Eve of
prayer vigils, joyous choirs, and rousing gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   A midnight mass was held inside the Church of the Nativity,
built upon the grotto where tradition holds that the Virgin Mary
took shelter and gave birth to the infant Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   On that cold night some 2,000 years ago the land was a rocky
desert expanse with caves where shepherds protected their flocks,
but Friday it was a scene of satellite TV trucks and a high-tech
sound and light shows on the theme of the Nativity beaming out to
the world's Christian believers.
</P>
<P>
   A giant, outdoor video screen broadcast the Mass and also
carried the ``Opening of the Holy Door'' at the Vatican by Pope
John Paul II, which opens the festivities of the ``great Jubilee of
the Incarnation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are having a celebration, like a birthday. But one of our
messages tonight is, `Don't forget what it is all about, don't
forget whose birthday this is,''' said Rev. Robert Fortin, an
Assumptionist priest appointed by the Catholic Bishops Conference
to head up the Jubilee Celebrations in the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that amid all this hype all over the world, there will
also be quiet prayer and reflection on the meaning of the birth of
our Lord,'' said Fortin.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of the calendars of all three monotheistic
faiths in the Holy Land made Friday the Jewish Sabbath, the Friday
prayers for the Muslim Holy month of Ramadan, as well as Christmas
Eve.
</P>
<P>
   At noon in Bethlehem, which is overwhelmingly Muslim, the Omar
Bin Al Khatab mosque off Manger Square was packed with a thousand
worshipers, hundreds of whom put down prayer mats in the outdoor
plaza, bumping up against tourists and TV crews amid the Christmas
decorations and floating mylar Santa balloons.
</P>
<P>
   In the Muslim faith Jesus is revered as a prophet, and many
passages of the Koran show praise and love for Mary. The message
broadcast over loudspeakers from the mosque Friday was one that
emphasised the unity of Palestinians, about 98 percent of whom are
Muslim and 2 percent Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were like a stone during the intifada together, standing up
against the Israeli occupation,'' the Muslim cleric Khalid Tafish
said.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian President Yasser Arafat prayed with the Muslims in
the mosque and later arrived in a motorcade at the ancient
stone-facade of the Church of Nativity to attend the midnight Mass,
along with his wife, Suha, who is Christian.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the celebration seemed tinged with Palestinian
patriotism as Arafat used the platform to show off Bethlehem, which
has been dramatically refurbished since it came under Palestinian
rule during Christmas 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The square was ringed with Palestinian flags. At the base of the
stage, an enormous sign in Arabic read, ``From Bethlehem 2000 to
the indepedendence and building of the Palestinian state, with its
capital being holy Jerusalem and under the leadership of President
Yasser Arafat.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the Latin Catholic Patriarch Michel Sabbah's Christmas
message was punctuated with political demands for the release of
Palestinian political prisoners and the right of return for
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Manger Square housed the Israeli police station
during the Israeli occupation, which ended as a result of the
ongoing peace process. At that site, the Palestinian Authority has
constructed a new ``Bethlehem Peace Center.''
</P>
<P>
   The white cinderblock structure has the non-descript character
of an office park off an American interstate highway. And some wry
observers have even remarked that the edifice is a metaphor for the
peace process _ built at the last minute amid hopes by its
architects that the whole structure does not collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists with video cameras and travel guide books, who had
traveled here from all over Europe, Asia, and America, seemed
oblivious to the political trappings but fully engaged in the
significance of being present at the place where Jesus was born.
They flocked into the Church of Nativity to descend into the shrine
to touch the excavation of the grotto believed to be Jesus'
birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Leah Mitchel, a Methodist kindergarden teacher from Greenville,
S.C., said, ``I just wanted to be here and to experience Bethlehem,
the place of our Lord's birth. What better place to be in the world
on the eve of the new millennium?''
</P>
<P>
   She said she ignored the US government's travel warnings
regarding threats of terrorism in the Middle East on the
millennium. ``My heart breaks for all those who kept at home. They
are missing so much,'' she said, her words punctuated by unsettling
bursts of firecrackers and bottle rockets over the square.
</P>
<P>
   Down a narrow street, away from the noise and the crowds
gathered in Manger Square, is an orphanage known as ``The Creche.''
In the small convent of the Catholic Daughters of Charity, some 55
orphaned children, from newborns to six year olds, were running and
crawling around in a playroom which was decorated with a wooden
replica of Jesus' grotto, often refered to as a manger. The
youngest infant, a 6-day-old boy named ``Jihad'' who had been
abandoned by his parents, was placed before the Creche as the nuns
handed presents to the children and led them in the song, ``Oh
Little Star of Bethlehem'' in Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Ursula, a Palestinian Christian from the French order of
Daughters of Charity, said, ``We all celebrate the birth of Jesus,
Christian and Muslim alike. We celebrate by caring for these
children. We see in their eyes the hardship that Jesus suffered in
this land, but we also see in their eyes the hope and the light
that the baby Jesus signifies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1856EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
