<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MODERN-MASKS-NYT &LR;      12-24 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MODERN-MASKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASKS REVEAL AS MUCH AS THEY HIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photos, NYT7,8,9,10, have been sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once upon a time masks belonged to anthropology. They were
strange objects made of wood, shells, feathers and bells that
primitives wore for coming-of-age rituals, funerary rites, rain
dances, fertility festivals and seasonal get-togethers. As recently
as 1975, Claude Levi-Strauss wrote a study about the masks of the
Northwest Coast Indians, ``The Way of the Masks,'' showing their
relationship to the Indians' kinship patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are gone. There are no more primitives. Or rather, we
are all primitives. Modern people wear hockey masks, gas masks and
surgical masks. You could say that modern masks are just for
protection. You could also say that hockey, war and surgery are
rituals and that these masks reveal something about the
relationships of the people who wear them, but there's more to it
than that.
</P>
<P>
   Puppeteers, artists and dramatists are spinning their own
theories about the place of masks in modern culture now, and they
are finding that it is not all kinship or cranial protection.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall 1999 issue of The Drama Review, which was devoted to
puppets and masks, Stephen Kaplin, an artist and puppeteer who has
worked with Julie Taymor (the director of ``The Lion King'') and
the Bread and Puppet Theater, proposes an intriguing taxonomy of
``performing objects'' _ masks, puppets, Claymation figures,
animated cartoon characters, even actors. He suggests looking at
the ``puppet/performer dynamic.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for example, the real physical distance between the
performing object and the performer. Animated cartoon figures
perform at a distance, in time and space, from the person who
animates them. Shadow puppets are closer to their operator, but not
as close as the hand puppet to the puppeteer. The closest
relationship, of course, is that of the actor and the character he
plays. Physically they are inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the case of Spaulding Gray or Annie Sprinkle, actors who
represent themselves on stage, the two are not the same. As Kaplin
writes, the actor who plays himself is still presenting ``a highly
edited, crafted and shaped self.'' (The issue becomes especially
tricky in the recent movie ``Being John Malkovich,'' in which
Malkovich plays himself being inhabited and operated by a rogue
puppeteer and a host of other people.)
</P>
<P>
   In Kaplin's scheme, masks are somewhere between puppets and
actors. A mask recontours the actor's face, Kaplin writes, but
``doesn't alter the actor's center of gravity.'' (According to this
logic, the mask of Scar in ``The Lion King,'' worn high above the
actor's face or held far in front of it, starts to become a
puppet.)
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean for a mask to be midway between a puppet and
an actor? The mask's split nature suggests a split purpose: the
person in a mask can pass as someone else while still acting on his
own behalf. Masks, in this sense, are transportation devices. The
wearer can travel to the unknown _ from life to death, earth to
spirit world, earth to moon _ while still retaining his place at
home.
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of masks at the St. Louis Art Museum, ``Masks:
Faces of Culture,'' which includes everything from a 7,000-year-old
funerary mask from the Middle East to a modern hockey mask and a
space helmet, bears this out. The show begins with a replica of one
of the cave walls in Lascaux, France, showing a 17,000-year-old
drawing of a man with a bird mask on his head and a speared bison
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   John W. Nunley, one of the curators, ventured an interpretation:
``By wearing the bird mask,'' Nunley said, the shaman believed he
could ``fly into the spirit world,'' where he could ask the bison's
spirit to come back the next year to be killed again.
</P>
<P>
   Cara McCarty, the other curator of the exhibition, suggested
that masks are for ``exploring other places.'' The look of the
masks can sometimes suggest what kind of passage is being
negotiated: life into death, winter into spring or boyhood into
manhood. For example, masks to bring rain may have lightning bolts
or serpents on them. Masks that allow soldiers to pass through
poison gases often have hoses sticking out of them.
</P>
<P>
   The very last object in the exhibition is a space helmet, a
bubble-shaped mask whose visor reflects the Earth. If you look at
it alongside all the other masks, the space helmet does not seem so
different from a shaman's bird mask. It is made for travel to an
alien world.
</P>
<P>
   If masks can do all this for astronauts and shamans, you might
wonder what they could do for the aliens among us.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Critical Vehicles'' (M.I.T. Press, 1999), the artist
Krzysztof Wodiczko describes the masks and instruments he has
designed to help immigrants make their way into a strange new
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   One is a mouthpiece or porte-parole that ``covers the mouth of
the wearer like a gag.'' This little mask has a small video monitor
that shows the immigrant's lips moving and a loudspeaker that
broadcasts a narrative the immigrant has recorded. The person who
wears it is immediately given ``a specific kind of power,''
Wodiczko writes. It transforms the immigrant ``into a kind of
cyborg'' who becomes ``an expert in the technology of speech in the
cyberspace era, an alien who has arrived in a xenophobic land.''
</P>
<P>
   Wodiczko has also created a puppetlike instrument called the
alien staff, which looks like a shepherd's crook, but it is not
used to tend sheep. It is a device to help immigrants and strangers
find their way in a new land, to help them talk to strangers about
``the unbearable complexity of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the staff, at eye level, is a small video monitor
showing the immigrant's face. The rod of the alien staff, which
Wodiczko calls the xenalog section, presents the relics of the
immigrant's history: ``rejected visa applications, immigration and
legal documents, apartment keys, old photographs and the various
identity cards acquired by the owner.'' Like the mouthpiece, the
alien staff is something that inspires curiosity and understanding
in a strange land.
</P>
<P>
   There is something strange and telling about these immigrant
inventions, which appear at once archaic and forward-looking,
shepherdly and cyborgian. They are made for immigrants to get the
upper hand, to appear more technologically advanced than the
strangers they walk among. Yet the thing the operators want to
communicate with all this gadgetry is their past.
</P>
<P>
   Wodiczko's instruments have something in common with an
18th-century gadget called the automaton chess player, which Marc
Sussman, a scholar and artist, describes in an essay in The Drama
Review. The automaton has mechanical hands that move the pieces on
a chess board, while the operator, a human chess player, crouches
concealed in the cabinet beneath. As Sussman points out, the
philosopher Walter Benjamin interpreted the hidden player as sacred
archaic thinking, ``which has to keep out of sight'' while history
and progress march straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The chess player beneath the automaton, the immigrant with the
cyborgian device, the shaman in the bird mask and the astronaut in
the space helmet are all wearing masks, and their masks say two
things at once: I'm marching forward into the unknown, but I'm
looking backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
