<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT CLEARS WAY FOR NCAA ELIGIBILITY STANDARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ruling came out of Philadelphia Wednesday and didn't create
much of a stir. But the ramifications are significant.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd US Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a lower court
ruling that said the NCAA couldn't use minimum standardized test
scores to determine freshman eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, a lower court threw out the minimum standards for
freshman eligibility, saying the policy was unfair to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Chaos loomed, especially in college football and basketball,
where freshmen are intregral.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the decision, according to the court, was that
since the NCAA did not directly receive federal funding, it did not
have to abide by Title VI of the 1964 Civil Rights Act, which
forbids discrimination on the basis of race, color, or national
origin.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the NCAA's minimum standards of eligibility based on
test scores, contended that the SAT and ACT tests were culturally
biased. A 2.5 point grade point average in 13 core academic courses
also was required.
</P>
<P>
   Debate on that issue will continue. But one thing was certain.
Some minimum requirements were better than none. An entire semester
passed with colleges and universities in limbo over who was
eligible and who was not.
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, the case finally will be decided by the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   So be it. Frankly, making freshmen ineligible would solve the
problem, but that will never happen, especially with basketball
coaches battling the NBA for top high school prospects. Freshmen
ineligibility merely would increase the flow of top talent from
high school to the pros.
</P>
<P>
   For now, however, the new rules of freshmen eligibility are the
same as the old, and those are better than none.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orange squeeze
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse is 8-0, is ranked ninth, and is playing like, well,
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   For some people that is not enough, which is hard to understand.
Few coaches anywhere do a better job than Jim Boeheim, but he still
hears the critics. The latest shot came last week when a four-part
series was published in the Syracuse papers detailing the decline
of Orangeman recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Interesting stuff. But let's look at some numbers. This year's
start marks the 11th time in 24 seasons Boeheim's teams have been
at least 8-0. Winning 20 games is almost a guarantee. So is winning
a game or two in the NCAA Tournament. So is playing good defense.
This year's team is the runaway leader in defense in the Big East,
allowing 54.8 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of UConn, a guarantee of a 20-win season for any head
man in New England would get him coach-of-the-year votes, not
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Boeheim continues to take blasts. Granted, the Orangemen
have yet to play outside the Carrier Dome. But is there any doubt
about this team winning 20? And so what if other schools appear to
have better recruiting seasons. Let them translate that to 20 wins
a season and then give them praise.
</P>
<P>
   Boeheim's teams play hard, they play well, and they win. It's
hard to ask for more from a program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Take it from top
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers's 85-65 loss to Florida last week continued the drought
the Scarlet Knights have had against Top 10 teams. Rutgers is 4-39
against Top 10 teams, with its last victory coming Dec. 3, 1981,
when it upset UCLA in first college game ever played in the
Meadowlands . . . Hot shooting award of week goes to St. John's in
its 98-86 win over Hofstra. Anthony Glover led the way with 35
points, which included 12 of 12 from the field and 11 of 13 free
throws. The Red Storm made 18 of 21 field goals in the second half
. . . The addition of 7-foot-2-inch transfer Karim Shabazz from
Florida State should improve Providence coach Tim Welsh's mood over
the holidays. But with losses to Holy Cross and Central
Connecticut, there's still more coal than candy in Welsh's holiday
stocking. Guard John Linehan is probably out for the season with an
injury and the Friars are young and inexperienced. ``We're going to
have to change things around without John,'' said Welsh. ``The way
things are right now we've only got one of our top seven players
back from last season.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A tough break
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State was hoping that All-America guard Mateen Cleaves
(broken foot) would be back by the Spartans' game against
Mississipppi Valley State, but it now looks more like the first of
the year and the start of the Big Ten season . . . Hanno Mottola,
in his second game back after preseason knee surgery, sparked Utah
in Wednesday night's 79-73 win over Texas with a career-high 32
points . . . Former Indiana and Arizona player (for a few months)
Luke Recker is petitioning the NCAA for a waiver that will allow
him to play at Iowa next fall instead of sitting out two semesters.
Recker is claiming a medical hardship. He transferred to Iowa to be
closer to his girlfriend, Kelly Craig, who was paralyzed in an
automobile accident last summer . . . New Mexico has picked up the
pace under Fran Fraschilla. Beating Arizona in Tucson, as the Lobos
did early last week, is no easy accomplishment . . . What's with
UCLA? The Bruins look good one game, horrible the next, with
Wednesday's 55-54 loss to Colorado State being the latest example
of the bad Bruins . . . Michael Jordan is struggling. That's Penn's
Michael Jordan, last season's Ivy League Player of the Year, who is
shooting just under 22 percent from 3-point land, which is part of
the reason the Quakers are 1-4 entering a tournament next week in
California. An ambitious schedule is the prime reason . . . In a
win over UNLV last week, Oklahoma State held the Runnin' Rebels to
1 of their first 23 3-point attempts . . . Ohio State might think
twice before scheduling state rival Toledo. A year ago the Rockets
upset the Buckeyes in Columbus. Wednesday night, the Buckeyes had
to go all-out to get a 64-61 win. ``Give Toledo credit,'' said Ohio
State coach Jim O'Brien. ``But we gave them way too much.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tigers on his tail
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Memphis has talked to former UMass head man and current
Philadelphia 76ers assistant John Calipari about coaching the
Tigers. Calipari has put that on hold until the end of the season.
Memphis coach Tic Price resigned at the start of this year. Johnny
Jones is running the Tigers now, but the administration wants a
high-profile guy . . . What's happening at Clemson? The Tigers
already have lost to schools from the MEAC, Midwestern Collegiate
Conference, and Southern Conference, with home losses to South
Carolina State and Wofford, two in-state rivals. That would be like
Northeastern beating BC at Conte Forum. Well, maybe not this season
. . . Mississippi might be this season's sleeper in the SEC. The
Rebels are 9-1, with only a loss at Oklahoma marring their record.
``We're good,'' said Ole Miss coach Rod Barnes. ``We're not a great
basketball team by any stretch of the imagination.'' . . . The ACC
is back to its old tricks, with five of its nine teams ranked in
the Top 25: North Carolina (6), Duke (10), Maryland (17), Wake
Forest (23), and North Carolina State (25). The last time the four
North Carolina teams wre ranked in the same poll was Dec. 20, 1960
. . . Duke has not lost to a non-conference in-state opponent since
1981, when Davidson upset the Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mass panic
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With two losses in three games in Puerto Rico, UMass basketball
is in crisis. Coach Bruiser Flint basically knew entering the
season he not only would have to advance the team into the NCAA
Tournament, but he had to win a game to feel secure about his job.
A 6-5 start, with the Atlantic 10 season still ahead, increases the
sense of urgency . . . Fans of Marshall have yet to see their
football or basketball teams lose this season. The unbeaten
football team will face BYU in the Motor City Bowl next week, while
the basketball team is 8-0, matching its best start since 1973-74 .
. . Trouble in Miami? It looks that way after the Canes' Johnny
Hemsley walked off the court in a middle of a win over Detroit in a
tournament game in Puerto Rico this week. Hurricanes coach Leonard
Hamilton suspended Hemsley for two games, which just adds to the
frustration of the team that is a mediocre 5-5 after a sixth-place
finish in the San Juan Shootout.
</P>
</TEXT>
