<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASSELBECK: HIS RED FLAG WAS IGNORED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was 20 years ago, when he was playing tight end for the New
England Patriots, when Don Hasselbeck cautioned the National
Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they should change,'' said Hasselbeck. ``I called
the league office a couple of times when the season was over, but I
guess no one ever paid attention to me. Nothing changed. Now this
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, 1979, during the final game of the season in
Foxborough, Hasselbeck was cut in the face with a flag thrown by an
official and needed six stitches. ``I thought I was shot,'' said
Hasselbeck. ``It knocked me right to the ground. I was in
tremendous pain. I put my hand up to my mouth and there was blood
all over the place. I looked down, and there was this metal sinker,
like you fish with, on the ground right in front of me. That's what
the official had in his flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward 20 years and three days to Dec. 19, 1999. In
Cleveland, referee Jeff Triplette threw a flag and hit Browns
offensive lineman Orlando Brown in the eye. Brown responded by
knocking Triplette to the ground, and has been suspended
indefinitely. He is still hospitalized with potentially permanent
eye damage.
</P>
<P>
   Triplette's flag contained small metal pellets to give it
weight, as opposed to the sinker that dropped Hasselbeck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were playing the Minnesota Vikings and going in for a
score. I was blocking Jim Marshall. He was 41 years old, and I
still held him,'' said Hasselbeck, laughing at himself. ``I saw the
official (field judge) at the back of the end zone throw the flag
in my direction. I didn't pay any attention to it except that I was
mad for getting caught holding. Next thing I knew it hit me.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took me into the locker room. My lip was split from the
bottom of my nose down. If I didn't have a mouthpiece in, I would
have had my teeth knocked out. As it was, my teeth were a little
loose. They stitched me up and I played the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of months later, during the offseason, I called the
NFL office and asked them what was going to be done about it. I
never got a straight answer.''
</P>
<P>
   At times there are ``spot penalties'' in football, and the
officials are supposed to throw their flag to the spot where the
foul occurred. A flag with no weight to it would not reach the
spot, or blow away. So officials are told to put their own weight
in the flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recommend popcorn (kernels),'' says Jerry Seeman, head of
officals, ``and small BBs like Jeff used in this case. It was an
unfortunate accident. The right guard moved on the play before the
snap so Jeff threw his flag toward the right guard and Brown (at
right tackle) was going in that direction when he got hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the spin the Browns are trying to put on the incident,
Brown is described by former teammates and coaches as a violent
person with a quick trigger. They are not suprised he went off on
the official. In Baltimore, he had to be prevented by his teammates
from trying to attack a sportswriter on the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if he really wanted to, he could have hurt Triplette,
because Brown is one of the strongest guys in the league, which is
why he has the nickname ``Zeus.'' Brown originally was a free agent
nobody wanted. He was ready to sign on with World Wrestling
Federation when the Browns signed him for $100. During his first
workout, he hit the blocking sled so hard, the guy holding it flew
through the air and separated a shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Those feeling sorry for Brown should remember there have been
probably hundreds of officials who have been run over and injured
by NFL players in accidents during games, and not one has sued a
player yet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were so close to signing Orel Hershiser they were
preparing an announcement when he opted for Los Angeles instead.
``We thought we had him,'' said Red Sox general manager Dan
Duquette. ``He was going to come to us, and then the Dodgers, who
hadn't shown any interest, suddenly got into it, so Orel decided to
close out his career with the team he started with. If they didn't
get into it, I'm confident we would have had him.'' Duquette said
that what encouraged to Sox to sign 36-year-old Jeff Fassero was
the finish he had last season. ``He had elbow surgery in September
of 1998, and many times it takes a pitcher two years to get back to
where he was,'' said Duquette. ``We looked at him in the final
month of the season when he was with Texas and felt he was throwing
better than he did all of last year. We needed a lefthanded
pitcher. We're still going to sign another pitcher before training
camp, and try to pick up a free agent righthanded bat who might
surprise us in training camp.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Orr didn't want to say much about the young man except:
``He is a terrific kid, with great talent, who works hard, who
wants to be good, and who comes from a terrific family.'' Orr was
talking about Jason Spezza, a 16-year-old phenom currently playing
with the Canadian National Junior Team who is being billed as the
next, well, Bobby Orr. Orr is a consultant to his family and wants
to stay in the background. But hockey types who have seen Spezza
play in juniors north of the border say he could be the real deal.
Spezza is over 6 feet already, and even though he is two years away
from the big show, he has a can't-miss label on him already.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles' Troy Vincent had a big game against the Patriots
last Sunday, with two interceptions, and he didn't like what he saw
in New England quarterback Drew Bledsoe's eyes toward the end of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad for him,'' said Vincent on his Philadelphia radio
show Monday night. ``In the fourth period you could see fear in his
eyes. He could see we were coming hard with the pass rush and they
couldn't block it. He knew he has going to get hit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only normal to look at way he did, after the hits he
took all afternoon. Any other quarterback who ever played the game
would have looked the same way. All day long we just rushed more
people than they could block, and that allowed us (defensive backs)
to play more aggressive and go after the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no logical reason for middle linebacker Ted Johnson,
after being injured most of the season, and playing now with a
brace on his arm, to play the final two games for New England,
which is out of the playoffs. Hopefully, before kickoff Sunday
someone wakes up at Foxboro Stadium and gets him off the field. The
team would be better served by putting Andy Katzenmoyer back on the
field to gain more experience, and making sure Johnson is 100
percent for next season . . . Vinny Vecchione, fight manager:
``They're going to have to create a super heavyweight division in
boxing. These guys are getting bigger all the time. I saw a couple
of Russians recently that were 6-6, 6-7. How can you ask someone
190 pounds (the heavyweight minimum) to go up against guys like
that?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Times's most recent NFL computer
rankings, the Oakland Raiders have played the toughest schedule in
the league this year, with their opponents compiling an 86-68
record. Now here are two schedules to pay attention to when
evaluating the playoffs. St. Louis, which will be favored to win
the NFC, has played the easiest schedule, with opponents combining
for 53 wins and 74 losses. Jacksonville, most likely the pick in
the AFC, has the second-easist schedule, its foes compiling 55 wins
and 86 losses. The Patriots have played the softest schedule in the
AFC East (69-73), and the Jets the toughest (82-58).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strangest scene your humble servant ever witnessed involving
a player and official in the NFL came in a game in Baltimore when
Bert Jones was playing QB for the ``original'' Colts. Jones,
scrambling with time running out in the first half, was on the
ground and sliding out of bounds near the Patriot bench. The field
judge in those days fired a starter's pistol with blanks to signify
the end of the half, and the game. As Jones was sliding toward him,
the field judge was too busy paying attention to his watch, and
just about the time Jones arrived at his feet, he fired it. Jones
1) thought he was shot; 2) thought he may have been dead; and 3)
rolled around on the ground for a long time holding both hands over
the earholes of his helmet. ``We had one like that once with the
Giants in Yankee Stadium,'' said Art McNally, retired former head
of officials in the NFL. ``Our of our guys (a field judge) got a
little bit excited and fired off the gun at the two-minute warning
by mistake. Andy Robustelli of the Giants had been in the service
and hit the ground, thinking someone was shooting at him. When he
got up, let's just say he wasn't so happy with our guy.'' But he
didn't knock him down either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
