<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8544 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-PRESS-860(2TAK     12-24 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-PRESS-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S UNMATCHED AVAILABILITY YIELDS GOOD RELATIONS WITH PRESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (mk) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ No one could accuse John McCain of shirking
his obligations to the newspaper readers of Norway. For 30 minutes
of his precious campaign time the other day, the senator from
Arizona took questions from a reporter from Oslo as the two sat in
the back of the bus that his staff has christened the Straight Talk
Express.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really appreciate being on the bus with you,'' Anne
Thurmann-Nielsen, correspondent for the Norwegian daily Dagbladet,
said as the exchange wound down.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate winked. ``Well, we do feel the critical vote in
this campaign will be out in Minnesota,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other journalists on the bus, representing news
organizations as diverse as ABC News and The Arizona Daily Star of
Tucson, laughed at the senator's allusion to the Midwestern state's
large population of Scandinavian-Americans. But in his wry
acknowledgement that this encounter was unlikely to help him win a
single vote, McCain was actually telling a joke on himself, one
that everyone on the bus was in on: These days, he never meets an
interviewer he doesn't like.
</P>
<P>
   Among political reporters, the extraordinary access that McCain
provides has become the stuff of instant legend, and it is not only
the Norwegian media that has benefited. Opportunities for face time
with the other major candidates tend to be limited and fiercely
regimented. ``I was on the campaign with Gore, but he was on the
other bus,'' Ms. Thurmann-Nielsen said of her inability to get
close to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for hour after hour, McCain takes on all comers on the
Straight Talk Express as it crosses early primary states like New
Hampshire and South Carolina. In fact, this maverick Republican
conservative will spar and ruminate, banter and cajole, kick back
and hold forth for as long as anyone with a pad or a microphone
cares. And sometimes, even longer.
</P>
<P>
   The result: an unusually tension-free relationship between the
press and a candidate from a wing of a party that has often viewed
journalists as the enemy. Indeed, some in the conservative movement
are so deeply resentful of McCain's clubbiness with the press and
incredulous at the huge amount of attention he has garnered _
earlier this month, for instance, Time ran his photo on the cover
and a package of five stories on his candidacy _ that they detect a
strong whiff of favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much like the boomlet for Colin Powell,'' declared Tim
Graham, director of media analysis for the Media Research Center, a
conservative think tank. ``There is the hero part, and they're
liking this guy because he's fun, he's very candid. To me, it's
disturbing that the biggest test for deciding who's presidential
timber is which candidate is the fastest returning your phone
call.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham reported in the weekly press release that the center
calls its ``Media Reality Check'' that between Sept. 27 and Dec.
10, McCain, his wife, Cindy, and his campaign manager appeared on
``Good Morning America'' eight times, or once ``every nine days.''
During the same period, he said, the other Republican candidates
were on once or never.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters dismiss the idea that a ride on the Straight Talk
Express means a free ride for the candidate. But they sure do like
the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unique,'' said Joe Klein, political writer for The New
Yorker and author of the Clinton-years novel ``Primary Colors,'' as
he rode the bus from Cambridge, Mass., to this historic seafaring
city on New Hampshire's tiny coastline. ``Most politicians, even at
this stage, don't give the level of access that he's giving now.''
</P>
<P>
   And reporters suspect that any minute, they and the senator will
awake from this dream, and the candidate will trade in his plush
recliner in the back of the bus for the enveloping cocoon of his
strategists and media consultants at the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long can you keep this up, the letting us grill you for
hours?'' Dana Millbank, a New Republic writer, asked the senator
one evening on the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, McCain replied. ``This is one thing I can't
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the race, McCain's staff tried their best to change
him, to get him to follow the unwritten political commandment that
says, Thou shalt not be too available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trained to parcel out access, to vet every
question,'' said John Weaver, the campaign's political director.
``But he refused, and finally we just surrendered. And you know, he
was right. Not every candidate can do this, but what we've
discovered is, so what if he makes a mistake? The interesting thing
is that the more the press sees the candidate is a real person, the
more likely they'll be to give him a pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and other aides to McCain say that reporters may find the
candidate appealing for the same reasons as the public. He is a
charismatic speaker and a natural object of admiration, having
emerged from five and a half years in a North Vietnamese prison
with his sense of humor intact. But even if some reporters say they
do like him, it is for the most part an attraction born of
pragmatism. ``He's good copy, and he returns my phone calls,'' said
one veteran Washington correspondent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who pointed out that this is the seventh New Hampshire
presidential primary he has covered, acknowledged that the question
of how much extra slack reporters may cut McCain is a tough one.
The potentially damaging episodes of the senator's past _ his
involvement in the Keating Five affair, the reports of his angry
outbursts _ have been widely reported. But would the reporters pull
out their cell phones if a gaffe were committed on the Straight
Talk Express? Klein said he might not, but not because of his
feelings about McCain. ``I have a `no gotcha' rule,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The romance of the sharp-tongued McCain and a demanding press
corps is, of course, more complex than it appears.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case with veteran lawmakers, he and his hometown
paper, The Arizona Republic of Phoenix, have feuded off and on,
over such issues as the content of its editorial cartoons and his
reputation for being quick to anger. ``It's never been a good
relationship,'' the senator said. And the campaign acknowledged
misstepping when it tried recently to control a sensitive story,
the release of McCain's medical records, by giving it early to
selected reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Salkowski, a technology reporter for the Tucson paper who
traveled with the candidate for several days last week, said that
while he found the senator ``good to deal with _ he'll return my
calls,'' some of his Arizona colleagues found him mercurial. ``The
perception is, he is more difficult to deal with than his national
reputation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Straight Talk Express, however, the atmosphere of all
candor all the time bathes the campaign in a nonconfrontational
informality. The bus design itself contributes to the feeling. It
is more Winnebago than standard-issue charter, with kitchen and
shower and couches built into the walls. McCain genuinely seems to
like reporters; he not only knows their names, he reads their
stories. He talks politics and policy but also boxing and books and
history and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons I do it is because I enjoy it,'' he said
one afternoon, as the bus descended from the White Mountains on the
way to Manchester. ``Some of the smartest people I've ever met are
in the media, and some of the dumbest people I've ever met are in
the media.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about an insatiable appetite for spectator sports _
``I would watch guys picking up refrigerators,'' was how he put it
_ and an aversion to being ``handled,'' saying, ``I won't take
security: I don't need it, I don't like it, I don't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered innocuous quips about well-known politicians and
praise for the press for its hands-off treatment of Chelsea
Clinton, and when asked about it afterward by Salkowski, a mea
culpa for overstating his legislative achievements in an interview
with a radio reporter. ``That was a bit disingenuous,'' he
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters are taken aback by all the attention. A look of
something like shock comes over the faces of some newcomers to the
Straight Talk Express as it dawns on them that this candidate
actually wants to sit next to them. The thought is expressed by
some professional skeptics _ reporters, pundits and politicians _
that it is a ploy, that the guarantee of access translates to
better coverage, and that this partly accounts for McCain's growing
popularity with the voters here.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, for one, thinks not. ``It's not us,'' he said, referring
to McCain's surge in various polls in New Hampshire. ``If it were
us, Bruce Babbitt would have been elected president. There's always
a press favorite in a campaign, and it's usually the loser.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
