<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-BETHLEHEM- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BETHLEHEM, A MIX OF CHRISTIAN FAITH AND PALESTINIAN
NATIONALISM 
</HEADLINE>
 1STLD-WRITETHRU- ART-NYT  
(Subbing to correct spelling to `Filipino' sted `Filipina' in
lede.) (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and 2 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ In this little town, the traditional
birthplace of Jesus, the Palestinian police stood guard on the
rooftops of Manger Square on Friday night as Italian nuns prayed
with clasped hands, American gospel choirs belted out carols and
Filipino immigrants wearing Santa hats boogied on plastic chairs.
</P>
<P>
   And that was just the prelude to a long, surreal Christmas Eve
in the newly refurbished town, where Christian spirituality,
Palestinian nationalism and party fever intermingled beneath
gold-laced trees. The eve built in a crescendo to a midnight Mass
featuring Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, accompanied by assorted
leftist leaders of the world, and rolled into Christmas Day with
fireworks and a Middle Eastern banquet.
</P>
<P>
   Above the square a new clock, a present from Athens, counted
down the days, hours and minutes to the third millennium while
television cameras from around the globe _ a thousand journalists
had registered _ trained themselves on the crowds of pilgrims,
tourists and locals that built steadily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you direct me to Nativity Square?'' asked Kevin Brown, an
Englishman with a five-o'clock-shadow and a backpack. When told he
was there, he looked around and said, ``Wow! It looks nothing like
the Christmas cards. Wow! It's a dharma-like thing to be at this
site at the millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jerusalem quieted to a rainy whisper with the onset of the
Jewish sabbath at sundown Friday, the sleepy town of Bethlehem came
to life in a way that approached Arafat's vision of a
Palestinian-ruled international crossroads. Arafat has invested
heavily _ $270 million in foreign dollars and a good deal of
rhetoric _ in putting Bethlehem on the millennial map, as a lure
for pilgrims and international recognition alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manger Square's not a parking lot anymore,'' said Tony Paris,
a Jerusalem resident from Atlanta, as he addressed dozens of
postcards to be postmarked ``Bethlehem, Dec. 25'' and sent to
friends and relatives in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Early on Friday, Manger Square filled with Muslims who spilled
out of the mosque, lit for the day with Christmas green, that faces
the Church of the Nativity. Arafat, a Muslim, had joined them in
Friday prayers, starting his day by observing the holy month of
Ramadan and ending it with a Mass. The Muslims kneeled between
police barricades as Christian tourists politely watched.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Latin patriarch, the Rev. Michel Sabbath, a native
Nazarene wearing flowing pink robes, rolled through the bumpy
streets of town, flanked by Palestinian police on horses. His
procession of some 150 altar boys was led by a Palestinian man
dressed in an Ottoman-era costume with a sword in his waistband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this just beautiful?'' asked Suha Arafat, Arafat's wife,
who was raised as a Christian, while she waited with foreign
dignitaries and scores of bodyguards to greet him at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Ducking through a pint-sized door in the church's battered
facade, tourists queued up to descend into the grotto that is
considered Jesus' birthplace. Pilgrims from Jakarta filled the
cave, singing ``Silent Night'' in Indonesian as one by one they
approached, kneeled and kissed the star of Bethlehem. One young
woman, tears rolling down her face, was so overcome with emotion
that she had to be helped back up the stone stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a worldwide terrorism alert, the tourists seemed utterly
unconcerned. Joergen Fischer of Germany wore an ``I (LOVE)
Palestine'' sticker on his lapel. ``The terrorists wouldn't attack
the Palestinians, would they?'' he said. ``This is probably one of
the safest places on the planet earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with sporadically heavy rains, the crowd grew thicker as
the night grew wetter. Three soggy Santas patrolled the streets
atop a local rental car, bravely ringing their bells into the mist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who runs this? The Jews?'' asked a pilgrim from New Delhi,
Laxmi Batav, who like several foreigners interviewed, did not know
Bethlehem is a Palestinian town.
</P>
<P>
   Many foreign workers from Israel, especially Nigerians and
Filipinos, showed up in full regalia. But half those who attended
were Israeli Arabs or Palestinians, many of them Muslims, turning
out not so much to commemorate Jesus as to be there, in force.
(Most Palestinian Christians are Orthodox and celebrate Christmas
on Jan. 7).
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coming here to participate with our brothers in their
celebrations,'' said Ashraf Yassini, 38, a Muslim who came with his
family of seven. ``It expresses a kind of unity, our presence here.
It's a beautiful feeling to witness the presence of the Palestinian
Authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Nassar, a Palestinian Christian who runs a photo store,
said many friends of his, including priests, would not attend the
Mass because it was not primarily a religious event. ``It has
become not a time of prayer but a time to show all the world who is
ruling here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Palestinians took control of the town in 1995,
Christmas Eve has turned into a pride day and, for the young, a
staid social scene. During the evening, a line of teen-agers belted
out ``Jingle Bells'' in Arabic as they sat cross-legged, their arms
linked, in Manger Square.
</P>
<P>
   But when a James Brown-style rhythm and blues band took to the
stage, young Palestinian men turned the square into a mosh pit,
much to the chagrin of a group of Japanese nuns. ``We thought we
were coming for an outdoor Mass,'' said one horrified Sister of
Charity.
</P>
<P>
   The midnight Mass, held in the Franciscan Church of St.
Catherine adjacent to the Church of the Nativity, was a
ticket-holders event. After a substantial delay, it was broadcast
to the big screens outside. Relieved, the Japanese sisters and some
nuns from Ireland witnessed a first-time event in the Holy Land,
where the Christian denominations are divided and sometimes
warring: Eastern clerics celebrated the Mass with Roman Catholic
priests in a nod to the turn of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat entered late, taking a seat in the front row beside his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   She wore black lace on her head, he his keffiyeh. When she
offered to share her prayerbook, he brushed it away with one hand.
Then he was brought his own.
</P>
<P>
   Standing, Arafat and his wife bowed together in prayer, and as
Christmas Day began, a hush fell over the crowd in the square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1930EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
