<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSOCIATE OF TERROR SUSPECT SOUGHT IN CANADA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (kd) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Canadian authorities said Friday that they had
issued an arrest warrant for a man believed to be an associate of
Ahmed Ressam, the man who was arrested at a border station in
Washington state and indicted on charges of illegally possessing
explosive materials.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian authorities identified the man they were seeking as
Abdelmajed Dahoumane, who is said to be 32 and the man who for
three weeks shared a motel room in Vancouver, British Columbia,
with Ressam before Ressam tried to enter the United States on Dec.
14 in a rental car.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials said that in the car they found vials of
nitroglycerine, more than 100 pounds of urea and digital timing
devices, all of which were components that federal authorities have
said could have been fashioned into a crude but powerful bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials have said that Ressam was accompanied
for at least part of the trip by car ferry from Vancouver to Port
Angeles, Wash., north of Seattle. They initially identified the man
who was with Ressam as Karim Said Atmani, who was said to have
shared an apartment with Ressam in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Friday whether or how Canadian authorities had
come to believe that the man who accompanied Ressam from Canada was
not Atmani but Dahoumane.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam was alone when he was stopped at Port Angeles by a
customs inspector, but he was carrying two ticket receipts, leading
officials to theorize that Ressam's companion had boarded a ferry
but returned to Canada before it reached an American port.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Ressam was formally charged in federal court in
Seattle with illegally carrying bomb materials. Ressam, who has not
agreed to cooperate with the authorities, could face a maximum
penalty of more than 40 years in prison if convicted. He has
pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The apparently chance discovery of explosives in the car driven
by Ressam has ignited a spate of warnings and alerts in recent days
about the possibility of terrorist acts against Americans, even as
the authorities continue to emphasize that they have no evidence of
any specific acts planned in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have said that they suspect Ressam is associated
with people who appear to be linked to terrorist organizations,
possibly the loose network of Islamic militants whose inspirational
leader, Osama bin Laden, has been indicted as the mastermind behind
the bombings of American embassies in East Africa in 1998. But the
officials have acknowledged that they cannot explain Ressam's plan
or motives for trying to bring explosive materials into the United
States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
