<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATIN-Y2K-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      12-24 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-Y2K-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL, LEADING LATIN AMERICA IN TECHNOLOGY, BRACES FOR Y2K
PROBLEMS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Conn.)   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Approximately 37,000 clients of Banco Itau
SA, one of Brazil's largest banks, got a glimpse last month of the
problems Latin Americans might encounter from the Year 2000
computer problem when they received a letter saying certain fees
would be charged to their accounts as of Jan. 4, 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The bank, which attributed the mix-up to human error and not to
its technology, quickly remedied the problem with follow-up
correspondence correcting the date to 2000. But doubts remained
since Itau was said to be among the region's best prepared
companies for the Year 2000, after investing more than $30 million
to prepare its computers for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   With a week to go, no one is quite sure what the fallout will be
from Latin America's mixed approach to dealing with the Year 2000
bug. According to analysts dealing with the problem, some of the
region's poorest countries, like Paraguay, are dramatically
ill-prepared, while other nations, like Chile and Mexico, planned
ahead and budgeted funds to sufficiently adapt their government
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, there appears to be a consensus emerging among the
people who have been rushing to prepare the region for the year
2000: The parts of Latin America most at risk are also the most
technologically advanced, while the most underdeveloped regions,
while they will almost surely also be affected by the bug, are not
likely to suffer as much as the region's pockets of relative
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like bank robber logic,'' said Dale Vecchio, a research
director at the Gartner Group, a Stamford, Conn.-based consulting
firm that has examined preparations for the bug around the world.
``Bank robbers search out the bank with the most money, just like
Y2K will affect the societies with the most technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nowhere in Latin America is this relation played out
with greater tension than in Brazil, the region's largest country
with 165 million people. While many parts of Brazil are relatively
underdeveloped and not that dependent on technology, cities like
Sao Paulo are highly wired. Ground zero for Brazil's race to
prepare for the bug could be said to be along the banks of the
Pinheiros, a murky river flowing through this city.
</P>
<P>
   Flanking the Pinheiros are several dozen skyscrapers that
developers built over the last decade as Brazil opened its economy
in an embrace of foreign technology and investment. These
structures, wired with state-of-the-art fiber optics, guarded by a
legion of armed security personnel and topped with helicopter
landing pads, have spent the last year under preparations to deal
with the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   For Sylvio Roth, the technician in charge adapting computer
systems for Jones Lang LaSalle, the London-based
skyscraper-management firm that manages some of Sao Paulo's most
exclusive commercial buildings, this means his schedule has been
put into overdrive. Roth heads a team stocking up on electricity
generators, diesel fuel and water supplies. Concerned with the
possibility of a surge in crime after the new year, provisions are
also being made for additional armed security forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've screened our buildings for possible problems, but now
our priority is contingency,'' said Roth. ``We're going to make
sure our clients can do business for five to 10 business days after
the first of the year, but this depends on things outside our
control, like the capacity of electricity utilities and telephone
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, large companies in Brazil are generally
prepared for the Year 2000 problem, thanks in part to the fact that
many state firms, including many utilities, were privatized in
sales to foreign concerns during the last few years. The federal
government has said its computers will prove resistant to the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, while it is generally acknowledged that most large
companies could fare fairly well, many small firms which have not
recognized the magnitude of the problem could suffer and put a drag
on some parts of the economy, analysts said. While this mixed
approach has created worries in large countries like Brazil, other
nations, like nearby Paraguay, offer a striking contrast in their
Year 2000 preparations.
</P>
<P>
   The poorest and most politically and economically unstable
member of Mercosur, the customs union also formed by Argentina,
Brazil and Uruguay, Paraguay is considered one of the least
prepared countries for the Year 2000 computer problem. Things were
made worse recently when Walter Schafer, the country's coordinator
to deal with the issue, was dismissed after foreign news reports
called attention to Paraguay's lack of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people in power got worried about Paraguay's image
abroad,'' said Schafer in a telephone interview from Asuncion,
Paraguay's capital. ``We Paraguayans have so much else to worry
about that it's no wonder our effort to deal with the bug was too
little, too late, and now almost nonexistent.''
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, the small country of 5 million seems to have
more pressing problems to deal with. In late November, rumors swept
Asuncion that some members of the armed forces were planning a
coup. Authorities loyal to President Luis Gonzalez Macchi arrested
14 army members suspected of disloyalty.
</P>
<P>
   According to Carlos Guedes, the official at the Inter-American
Development Bank in Washington responsible for coordinating the
institution's efforts to help Latin American countries deal with
the Year 2000 computer problem, Paraguay's situation is similar to
that of other small countries in the region, like Guatemala,
Bolivia and Ecuador. In an attempt to help countries like these
prepare for the problem, the bank this year opened a $200 million
emergency credit line to finance computer upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these countries have been hurt by natural phenomena
like hurricanes and a decline in the prices of their main commodity
exports that make dealing with Y2K more difficult,'' said Guedes.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador is one country in the region that has suffered damage
from natural disasters and, until recently, a weak market for oil,
one of its main exports. Yet in a sign that the situation in places
like Ecuador might actually be better off than some critics expect,
the country, like most other Latin American countries, has an
organized task force to deal with the Year 2000 computer problem.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Herrera, the official in charge of the task forces,
said she is confident that crucial parts of the economy, such as
electricity generation, telecommunications, water treatment and air
travel, are prepared for the potential effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're better prepared than a lot of people might expect,''
said Ms. Herrera. ``And we're in constant contact with other task
forces in Latin America, so we know that our efforts are in line
with others.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The saving grace of countries like Ecuador and Paraguay may lie
in their relatively unsophisticated computer networks when compared
with those in rich industrialized nations, or even those in more
prosperous Latin American countries like Chile. Even if problems do
arise, it is unlikely that they will have much of an impact on
bigger trading partners like Brazil or Argentina, since economic
integration is still somewhat low in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Even in those parts of Latin America where the Year 2000
computer problem might actually do damage, it is being shrugged off
by many people without much ado. The relative nonchalance among
Latin Americans to the issue might have something to do with their
approach to the economic, political and social turbulence that have
been common throughout the region's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin Americans tend to be more passionate than their
colleagues above the equator when it comes time to make a
decision,'' said Max Gehringer, a Sao Paulo businessman who writes
a column on corporate culture for Exame, Brazil's leading business
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practical terms this means we either magnify a problem
which really isn't that large or we underestimate something we
don't understand entirely,'' said Gehringer. ``Two things can
happen on the first day of January: Either our companies will enter
in reactive panic or an absence of problems will have us saying,
`See? It was all just hype.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8568 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MILLENNIUM-CHRISTMAS-     12-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CHRISTMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS SPIRIT SURVIVES FAMILY'S EVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, Mass. For the past 37 years Santa has had to bundle a
few extra sacks in his sleigh to keep the kids smiling at the big
white house on School Street.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas at Raymond and Claire Shea's century-old clapboard
home has never been a simple gift-giving affair. The couple's eight
boys and three girls have seen to that.
</P>
<P>
   And now that the Shea's children are grown, and Papa and Nana
have 17 grandchildren, the anticipation for new hockey skates,
train sets and video games runs even higher.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Christmas has stayed the same at the Shea's
ornament-strewn home since Ray and Claire began trimming trees and
lighting candles there in 1962, things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The cheery chaos of the Shea's household of a generation ago has
passed. The kids, now ranging in age from 29 to 47, often spend
Christmas day in their own homes with their own children. And their
grandchildren live in more typical families, with working moms and
fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   But as Claire prepared for her family's 47th Christmas Eve, a
time when in-laws, spouses and cousins join the immediate family to
also celebrate Ray and one of his son's birthdays, she reflected on
the differences between her children's and grandchildren's
upbringings.
</P>
<P>
   The raucous big-family Christmas of past decades, when children
had to share gifts, has given way to small-family Christmas, when
parents feel compelled to give more presents and lavish more
attention on their fewer children.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the ritual of rounding up the whole family for
Christmas Eve, when the candles still burn in the big Queen
Anne-style home, Claire feels something has been lost through the
long tunnel of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a very different world today,'' said Claire, 68,
whose main profession over the years has been being a mother to her
11 children. ``This used to be a neighborhood with a lot of noise.
But now we never see many of our neighbors. Kids aren't playing as
much as they used to and people keep to themselves a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Claire and Ray say they're lucky to have raised so many
children. But if they had to do it today, they probably couldn't
foot the cost, let alone stuff all the stockings. Buying enough
clothes, delivering more than a score of daily meals and paying for
their kids to go to school would just be too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impractical to have a family like ours today,''
Claire said. When Claire wasn't minding her children, she was
helping Ray, who owns a printing shop, where six of the family's
kids now work. ``It's just too expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sheas regret that so few couples choose to have large
families these days. In 1997, according to the US Census Bureau,
fewer than 2 percent of American families had six or more children.
</P>
<P>
   Big families have many advantages, they say. Brothers and
sisters competing for everything from attention to the last piece
of cake have to learn to share. They have to learn to distinguish
themselves from one another and they have to become self-reliant,
the Sheas said.
</P>
<P>
   Children in small families, such as Ray and Claire's children's
clans, may get too much attention, come to value possessions more
than relationships and expect things to be done for them, Claire
and Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Their kids learned to be patient, to compromise and to
appreciate what may have been relatively little compared to what
their friends had.
</P>
<P>
   When they wanted to shower before school, they had to wait in
line for the home's only bathroom. When they wanted to wear a
particular sweater or pair of jeans, they had to negotiate with
their brothers or sisters, all of whom shared clothes. When they
wanted to use the phone or watch TV, they had to deal with the fact
that the family only had one phone and one small set.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned that if you wanted something, you had to do it
yourself,'' said the Sheas' daughter Mary, now 41 and married with
three boys of her own in Belmont. ``Sure, having a lot of brothers
around when you were a teenager wasn't always easy. But we got
along.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wonder how my parents did it,'' said another
daughter, Patti, 37, once the goalie on the women's US Olympic
field hockey team who lives in Hadley and coaches at the University
of Massachusetts at Amherst. ``But we learned values like
discipline and working hard for what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there was no privacy, no place to hide,'' said Jim,
34, a software developer living in Arlington with his wife and two
children. ``But the pros definitely outweighed the cons.''
</P>
<P>
   As the afternoon wore into the evening, and Ray and Claire set
out the shrimp before their friends and family arrived, they said
even if their grandchildren were losing out by growing up in
smaller families, they weren't much different from their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Papa and Nana still have to hide the family's presents in a
small room next to the attic. They still worry whether the children
will have hoped they got different presents. And they continue to
talk about Santa's imminent arrival, even if the kids know there's
no such thing as Santa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still get anxious to get and give out their presents,''
Claire said. ``And so do we.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
