<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NY-HOMELESS -- Jill Flesch
spent years on the street, often being arrested or carted off to
psychiatric wards. A supported housing development is now her home.
``It's unspeakable to have my own place,'' she says. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NYC-CHRISTMAS-LIGHTS --
Christmas time in New York offers up brilliant presents for the
eye, including this glittering holiday tribute on Wall Street in
front of the New York Stock Exchange. The spirit such holiday
presentations engender makes you remember, for a minute, why you
put up with the crazy rents. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WINNIPEG, Manitoba -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- CANADA-INDIANS-2
-- Students in an English literacy program at the Winnipeg
Aboriginal Center ponder a writing assignment. Situated in a former
Canadian Pacific railroad station, the center provides job
counselling, employment services and education. Despite boasting
Canada's highest population of urban Indians, jobs are difficult
for the Aboriginal population here to get or to keep. (Kevin
Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WINNIPEG, Manitoba -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- CANADA-INDIANS-1
-- A construction worker swings a hammer in front of a new
community center for Native Americans in Winnipeg. Despite boasting
Canada's highest population of urban Indians and a healthy economy
that has local employers ready to hire, jobs are difficult for the
Aboriginal population here to get or to keep. (Kevin Moloney/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- OBIT-LAMPORT -- Felicia
Lamport, a poet and satirist who took delight in skewering the high
and mighty with verse, quips, puns and parodies, most of them first
appearing in a column in The Boston Globe called Muse of the Week
in Review, died Thursday at her home in Cambridge, Mass. She was
83. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- BEANIE-BABY-REFERENDUM --
Four months ago, Ty Inc. shocked children and other collectors by
claiming it would kill off its wildly popular Beanie Babies line
come Dec. 31. But Friday, just in time to spread some extra
Christmas cheer - and, perhaps, stoke the ebbing flames of the
toys' popularity - the privately held company said it would
reconsider. Ty's abrupt change of heart makes one wonder whether it
ever intended to discontinue the miniature stuffed toys. (Jeffery
Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CAIRO, Egypt -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- EGYPT-BEER -- Nearly
three years after taking control of Al Ahram Beverages Co., Ahmed
Zayat, 37, an Egyptian entrepreneur, has turned the bedraggled
national beer company into one of the best-performing companies in
Egypt. Zayat says that investors who passed up a chance to buy the
company ``totally misunderstood the opportunity.'' (Joe
Treaster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) DARIEN, Conn. -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- WHITE-CHRISTMAS --
Alan Bothwell, of Snowman Services Inc., watches as his snow-making
machine fills a customer's lawn on Friday. Come Christmas morning,
the customer's grandchildren will awake to a perfect place to test
out the sleds and toboggans they will receive as presents on
Saturday -- a result of latest indulgence of the go-go 90s: a
man-made, made-to-order white Christmas. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PLOIESTI, Romania -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- ROMANIA-ENGINEERS
-- Peter Stephenson, general manager of Raytheon's 300-person
operation here, left, and Marion Nicolescu, the company's
engineering manager, in Stephenson's office in front of
computer-generated drawings of a petrochemical plant. American
companies are taking advantage of one of the legacies of Romania's
dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. Obsessed with training engineers to
build his dream of industrialization, Romania is now top-heavy with
engineers and has twice the number of computer-science graduates
per capita then that of the United States. (Donald G. McNeil
Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
