   (NYT4) BUJUMBURA, Burundi -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- BURUNDI-CAMPS-1 --
A boy stands in front of makeshift huts in a camp called Mukonko
II, on a hillside southeast of Bujumbura where 5,800 people now
live. In the last three months, Burundi's government has herded
350,000 people, mostly poor farmers, from their homes into grubby
new villages atop the hills that encircle Bujumbura. The camps are
supposed to be temporary but a permanence is settling in. (Ian
Fisher/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) KRAJLEVO, Yugoslavia -- Dec. 24, 1999 --
YUGOSLAVIA-FATHER -- Dusan Vukovic at his sons grave. Vukovic has
become a popular figure in Serbia after denouncing the war in
Kosovo, in which his son Aleksandar, died. Offered his son's
posthumous medal, he wanted it sent to Presidennt Slobodan
Milosevic. (Carlotta Gall/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BETHLEHEM, West Bank P Dec. 24, 1999 --
CHRISTMAS-BETHLEHEM-2 -- A Palestinian in Turkish dress leans on
his staff as he waits to lead alterboys and clergymen during a
procession which escorts the Latin Patriarch into the Church of the
Nativity, seen in the background, on Friday, Christmas Eve. The
ancient church was erected over the site traditionally believed to
be the birthplace of Jesus. The Turkish dress tradition dates back
to the time of the Ottoman Empire rule in Palestine. (Rina
Castelnuovo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) BETHLEHEM, West Bank P Dec. 24, 1999 --
CHRISTMAS-BETHLEHEM -- A group of nuns join a Palestinian police
officer on a rooftop overlooking Manger Square to watch a
procession, Friday. In 1995, Israel transferred control of the city
to the Palestinian Authority, run by Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
