<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 12/24/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
800-601-6397. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NY-HOMELESS -- Jill Flesch
spent years on the street, often being arrested or carted off to
psychiatric wards. A supported housing development is now her home.
``It's unspeakable to have my own place,'' she says. (Librado
Romero/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NYC-CHRISTMAS-LIGHTS --
Christmas time in New York offers up brilliant presents for the
eye, including this glittering holiday tribute on Wall Street in
front of the New York Stock Exchange. The spirit such holiday
presentations engender makes you remember, for a minute, why you
put up with the crazy rents. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WINNIPEG, Manitoba -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- CANADA-INDIANS-2
-- Students in an English literacy program at the Winnipeg
Aboriginal Center ponder a writing assignment. Situated in a former
Canadian Pacific railroad station, the center provides job
counselling, employment services and education. Despite boasting
Canada's highest population of urban Indians, jobs are difficult
for the Aboriginal population here to get or to keep. (Kevin
Moloney/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WINNIPEG, Manitoba -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- CANADA-INDIANS-1
-- A construction worker swings a hammer in front of a new
community center for Native Americans in Winnipeg. Despite boasting
Canada's highest population of urban Indians and a healthy economy
that has local employers ready to hire, jobs are difficult for the
Aboriginal population here to get or to keep. (Kevin Moloney/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- OBIT-LAMPORT -- Felicia
Lamport, a poet and satirist who took delight in skewering the high
and mighty with verse, quips, puns and parodies, most of them first
appearing in a column in The Boston Globe called Muse of the Week
in Review, died Thursday at her home in Cambridge, Mass. She was
83. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- BEANIE-BABY-REFERENDUM --
Four months ago, Ty Inc. shocked children and other collectors by
claiming it would kill off its wildly popular Beanie Babies line
come Dec. 31. But Friday, just in time to spread some extra
Christmas cheer - and, perhaps, stoke the ebbing flames of the
toys' popularity - the privately held company said it would
reconsider. Ty's abrupt change of heart makes one wonder whether it
ever intended to discontinue the miniature stuffed toys. (Jeffery
Salter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CAIRO, Egypt -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- EGYPT-BEER -- Nearly
three years after taking control of Al Ahram Beverages Co., Ahmed
Zayat, 37, an Egyptian entrepreneur, has turned the bedraggled
national beer company into one of the best-performing companies in
Egypt. Zayat says that investors who passed up a chance to buy the
company ``totally misunderstood the opportunity.'' (Joe
Treaster/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) DARIEN, Conn. -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- WHITE-CHRISTMAS --
Alan Bothwell, of Snowman Services Inc., watches as his snow-making
machine fills a customer's lawn on Friday. Come Christmas morning,
the customer's grandchildren will awake to a perfect place to test
out the sleds and toboggans they will receive as presents on
Saturday -- a result of latest indulgence of the go-go 90s: a
man-made, made-to-order white Christmas. (Nicole Bengiveno/The New
York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) PLOIESTI, Romania -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- ROMANIA-ENGINEERS
-- Peter Stephenson, general manager of Raytheon's 300-person
operation here, left, and Marion Nicolescu, the company's
engineering manager, in Stephenson's office in front of
computer-generated drawings of a petrochemical plant. American
companies are taking advantage of one of the legacies of Romania's
dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. Obsessed with training engineers to
build his dream of industrialization, Romania is now top-heavy with
engineers and has twice the number of computer-science graduates
per capita then that of the United States. (Donald G. McNeil
Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NY-HOSPITALS-Y2K-2 -- June
Vetter, a patient care technician, left, is helped into a level 2
biohazard suit at the Maimonides Medical Center in Brooklyn earlier
this week. Almost two dozen doctors, nurses and other hospital
staff members here have taken part in a two-day rigorous training
program in protecting themselves and treating victims of a chemical
weapons attack, should they be wheeled into their emergency room on
New Year's Eve. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NY-HOSPITALS-Y2K-1 -- June
Vetter, a patient care technician in a level 2 biohazard suit, sits
in a decontamination shower stall at the Maimonides Medical Center
in Brooklyn earlier this week. Facing the last New Year's eve of
the century, which some security officials have cited as a possible
key evening for terrorism, hospitals like Maimonides are beefing up
their procedures. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- NY-CREW-ASSESS -- Rudy
Crew, the outgoing chancellor of the New York City Board of
Education, walks his dog Chance outside his apartment in Brooklyn
Heights on Friday. Thursday's vote by the board not to renew Crew's
contract ended his sometimes turbulent term as the head of the
nation's largest public school system. The city has had 10
chancellors in the last 30 years, with seven of them ousted or
pressured to resign. (Aaron Lee Fineman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ISTANBUL -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- TURKEY-SULTAN -- A young
Turkish couple look at a portrait of Turkey's most famous sultan,
Mehmet II, by Italian painter Gentile Bellini, on exhibit at the
Yapi Kredi Bank in downtown Istanbul earlier this month. The
painting is on loan from the London Museum and is being exhibited
under very heavy security. (Staton Winter/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- KENEALLY-IRISH -- Thomas
Keneally, most recently the author of the non-fiction work ``The
Great Shame and the Triumph of the Irish in the English-Speaking
World,'' at the American-Irish Historical Society. Keneally says
that writing his latest book ``was an experience akin to being
locked in a cupboard with a Tyrannosaurus rex.'' During a recent
visit to New York, Keneally acknowledged the difficulty of the
project and added, ``It was the longest endeavor I've ever embarked
upon.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- MODERN-MASKS-4 -- ``The
Abstract Mask,'' a 1999 reconstruction of Oskar Schlemmer's 1922
original and ``Darth Vader's Mask'', a 1980's reproduction of the
1977 original. Sometimes what a mask reveals about society is alot
more than what it masks. (the St. Louis Art Museum/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- MODERN-MASKS-3 -- Exhibits
from the St. Louis Art Museum's show ``Masks: Faces of Culture,''
include a 15th-century Austrian jousting helmet, and early
20th-century Congo mask. Sometimes what a mask reveals about
society is alot more than what it masks. (the St. Louis Art
Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- MODERN-MASKS-2 -- Exhibits
from the St. Louis Art Museum's show ``Masks: Faces of Culture,''
include a 1983 German theater mask and a 1930 Eastern Cherokee deer
mask. Sometimes what a mask reveals about society is alot more than
what it masks. (the St. Louis Art Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- MODERN-MASKS-1 -- Exhibits
from the St. Louis Art Museum's show ``Masks: Faces of Culture,''
include, a 19th-century Congo mask and a 1985 baseball catcher's
mask. Sometimes what a mask reveals about society is alot more than
what it masks. (the St. Louis Art Museum/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BUJUMBURA, Burundi -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- BURUNDI-CAMPS-3 --
Children stands in front of under construction in a camp called
Mukonko II, on a hillside southeast of Bujumbura where 5,800 people
now live. In the last three months, Burundi's government has herded
350,000 people, mostly poor farmers, from their homes into grubby
new villages atop the hills that encircle Bujumbura. The camps are
supposed to be temporary but a permanence is settling in. (Ian
Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) BUJUMBURA, Burundi -- Dec. 24, 1999 -- BURUNDI-CAMPS-2 --
Pastor Samuel Ndikumana, 30, left, Sampson Bizimana, a member of
the church's choir, put together timbers for their new church, the
Church of the Holy Spirit, at a camp in the outskirts of the
capital where some 18,000 people live. In the last three months,
Burundi's government has herded 350,000 people, mostly poor
farmers, from their homes into these new villages atop the hills
that encircle Bujumbura. The camps are supposed to be temporary but
a permanence is settling in. (Ian Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
