<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8582 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-HOLIDAY-SHOPPING-ART-     12-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-SHOPPING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS EXPECT STRONG CHRISTMAS SEASON, POSSIBLY A BLOWOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The season started at 4:30 a.m. the day after
Thanksgiving with shoppers lining up outside of Toys ``R'' Us in
Atlanta to buy coveted Pokemon cards _ and it built from there.
Yahoo, the leading Internet portal, recorded more purchases through
its web site in five days this month than during its entire 1998
holiday season. In Manhattan, the Gap ran out of $175 leather pants
so fast that the sight of shoppers breaking into tears of
frustration became common.
</P>
<P>
   The millennium may turn out to be a bust, but by any measure
Christmas 1999 was swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers will not officially report their December sales until
early January, and many of the biggest shopping days are still to
come with post-Christmas sales. But already, retail analysts are
saying the nation's largest stores are on track to see a
year-over-year rise in purchasing well in excess of 6 percent,
making this the strongest Christmas since 1994. Some merchants are
even whispering about a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   The International Council of Shopping Centers, which tracks
actual purchases in small stores in a cross-section of malls, was
showing a 6.6 percent rise in sales through last weekend. And, said
the group's president, John Konarski, ``we might possibly see it go
up to 8 or 9 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Telecheck Services Inc., which tracks check writing at a broad
swath of the nation's retailers, seconded the assessment. ``We are
looking at close to an 8 percent gain for retail sales for the
month of December,'' said William Ford, a Telecheck official. ``It
is an amazing season for the retailers.''
</P>
<P>
   A copious holiday season makes a fitting, if not unexpected,
climax to a year where Americans _ encouraged by a soaring stock
market and rising wages _ have indulged in a sustained shopping
spree. And in keeping with their fattened wallets, shoppers showed
a lust for the finer things in life _ though not necessarily at any
cost. If the holiday had any theme it was luxury at all price
points.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was packaged as gauze-thin v-necks by the discounters
or as a $375 hand-woven Pashmina muffler in wildberry (think deep
pink) at Saks Fifth Avenue, customers could not get enough
cashmere. ``I am getting cashmere for my mother, my sister and my
housekeeper,'' said Catherine Russell, an actress in Manhattan who
started her holiday shopping just last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of jewelry, a category whose performance is tied directly
to the state of the economy, were up 10 percent, according to the
shopping center group's surveys. Zales Inc. reported a tremendous
interest in relatively affordable solo diamond pendants; at Neiman
Marcus, the upscale department store, sales of much more expensive
baubles, like ruby and emerald bracelets, were ``outstanding,''
according to Karen Katz, executive vice president of stores.
</P>
<P>
   While luxury was the watchword, discounters hardly ceded their
role as the 800-pound reindeer of the shopping season. Wal-Mart,
the nation's largest retailer, said it was going to meet
expectations of sales growth of 5 to 7 percent, as consumers
thronged it stores to buy everything from Thunder Punch Buzz, an
action figure from Disney's ``Toy Story 2'' movie, to flat-screen
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Electronics retailers also fared very well as Americans clamored
for the latest digital cameras, DVD players, and personal digital
assistants. According to the shopping centers council, the
electronics category had the single biggest increase in sales, up
14.6 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with recent trends, department stores, as a group,
were not faring as well as the rest of the retailing pack. The week
before Christmas, many resorted to deep price cutting to meet sales
expectations. Dillard's, in the most dramatic example of the
phenomenon, was offering ``after Christmas prices'' of up to 50
percent off many items.
</P>
<P>
   The result may be that while the department stores will post
solid sales numbers, their margins could be thin _ a possibility
that Wall Street is watching carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of retailers are giving it away this season,'' said John
Morris, a retail stock analyst at Gerard Klauer &AMP; Mattison.
</P>
<P>
   There was another casualty in this unusually flush season:
customer service. Data from the Labor Department indicates that
retailers did not substantially increase their staffs for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail employment numbers are down a little on a seasonal
adjusted basis, which is remarkable really,'' said Carl Steidtman,
chief retail economist with Pricewaterhouse Coopers. Steidtman
speculated that a tight labor pool and automated check-out
technologies were partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for their absence, human helpers were sorely
missed. ``This was by far the biggest Christmas for complaining
about sales help,'' said Britt Beemer, chairman of America's
Research Group, which conducts annual holiday surveys among
shoppers. ``Some 33.8 percent of shoppers felt stores were too
short-handed, which was nine points higher than last year, which
was already an all-time high.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet merchants benefited from the public perception that
brick-and mortar stores are a hassle _ and from heavy spending on
advertising. Visa International, which accounts for about half of
the nation's credit card spending, estimated that online purchases
roughly tripled from November and December of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a Christmas of different proportions than last year,''
said Kenneth Seiff, chief executive of Bluefly.com, on online store
featuring cut-rate designer fashions. ``Instead of being a novelty,
people were here to shop.''
</P>
<P>
   Seiff estimated that his company did more business in its two
peak days, Dec. 13-14, than it did in the entire fourth quarter of
last year. Items popular offline were in demand online as well.
``We re-ordered pashmina four times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all its geometric and well-touted growth, Internet sales
still only accounted for about $3 billion, or less than 2 percent,
of what the National Retail Federation estimates was $186 billion
in total holiday retail sales of general merchandise, apparel and
furnishings. That meant plenty of people were sticking loyally to
their local mall, despite the inconvenience of crowded parking lots
and absentee sales associates.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara and Larry Hudgins of Athens, Ga., shopped for their five
children and six grandchildren at Rich's, a regional department
store chain owned by Federated Department Stores. Although Mrs.
Hudgins said she had had trouble finding a sales clerk to help her
in the children's department, her husband, who owns an electrical
contracting company, said he would not consider switching to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right at the present time, I don't trust it,'' he said. ``I
don't trust anybody who wants my credit card and who I can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there were last-minute shoppers who just did not trust
web merchants to deliver on time. John Suh, a lawyer doing last
minute shopping Thursday in Manhattan's Herald Square, said that he
had heard mixed stories about the Internet and just wanted to
``have my gifts in hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Manhattan, the nation's shopping capital, a
holiday-swelled tourist population helped keep stores churning. At
the new Banana Republic store at Rockefeller Center, Monica
Karalis, a concierge fluent in five languages, had her mouth full
flipping back and forth from Spanish to Italian to French as she
helped customers track down items like pony-skin belts.
</P>
<P>
   While apparel with ``Y2K'' and ``Year 2000'' logos racked up
disappointing sales nationwide, merchants in New York said the
market for themed plates and stuffed animals was brisk enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that anything that had `New York' on it and the year
2000 in combination was instantly gone,'' said Joe Denofrio, a
spokesman for Macy's Herald Square. Other hot sellers at the store
included Champagne flutes with 2000 embedded in their stems ($19.99
a pair) and musical snowglobes of Times Square playing ``Auld Lang
Syne'' ($35).
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the non-New York customer buying,'' Denofrio said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
