<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-WHITE-CHRISTMAS-2TAKE     12-24 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-CHRISTMAS-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW COMES HOME FOR CHRISTMAS, AT A PRICE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn. N.H., Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARIEN, Conn. _ The meteorologists may say that there hasn't
been any snow this winter in this quaint, affluent town. But don't
tell that to Henry and Doris Herbert's 11 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Come Christmas morning, they will discover up to 6 feet of snow
blanketing their grandparents' two-acre property here, giving them
the perfect place to test out the sleds and toboggans they will
receive as presents on Saturday. What's more, the six boys and five
girls will discover that they will be the only ones for miles and
miles with a patch of winter in a landscape of green and brown _
offering irrevocable proof, no doubt, that this year, Santa decided
that no one was more special.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Santa, they might want to give thanks to Snowman
Services of Darien for the reminder that in the go-go '90s, you
don't have to dream about a white Christmas, you can just order a
man-made, made-to-order version if you're looking for the ultimate
Christmas-morning indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   For a minimum of $750, Snowman Services can manufacture snow to
be dumped in backyards, front yards, parking lots or country
estates, using a quieter version of the snowmaking equipment used
by ski resorts. And in a booming economy, the prospect of summoning
winter with a simple phone call, take-out style, has been quite the
fashionable gift or gesture this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have got into a bidding war,'' said Jonathan
Sweeney, Snowman's owner, who controlled the Herbert family
snowstorm Friday afternoon. ``One guy from Scarsdale said, `I'll
pay you $5,000 if you do us and blow the other people off
tonight.''' (Sweeney declined the offer, saying that his policy was
``first come first serve.'')
</P>
<P>
   Creating snow, or faux snow, is not new, of course: Ski resorts
do it, on a huge scale. Movie studios in California do it, for
special effects. Even malls in Florida occasionally do it, for
promotional purposes, by chopping up ice to get _ voila! _
something that feels like snow.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of creating snow for purely personal reasons _ so
that one family can have it, while everyone else does not _ has
caught on in only the last year or so. Sweeney, for one, takes
orders for snow-filled birthday parties, corporate events and
Christmas surprises throughout Fairfield County.
</P>
<P>
   In Manchester, N.H., Kendall and Colette Veilleuxbegan a
snow-making business this year, after stumbling upon Sweeney's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   And in Midland, Mich., SMI Snowmakers, one of the country's
leading manufacturers of snow-making equipment for ski resorts,
occasionally accepts orders for private parties, usually from the
rich and famous (an example: Celine Dion), at a cost of $3,000 to
$10,000, said Joe VanderKelen, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   Snowmaking can be a finicky business. The temperature, for one
thing, cannot exceed 30 degrees Fahrenheit. Snowmaking requires a
lot of water, too, about 20,000 to 100,000 gallons per night. And
the customer is usually expected to supply the water, whether from
a swimming pool, a sewer or a pond.
</P>
<P>
   So to get, say, an acre of man-made snow, one-foot deep,
requires about 27,000 gallons of water, or a little less than a
swimming pool, which can be accomplished in six to eight hours,
Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   To do it right, Sweeney said, you would also need to spend about
$75,000 in start-up capital to procure a snow-making machine, which
resembles a wayward jet engine; a generator; a trailer; cables;
hoses, and a pressure booster.
</P>
<P>
   And for the prospective client, of course, there is the cost,
which is just a euphemism for sticker shock: $750 per night, per
machine, in Sweeney's case. But here in Fairfield County, one of
the wealthiest places in the country, cost is usually an
afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney first got the idea in 1995, when one of the clients (a
well-known Wall Street financier) of his full-time landscaping
business, Darien Tree &AMP; Lawn Care, asked if man-made snow would be
possible for a holiday party.
</P>
<P>
   Though that project never came about, Sweeney eventually bought
some equipment and tested it at his own house for a couple of
years, overcoming problems like excessive noise and more technical
matters. Then, in 1997, he tackled his first job: a children's
party for a prominent doctor in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like a huge sperm whale that landed in their
driveway,'' said Sweeney, 36, about that project, which measured 8
feet tall, 25 feet wide and 100 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, people started noticing Sweeney's creations popping up all
over Fairfield County. And this year, Sweeney began advertising on
WKHL, an oldies station in Norwalk, Conn., and on the Internet, at
www.snowmanusa.com or www.darien-lawn-tree.com.
</P>
<P>
   It has grown so frenzied, he said, that he has had to hire extra
people in recent days to work three round-the-clock shifts to match
demand, and turn down numerous requests because of scheduling
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas H. Fingelly Real Estate Inc. was one of the groups that
made the cut. On Thursday afternoon, the company celebrated a very
good year with a blanket of man-made snow surrounding its new
office in Westport, topped by Christmas caroling and the occasional
snowball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people dream of a white Christmas,'' said an ebullient
Victoria Fingelly, a co-owner who was bedecked in a black mink coat
dotted with fake snow. ``We make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone has had the same reaction, naturally, to the sight
of uneven snowfall. A few bah-humbugs say that the practice could
engender neighborhood envy; others say that it's just another
convenience for the well-to-do.
</P>
<P>
   But here, in Darien, Henry and Doris Herbert's five children
decided that they could think of no better gift _ or surprise _ for
the 11 grandchildren, whose ages range from 2 months to 16 years,
than to pull a fast one on Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it has been a few years since there was any snow on
Christmas Day, said Lauren Banerjee, one of four Herbert daughters.
And by splitting the $750 cost, the gift would actually be cheaper
than a trip to, say, Radio City _ plus, the snow will last for
perhaps a month.
</P>
<P>
   There was a close call on Thursday night, however. When Mrs.
Banerjee's 4-year-old nephew, Jack Fisher, talked about the weather
on Friday, he calmly told his mom, Bebe Fisher, ``There will be
snow tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Nervous, Mrs. Fisher asked Jack why. Did he know? Had someone
slipped and let the secret out?
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the boy, who has never experienced a white Christmas
before, simply smiled and said, ``Because it's Christmas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
