<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CANADA-INDIANS-ART-81     12-24 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-INDIANS-ART-816(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE MANITOBA'S LABOR GAP, INDIANS GO JOBLESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT21, 22 are being sent to NYT photo clients. A
map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba _ At first glance, it seems that this city's
business establishment prefers its Indians from New Delhi rather
than from Dakota Tipi, a village 50 miles down the Trans-Canada
Highway.
</P>
<P>
   In Winnipeg, the city with the Canada's largest unemployed
aboriginal population, business leaders have begun a campaign to
triple the number of immigrants lured annually to this heartland
city nearly at the country's geographic center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor is our No. 1 constraint,'' said Bob Silver, owner of
Western Glove Works Ltd. Among the 1,000 people sewing jeans at his
factory here are workers from India, Laos, the Philippines,
Ukraine, Vietnam and Yugoslavia, along with a few aboriginal
Canadians. Unable to find more workers, Silver has set up shops in
China and Mexico, as well as Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   But while business owners complain of a labor shortage,
aboriginal unemployment rates stubbornly hover around 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why go abroad when we have so many resources right here?''
asked Sean Kocsis, a Mohawk who directs the Aboriginal Business
Development Center here. ``We have a pool of individuals right here
that could be tapped but are underutilized.''
</P>
<P>
   Manitoba's employment problem is a Canadian echo of a familiar
paradox in the Great Plains of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Much as the American plains states constitute a low-unemployment
belt, Canada's Prairie Provinces _ Alberta, Manitoba and
Saskatchewan _ have this country's lowest jobless rates, about 5.5
percent compared with a national average of 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Manitoba and Alberta recorded Canada's highest
rates of economic growth last year, around 3.3 percent. Although
still a Canadian granary, Manitoba now exports more manufactured
goods than agricultural products, shipping books, buses, furniture
and airplane parts to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortage of qualified labor in Manitoba has been the fastest
growing issue among our members,'' said Dan Kelly, local vice
president for the Canadian Federation of Independent Business. ``In
Manitoba business owners are getting quite desperate to attract
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But just the way Bismarck, N.D., records virtually no
unemployment while nearby Indian reservations suffer double-digit
jobless rates, there are two different societies in Manitoba, a
province of 1.1 million people scattered over an area larger than
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of 500 aboriginal adults we tested, 200 came out at grade five
level,'' said Marileen McCormick, executive director of the Center
for Aboriginal Human Resource Development, this city's largest job
placement center for indigenous people. In Winnipeg dropout rates
of aboriginal high school students are double those of the rest of
the population. Half of the aboriginal households with children are
headed by single mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The waves of Indians migrating here from distant reservations
often arrive with little conventional work experience, said Ms.
McCormick, who is Metis. Accounting for about 20 percent of
Canada's aboriginal population and concentrated in the Prairie
Provinces, Metis are descendants of plains Indians and European
trappers and traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get people coming from generations of welfare,'' she said.
``When anything happens in the family, in the community, they just
go.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Canada, a largely urbanized country, could largely
ignore the rural reality of Indian Canada, throwing money at an
invisible problem and hoping for gradual improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But now demographics and migration are forcing the issue. Since
1980, Canada's birthrate has dropped by one quarter. Now it is
heading below the replacement level.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, indigenous Canada is enjoying a population
explosion. With birthrates rising, half of Canadian aboriginal
people _ North American Indians, Metis and the Inuit, or Eskimo,
inhabitants of the far north _ are under 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is probably no single more important issue for the
economic future of the Prairies, particularly Manitoba and
Saskatchewan, than the advancement of its aboriginal human
resources,'' concluded a recent study by the Caledon Institute of
Social Policy, a private research center based in Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   The demographic shift is striking in Winnipeg, a virtual
city-state, which encloses 60 percent of Manitoba's population
within its beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Within 15 years aboriginal people are expected to account for as
much as a quarter of the working-age population. At the same time,
retirement looms for waves of plumbers, welders, electricians and
carpenters _ skilled tradesmen whose average age here is 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is education,'' said James Carr, president of the
Business Council of Manitoba, a private group that seeks to draw
aboriginal workers into Manitoba's economic mainstream. ``The
number of aboriginals entering and completing high school is
doubling, tripling, quadrupling _ the same for our community
colleges.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a mentoring program, 10 Business Council member companies
have established close relationship with aboriginal companies, a
program that Carr plans to expand soon to all 50 member companies.
In addition the council is promoting aboriginal hiring policies and
spotlighting aboriginal ``role models,'' or success stories.
</P>
<P>
   As these and other efforts start to take effect, the face of
Winnipeg, a white-bread city that once fancied itself as ``the
Chicago of the North,'' is gradually changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started here, in 1982, aboriginal people didn't work in
banks, in stores,'' Ms. McCormick recalled. ``You could count the
number of aboriginal apprentices on the fingers of one hand. Now we
are placing 1,200 people a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting growing consumer clout, advertisements in Manitoba's
two new aboriginal monthly newspapers, Grassroots News and The
Drum, included the following phrases recently: ``aboriginal-owned
and -operated,'' ``Ray Scaife, your First Nations automobile sales
consultant'' and Richard Harris, ``your aboriginal tire expert.''
</P>
<P>
   Winnipeg's mayor, Glen Murray, is pushing to expand the number
of aboriginal officers on the city police force.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of aboriginals' growing political clout here, Ms.
McCormick's employment center and a host of other native groups now
occupy a grand building downtown that once was the passenger
terminal for the Canadian Pacific Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   The center is the keystone for a multimillion-dollar aboriginal
development that is to include a park, a sweat lodge, a roundhouse,
a market, an art gallery, a youth center and the headquarters of
the provincial Metis federation.
</P>
<P>
   With such activity going on, some aboriginal leaders do not see
a threat in the business community's goal of bringing in 8,000
immigrants a year. Although the basement of the old railroad
terminal still contains quarantine holding cells for just-arrived
immigrants, no one at the Indian Center upstairs talks of putting
them back into use.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Canada we are such a massive country with such a small
population,'' said Mary Richard, a Metis, who directs the
aboriginal urban renewal program from the old rail terminal. ``I
don't see immigration as interfering with what our community is
working on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
