<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS MANDATE: TRADE NOW. SIGN NOW. WIN NOW.  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Phillips was not at his office Friday; at least
he didn't answer the telephone there. His wife, Marni, said he was
not at his office. But when she answered the telephone at their
home in Connecticut, he was not there either.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' general manager was not supposed to be working _ the
Mets' offices, like those of other teams and Major League Baseball
itself, are closed until Jan. 3 _ but maybe if he made just one
more call at the right time Friday, he could have found another
general manager in the mood to make a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips loves to make trades. As long as they improve his team,
of course. He has been making trades to improve his team for 19
months now, since the Mets acquired Mike Piazza in May 1998. He has
had an impressive run.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has a mandate, not to mention a difficult task. It is
his job to pull the Mets up to the level of the other team in town.
The other team has won the last two World Series and three of the
last four. That is some task.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what the flurry of activity was all about last
winter, and it is the reason for this winter's activity. The Mets
had conceded the city to the Yankees long enough, and the Mets'
owners did not like their position. Whether they could ever out
slug George Steinbrenner in a checkbook battle for New York's heart
and soul is debatable, but they at least wanted to be in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Winning is expensive. In his 27 years as the principal owner of
the Yankees, Steinbrenner has spent more money than any other
owner. Sometimes he has spent it wisely and productively; other
times he has squandered it on players who were the baseball version
of fool's gold. With the Yankees' revenue sources, however,
Steinbrenner could afford to make mistakes, then spend to try to
correct them.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wilpon and Nelson Doubleday have not always been willing to
spend on Steinbrenner's level. But in an era in which teams
apparently have to be among the biggest spenders to have a chance
to reach the playoffs every season, they know they have to raise
their ante.
</P>
<P>
   With the acquisition of Mike Hampton and Derek Bell, the Mets
have raised their payroll to $75 million for the 17 players they
have signed. That amount already exceeds their 1999 payroll of
$71.3 million for 33 players, including 8 on the disabled list when
payrolls were computed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have 13 players signed for next season. Those
players have a total salary of $52 million. Only a few weeks ago,
after the Yankees signed David Cone for $12 million, speculation
spread that the Yankees were heading for the first $100 million
payroll in baseball history. They will fall well short, even after
Derek Jeter and Mariano Rivera collect whatever they want in salary
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees trimmed more than $6 million from their payroll by
trading Hideki Irabu and Chad Curtis. Who would have thought
Steinbrenner would be in the business of downsizing a payroll?
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets' continues to rise. Phillips has said there is a
magic number beyond which he is not supposed to go, only he will
not say what it is. Competitive reasons, he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, Wilpon and Doubleday have said, ``You just keep
making the team better; we'll tell you if or when you have to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   All general managers would like to have that kind of guideline.
Not all general managers, though, could execute all of the moves
that Phillips has pulled off in the last year or so. Last winter he
added Robin Ventura, Armando Benitez, Rickey Henderson and Roger
Cedeno, retaining Piazza and Al Leiter at the same time. All right,
so he added Bobby Bonilla, too. No general manager is perfect.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31 he brought in Darryl Hamilton, who fit quite well in
the Mets' scheme of things. Billy Taylor and Chuck McElroy came
too? See previous paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   This off-season Phillips failed to retain John Olerud, but he
snatched a solid run producer, Todd Zeile, out of the Texas
Rangers' grasp as a substitute. Now he has acquired Hampton, a No.
1 starting pitcher most teams would like to have, maybe even the
Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton does not bring with him a guarantee that he will reprise
his 22-4 performance of last season with Houston, but even if that
should turn out to be his career year, Hampton is at the stage of
his career where he can be a credible No. 1 starter.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets' No. 1 starter, he can make an impact on the rest of
the rotation. Relieved of the pressure of being No. 1, Al Leiter,
who does not have the stature of Pedro Martinez, could benefit,
becoming more effective and contributing more victories. The
addition of Hampton could have a similar domino effect throughout
the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Some people would not have traded Octavio Dotel, even for
Hampton. Dotel certainly has a future of great promise, but
Hampton, at 27, is only three-years older than the ``youngster''
and has already been a major league starter for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Can the Mets lose on this trade? Yes, if they don't make the
playoffs next year and they don't retain Hampton beyond next
season. If they should win the World Series and Hampton still
leaves as a free agent, no problem. He undoubtedly would have
served his purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Teams at the level at which the Mets want to remain do not deal
in futures. They trade and sign free agents to win now. Phillips,
even if he takes a few days off in the next week, has learned that
role and practiced it well. The Hampton trade should be no
different. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
