</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TIMELY GIFT IS BESTOWED ON NEW YORK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Fla.)  By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No one should come to New York to live unless he is willing to
be lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   _E.B. White &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two months after the loss to Atlanta in a
spine-tingling playoff series, Mets fans have gained a star
pitcher. Mike Hampton, one of the three best pitchers in baseball
in 1999, is a Met. The Mets acquired the 22-game winner from the
Houston Astros on Thursday along with outfielder Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   To get Hampton, the Mets gave up rich young blood: outfielder
Roger Cedeno, the rookie right-hander Octavio Dotel and the minor
league left-hander Kyle Kessel. Within the last two weeks, the Mets
also acquired the free agent Todd Zeile to replace John Olerud at
first base.
</P>
<P>
   The clock is now ticking. Can Hampton pitch the Mets to a World
Series? Can the Mets entice Hampton, who is from Brooksville, Fla.,
to stay in New York?
</P>
<P>
   For Zeile, New York was the attraction. ``I always felt Texas
was the safe choice,'' he said. ``In my heart, I kept coming back
to New York.''
</P>
<P>
   E.B. White, in his classic 1948 essay ``Here is New York,''
describes three New Yorks: The city of those who were born here;
the city of the daily commuter and finally the city of those who
were born somewhere else and came to New York seeking fame and
fortune. Since then, a fourth New York has emerged: the New York ofthe mercenary free agent ballplayer who gambles on playing in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   The free agent athletes gamble that they will perform
successfully onstage, convincingly manipulate the news media and
catapult their careers, stature and pocketbooks before being
consumed. The championship series with Atlanta last October gave
clear and hopeful signs that the Mets are one behind-kicking
superstar from the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Mistakenly, I thought the missing player was Seattle's Ken
Griffey Jr. Who wouldn't welcome the challenge of coming to New
York, leading the Mets to the long-awaited Promised Land? Well,
Junior, for one.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out that New York is too dense for Griffey; he wants more
elbow room, not less. He is also too secure with his place in
baseball history to volunteer for a rat race that he cannot win. He
does not need the aggravation of journalists who often take
themselves too seriously and frequently put themselves above the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third base coach and their
longtime second baseman, who was born in New York, has seen careers
flourish and go to ashes in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have total belief in your ability to play, if you
can't face the media and handle the media, you can't survive,'' he
said. ``You have to stay focused on winning, not just your own
stats. That's hard, because if you're a big free agent, more than
likely you've signed a big contract and you feel that you have to
meet expectations. If you let that get in the way, you're in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens took an entire season to settle into a New York
Yankee state of mind, to realize that the Yankees were great before
he arrived, that he did not have to pitch a no-hitter every time
out for the team to win. All he had to do was play a role.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph also said that in two seasons, the wear and tear of New
York pressure has shown on Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piazza is a great player,'' Randolph said, ``but it looks like
he feels the pressure of being `the man.' He doesn't look like he's
enjoying himself maybe the way he should.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Piazza recruited Zeile, volunteered to call
Griffey and is so pleased to see Hampton. Hampton, at least, is in
the driver's seat. I'm a little more concerned about Zeile, the
former Ranger who chose the challenge of New York over the comfort
of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   While Hampton provides a missing presence, Zeile is replacing a
very popular player. Does the West Coast Zeile have the mettle to
contend with slumps when they come, to live with the fact that he
is not John Olerud?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're different players,'' Zeile said. ``He's a great first
baseman, but I'm not coming here to be John Olerud. I'm my own
player.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be a pressurized season of high expectations. Steve
Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said the acquisition of
Hampton ``catapults us beyond the team that won 97 games last
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The substitutions of Bell and Zeile for Cedeno and Olerud
represent an increase in strikeouts from 166 to 223 and a decrease
of 50 stolen bases. More home runs, less speed, lower on-base
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Mets get a great pitcher in Hampton and a hopeful
first baseman in Zeile. At least for now, there is happiness on the
Mets' side of New York. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
