<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8599 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-DAVIS-TEX     12-24 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-DAVIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGHORNS LINEMAN GIVES NEW MEANING TO GARGANTUAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ As the youngest sibling in a large family, the
Christmas holidays provided some magical moments for Leonard Davis
during his formative years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until third or fourth grade, all of my brothers and sisters
were still buying toys for me,'' Davis said. ``I'd clean up every
year.''
</P>
<P>
   With 21 siblings stuffing packages beneath the Christmas tree,
tales of Davis' holiday hauls became legendary to envious youths in
Wortham, a farming community roughly 90 miles southeast of Fort
Worth. Like stories about Davis himself, they border on the
Bunyanesque but can be verified by those who have watched the
6-foot-6, 360-pounder develop into the player Texas coach Mack
Brown calls ``our most dominant offensive lineman.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a junior left tackle, figures to be the only player
suited up in the Jan. 1 Cotton Bowl game vs. Arkansas who:
</P>
<P>
   Grew up sharing a bunk bed with a nephew five years older than
he.
</P>
<P>
   Learned to drive a tractor as a 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Served as a 300-pound water boy in the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   Forced a submission from teammate Casey Hampton, a fellow
300-pounder, in an all-you-can-eat challenge involving platters of
chicken wings in the campus dining hall.
</P>
<P>
   Learned the art of patience during holiday meals with 50
relatives in a house with one kitchen and one bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, there is little understated about the Longhorn who
answers to the nickname ``Big.''
</P>
<P>
   No second word necessary. Just ``Big.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been Davis' handle since the fifth grade, when he topped
6 feet and 200 pounds. It took on additional meaning in the seventh
grade, when Wortham High School's 6-4, 300-pound water boy towered
over every player on the varsity roster.
</P>
<P>
   It fits nicely in describing Davis family gatherings, like the
one scheduled to unfold this weekend at the home of Leonard's
parents, L.A. and Sammie Davis. The couple married in 1977, after
each went through the death of a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. entered the marriage with nine sons and two daughters.
Sammie had six daughters and four sons. A year later, Leonard
became the only child produced from the marriage of Sammie and L.A.
Davis. He was 10 years younger than his next-closest sibling, 27
years younger than his brother, Charlie, a standout defensive
tackle at TCU (1971-73) who played 10 seasons of professional
football in the NFL and USFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always telling him, `I've got rings older than you,'''
Charlie Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   But none would fit on Leonard's fingers.
</P>
<P>
   In a family of large men _ L.A. (6-1, 195) is small by Davis
standards _ Leonard clearly stands out. Lamonte Chambers, the
nephew who shared a bedroom with Leonard when both were growing up
in Wortham, recalled the day he learned that lesson. Chambers, 26,
played running back at Tarleton State and is five years older than
Leonard Davis, 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I picked on him a lot when we were kids, but he got too big,''
said Chambers, a junior high football coach in Mineral Wells. ``It
was my freshman year in college, and I was home for the weekend. I
jumped on his back to knock him down, like I'd always done, but he
continued to walk around the room. He just laughed at me and kept
walking.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Davis was 14. He still laughs a lot, especially
when asked how he keeps track of important dates in family history.
</P>
<P>
   Because of all the older siblings, Davis said he has so many
nieces and nephews that he ``can't even count them.''
</P>
<P>
   How does he track all the birthdays?
</P>
<P>
   ``I depend on Mom and Dad,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Dad is 76. Mom is 63. Together, they will be hosts to a
Christmas gathering this weekend for more than 30 family members
(down from previous years), including Leonard. All who attend
consider it an annual highlight. But there will be logistical
challenges in the three-bedroom house, Chambers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cars are parked all over the place, and the bathroom doesn't
get any rest,'' Chambers said. ``People are always coming up and
asking, `Which child are you?' We should wear name tags.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Davis likened the buffet-style family feast to a major
sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to do something, there's always a line,'' Charlie
Davis said. ``Everywhere you turn, there's a crowd. I couldn't
imagine getting ready for school if we'd all been in the same house
at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither could his youngest brother. Fortunately, that was never
an issue. When Leonard Davis was born, he was one of eight children
living in the house. By the time he was old enough to attend
school, it had thinned out to four. By the time he was 9, Davis and
Chambers _ the only remaining school-age children _ were assigned
their own bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture, Leonard Davis had yet to distinguish himself
as a football player. But he turned some heads by plowing fields as
a 3-year-old while his father tended to the cows on the family
farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could go a couple of hours at a time by himself, driving a
tractor, at 3 years old,'' said Chambers, who watched from atop
another tractor in an adjacent field. ``My grandfather always kept
an eye on him, but Leonard literally plowed the fields. He was
always well-advanced for his age. His size and his mind grew pretty
well at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his size and skill have earned Davis a spot on the All-B]
ig 12 team. As the Longhorns' left tackle, he protects the blind
side of quarterback Major Applewhite. Offensive coordinator Greg
Davis pinpointed the junior's return to the lineup after missing
four games with a sprained ankle as the start of major strides in
an offense that averaged 410.1 yards and 34.2 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard has come 100 miles this year,'' Greg Davis said.
``He's not the finished product. But he's got great feet and upper
body strength. The sky's the limit on what he could do. If you went
to draw the prototype offensive tackle, you'd draw Leonard Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   Without question, Leonard Davis has the physical tools. He bench
presses more than 500 pounds. He wears a size 56-long sportscoat.
His pants require a 48-inch waist with a 34-inch inseam. Coaches
praise his work ethic, which he attributes to Chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been more of a mentor to me than anybody else,'' Davis
said. ``He taught me a lot about the mental aspects of the game,
about being tough and being a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't teach him anything about being ``Big.''
</P>
<P>
   For Leonard Davis, that comes naturally. Both on and off the
field.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
