<SLUG> BC-BKC-COACHES-HOLIDAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COACHES MAKE HOLIDAYS HOMEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For as many Christmases past as Kellen Sampson can remember, he
has been jostled, wrestled about and had to contend with bigger
kids to play with his own toys.
</P>
<P>
   And he has loved every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad's players coming over to our house on Christmas has
become a tradition,'' the 14-year-old son of Oklahoma basketball
coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``It's special. Especially \Rwith\S the
players who can't go home. It's been fun because they're all kids
in a way. They've become a part of our Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas is a time for sharing, and many college basketball
coaches choose to share time with their players during what can be
a difficult time for young athletes spending the holidays away from
home. Some coaches invite their team over on Christmas Day or have
a party or take time to have a special dinner if the team is on a
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Some mark the holidays with special observances, doing for
others.
</P>
<P>
   At Kansas, each of Roy Williams' players shop for gifts with
donated funds for a designated family and arrange a time to
personally deliver them. The Oklahoma women's team recently took
the ``Little Sooners'' to see ``Toy Story 2'', and will participate
in the local Meals on Wheels program on Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And today, as usual, will be open house at the Sampsons' home in
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Sampson hasn't planned a sit-down dinner for the
half-dozen or so players who won't be able to be with their
families on this family day. But there will be plenty of food set
out in the kitchen throughout the afternoon. And perhaps a few
extra pillows scattered about for those guests who customarily fall
asleep on the floor in front of the television, stomachs full, with
thoughts of loved ones separated. And of those around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going over to coach Sampson's house for Christmas is a
beautiful thing,'' former Sooners guard Eric Martin said. ``He has
a beautiful family, and he and his wife treat us like sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so important for players who can't go home for Christmas
to have somewhere to go. Spending Christmas \Rwith the Sampsons\S
is something I'll always remember. I'm going to miss it this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is playing basketball in Argentina, planned to be
home with his immediate family in Kentucky today. But he can
remember the loneliness of the holidays separated from family.
</P>
<P>
   So can Karen and Kelvin.
</P>
<P>
   Karen remembers waking up on Christmas Day, 1980, in a drafty
apartment in Butte, Mont. Kelvin was a young assistant _ soon to be
a head coach _ at Montana Tech. The young married couple was living
in and managing a wooden apartment building leased to the school by
Anaconda Mining Co. for $1 a year, and worth every penny.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the second year we were married and we just couldn't go
home \Rto North Carolina\S,'' Karen said. ``The apartments were
just awful. The winds of Montana left sheets of ice on the windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember just wanting \RChristmas Day\S to be over with. You
should see the pictures of us on that day. We look pitiful. And
after that, we decided no more Christmases alone. Our house was
going to be open for our players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an 18-year-old daughter \RLauren\S who's never had a
Christmas when there weren't players around, and she's loved it.
One of our greatest joys has been seeing the players come and play
with our kids when they were little. I think that kind of thing was
special to those who had little brothers and sisters they couldn't
be with.''
</P>
<P>
   Other memories are of players helping put together Ninja Turtle
sewers, Barbie's kitchen and other toys that require assembly that
often baffle grownups. Then there was the time at Washington State
(1987-94) when several players dropped by Christmas Eve and Karen
passed out potato peelers and formed a work party to help prepare
the next day's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a player named Benny Seltzer,'' Karen said. ``He
could really make those peelings fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Sampsons will make sure that each player calls his
family, wherever they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas is a time for celebration of the birth of Christ,''
Sampson said. ``But it's also a time to be with family, to share
memories and warmth. The experience we're going through makes you
realize how important coaches are in the lives of their kids and
how you have to try to make them feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all team gatherings are in Hallmark Card settings. The
Baylor women's team recently had their Christmas party at a
restaurant on a pier overlooking the Pacific Ocean in Santa Monica,
Calif. Because of the team's schedule, coach Sonja Hogg didn't have
the traditional team party at her house before sending the players
home for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you can have your team together for the holidays, it
doesn't matter where you are,'' Hogg said. ``It's always a special
time that you always remember.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
