<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CREW-ASSESS-ART-70     12-24 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-ASSESS-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CREW'S VISION FOR NEW YORK SCHOOLS REMAINS UNREALIZED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-CREW-SEARCH) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT13 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(kd) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the day Rudy Crew arrived in New York City to
take over its troubled yet ever hopeful school system, he was
nothing if not bold. He called on New Yorkers to join him in a
revolution that he likened to the civil rights movement, declaring:
``This is not a faint-hearted exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Driven by the conviction that all children can learn and that
the adults responsible for them should be held accountable, Crew
galvanized a potent coalition of business, education and
legislative leaders to carry out big reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his boldness and ability to effect structural change _ not
his ultimate accomplishments _ may turn out to be his legacy, after
he was ousted Thursday in a bitter battle with Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani. Crew pushed through some sweeping changes in the
organization of the school system, from gutting corrupt and
incompetent community school boards to ending lifetime job
guarantees for principals. But former education officials, union
leaders and education advocates said he never got to the point
where he could work those changes through a huge bureaucracy and
make a difference where it mattered most, to teachers and children
behind closed doors in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``He set the table,'' said Raymond Domanico, education adviser
to the Metro Industrial Areas Foundation, a coalition of civic and
church groups. ``But his team was not strong enough to reach deep
into the school system and make day-to-day changes in the
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   As Crew, the former small-town superintendent from Tacoma,
Wash., bids farewell to four turbulent years in New York, his story
is a paradigm of how difficult it is to make a difference in any
urban school system, let alone New York, with its 1.1 million
children, 1,100 schools, 75,000 teachers and treacherous
intermingling of politics and education. Just surviving four years
was an accomplishment, in a country where the average life span of
an urban superintendent is two and a half years, and a city where
some chancellors have lasted no longer than two.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after settling into his city-owned brownstone, Crew became
caught up in the complexities of moving an unwieldy institutional
bureaucracy, where the attitude of special interests, from unions
to community groups to civil servants, is that chancellors come and
go, but the system remains. Some say he lost his way.
</P>
<P>
   Crew himself struck a philosophical note Friday, as he subtly
sought to take the initiative in defining his legacy. ``History
will have to speak to that,'' he said. ``I had a great time
bringing back the arts and bringing technology into the classroom.
I feel with standardized tests, warts and all, children are leaving
at a higher level, sufficient to walk into the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, Crew's close alliance with Giuliani, who had
driven out a previous chancellor, gave him the political peace he
needed to move his broad agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he was brought to a halt by the political system, as
he and Giuliani sparred over core issues, like Crew's refusal to
spend tax money to send children to private school. Over the last
six months, as his alliance with Giuliani came apart, he squandered
much of his passion and energy on political rhetoric and power
struggles, losing the connection to parents, children and educators
that he needed to survive and make a difference, education
advocates and union leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a long time, the relationship between Rudy Giuliani and
Rudy Crew was such that you didn't know whose idea was whose,''
Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of Teachers,
said Friday. ``His legacy is in some ways the mayor's legacy on
education.''
</P>
<P>
   As his own Board of Education turned against Dr. Crew on
Thursday, refusing to extend his contract by a 4-3 vote, the
protests came mainly from Giuliani's political rivals, like Mark
Green, the city's public advocate, who hopes to succeed the mayor
if he is elected to the U.S. Senate. But there was little outcry
from ordinary people in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``People believed he had the interests of kids at heart,''
Domanico said. ``But I don't think people really knew him. So when
he lost his primary patron, he was kind of cut loose.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carol Gresser, the former president of the Board of Education,
who brought Crew to New York and then had a falling out with him,
said the chancellor was ``terrific in Albany,'' as a lobbyist, but
less visible in the schools. ``It seemed to me that he visited
schools when a photo op was needed,'' Ms. Gresser said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of his own legacy, Crew released a statement after his
ouster saying that he had turned schools in New York into a model
for the nation. He cited his emphasis on literacy and his push for
higher standards. He trumpeted the passage of sweeping state
legislation that gave him more power over the city's 32 community
school boards, recentralizing the system after nearly three decades
of community control. He talked about how he had taken over failing
schools and sent thousands of failing children to summer school,
ending the practice of automatic promotion.
</P>
<P>
   But other educators argued that Crew's accomplishments, while
substantial, were a testament to his political skills, and that his
educational legacy remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   While reading and math scores rose in some years, over the
cumulative four years, they remained relatively stable. On almost
every other statistical measure, including spending per pupil, high
school graduation rates and the percentage of students passing
tough new Regents tests required for high school graduation, New
York City still lags behind the state average.
</P>
<P>
   In the last weeks of his administration, Crew became the target
of the kind of problems he had attacked in the community school
boards, whose powers he successfully cut back. He was unable to
change the public perception of a corrupt school system, symbolized
in the release of two investigations just weeks before his contract
came up for renewal. One found that teachers had cheated on
standardized tests, and the other that high schools had inflated
attendance to gain more state aid. The reports were poorly
documented, and Crew's allies argued that they were politically
motivated; still, the chancellor did not prove strong enough to
weather them without damage to his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crew took over more than 40 failing schools and ousted
five superintendents, he never convincingly showed that he could do
better than the local officials he had replaced. While scores in
some of the schools improved, in others they did not.
</P>
<P>
   Even Crew's closest allies said sadly Friday that he had never
had the chance _ or perhaps the ability _ to translate his vision
into systemic results. His downfall, one educator said, was that
``he believed too much in the belief theory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
