<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8604 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BOULDER-HOMELESS-ART-     12-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOULDER-HOMELESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOWN LENDS A HAND WITHOUT SEEKING ONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Many Boulder residents remember the place as
the Lucky 7 Motel, a seedy joint on the western edge of town where
hot tubs in each room drew guests in but kept them for only an hour
or so in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As business fell off, the Lucky 7 drained its hot tubs for good
in the late 1980s, but the place did not remain dormant for long.
Using a federal grant, city officials bought it, removed the tubs,
knocked down a few walls and opened the Boulder Shelter for the
Homeless in 1987, with enough space for 68 people.
</P>
<P>
   But even in an upscale, bohemian community like Boulder, where
more than a quarter of the 95,000 residents have advanced degrees
and most voters are that endangered Colorado species, the liberal
Democrat, that was hardly enough. With strict growth limits fueling
a sharp rise in housing prices over the last decade, the number of
homeless people here has been soaring. By recent estimates, as many
as 1,000 people in Boulder County, which has a population of
300,000, need shelter on any given night, twice the number on the
streets just five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, city officials have scrambled to find beds. In
1991, the First Church of the Nazarene made space for about 30
people. But as the congregation grew, creating a demand for more
programs, church officials decided this year to end its outreach to
the homeless, forcing Boulder officials to look elsewhere for
space.
</P>
<P>
   This time they looked inward.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rely solely on federal and state grants and private
donations to support human services programs, the City Council on
Tuesday voted unanimously to donate space from a municipal building
to accommodate some of the overflow from the old Lucky 7.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next month, the large meeting room in the converted
church that has been headquarters of the Boulder Department of
Parks and Recreation since 1991 will become a sleeping place for as
many as 49 homeless people a night, from October through April.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with homeless advocacy groups say they know of nothing
like this anywhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's unique,'' said Mary Ann Gibson, executive
director of the National Coalition for the Homeless, a nonprofit
group based in Washington, ``but this is very unusual and
admirable. Most cities don't do anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Foscarinis, executive director of the National Law Center
on Homelessness and Poverty, another nonprofit group, said cities
typically used federal and state dollars _ as well as buildings
owned by the federal and state governments _ for homeless programs,
although some cities have pitched in with municipal assets, even if
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, where 21,000 people use the shelter system on any
given night, a homeless registration center served as a makeshift
shelter for four years _ but not through any altruism by city
officials. Shelters had grown so crowded that people with nowhere
else to sleep made use of desks and chairs. A judge put an end to
the situation in early January, forcing the city to find more
suitable arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Boulder, city officials encountered little resistance to
addressing the needs of the homeless. Susan Purdy, director of the
Department of Human Services, said meetings with neighbors and with
office workers in the parks building to apprise them of plans for
the meeting room produced expressions of concern but no objections.
</P>
<P>
   When the question of using the building came before the City
Council, all nine members _ seven Democrats and two Republicans _
voted to allocate $27,000 from this year's budget for the project,
most of it to allow the parks department to seal off its offices at
the end of the workday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boulder has a long tradition of protecting the environment and
human services,'' said Will Toor, a councilman. ``We had a need for
a facility, and the building owned by Parks and Recreation needed
only some minor modifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boulder initiative comes as the streets are growing ever
more dangerous for homeless people around the country, with no more
gruesome example than Denver, 30 miles to the southeast. In recent
months, the police have found seven homeless men dead, two of them
decapitated.
</P>
<P>
   Robert G. Mann, executive director of the shelter at the old
motel, said Boulder had suffered its share of tragedies, as well.
By his count, 25 homeless people have died in the last five years.
Three drowned, one was choked, one was hit by a car, one committed
suicide and the rest died as a result of alcoholism and
hypothermia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are compassionate,'' said Chris Dropinski, the
director of Parks and Recreation. ``We see what's happened in
Denver, but a lot of people here don't understand the magnitude of
the homeless population in Boulder. It's bad. Now, they are gaining
an awareness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
