<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOLIDAY-WORKERS-NYT &LR;      12-24 1359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-WORKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YEAR'S EVE WILL BE A BUSINESS-AS-USUAL DAY FOR MANY WORKERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ill., Mass.)   By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ George Fernandes was planning to throw a big party on
New Year's Eve. But then he learned many of his guests could not
come. They had to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple work for utilities,'' he said. ``Some are involved
with computer systems. Some work in hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   The more he thought about it, Fernandes, an electrician foreman
for the city of Cambridge, Mass., decided he should probably be
working too. ``So we canceled,'' he said. ``We're going to have it
the following Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   For many American workers, the dawning of a new millennium is
simply going to mean another day, or night, at the office, as
employers gird for any problems that arise from Year 2000 computer
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Computer systems workers will be at the front lines, making
certain that programs cope with the changeover to 2000. But they
are not the only ones who are going to be on the job.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 832 companies found that some 3.2 million extra
employees would be showing up for work on New Year's Eve, said
Howard Rubin, the head of the computer science department at Hunter
College, who conducted the study for the corporate consulting firm,
Cap Gemini America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be like a Wednesday on New Year's Eve,'' Rubin
said. ``Companies are preparing to deal with any business problems
in a business-as-usual manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides gazing at computer screens, workers will be answering
telephone calls from customers, checking automated teller machines,
inspecting elevators and reading gas and water meters. Someone has
to cook, clean and park cars for all the moonlighting employees.
Police and fire departments in most cities have dispatched extra
workers.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, 37,000 police officers will be on duty Dec. 31 into
New Year's Day. Detectives and others who usually wear plain
clothes will be in uniforms instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody expects any problems,'' said Pat Camden, a spokesman
for the Chicago police department. ``But everybody's feels they've
got to be prepared for a worst-case scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   On most holidays, it's the people at the lower rungs of
companies who tend to draw work duty, but on this New Year's Eve,
the corporate brass is punching the clock.
</P>
<P>
   Some 500,000 upper-management executives are planning to be
working as the millennium dawns, according to Rubin's study. If
anything goes awry, companies will need top decision makers to call
the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Even many chief executives will work, said Steve Vitoff, a
spokesman for Cap Gemini. ``It's as if the top guys are saying, `I
better go down there and do this myself,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lights will be burning late on Wall Street. The big securities
companies have called in thousands of workers to monitor the
computers and answer questions from customers.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell Shivers, a managing director in investment banking for
Merrill Lynch, will greet the new millennium in his office at the
World Trade Center. Hopeful that he will not have any catastrophes
to quell, Shivers plans to bring some of his favorite movies to the
office, including ``Ferris Bueller's Day Off.''
</P>
<P>
   The securities industry has also organized a command post on
Water Street, where reports on the status of Year 2000 problems
will be sent to financial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Draper, the spokeswoman for the Securities Industry
Association, said it was vital to keep communication open, so that
``rumors will be squashed before they get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Schwab, the discount broker in San Francisco, will
dispatch more than 1,000 extra workers on New Year's Eve, largely
for customer support. Branches will be open on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Harris has been the Year 2000 coordinator for the Wachovia
Bank since 1995, and now eagerly awaits the fruits of her labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``After four years, I really want to be there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies will follow the sun, closely monitoring places
like New Zealand, which sees midnight 16 hours before New York, and
then seeing what happens as the New Year dawns closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's no disaster by the time things wrap around to
western Europe,'' said Rubin, ``some companies may stand down and
send some workers home.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some companies, the alert could mean extra work for
several days after the New Year. Julie Davis, a spokeswoman for
Bank of America in Atlanta, will be traveling to the company's Year
2000 headquarters in North Carolina for the weekend. To be safe,
she has packed enough clothes for a week's stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is the great unknown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging the sacrifice of families on the big night, some
companies have planned a party atmosphere at work and invited
spouses and children to come along.
</P>
<P>
   At its control center in Columbus, Ohio, Bank One will provide
movies for children, popcorn, sandwiches and soda. There will be no
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be kind of coherent,'' said Mike Baldwin, a manager
in the bank's phone division, who will be joined at work by his
wife, Brenda. ``That's all we'd need, if things go wrong, to be
about half crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Althoff, who works for Techsource, a building consultant in
Chicago, said he was delaying telling his wife about working on New
Year's Eve. ``There's no reason to get into an argument ahead of
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the workers expressed confidence that Year 2000
problems pose little threat. But they expect anxious customers to
keep them busy.
</P>
<P>
   Steve George, a manager at GTE Internetworking in Burlington,
Mass., said people were preparing for ``the curiosity factor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients will be wondering, `Is my Web site up? Do I still
have Internet access?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some ordinary problems on New Year's Eve will almost certainly
spark fears of extraordinary trouble. At any given time, about 2
percent of the nation's automated teller machines are out of cash
or paper for receipts, industry experts say. But if that happens to
someone at 12:01 a.m., said Ms. Harris of Wachovia, ``people will
say it's Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   Althoff, who works with engineers who check the office
mechanical systems such as water and heating, said some people will
find trouble simply by looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be testing power generators that they
haven't tested in who knows how long,'' he said, ``and some of them
are going to have problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For people who had entertained fanciful notions about
celebrating the millennium, the notion of sitting at a desk on New
Year's Eve does not exactly seem thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Richey, who answers customer service calls for the Public
Service utility in Colorado, said his family had been dreaming for
five years about how to ring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sort of drew the short straw,'' said Richey. ``Instead of
being at Disneyland or a tropical island, we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many workers said they expected, and hoped, to be doing little
more than passing time on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes said he would be sitting with his two-way radio at the
Cambridge Electric Light Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be bored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cushman, who manages an office building in Century City,
Calif., said he usually goes to work in a business suit and tie.
But as he trudges off to his office on this New Year's Eve, he will
be wearing jeans, tennis shoes and a T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to be prepared to throw in myself and do some manual
labor, just in case,'' Cushman said. To be on the safe side, he
said, his building will shut down the elevators at 11:50 p.m. and
keep them idle until 10 minutes after the New Year. He said he was
not taking any chances with somebody getting stuck in an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, Cushman, 36, had wondered, as a child what he
would be doing on the big night that ushered in a new millennium.
``I never anticipated this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Years from now, he said, he expects his children to ask what
marvelous experience he remembers from the dawning of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'll have to tell them, `Well, I went to work.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
