<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: GURKHA PENSIONS INCREASED
</P>
<P>
   The government said it would increase, by at least 100 percent,
the pensions of retired Gurkha soldiers, Nepalese who have served
in the British army, but they fell short of demands. A retired
Gurkha staff sergeant who currently receives $1,250 a month will
get about $3,500. By contrast, a retired Briton of the same rank
gets about $24,000. About 30,000 Gurkhas have served in the British
Army over the past 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PIPE BOMB BLAST
</P>
<P>
   A briefcase containing a pipe bomb exploded in a Netanya bus
station. There were no injuries because Israeli policemen cleared
the area after a shopowner reported the bag as suspicious. Israel
Radio said witnesses saw a man in black hat and coat, presumed to
be disguised as an ultra-Orthodox Jew, leave the bag.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: CONCERN OVER VOTE
</P>
<P>
   Election observers from the Carter Center expressed concerns
about the vote-counting process in Mozambique's national elections.
The observers said they were denied access to the final tabulation
and verification procedures, despite repeated requests. Afonso
Dhlakama, declared the loser in the presidential contest against
the incumbent, Joaquim Chissano, has petitioned the Constitutional
Court for a recount.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: POACHER GETS 20 YEARS
</P>
<P>
   An elephant poacher has been sentenced to 20 years in prison,
the longest sentence ever handed down in a poaching case in South
Africa. Shalate Khoza, who shot an elephant in Kruger National Park
and cut off the tusks, was arrested in July after he was caught in
the park carrying elephant meat, a rifle and several rounds of
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   COMOROS: THREAT TO SEPARATISTS
</P>
<P>
   African leaders threatened to isolate separatists on the Comoran
island of Anjouan if they refuse to sign an agreement aimed at
keeping the archipelago nation from coming apart. The country has
been wracked by political turmoil for two years, and regional
leaders consider the accord a big step toward bringing stability to
the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
