<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8612 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-CREW-SEARCH-2TAKES     12-24 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CREW-SEARCH-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING A SUCCESSOR FOR CREW WILL NOT BE EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-CREW-ASSESS)  
(lh) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With speculation already frenzied about potential
successors to schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, officials at City Hall
said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani would urge the Board of Education to
conduct the search on its own, as it did in 1995 in selecting Crew,
rather than by appointing an outside committee or using an
executive headhunting agency.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Giuliani said he believes that returning to the
practice of using a search committee would only add a layer of
bureaucracy to a historically tortured process. But with the
atmosphere surrounding the chancellor search expected to be even
more politically charged than usual, direct action by the
seven-member board would also ensure that the mayor, through his
three allies on the board, has a role from the very beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday that they were also focused on the
increasing likelihood that Crew might not finish out the academic
year, either because he was infuriated by the board's 4-3 vote on
Thursday not to renew his contract or because some board members
would prefer he leave immediately. If Crew leaves in the next few
weeks, the board would have to select an interim chancellor before
it could begin looking for a permanent replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Crew, speaking to reporters outside his brownstone in Brooklyn
after returning home from Christmas shopping, said Friday that he
would be willing to stay on until his contract ends in June but
also said it might not be appropriate for him to do so without the
support of the board or City Hall. Asked if he was relieved after
months of uncertainty, Crew said: ``I'm not so much relieved, but
this is the way it ends. God bless everybody. It didn't turn out
that I could do it any longer. I have had a good, long run and I'd
do it all over again, even knowing what I know now.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged off questions about whether the mayor was to blame
for his ouster. ``It's not really a time for pointing fingers,'' he
said. ``That's not where my heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   Board members said they hoped to resolve the question of how
long Crew will remain before their next meeting, which is scheduled
for Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would imagine the first we would need to do is decide on an
interim if the chancellor is leaving right away,'' said Terri
Thomson, the board member from Queens who cast the deciding vote
against Crew. ``We'll talk on Tuesday about the process by which we
pick an interim and the process by which we pick a permanent
replacement. The issue at stake is how do we find the best
chancellor that's out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Under normal circumstances, a search to head the school system,
which has about 1.1 million students, is a daunting venture,
complicated by the city's racial and ethnic divisions, the concerns
of parents and the demands of unions. The search in the coming
months will be further entangled by the politics of a busy election
year, particularly the expected Senate contest between Giuliani and
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle facing the board is that even the most informal
suggestion of names is likely to be fraught with political
motivations, a point that Giuliani acknowledged Friday. ``There is
no important job in which lots of names don't get thrown out, some
of which are thrown out just for who knows what purpose,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Education has already emerged as an issue in the Senate race.
Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, said on Thursday that the
mayor should be held responsible for the vote to oust Crew, and he
made it clear Friday that Mrs. Clinton and her Democratic
supporters would be watching the mayor's every move during the
chancellor search.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy Giuliani does three things when people disagree with him:
He sues, he tries to fire them or he has them arrested. And you
can't operate that way in the United States Senate,'' Wolfson said.
``Rudy Giuliani will want to install his person as chancellor.'' He
added, ``I think it's imperative that the next chancellor continue
to put New York's children ahead of the mayor's political agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   How strong a hand Giuliani looks to have in the search may be
further complicated by his expected run for the Senate and the fact
that regardless of the Senate race, he is barred by term limits
from remaining at City Hall after his second term ends in 2001.
That would mean that any new chancellor would run the schools for
only a year or two before being faced with a new mayor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Even mayors change,'' Giuliani explained the other day. ``It's
going to happen pretty soon. Change is good. It gives you another
opportunity to reinvent things.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who said he supported the board's decision to end
Crew's tenure, repeated that position Friday. ``I think the system
has an opportunity to go the next level now, which means really
serious thorough reform,'' he said at a holiday charity event.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's desire for the board to conduct a direct search was
met with skepticism by the teachers' union. ``The mayor's
micromanaging the process already,'' said Randi Weingarten, the
president of the United Federation of Teachers. ``I guess the
reason that the mayor wants it that way is he wants to have a hand
in the search.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Weingarten said the seven board members should determine how
to conduct the search, keeping in mind some recent educational
initiatives that need to be maintained. Those initiatives, to
improve 40 of the lowest performing schools and to end social
promotion, should be at the top of the board's agenda, she said.
``It's very important that they play a leadership role in calming
the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   While board members said they had not yet discussed specific
candidates, either for an interim or permanent post, people inside
and outside the field of education have already begun tossing
around names, many of people with experience in New York, including
two former chancellors _ Anthony Alvarado and Frank Macchiarola _
as well as the current school superintendents in Dallas, Atlanta
and Springfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas superintendent, Bill Rojas, worked in the New York
City school system for 23 years, served as superintendent in San
Francisco for seven years and was a top candidate in the last two
chancellor searches in New York. The Atlanta superintendent,
Beverly Hall, headed Newark, N.J.'s schools from 1995 until last
July and previously served as a deputy chancellor for instruction
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Springfield superintendent, Peter Negroni, moved to
Massachusetts in 1989 after serving as superintendent of District
12 in the Bronx. All three of the superintendents are considered
more likely contenders than the two former chancellors. Alvarado,
now working in the San Diego school system, was chancellor from
1983 to 1984 but resigned amid a personal financial scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Macchiarola, who served the longest tenure as chancellor in
recent history, from 1978 to 1983, is now president of St. Francis
College in Brooklyn, and associates say he is extremely happy in
that job. One City Hall official said that a top aide to the mayor
had suggested Macchiarola as a successor to Crew and that Giuliani
had already rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crew, in his conversation with reporters, spoke wistfully about
his time as chancellor and hinted that politics was behind his
ouster, before heading off to walk his golden retriever, Chance,
along State Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor and his board members did what they needed to do,''
Crew said. ``I'm not shocked. It's what I anticipated with an
election brewing. It's time to move on. I have had a wonderful
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
