<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S GOOD TO HAVE OREL BACK AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This is the story I tell when people ask what Orel
Hershiser is really like.
</P>
<P>
   Three or four years ago, I go to an Angels game to write about
Valley-boy pitcher Jack McDowell, who's in town with the Cleveland
Indians. Hershiser is an Indian at the time.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell has a few minutes for an interview in the dugout before
batting practice. We talk about his local connection, his team, his
career, his season. Then he jogs out to shag fly balls.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Indians publicist mentions McDowell and his wife expect
a child any day. McDowell will have to fly home right after
tonight's game and probably miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   I've got to ask McDowell about his wife and the baby. But he's
in the outfield. When he comes off the field, he runs straight into
the trainer's room, which is off-limits to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   I wait at his locker. He isn't hurrying back. Meanwhile, I'm
chatting with Hershiser, whom I'd covered in his original Dodgers
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you're going to have to get out of here,'' Hershiser
says, looking at the clock, nearing 45 minutes before game time,
closing time for the writers.
</P>
<P>
   I explain my predicament, how I have one more question for
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you need to know?'' Hershiser says.
</P>
<P>
   I tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give me your tape recorder,'' he says, and he disappears into
the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, Hershiser is back with my tape recorder
</P>
<P>
   containing a quote from McDowell about his growing family.
</P>
<P>
   This small kindness isn't unique in the annals of the
player-writer wars, but it's close.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like the story Jack Disney tells about interviewing
Sandy Koufax for the Los Angeles Herald Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   This happens in Vero Beach, Fla., one spring in the late '70s.
Koufax, retired and reclusive for a decade, returns to the Dodgers
as a pitching instructor. Disney asks for an interview and Koufax
says yes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I borrowed a tape recorder, because it was to be a
question-and-answer format. I didn't own a tape recorder,'' the
writer remembers. ``We went out in a golf cart into the outfield,
way off in the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   For half an hour, Koufax delivers thoughtful answers to Disney's
questions, and the delighted writer thanks the great man for his
time.
</P>
<P>
   Then Disney rewinds the tape, just to make sure he'd got a crisp
recording.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was nothing on it,'' he says. Disney had pushed the
wrong buttons. And he hadn't taken notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feeling of dread engulfed me,'' he says. ``I thought,
`How am I going to explain this to my editor?' I'd just have to
tell the truth I blew the interview because of my mechanical
klutzmanship!
</P>
<P>
   ``Then Koufax said, `Let me see that.' He pushed a couple of
knobs, made sure the recorder was working. He said, `Let's do it
again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat there for another 25 minutes. It wasn't as good as the
first interview, but it was still pretty good. Every time he saw me
after that, he called me Young Tom Edison.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, this isn't a one-of-a-kind memory, but it suggests the
company Hershiser is in among all-time Los Angeles Dodgers good
guys.
</P>
<P>
   In my first season on the Dodgers beat in the mid-'80s, I fly
from Atlanta to Cincinnati with a pair of veteran writers after a
Sunday afternoon game. When we get off the plane, a lone individual
is sitting at the Delta gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garv, what are you doing here?'' one of the veteran writers
exclaims.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Garvey, a San Diego Padre now, explains that he'd been
waiting at another gate for his team's flight out of Cincinnati.
He'd started reading the ``Arrivals'' board, saw a flight was
coming in from Atlanta, and was aware the Dodgers had been playing
there.
</P>
<P>
   He says he knew the Dodgers players and other employees would
take a charter flight. But maybe some writers he knows would fly
commercial, and he figures he'll stroll across the terminal and say
hello.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, Koufax, Garvey. Pretty good company, that.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Hershiser signed a free-agent contract to return to
the Dodgers after five seasons with the Indians, San Francisco
Giants and New York Mets. Hershiser and Dodgers officials held a
conference-call press conference.
</P>
<P>
   New Dodgers chairman Robert Daly introduced Hershiser as ``the
perfect person to have on the team not only as a pitcher but as a
leader.'' General manager Kevin Malone said Hershiser ``just
commands respect because of who he is and how he goes about his
business.''
</P>
<P>
   But late in the give-and-take, the 41-year-old pitcher sounded
as if he'd heard enough about his sterling character and hoped-for
influence onyoung teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to walk into that locker room,'' Hershiser said
to the writers on the phone, ``and have you guys to make me out to
be a saint. I haven't run my life perfectly and I haven't run my
baseball career perfectly....''
</P>
<P>
   OK, then: Hershiser is not a saint. Neither is Koufax. Neither
is Garvey.
</P>
<P>
   From what I remember, though, he's a heck of a good guy to have
in the clubhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
