<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8618 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EGYPT-BEER-1STLD-WRIT     12-24 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-BEER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPTIAN ENTREPRENEUR FINDS GOLD IN DIRTY BEER 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to rewrite last sentence of 1st take to relect fact that
stock market was closed Friday.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT 18 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ When the Egyptian government put the national
beer company up for sale a few years ago, nobody was buying.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the brewery had no competition and had been steadily
turning a profit, it was a management nightmare. Workers lounged
around reading newspapers or napping while grimy, ancient machines
gushed foaming beer into dirty green bottles, often along with
insects, twigs and clumps of dirt. Sales were falling. And, as if
all that were not enough of a headache, beer drinking for many
people in Egypt, a predominantly Muslim country, is considered a
sin.
</P>
<P>
   But Ahmed Zayat, an Egyptian entrepreneur who had earned degrees
at Harvard and Boston University and flourished at Wall Street
firms specializing in real estate and leveraged buyouts, spotted
potential where others saw only pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three years after taking control of Al Ahram Beverages
Co. _ which required some inventive negotiating and a high-flying
stock offering on the London Stock Exchange _ Zayat, 37, has turned
the bedraggled enterprise into one of the best-performing companies
in Egypt. With the help of consultants from Carlsberg, the Danish
brewer, he has begun turning out first-rate beer. Moreover, Al
Ahram has gained enough respectability that early next year it will
also begin producing Carlsberg and Guinness beers.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, he has discovered that the real profit may be in a
line of nonalcoholic beers _ some with apple, lemon and strawberry
flavors _ that have been flying off the shelves. ``It tastes like
beer,'' said Fatenn Mostafa, the director of marketing whom Zayat
hired away from PepsiCo, ``and it's a little naughty.''
</P>
<P>
   While expanding sales across Egypt with a blitz of television
advertising, an army of sales representatives and a fleet of trucks
that provide home delivery _ all new tactics here _ Zayat has begun
exporting nonalcoholic beer to Saudi Arabia and is gearing up to
move into other Middle East, African and Asian countries,
particularly places like Nigeria and Indonesia with big Muslim
populations. Sales revenues jumped 60 percent in the last fiscal
year ended June 30, and profits rose nearly 30 percent, to $26
million.
</P>
<P>
   Zayat's success has been a catalyst for a new wave of investment
in Egypt. The beer company was just one of more than 300
state-owned companies that the government had been hoping to sell
as Egypt took the lead in a shift across the Middle East from
top-down control and state ownership to the more freewheeling style
of capitalism. For most investors and investment bankers, the
universally troubled companies had been a yawn. But when they saw
what Zayat was able to do with Al Ahram, they began searching for
other diamonds in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a model for other investors,'' said Josse Dorra
Fiani, the president of Fiani &AMP; Partners, a Cairo consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Before Zayat closed his deal in early 1997, five state-owned
companies had been sold since the privatization push began in the
early 1990s. Now the number is 18, with two state-owned cement
companies bought by corporations in Mexico and Britain in recent
weeks. Government officials say more than a dozen other deals are
in the works.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing a different attitude,'' said Mokhtar Khattab, an
undersecretary in the Ministry of Public Enterprise, the
clearinghouse for the sale of state-owned companies. He added,
however, that he thought some of the new enthusiasm was the
cumulative effect of years of government effort.
</P>
<P>
   Zayat, puffing on a Cuban cigar late one evening in his office
at the brewery, said that investors who passed up a chance to buy
the company ``totally misunderstood the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   He managed to take over the brewery for about $70 million, only
about one-third the government's asking price. That so angered some
government officials that they still find it hard to applaud his
achievements. But it demonstrated to investors that Cairo could be
flexible _ something many had doubted. And he has shown the
government that the sale price is only one part of a successful
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Besides helping to attract other investors, Zayat has fulfilled
several other goals of the government's privatization program. He
has begun contributing to Egypt's export earnings and he has
inspired a group of local investors to start a new beer company,
creating competition and new jobs in a country with unemployment of
around 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When a third beer company was about to start up, Zayat, whose
company has an overwhelming share of the domestic market, concluded
that too much competition too soon might not be good. So he bought
out the fledgling company as part of his expansion.
</P>
<P>
   To get started in the wine business, he went back to the
government and bought its small winemaker, taking another company
out of the state's inventory. Zayat, whose company already sells
soft drinks, said he plans to introduce vodka, Scotch and other
hard liquors, aimed at Egypt's tourist trade and its growing
population of affluent, foreign-educated young people.
</P>
<P>
   No one would have predicted such success. There was so little
interest among big investors in Egypt's state-owned companies that
the government sold more than 80 of them piecemeal on the Cairo
stock exchange. Out of frustration, it liquidated nearly 30 other
companies it deemed unsalable.
</P>
<P>
   When no investor was willing to buy the beer company, the
government turned to the local stock market. But the brewery's
reputation was so bad and so many local investors were reluctant to
add a ``sin stock'' to their portfolios that the government cut
back an initial public offering in mid-1996 to 5 percent of the
company, and settled for an offering price of $4.925 a share
adjusted for a recent stock split, rather than a hoped-for $6.25.
It sold two other similarly sized blocks of the company to two big
Egyptian institutional investors and gave another 10 percent to
employees.
</P>
<P>
   The poor reception in the local stock market helped Zayat talk
down the price for the remaining 75 percent. His real estate
experience helped him, too. The government wanted nearly $200
million in exchange for the stake, in part because the main plant,
more than 100 years old and looking like a crusader's castle, sits
on some of Cairo's most valuable real estate, near the center of
town and just across the street from Cairo University.
</P>
<P>
   But Zayat wanted to buy a business, not invest in real estate.
So he proposed that the government keep the land, but lease it to
him for five years. In the meantime, he would build a $50 million
advanced brewery like nothing the Middle East had ever seen, in the
desert on the outskirts of Cairo. He bought the land at below
market price as one of the anchor developers in a new industrial
village the government was starting. As part of the package, Zayat
negotiated a 10-year tax holiday on the new plant.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1996, the government finally accepted a bid from
Zayat of $5.51 a share, adjusted for the split, or 11 percent more
than the disappointing offering price on the Cairo exchange. Today
the stock is worth $19.85 a share.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Reaching his goal took 18 months and 22 negotiating sessions.
Zayat's meetings with platoons of government officials often ran
more than 12 hours. ``One time,'' he said, ``I spoke 16 hours and
ended up with everybody in the room asleep but me and the person I
was talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after the government said yes there was still a problem:
Zayat did not yet have $70 million. He had to sell the idea of
selling beer to Muslims to international investors. He lined up a
public offering of global depository receipts in Europe and set off
on a road show across Europe and the United States that yielded
Zayat not only enough money to pay the government but even more to
pocket himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the people in the government are still asking, `If he did
it, couldn't we have done it?''' said Daniel Kurtzer, the American
ambassador to Egypt. Zayat paid his bankers and lawyers $10 million
and came away with $25 million in instant profit for himself and a
handful of American backers. And after all the financial wizardry,
Zayat and his backers wound up with a 12 percent stake in the
company.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Zayat has taken a creative approach to running his business as
well. He started home delivery because the government limits the
licensing of outlets for beer and because he correctly guessed that
people who might be embarrassed to go into a beer store would be
happy to have a few cases discreetly brought to their door. Stymied
by a government ban on advertising alcoholic drinks, he has
employed a Trojan horse technique, filling the airwaves with spots
for nonalcoholic beer that look very much like beer ads in Europe
and the United States and that have done wonders for both products.
</P>
<P>
   Before the government sale of the brewery, one would-be investor
had estimated that it could be run with a tenth of its 3,200
employees. But with wholesale dismissals forbidden by the
government, Zayat set out instead on a total reorganization. He cut
the production force to about 800 and hired experts from
Carlsberg's consulting unit. He transferred hundreds into the
brewery's new sales force and assigned others to work in warehouses
or as drivers. About 300 people accepted early retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He also created a group of inspectors and put them in charge of
quality control. He got rid of a committee system of management,
raised salaries, provided stock bonuses for employees and replaced
the brewery's six-day workweek of six-and-a-half-hour shifts with a
five-day, 8 a.m to 5 p.m. routine. Now, with business booming,
Zayat says, he has more employees than when he started.
</P>
<P>
   Zayat brought the plant into the late 20th century with some
simple equipment that speeded up work enormously. When he arrived
there were four telephones; now there are 1,600. He vastly
increased the number of desktop computers (from four to more than
300) and fax machines (from one to dozens). And he nearly doubled
the delivery fleet to 450 trucks.
</P>
<P>
   To help improve quality control, he installed a simple plastic
sheet to keep dirt and bugs from falling into beer bottles as they
trundled along a conveyor, and he bought an X-ray machine to
examine every filled bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Zayat said he always planned to expand the brewery's product
line. But even he has been bowled over by the nearly 400 percent
increase in the volume of nonalcoholic beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our future,'' said Ms. Mostafa, Zayat's marketing
director.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of the company's profit used to come from
regular beer, she said, but in three years, even with continued
growth in beer sales, the proportion is expected to fall to 45
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will never succeed in getting every Egyptian to drink
beer,'' Ms. Mostafa said. ``It will always be a Muslim country. But
nonalcoholic beer has all the elements to succeed. It's very
healthy. It doesn't have caffeine. It looks like beer. It tastes
like beer. But it's religiously accepted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2120EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
