<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8620 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CALIF-TOBACCO-NYT &LR;      12-24 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-TOBACCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TREASURER FAVORS SHEDDING OF TOBACCO STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Mass., Fla., Md., N.Y., Minn., Pa., Mich., Texas)  (lh) 
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The state treasurer of California said Friday that he would
press the state's two big public employees pension funds to sell
off their large holdings of tobacco company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Phil Angelides, said the holdings have lost more
than $500 million in value this year as cigarette makers fended off
lawsuits by the federal and state governments as well as
class-action lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe divestment is a prudent fiduciary course,''
Angelides said, because the financial position of tobacco companies
has been weakened by an ``unprecedented assault by the legal
systems, the regulatory system and, in effect, society as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The long-term prospects look dim'' because of these pressures,
he said. Angelides is on the boards of both retirement funds, the
California Public Employees Retirement System, known as CALPERS,
and the State Teachers Retirement System. At last week's market
prices, the funds had about $845 million invested in tobacco
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the treasurer placed a moratorium on the purchase
of tobacco securities by a $33 billion fund that he controls, the
Pooled Money Investment Account, which holds the short-term
investments of the state as well as those of many local
governments. The account had already reduced its holdings of
short-term tobacco securities from a high of $2 billion in the
early 1990s to zero in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Angelides' moves, Philip Morris Cos., the world's
biggest tobacco company, noted that its stock was one of the most
widely held by professional money managers. It added that, ``Public
pension fund managers have a fiduciary responsibility to manage
their portfolios to produce the best financial returns for their
beneficiaries, the public employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Goldman, an analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said he did
not think that private investors would regard Angelides' action as
noteworthy because the concept of divestment ``has been around for
a long time, and tobacco stock prices are so low, while yields are
substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris shares, which closed at $23.4375 Thursday on the
New York Stock Exchange, have plummeted more than $32 from a year
ago, helping drag down the growth of the Dow Jones industrial
average.
</P>
<P>
   At least six other states have taken steps to restrict tobacco
investments in the last four years, according to Doug Cogan, who
tracks the issue for the Investor Responsibility Research Center, a
nonprofit organization in Washington. State pension fund holdings
have been estimated at about 6 percent of tobacco shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Cogan said that Florida, Maryland, Massachusetts and Vermont had
sold all their holdings. New York and Minnesota, as well as the New
York City retirement fund, have partly restricted purchases. Total
sales in the last three years were about $1.5 billion, he said,
including $825 million by Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A number of universities have also sold off tobacco stocks,
including Harvard, Johns Hopkins, the City University of New York,
Smith, Tufts, Haverford, Wayne State, and public universities in
Texas and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   With about 2.5 billion shares outstanding, Philip Morris has a
market value of about $59 billion, which Cogan said was 75 percent
of the market value of the four biggest cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   Angelides said that the teachers system would consider the issue
at a Jan. 5 meeting of its subcommittee on corporate governance,
which he heads. He said he also discussed the issue last week with
Jim Burton, chief executive of CALPERS.
</P>
<P>
   But Cogan said that officials of the California funds had told
him they were reluctant to set a precedent under which they might
be pressured to sell other types of investments in any future
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of CALPERS could not be reached Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
