 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Drug Industry Warned About Price Controls
</P>
<P>
   Armed with new data showing that the drug industry earns higher
profits and pays lower taxes than most other industries, White
House officials say drug companies may bring price controls on
themselves if they continue to resist President Clinton's plan to
have Medicare provide pharmaceutical benefits. Clinton has
repeatedly said that his proposal for Medicare drug benefits does
not envision federal regulation of drug prices, and such a measure
is highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Retailers Flock to Net
</P>
<P>
   After standing on the sidelines of Internet commerce, many
traditional retailers have recently jumped onto the Web with both
feet, trying to capitalize on some of the advantages they enjoy
over their virtual competitors.
</P>
<P>
   `Millionaire' Makes Early Return
</P>
<P>
   ABC has decided to bring back its hit game show ``How to Be a
Millionaire,'' in a mini-marathon before its begins its previously
announced three-day-a-week run.
</P>
<P>
   Return of the Beanie Babies?
</P>
<P>
   Ty Inc. is reconsidering its decision to end its popular Beanie
Babies line on Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunites in Romania
</P>
<P>
   American companies are taking advantage of a legacy of the
Romanian dictator Nicolae Ceausescu. Many huge steel mills and
factories built during his tenure now lie rusting, but the
engineering schools he added to Romania's education system still
pump out graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Divestiture Urged
</P>
<P>
   The state treasurer of California presses the state's two big
public employees pension funds to sell off their large holdings of
tobacco company stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Yen Posts Decline Against Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Japan sold an estimated $2 billion to $3 billion yen in
an effort to keep the recovery on track. The currency rate slid to
102.65 a dollar.
</P>
<P>
