<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RELIGIOUS DIMENSION OF THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Religion Column) 
(mk) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let next Saturday belong to the revelers, the entertainers, the
makers of lists. For Christianity, the new millennium begins this
Saturday, Christmas Day.
</P>
<P>
   Christians should be grateful to the members of other faiths who
have dismissed the millennium celebration as not their party, Jews
for whom this is the 10th month of the year 5760, for instance, or
Buddhists and Hindus who have cited their own significant religious
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these dismissals might have been unnecessarily huffy or
too quick to overlook common ground with those who honor a
different sacred calendar. But they at least had the merit of
recognizing the religious dimension of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Why haven't Christian leaders _ the pope and some minor
preachers of doom excepted _ made more out of that dimension?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Abernethy, the anchor of ``Religion &AMP; Ethics News Weekly,''
a program seen on many PBS stations, raised that question in a
panel discussion on this weekend's show.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Marty, a church historian who was one of the panelists
(this writer was another), suggested that Christians were both
hesitant to appear boastful about the good things in Christianity's
past and reluctant to reflect on the bad things. But mostly, Marty
said, they were overwhelmed, and perhaps frightened, by the
commotion created around a secular pseudo-event.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, as Abernethy noted, has been the exception.
Five years ago, the pope issued a letter, ``Tertio Millennio
Adveniente'' (``The Coming of the Third Millennium''), on preparing
for the jubilee year that he initiated this Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The letter outlined an ambitious plan of preparation and
celebration. The plan included papal journeys to the Middle Eastern
sites associated with Abraham and Moses, Jesus and St. Paul, but it
also called for an examination of the church's conscience and
repentance for evils perpetrated in the church's name or tolerated
through its indifference.
</P>
<P>
   The letter urged a search for unity among Christians; more
interreligious dialogue, especially with Jews and Muslims; an
honoring of men and women (and not just Catholics) who have been
martyred for their beliefs in this century; and a renewed emphasis
on ``the church's preferential option for the poor and the
outcast.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the year 2000, the pope said, was nothing less
than ``a hermeneutical key'' for understanding his pontificate, and
one could see a synopsis of his concerns in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   It was striking how many things proposed in the letter have
already been accomplished or have been set in motion. The letter
also added pathos to the many ways in which these efforts have
fallen short of the pope's hopes, either because of things beyond
his control or because of opposition and suspicion stirred by his
policies.
</P>
<P>
   But why tie such an agenda specifically to the year 2000? ``In
Christianity,'' the pope wrote, ``time has a fundamental
importance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tertio Millennio Adveniente'' begins with a meditation on the
phrase ``the fullness of time.'' It is St. Paul's phrase: ``When
the fullness of time had come, God sent his son, born of a woman''
(Galatians 4:4). In Christ, God set forth his purpose, ``as a plan
for the fullness of time, to unite all things in him, things in
heaven and things on earth'' (Ephesians 1:10). ``The fullness of
time'' is a resonant phrase, at once majestic and somehow
comforting, yet haunting and mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   What is this fullness of time? Certainly not the frenzied
busyness with which people fill their day at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   For Paul and for Pope John Paul II, the phrase refers both to
the coming of Christ 2000 years ago and to the Messianic age of
reconciliation that is yet to come. The fullness of time is a
culmination, a ripening, a cosmic event, in which what is beyond
time enters time and humanity receives a definitive promise of
transcending the limits of time.
</P>
<P>
   History is not just a speeding car, more or less out of control,
whose speedometer is about to flip over. History is a story, a
drama, with a turning point, climax and denouement. That is
something that can be affirmed even by those who do not believe in
this particular Christian cosmic story.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed those who share the pope's faith and those who do not can
find memorable many of the expressions that he uses: ``In Jesus
Christ, the word made flesh, time becomes a dimension of God, who
is himself eternal.'' Eternity enters time. Time is taken up into
eternity.
</P>
<P>
   Which imposes on Christians, the pope wrote, ``the duty to
sanctify time.'' Here, in fact, is one of those points of
convergence with other faiths. Holy days, sabbaths, seasons,
anniversaries, rites of the life cycle: John Paul could well have
embraced other religions in noting, ``The solar year is thus
permeated by the liturgical year.''
</P>
<P>
   One particular way of sanctifying time, rooted like Christianity
in the faith of Israel, is the jubilee, ``the year of the Lord's
favor'' proclaimed in the passage from Isaiah that the Gospel of
Luke described Jesus reading in the synagogue in Nazareth.
</P>
<P>
   According to the law of Moses, the jubilee years, every 7th and
15th year, were times for freeing slaves, letting the earth lie
fallow and rejuvenate itself, restoring to each family its
ancestral land.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jubilee year was meant to restore equality among all the
children of Israel,'' the pope wrote. Justice consisted in
protection for the weak, based on the conviction that ``the riches
of creation were to be considered as a common good of the whole of
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The new millennium, in this view, cannot be adequately
celebrated in a minute, an hour, an evening or a day. It will take
at least a year. After all, for Christians it calls to mind not a
changed calendar but a changed world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2140EST &QL; 
