<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8630 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GEN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-24 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Touched by an angel and filled with hope
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LaJuan Moore smiles and nods proudly, as a motor underneath his
hospital bed begins to hum, the mattress shifting automatically and
moving his legs into another position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus came early,'' he says of the motorized bed.
</P>
<P>
   He is bright and happy. He is determined and full of ambition.
He is the centerpiece of a Christmas story that warms the heart and
brightens the day despite so much pain and so many challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If God didn't think I could handle this,'' he says, ``he
wouldn't have put me in this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the story of a mother, a son and an angel of hope named
Sean Jones, a giant-hearted former Houston Oilers great who
probably never will spend another Christmas without thinking of the
kid that affected his life deeply.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sept. 30 at Butler Stadium. Moore, a talented junior
safety for the Sharpstown Apollos football team, was having the
game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first quarter of that game against Westbury,
Moore already had five tackles. He was crushing ball-carriers and
knocking away passes, using speed and football instincts that
coaches called among the best on the team.
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Moore had 10 tackles. By the third quarter, someone
told his mother, Charlotte Beverly, ``It's the LaJuan Moore show
tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly smiled and nodded, proudly wearing the bright green
colors of Sharpstown High and chanting with friends and family,
``LaJuan LaJuan LaJuan.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third quarter, Moore saw the Westbury tight
end sprinting across the middle of the field. He stepped up to hit
the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came straight at me,'' Moore said. ``I knew I'd get a good
hit on him, but I hit him kind of funny and just fell straight
down. I tried to get up, but I was just lying there looking around
and didn't know what was going on. My head hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly screamed when she heard the vicious collision involving
her son, but it was a scream of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him make that last tackle,'' Beverly said, ``and I just
turned away. I didn't think he was hurt, I just thought, `This
really is the LaJuan Moore show tonight.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Beverly's eldest son, Desmond, noticed LaJuan wasn't moving.
His sister, Berry, grabbed his mother by the arm and said,
``LaJuan's hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Beverly descended to the bottom of the grandstands and began
pacing, looking for her son in the huddle as trainers and coaches
gathered around the player lying motionless on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started looking at the players in the huddle trying to find
No. 11,'' Beverly said. ``I said, `Where's No. 11? Where's LaJuan?
I started panicking and then I started praying. When I saw that it
was LaJuan on the ground I thought, `My baby's dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the night was a blur, a mother's worst nightmare. A
Sharpstown coach reached Beverly in the stands and said, ``You have
to come down here right now.''
</P>
<P>
   She stood on the field near medical personnel as trainers
clipped off LaJuan's chinstrap and unbolted his facemask. She
waited for 10 minutes, 15 minutes, as paramedics attended to her
son. LaJuan never moved. She boarded the ambulance and saw
paramedics cut the jersey from his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   She saw the blank expression on her son's face, a neck brace
carefully placed on him and doctors and nurses scurrying to her
son's side as they arrived at Hermann Hospital. She sat in the
waiting room, crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor came in and told me to sit down,'' Beverly said.
``He told me, `LaJuan is severely injured. He will never walk
again.' I don't know what I thought. I couldn't feel anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day _ Beverly's birthday _ she again sat in the waiting
room at Hermann as LaJuan underwent 10 hours of surgery after
fracturing the C-4 and C-5 vertabrae in his neck. His prognosis was
good, but he was a paraplegic, able to move his arms only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't ask why,'' Beverly said. ``You just try to deal with
it and be strong. You try to find some hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, hope doesn't come wrapped in Christmas paper and
sealed with a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, hope is a 17-year-old kid with more perspective and
faith than anyone around him. And sometimes hope stands 6 feet, 6
inches tall, with broad shoulders, a Super Bowl ring and walks
through the door of the TIRR rehabilitation center and immediately
connects with a kid he never saw before.
</P>
<P>
   Only days after Moore's injury, Jones went to the rehab center
with Dallas Cowboys rookie defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban to visit
another player, Michael Mills, who suffered a similarly devastating
football injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked in there thinking maybe we could put a smile on
their faces,'' Jones said. ``But they put smiles on our faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones connected with the family, realizing Beverly had to take a
leave of absence from her job at a dry cleaners and had no means of
financially dealing with the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think they're having a hard day, but they
don't know what a hard day is,'' Jones said. ``When tragedy happens
you have to try and make some sense of it. Sometimes it's hard. But
you have to meet this kid to know how good a kid he is. I've never
seen him without a smile on his face. Sometimes he tells me not to
worry, that it's all going to be all right, and I don't have a
comeback. All I can do is smile. All I can do is try to help anyway
I can.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean has been like LaJuan's big brother,'' Beverly said. ``He
hasn't had to do anything that he's done for LaJuan, but he's been
like an angel to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones visited Moore regularly in the hospital and throughout his
rehabilitation, even attending a Sharpstown game in October and
watching from the sidelines with Moore. When a clerical error led
to Moore's Medicaid benefits being cut off two months after his
injury, Jones stepped in to help regain the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And when it became apparent the small one-bedroom apartment in
which Beverly alone raised her three children was not adequate for
Moore's condition, Jones opened a trust fund for the family at
Southwest Bank of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month when Beverly still could not return to work
as she cared for Moore and funds raised were not enough to pay for
an apartment, Jones stepped up again.
</P>
<P>
   He provided the family rent-free a two-bedroom condominium at a
complex he owns in southeast Houston. Jones also paid for the place
to be fitted with wider doorways, tile floors, a
wheelchair-accessible bathroom, a ramp at the entryway, a personal
parking space, appliances and even a trophy case for Moore's
numerous baseball, basketball and football awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sean has made things happen,'' Beverly said. ``This is not
going to be easy, but he's been a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jones: ``I think about LaJuan a lot, and it puts things in
perspective for me. Here's an honor-roll student that had
everything in front of him, but there's no bitterness. He has no
bad feelings about anything. I'm telling you, he's taught me a lot.
I don't want any credit for anything. I wish Charlotte hadn't told
anybody about this, because LaJuan should get all the credit.''
</P>
<P>
   When the holidays are over, Moore plans to return as a full-time
student at Sharpstown. For now, he lays in his new bed in his new
home, with his tattered No. 11 jersey hanging on a wall in his
room, and he dreams of what is ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm accepting what happened,'' Moore said. ``I would have
loved to keep playing football, but it didn't work out. I'm still
the same person. I have my family and my friends. I still want to
make something with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After high school, Moore wants to attend college, although he is
not sure about a field of study. His prognosis is good and with
limited movement in his arms and a friend in Jones, he considers
this a very good Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't get sad,'' Moore said. ``I try to just think
about what I'm going to do next.''
</P>
<P>
   On a wall above Moore's bed is a copy of a poem he wrote for an
English class. It reads, in part: ``Moore lover of God, who needs
to become a better man who gives his best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
