u a BC-NY-PRISON-STRIKE-280&AMP;     12-24 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-STRIKE-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSED OF STRIKE PLOT, 40 INMATES ARE MOVED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NINA SIEGAL  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty inmates were transferred out of a maximum-security prison
in upstate New York on Friday after correction officials discovered
that they were planning a strike, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The move added to widespread worries among prison officials that
inmates statewide were planning a work stoppage or protest that
could begin on New Year's Day. Over the last few months, inmate
advocates, prisoners' relatives and prison guards have reported
widespread organizing of inmates in at least three state prisons in
preparation for a work stoppage. The transfers from the Green Haven
Correctional Facility in Stormville on Friday was the most recent
evidence that an inmate strike was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   State Corrections Commissioner Glenn Goord ordered a lockdown at
Green Haven, which is about 95 miles south of Albany. He had the 40
inmates sent to other maximum-security prisons around the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This small group of inmates,'' he said, ``was attempting to
strong-arm unwilling inmates into supporting some unspecified work
stoppage in the future.''
   About 1,800 inmates at the Sing Sing Correctional Facility, in
Ossining, were also placed under lockdown Friday after five rounds
of 9-millimeter ammunition were found in a common area, officials
said. That incident was unrelated to the threatened strike, prison
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have said that rumors frequently arise that
inmates will refuse to do their prison jobs, but inmate advocates
said this threat was unusual because it was being organized at
prisons statewide, rather than at an individual institution. About
half the 72,000 inmates in state prisons work at jobs for an
average of $1.05 a day.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   James Flateau, a spokesman for the Department of Correction,
confirmed the reports this week that there had been rumors of a
strike, but he declined to discuss preparations the department is
making to handle possible disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, that inmates in more than one state prison had
been disciplined for having a copy of a letter calling for a
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The unsigned letter, titled ``Wake Up,'' urges inmates to
protest the state's parole polices, which the authors said are
unduly harsh, by refusing to perform their jobs or leave their
cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inmates who are found with that document are being
disciplined,'' Flateau said. ``Some are being transferred to other
facilities; some are being locked up in their cells.''
</P>
<P>
   Protests have already taken place at Green Haven, in Dutchess
County, and at Sing Sing. Forty-five inmates were transferred from
Green Haven to other state prisons in November because of their
involvement in plotting the work stoppage, Flateau said. Inmates in
other state prisons, like the Fishkill Correctional Facility in
Beacon, have told outside contacts of their intent to stop work.
</P>
<P>
   Denny Fitzpatrick, director of public relations for the New York
State Correctional Officers and Police Benevolent Association, a
union that represents state prison guards, said organizing efforts
of this magnitude were very rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times in every facility when the inmates are
spreading rumors, and generally it is isolated to a particular
facility,'' he said. ``This is a bit different because it's trying
to be generated statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudette Spencer, staff lawyer with the Prisoners' Rights
Project of the Legal Aid Society of New York, said many inmates
were angry because they believed they had been perfunctorily denied
parole, without proper consideration of their behavior in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Green, executive director of the Center for Law and
Justice in Albany, a inmate advocacy group, said: ``There's a core
of people who feel that there's nothing to work for, there's
nothing to work towards, because they have the feeling they're not
going to ever get out. Others are concerned that they think their
labor is being exploited in the system, and that they're being kept
in the system longer to support what they call the prison
industrial complex.''
</P>
<P>
   Most inmates employed in the prison system perform jobs that
help the prison function, like doing laundry or working in the
prison mess hall. Others are trained in general carpentry,
electrical work or plumbing. About 3,500 inmates across the state
earn about 75 cents an hour working for Corcraft, the correction
department's manufacturing division, which makes furniture,
wastebaskets, soap, inmate clothing and other products for sale to
government agencies and nonprofit groups.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzpatrick of the correctional officers' union said he was
concerned that a strike by inmate workers could lead to rioting.
``If you have a faction within the facility that breaks ranks and
decides to go ahead and go to work, or go ahead and eat in the mess
hall, then you've got one faction in the prison against another,''
he said. ``It's not a healthy situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legal Aid Society of New York, which runs a program for
families of inmates, has warned clients that disruptive protests in
prison are not protected by the First Amendment, and could lead to
disciplinary action. Ms. Spencer said Legal Aid was investigating
recent parole board decisions, and might file a class action
lawsuit next year on behalf of inmates who believe they were
unfairly denied parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
