u a BC-DEADBEAT-DIPLOMATS-NY     12-24 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADBEAT-DIPLOMATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADBEAT U.N. DIPLOMATS A HEADACHE FOR LANDLORDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By COREY KILGANNON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The minister of the Mission of Guinea-Bissau sat in
his darkened office one afternoon last week, near a large window
overlooking East 43rd Street.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, Joao De Gama, was working alone in the seven-room
office because the mission's staff, once eight people, has been
cut, for the most part, to one: De Gama. He was working in darkness
because the landlord recently cut off the electricity.
Guinea-Bissau has not paid the rent in 15 months. De Gama keeps his
cell phone handy because the office phone service has also been
disconnected.
</P>
<P>
   There was more activity a block away, at the Liberian Consulate,
at 820 Second Ave., as officials in suits paced around the
13th-floor office suite with cell phones. Again the office was
almost completely dark. A secretary sitting in one pitch-black
office room turned on a battery-powered camping lantern to tell a
reporter that late last month, the building's management cut the
electricity to the mission and consulate, which has not paid its
rent in five months, an outstanding bill of roughly $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries are getting over civil wars in their homelands
and have interim governments that are not financing the missions.
And local landlords say that this is not a unique situation around
the United Nations. At any given time, several diplomatic offices
are having financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In their darkest hours, the missions of economically wobbly, and
often warring, countries often stop paying rent (and officials'
salaries) without permission. Since they have diplomatic status,
landlords cannot evict them. Even court judgments ordering
diplomats to pay back rent cannot be enforced, so frustrated
landlords often apply pressure by cutting electricity, heat and
sometimes phone lines. So an African civil war can really hang up a
landlord in Turtle Bay, the East Side neighborhood near the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia and Guinea-Bissau are among 19 countries that have not
paid their UN dues in at least two years. Liberia lost its voting
rights in the Security Council, said Farhan Haq, a UN spokesman,
but Guinea-Bissau has been allowed to keep its vote because of
``extenuating financial hardship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deadbeat diplomats are more of a problem in New York City than
in other parts of the world because office space is so expensive,
Haq said. ``Rents around here are very high,'' he said, and that
poses a special hardship for poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, Rwanda's new government refused to pay expenses
incurred by its previous government, Haq said. And just before
Zaire became Congo, the outgoing Zaire ambassador took some
appliances from the mission and began conducting business out of
his New Jersey home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real history of missions having problems paying
rent and maintaining their facilities,'' Haq said. ``Desperate
things happen during changes of governments, but it's really
between them and their landlord and the City of New York.
Diplomatic immunity protects them from legal penalty while doing
their diplomatic work, so we stay out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvyn Kaufman, who is a part owner of several East Side office
buildings, has had several diplomatic tenants who stopped paying
rent but stayed in the offices, often without electricity,
telephone lines or even heat.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman has won various judgments for millions of dollars over
the years, but has never gotten any government agency to enforce
them, so he will no longer rent space to diplomats. ``We won't
touch them anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   De Gama of the Guinea-Bissau mission said that a year-long civil
war ended in his country in August, and the interim government has
cut funding. With no salary, he said, he gets by using money from a
modest expense account, but there is not enough to pay the
$6,000-per-month rent, which includes utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell your landlord he should wait for the rent
because your country's having a civil war,'' he said. ``We didn't
come here to cause problems, and we don't want to abuse our
diplomatic security. It's embarrassing, but we have work to do.
Where can we go?''
</P>
<P>
   The mission's office building at 211 E. 43rd St. is owned by
Eastgate Realty. ``We can't evict them,'' said Robert Hinds, a vice
president of Eastgate, ``so the only thing we can do is shut down
their electricity and hope they pay. I tried contacting all the
politicians, the governor, mayor, congressmen, the U.S. Mission.
Nothing works.''
</P>
<P>
   Chad, Bolivia and Mauritius are also tenants that are constantly
late with rent, he said, but they eventually pay up. And then,
Hinds said, there is Bangladesh, ``One of the world's poorest
countries. They pay like clockwork. It's unbelievable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
