<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-AD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN: AN EMPHASIS ON GORE'S EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This 30-second commercial is the seventh from Vice President Al
Gore. It discusses his experience and is being broadcast in Iowa
and New Hampshire beginning this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Century-Media.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SCREEN: The question is posed on a black screen: ``How
much experience does America need?'' Live color shots of Gore with
regular people appear sequentially as he talks about Social
Security (he hugs an elderly person), schools (a teacher appears
with children in a classroom), the environment (a spray of cherry
blossoms) and the economy (a roof-raising). Gore appears at the end
in a blue suit reviewing a piece of paper.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: A male voice narrates: ``How much experience does
America need? To protect Social Security from those who want to
raise the retirement age? To really take on the big drug companies
and get affordable prescription drugs? To fight against vouchers
that drain money from public schools? To preserve Medicaid and
strengthen Medicare? To keep our environment clean and our economy
strong? How much experience does America need? All it can get.''
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY: There are no factual claims in this commercial, but
there are several dubious implications. One is that the Social
Security retirement age is unchanging. In fact, the age at which
one can retire and receive full benefits is already scheduled to
climb gradually, to 67 from 65, over 24 years that begin in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   But the underlying supposition is that former Sen. Bill Bradley,
Gore's lone rival for the Democratic nomination, lacks the
experience to manage the big issues facing the country and that he
would do things detrimental to the national interest, or at least
the Democratic interest, like raise the retirement age. Bradley has
equivocated on raising the age, saying that all options should be
on the table. But Gore has not said specifically how he would shore
up Social Security either, saying only, ``I'm not for raising the
retirement age.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference to taking on ``the big drug companies'' is a
further dig at Bradley who, as a senator from New Jersey, received
significant financial contributions from those companies, many of
which are based in New Jersey. Other New Jersey Democrats,
including Sen. Frank Lautenberg, who has endorsed Gore, are also
mindful of the pharmaceutical industry's importance to their home
state and have voted accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   On school vouchers, Bradley has voted to allow experiments using
them while Gore opposed doing so.Gore is also reminding viewers
that Bradley has proposed eliminating Medicaid, although he would
replace it with other health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   SCORECARD: Like previous Gore advertisements, this one inches
closer and closer to a direct attack on Bradley's proposals, though
it does not name the former senator. Gore is trying to reach the
core Democratic constituency groups _ the elderly, teachers,
blue-collar workers _ and hoping to spur them to the polls to save
these fundamental Democratic programs by voting for him.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has only recently begun to emphasize his experience as a
qualification for the job of president. In this commercial, he
suggests he has the experience to maintain the status quo, that is,
the booming economy, without tinkering with core Democratic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   This spot will probably be followed by more that spell out in
even tougher language the threat that Gore believes a Bradley
presidency would pose.
</P>
<P>
   Four advertisements for Gore are available from The New York
Times on the Web at www.nytimes.com/politics
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2240EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991224.0255 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
