<SLUG> BC-GUNFIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAY BULLETS ARE CAUSE FOR CONCERN ON NEW YEAR'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KERRY FEHR-SNYDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - The last place you'll find Steve Martin, now that he
doesn't have to work New Year's Eve, is at an outdoor street
festival in downtown Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to be out on Phoenix streets on New Year's Eve
for one pretty major reason, stray bullets!'' said Martin, 27, a
manu facturing supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Random gunfire on New Year's Eve is as traditional as singing
Auld Lang Syne at the stroke of mid night. But this year, as
revelers ring in what they consider a new millen nium, even the
cops are taking cover and advising residents to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   From about 10 minutes till mid night and 10 minutes after, ``we
encourage officers to go out to a safe area,'' said Sgt. Jeff
Halstead, a Phoenix police spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There's two reasons for the advice to officers: to avoid
becoming targets and to be rested and ready for the flood of calls
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a busy time right after midnight, because we have a
lot of things that come down the line,'' Halstead said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, more gunfire has been ringing across the
Phoenix area on a daily basis as the population and number of guns
has grown. This summer, Shannon Smith, 14, was struck dead by a
falling bullet in her back yard. The shot could have come from as
far as a half-mile away.
</P>
<P>
   For police, the pop-pop-pop of gunfire, especially on New Year's
Eve and the Fourth of July, is hard to track down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear them non-stop throughout this time,'' Halstead said.
``We try to tell our officers, `Don't get caught up in this
mind-set that you need to track it down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But the safety issue extends beyond officers working a beat on
the street.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Van Leeuwen, a hair stylist at Salon Phoenix, said one
officer who patrols her historic downtown Phoenix neighborhood
urged her to leave town altogether for the holi day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like World War II with gunfire in constant directions for
two hours,'' Van Leeuwen said. ``Last year, I was calling the
police from inside my house, and they thought I was standing
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Leeuwen is taking the advice this year: She's packing up her
dog and going to Tempe to spend a quiet New Year's Eve with a
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sad,'' she said. ``I love my house and shouldn't have to
be laying low below the glass line of my windows for four hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of random gunfire is so great that Phoenix Police
Chief Harold Hurtt issued a statement to the news media this week
urging residents to hold their fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``This activity, random gunfire, is a serious and growing
problem in our community,'' Hurtt said. ``Ran dom gunfire places
additional de mands on the already burdensome requests for public
safety interven tion during the New Year's Eve celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is not limited to traditional nights of
celebration. Phoenix police responded to more than 13,212 calls of
random gunfire from Dec. 31 through Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   For Martin and others, that's enough to keep him inside as much
as possible on New Year's Eve. He's considering attending the Tempe
Block Party but plans on being in one of downtown's bars during the
peak celebration hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll be inside most of the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin also is relieved he isn't working the second shift at
makeup manufacturer Revlon, near 43rd Avenue and Buckeye Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``My truck would be full of holes by the time I get off, or I'd
get hit just walking out to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, people are killed and seriously injured by these
gun-firing idiots, most of whom are too intoxicated to contemplate
the con sequences of their actions _ for example, what goes up must
come down.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kerry Fehr-Snyder can be reached at &QL; 
kerry.fehr-snyder &LR; arizonarepublic.com &QL; 
or at (602) 444-8975. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
