<HEADLINE>
FELICIA LAMPORT, 83, A SATIRIST DEVOTED TO RHYME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Felicia Lamport, a poet and satirist who took delight in
skewering the high and mighty with verse, quips, puns and parodies,
most of them first appearing in a column in The Boston Globe called
Muse of the Week in Review, died on Thursday at her home in
Cambridge, Mass. She was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lamport's column appeared in The Globe since 1981 but her
work also appeared in The New Yorker, The Atlantic Monthly,
Harper's and other publications.
</P>
<P>
   Her first collection of poetry, ``Mink on Weekdays (Ermine on
Sunday)'' (1950), became a best seller and was followed by other
collections with titles like ``Scrap Irony'' (1961), ``Cultural
Slag'' (1966) and ``Political Plumlines'' (1984).
</P>
<P>
   She was born in New York and graduated from Vassar College in
1937, after which she worked as a reporter and wrote dialogue for
MGM films.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by her husband, Benjamin Kaplan, a retired
justice of the Supreme Judicial Court of Massachusetts; a son,
James Kaplan of Northampton, Mass.; a daughter, Nancy Mansbach of
Newton, Mass., and four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly remembered for a work called ``The Love
Song of R. Milhous Nixon,'' in which she borrowed from T.S. Eliot
to lampoon President Nixon at the height of the Watergate scandal
in 1973. It began:
</P>
<P>
   Let us go then, in my plane,
</P>
<P>
   For a weekend of repose in Key Biscayne;
</P>
<P>
   When the view beneath our eyes appears unstable
</P>
<P>
   Let us banish all incipient defeats
</P>
<P>
   In one of my retreats.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from political jabs, Ms. Lamport also turned her attention
to the human comedy, with verse like:
</P>
<P>
   The after-effects of a mother's neglects
</P>
<P>
   May spoil her boy's orientation to sex,
</P>
<P>
   But the converse is worse: if she overprotects,
</P>
<P>
   The pattern of Oedipus wrecks.
</P>
<P>
   In April William Safire praised Ms. Lamport in The New York
Times Magazine as ``the leading muse of the Deprefixers,'' which he
defined as poets who achieve effects by dropping prefixes, for
lines like ``Men often pursue in suitable style/The imical girl
with the scrutable smile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
