<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC--UTfreshmen-HNS &LR;      12-24 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC--UT </SLUG>
 freshmen-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas' freshmen impressive, if seldom seen, in 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JEROME SOLOMON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ In a week, the decade and the University of Texas' 1999
football season will come to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns will deem their season a success regardless of
what happens in the Cotton Bowl against Arkansas on New Year's Day;
a handful of lows can't overshadow the abundance of highs they
experienced in their surprising run to the Big 12 Championship
Game.
</P>
<P>
   For the Longhorns' 24 freshmen, tabbed by most experts as the
No. 1 recruiting class in the country, the Cotton Bowl is not about
closure. To paraphrase Karen Carpenter, they have only just begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The season has gone by so fast,'' freshman Roderick Babers of
Houston said. ``It blew by. That's what the older guys said. Now, I
know it because it seemed like just yesterday we were reporting in
on Aug. 2 for two-a-days and now we're getting ready to play the
last game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to me how fast things have gone by. But that's
the way it's going to be, so you have to take advantage of every
time you're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what this group of freshmen tried to do, in what, for
most, were limited opportunities. Half the freshmen on the roster
saw no action, taking a redshirt season.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who played, only Babers, a cornerback on specialty
defenses, and quarterback Chris Simms earned starts.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Dockery, the offensive lineman from Garland, saw
extensive playing time as the third guard, regularly subbing for
senior Roger Roesler. Kenny Hayter saw action in seven games at
running back and was third on the team in rushing attempts, but had
just 33 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, Babers led the freshmen in tackles with 28, 23
solo, and he topped all defensive backs with three sacks. Cory
Redding (26 tackles) made his way into the defensive line rotation.
</P>
<P>
   And the group has gone through some drastic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Stevens, star tight end at Cy-Fair, has moved to fullback.
O.J. McClintock, star receiver at Round Rock Westwood, is looking
to make his mark as a linebacker. Robo-backer Redding, about whom
teammates rave, is robo-end Redding.
</P>
<P>
   Redding points to Babers' spiritual growth as one of the more
poihanges among the new breed, citing his earnest
participation in a weekly Bible study/prayer group that has quietly
become a popular activity among college athletes.
</P>
<P>
   On a lighter note, according to Simms and Babers, none of the
transformations was more pronounced than that of defensive lineman
Tillman Holloway (Basalt, Colo.), who began the season shy and
reserved and ends it as a chatterbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not say a word the first three weeks he was here and
now he won't shut up,'' Simms said. ``It's really amazing. He just
talks and talks, until you just got to get away from him or your
ear's going to pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms is not shy about sharing a good-natured jab or two with
his classmates, though he said he is still too ``New Jersey-ized,''
to have a Texas twang; don't expect a ``y'all'' to be among his
utterances.
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the heralded group wanted to make more noise on the
field this season, but the players realize that will come with
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a group I can't say enough about how great a year it's
been,'' Simms said. ``We're at one of the best universities in the
country and we play for one of the best college football teams in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've handled it well. Everyone is used to being a star in
high school, but you get here and you're kind of the unknown
soldier. But we all know it's a great opportunity and we need to
keep working hard and hopefully you'll get to play a lot one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that day comes, the freshmen need to learn some things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know I could learn so much,'' said Redding, who is
from Houston. ``You've got meetings, you've got football, you've
got school, and rewind it and you've got meetings, you've got
football, you've got school. I thought I already knew everything
about football.''
</P>
<P>
   In what can only be viewed as shocking news to those he has
manhandled on the field, Redding said the biggest difference in him
after a full season of college ball is he has learned to be meaner
than he was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really take too much,'' Redding said. ``My whole
attitude is tougher. I've moved it up to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Redding, who was USA Today's national Defensive Player of the
Year after his career at North Shore, authored some vicious hits on
special teams and picked up three sacks but didn't have the impact
on defense he would have liked. Still, he had 26 tackles and was
chosen the Big 12 Freshman Defensive Player of the Year in a vote
by the league's coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled a little bit because I don't feel I have the
weight to hold the position,'' said the 245-pound Redding. ``But I
feel with a year of strength and conditioning with Mad Dog (coach
Jeff Madden), I'll put on the weight I need to and I will keep the
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of speed, Babers, who played at Lamar, toyed with
opposing offenses in high school, almost daring them to throw his
way. But on this level, he found out he is not as fast or as good
as he thought. At least that was his impression early.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone else, including his coaches, see it differently. Babers
just has high standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot more things you need to know, compared to high
school football, because the speed of the game is so different,''
Babers said. ``It's more about a football education than just going
out there and using my physical skills. Once I learn everything, my
physical skills will catch up to all of that and I will be on the
level I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As the individuals reach personal levels of accomplishment, so
shall the freshman class. And as it improves, so shall the
Longhorns. At least that's what the youngsters believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players in this class will do way more and be even better
players than what they're hyped up to be,'' Babers said. ``I have
no doubt about it. The skills that are in this group make it
special. A lot of guys are maturing physically, mentally and
spiritually. This class is going to shock a lot of people. We're
going to surpass the expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider ourselves a very special group. Even though we're
team players, we still have our pride in our class. And everybody
believes we're going to win a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to win the national championship every year. We
didn't get it this year, but we're working for that next year.
That's the next goal. There's a lot of pride in this class. We joke
about it all the time that there will never be another class as
good as this one. We'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we will.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
