<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BRACE FOR REMATCH WITH SPURS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Guess who's been invited to Christmas dinner?
</P>
<P>
   Hint: It's worse than the in-laws, or the neighbor with the Ford
Pinto parked on his lawn.
</P>
<P>
   By decree of the NBA schedule makers, the San Antonio Spurs will
spend this festive evening in the Los Angeles Lakers' new home. The
hosts can only hope their guests treat Staples Center more kindly
than they did the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   In the Spurs' last trip to Los Angeles, they turned the Forum's
finaleinto a 4-0 playoffs sweep of the Lakers, then went on to
claim the NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have recovered nicely from that meltdown and take an
NBA-best 22-5 record into tonight's game, the first meeting with
the Spurs since May.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game,'' Kobe Bryant said, ``it's a big game. It's a
big challenge for us to see where we are as a team. We haven't been
in a real close game in a long time, so it's going to be
interesting to see how we execute when it comes down to crucial
moments.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this rematch will bear little resemblance to the
playoffseries, no matter what happens.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs playoff hero Sean Elliott is now a broadcaster, trying to
come back after a kidney transplant. Will Perdue, San Antonio's
third tower who ensured Shaquille O'Neal always had two 7-footers
to contend with at once, signed with the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have struggled to a 7-7 road record and are clearly
not the dominant team they were just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have a pretty good team,'' O'Neal said. ``We know
they'regoing to be pumped. So we just have to do everything
right.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a refreshing change for the Lakers, considering
how muchwent wrong in the Western Conference semifinals. They lost
two close games at the Alamodome, then got routed twice at home, by
an average of 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Twin towers Tim Duncan and David Robinson combined to make
O'Neal a footnote with ferocious defense. The Lakers' bench was
nonexistent. Their defense was woeful, as Duncan averaged 29 points
and role players like Jaren Jackson beat them from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers, like the Spurs, are not the same team. Coach
Phil Jackson has molded them into a defense-minded unit, holding
opponents to 89.1 points per game and 40.5 percent field-goal
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green has provided a much-needed steady presence at power
forward, and even the Lakers' stars Bryant, O'Neal and Glen Rice
have improved since last season. Credit the triangle offense for
some of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different team,'' Bryant said, ``because the
system is completely different. The key personnel is pretty much
the same, but we're in a different system. ... So San Antonio has a
whole different look (to deal with) as opposed to last year. It's a
huge advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The triangle offense is so mobile, you get to do things
against a team like San Antonio, who has big guys that clog up the
lane. ... You cando certain things to bring them away from the
basket. So it's a huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, however, has changed with regard to O'Neal's challenge.
On defense, he'll probably defend Duncan and Robinson (though
Jackson hinted he'll spend more time on Duncan than in the past).
And on offense, O'Neal still has to fight through the most
intimidating double team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``One athletic center versus two athletic centers is probably
always going to be difficult,'' O'Neal acknowledged, ``but they're
going to haveto double me. They can't play me straight up. If they
double, they probably can be effective, but if they double, I'm
just going to try to get the ball to somebody open. But I'm not
worried about single coverage at all.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers don't seem to be worried about the outcome,
either. No matter the intrigue involved in this rematch, Jackson
said he's not treating this game, the first of four against the
Spurs this season, as any sort of barometer.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what happens (tonight),'' O'Neal said, ``there's
still a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Jackson had his players participate in a ``Secret Santa''
gift exchange, and it appears Derek Fisher got the most out of it.
Though there was a supposed $1,000 limit, Fisher received a
platinum Rolex from his Santa O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in limits when it comesto taking care of
friends and family,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   The gift exchange was a first for the Lakers, and Jackson seemed
pleased at their response.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a lot of laughter coming out of that locker room,'' he
said. ``(The gift exchange) is just something I've always done ...
where theyhave to think about a teammate and make some concessions
and put themselves in somebody else's shoes, as to what they think
this person would want. Usually it's a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
