u i BC-INDIA-HIJACK-2NDLD-WR     12-24 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-HIJACK-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN AIRLINES JET SEIZED
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES first seven grafs with plane landing in Afghanistan, new
number of passengers released, clarification on death) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
By SUSAN SACHS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five Sikh men said to be armed with grenades and rifles hijacked
an Indian Airlines passenger plane Friday and claimed to have
killed at least four of the 189 people on board during a forced
odyssey across India, Pakistan, Afghanistan and the Persian Gulf
be- fore landing in Kandahar, Afghani- stan, shortly after 10 p.m.
Eastern time Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Some two hours earlier, the air- craft took off from a military
air base in the United Arab Emirates for an unknown destination.
That leg be- gan nearly 14 hours after the gun- men had
commandeered the plane and after its third refueling stop.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 passengers, identified in news reports as some of the
women, children and injured people on board, were released after
the five-hour stopover at the al-Manhad military base outside
Dubai. There were also reports that one body was taken from the
plane. Soon after, the A-300 Airbus took off. Emirates officials,
who had allowed the plane to land after nearby Oman had refused
per- mission, said the hijackers had agreed to free some hostages
after the plane had been refueled.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the hijackers, their demands and their intended
destination remained a mystery. At one point in the erratic
journey, they ordered the pilot to fly to Afghanistan but the
ruling Taliban militia refused to allow the plane to land.
</P>
<P>
   The men were confirmed as Sikhs,  &UR; &AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP; &LR;  the BBC
reported Friday night, and both Indian and Pakistani officials said
the gunmen spoke Hindi, the official language of India and the
predominant language in the north- ern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was originally bound for New Delhi from Katmandu, the
capi- tal of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in the emirates said they were trying to negotiate
the release of women and children, but did not intend to try to
hold the aircraft. They said they did not have information about
the condition of the passengers and crew members and could not
confirm whether any- one had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will allow it to refuel and we will provide it with medical
aid and food if needed,'' Information Minister Abdullah bin Zayed
said. ``That airport is equipped with ambulances. We are not
interested in allowing them to stay for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in India had initially said the hijackers had told a
crew member that they had shot and killed four passengers during
the first forced landing, in Amritsar. The crew member reported the
statement to air-traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   But later, Indian aviation officials said they had been told by
their counterparts in Pakistan that no one had been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines officials said Flight IC 814, which left Katmandu at
4:25 p.m. local time, 5:55 a.m. Eastern time, had a crew of 11 and
178 passengers on board.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, however, had conflicting reports on passengers'
nationalities. At least 154 were reported to be Indian and 8
Nepalese. Officials told Reuters that other passengers included
four Swiss, four Spaniards, a Japanese, a Canadian and a Belgian.
The nationalities of the other five passengers were not known.
</P>
<P>
   The flight, which is usually a one-hour trip, was seized about
30 minutes after it took off and just as the plane crossed into
Indian airspace.
</P>
<P>
   The hijackers, armed with AK-47 rifles and grenades that they
had apparently carried when they boarded in Nepal, first ordered
the pilot fly to Lahore, Pakistan. After Pakistani authorities
denied them permission to land, the plane was allowed to land in
nearby Amritsar, in northwestern India, because it was running low
on fuel, with 20 minutes of flying time remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In Amritsar, the hijackers appeared to panic after having warned
authorities that they would begin killing passengers if anyone
tried to approach the plane except to refuel it. Airport officials
said the gunmen opened fire while the aircraft was on the ground
and then, without waiting for refueling, ordered the pilot to take
off.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said later that the pilot reported to air
controllers that the hijackers had told him that they had killed
four people and had injured several others.
</P>
<P>
   The plane again turned toward Lahore, sinking to an altitude of
just 500 feet before Pakistani officials finally agreed to let it
make an emergency landing on a darkened runway.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan had already sent army commandos to patrol the airport,
although officials tried hard to avoid having anything to do with
the plane. The airport manager, Ghulam Mustafa Mirani, told the
Agence France-Presse that the runway lights had been switched off
to prevent the plane from landing. Only when the plane was
dangerously close to a crash landing, Mirani said, did authorities
relent.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Foreign Ministry in Islamabad said
permission was granted on humanitarian grounds after the pilot
reported that he was almost out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In Lahore, the hijackers demanded fuel and food but apparently
did not speak directly to officials. A spokesman for the
government, General Rashid Qureshi, said the hijackers made their
demands through the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1-2 hours in Lahore, the plane again took off without
releasing any people. The gunmen ordered the pilot to fly to
Afghanistan, the authorities said. But it was again denied landing
permission.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghan Islamic Press, in a report from the southern Afghan
city of Kandahar monitored by the British broadcasters, said the
civil aviation minister of the Taliban, Mullah Akhtar Mansoor,
refused a request to land at Kabul.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known why the Afghans, who have close relations with
Pakistan, refused. In any case, press reports from the region said
the Kabul airport, badly damaged in years of war and civil strife,
does not have operating radar that would assist a pilot in making a
night landing.
</P>
<P>
   Security experts speculated that the hijacking could be linked
to the disputed territory of Kashmir, the object of a long and
bitter struggle between India and Pakistan that heated up into a
military confrontation this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
