<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOFT-MONEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SOFT MONEY'S STAYING POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., La., Fla., Mass. Mo., Pa.) (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Dec. 25:
</P>
<P>
   The political parties have absorbed exactly the wrong message
from the 1996 Clinton fund-raising scandals. Instead of steering
clear of schemes to subvert federal limits on campaign
fund-raising, party officials seem determined to keep raising huge
chunks of unregulated soft money to pay for candidates' television
ads.
</P>
<P>
   A story in Wednesday's Times reported that Democratic Party
officials have established fund-raising committees in several
states with hot Senate contests. These new state-level ``victory
funds'' will allow donors barred by federal law from contributing
more than $2,000 per election cycle directly to an individual
candidate to write a $100,000 check to a party account. The
candidates themselves will help raise the money with the tacit
understanding that a hefty portion of the funds will be used for
their television advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme relies on two fictions _ that the money is meant as a
contribution to the party, not to a specific campaign, and that the
ads are generic ``issue ads'' rather than commercials designed,
sometimes in consultation with a campaign, to help a particular
candidate. The New York State Democratic Party has started running
television ads financed mostly with unregulated ``soft money'' to
promote Hillary Rodham Clinton's Senate candidacy. Mrs. Clinton has
not ruled out running more such ads, and there are also Democratic
``victory funds'' up and running to help candidates in California,
Florida, Louisiana and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In their defense, Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee
officials say they are merely copying the Republicans, who
pioneered this type of fund-raising committee two years ago. The
Republicans have set up two such funds this year, for Senate
candidates in Missouri and Pennsylvania. ``We're learning from
them,'' say David DiMartino, a Democratic Senate committee
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   This escalation in the special-interest money game by both
parties is the price the nation is paying for the indifference
displayed by Attorney General Janet Reno and the Federal Elections
Commission in the last presidential election cycle. Both failed
completely to enforce existing contribution and spending limits
when the Clinton and Dole presidential campaigns made their
end-runs four years ago. As a result, the country again faces the
possibility of new scandals involving big money from tainted
sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-99 2340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
