<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-24 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8749 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHRISTMAS-VAGABONDS-K     12-24 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-VAGABONDS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 `Mayor of Jungletown' made Christmas special for vagabonds  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   CARTHAGE, Mo. _ Christmas, for George
Stump Sr., was always the best of times.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the years, millions have shared Stump's sentiment _ the
decorated tree, children's expectant faces, the good cheer, the
fulsome meal.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what Stump saw at Christmas was different. His attention was
drawn to the bums, vagabonds, vagrants, tramps, knights of the
road, itinerants, hobos and bindlestiffs.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade from the early 1930s and into World War II _ days
far darker than anything that exists today _ Stump ministered to
the cold, bedraggled, hungry and discouraged in a place nicknamed
``Jungletown'' on the north edge of this Jasper County town.
</P>
<P>
   His method? Mulligan stew.
</P>
<P>
   Plus celery, radishes and pickles, Irish potatoes, carrots,
tomatoes, onions, lima beans, oranges, cakes, coffee and milk.
</P>
<P>
   No booze. That was out. But after those dinners and since it was
a time when people weren't wound as tightly as they are now, there
were smokes.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning tailormades. For the road weary, a Lucky or Chesterfield
was like manna.
</P>
<P>
   We know about Stump, dead since 1959, because his granddaughter,
Rebecca Stump Schneider of Kansas City, Kan., was rummaging through
the effects of her father, George Stump Jr., after he died earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   George Stump Jr., incidentally, was a legend in Kansas City
radio.
</P>
<P>
   Among her father's papers, Schneider found a neatly typed,
untitled narrative written by her grandfather on how he became a
benefactor to the downtrodden and received the st ``Mayor of
Jungletown.'' The story began: ``I am just a small town printer.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump worked for the Carthage Morning Democrat. A printer then
was the indispensable performer in communications, meaning
newspapers. Reporters and editors were a dime or less a dozen; a
printer was the keystone who got the paper out.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, many printers, as Stump's narrative showed, wrote clearly
and well. Set enough type and the craft rubs off.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, Stump was fairly secure. He had a job, a comfortable
home, and food on the table for his family. He had a good brier
pipe and a Christmas tree.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stump was troubled, especially at Christmas. He would write:
``It seems to me as time rocks along the real spirit and the
holiness of Christmas...has been brushed aside and the marts of
trade are packed with gaudy gadgets and tinsel whose only meaning
is to relieve you of the few pieces of silver you possess.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more, especially as the Depression deepened. Legions
of Americans _ mostly men and teen-age boys but with a smattering
of women and girls _ roamed the land.
</P>
<P>
   What conveyed them were not the interstates or an old Chevy
Malibu _ both still far in the future _ but the railroads. Two
lines, the Frisco and the Missouri Pacific, converged at Carthage,
and the wanderers' way station here was a cut in what was called
Tiger Hill alongside the Spring River.
</P>
<P>
   That cut, under the old U.S. 71 viaduct and still visible, was
this town's ``Hobo Jungle,'' a place where the dispossessed could
fan out and look for the peculiar ideographs that told them ``This
is a place for a handout'' (circle with an X inside); ``Owner will
give food to get rid of you'' (two rectangles); or ``Good-hearted
woman, tell a moving story (a stick figure and a series of tepees).
</P>
<P>
   So Stump knew of the tramps. They rode in on the freight trains.
Some wandered around town, looking for work or handouts. They were
down by the river. He decided to do something about them.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Christmas 1934, Stump bought 10 pounds of boiling
beef plus some vegetables, enlisted the aid of a police officer,
and went to Jungletown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we drove up and the forlorn figures huddled around a
half-hearted fire saw a policeman's uniform their hearts sank and
only sullen stares were our greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when he explained the purpose of our visit the effect was
like the bursting of glorious sun rays through a rift in the storm
clouds....All pitched in with willing hands. Some started to rustle
wood, others for fresh water, and others peeled potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``One poor old fellow could scarcely believe it and seemed on
the verge of tears as he kept muttering, `Tell me there ain't no
Santa Claus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That first batch of mulligan stew, Stump wrote, gave him more
real joy than anything he had ever done. A verse from St. Paul kept
running through his head: ``Be not forgetful to entertain
strangers, for some have entertained angels unawares.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump had turkey and the fixings awaiting him at home, but he
stayed and ate.
</P>
<P>
   Eight were at that first dinner. It grew, over the next few
years to as many as 50. Grain doors from boxcars doubled as tables.
The hobos took pride in setting a neat table. Empty tomato cans
holding celery stalks formed the floral settings.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph taken during one of the dinners showed holiday
signs above a table piled with food; seven men and two women
standing ready to serve; off to one side a man in a dark overcoat
sucking on a pipe _ Stump himself.
</P>
<P>
   Stump wrote later that as the years passed, he started to see
familiar faces. The dinner, he said, had become a homecoming event
of sorts for the drifting, rootless souls who rode the rails. Some
made sure they were in southwest Missouri for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Nor were the railroads unsympathetic to Stump's endeavor. One of
his traditions was to print a menu _ just like the hotels in the
big cities did _ and send it around. On the back was printed the
arrival and departure of freights, ``so that my guests might make
proper connections.''
</P>
<P>
   Stump's granddaughter, Rebecca Schneider, remembers a story that
came later. After World War II, the family learned that two alumni
of the Christmas dinners found themselves under fire on a
battlefield in wintertime Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled together in a foxhole, the soldiers discovered that
years before they'd had mulligan stew in Carthage at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   As the bullets snapped overhead, one G.I. muttered, ``I sure
wish we was back in Jungletown now.''
</P>
<P>
   The other just nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Van Gilder, a local historian, said that the memory of
Jungletown and Stump has all but faded from Carthage. U.S. 71 has
been relocated and the old highway is lightly traveled.
</P>
<P>
   The grain door tables are long gone. So are the celery stalks in
the tomato cans and the simple decorations. Below is just the river
and the railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Once, though, the less fortunate gathered underneath the viaduct
and celebrated the birth of a child in a faraway land. Stump, being
a printer, put it simply:
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas has always been the greatest day of the year ever
since those three wise old boys headed across the desert on their
slow motion camels toward the little town of Bethlehem with nuthin'
but a star as a stop and go sign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
